const e=[{id:"wheeler-plan-before-cut",topic:"Plan before you start cutting",keywords:["plan","think","layout","begin","start","measure"],answer:"Stop and think through the whole build before you touch a saw. Sketch or list the parts, check your lumber, and sharpen dull tools first. Rushing into cuts without a plan is how most beginner mistakes happen."},{id:"wheeler-festina-lente",topic:"Make haste slowly",keywords:["hurry","rush","patience","pace","beginner"],answer:"Good woodworkers look slow at first because they set up carefully. Taking five minutes to lay out a joint saves an hour of fixing a bad cut. Work steadily rather than frantically."},{id:"wheeler-useful-projects",topic:"Build real projects for practice",keywords:["practice","exercise","joint","project","useful"],answer:"Skip endless practice joints that go nowhere. Build small useful items — a shelf, a box, a stool — and you will learn the same skills with more motivation."},{id:"wheeler-few-tools-enough",topic:"You need fewer tools than you think",keywords:["tools","minimal","basic","starter","few"],answer:"Skilled craftspeople have done remarkable work with a handful of sharp tools. Start with essentials and add tools only when a real project demands them."},{id:"wheeler-avoid-tool-chest",topic:"Avoid cheap pre-filled tool chests",keywords:["buy","tool","chest","set","starter"],answer:"Skip the big boxed tool sets sold to beginners — quality varies wildly. Buy individual tools from reputable brands as you need them."},{id:"wheeler-buy-as-needed",topic:"Buy tools one at a time",keywords:["buy","purchase","tools","gradual"],answer:"Add tools when a project actually requires them. You will take better care of a small kit and learn what each tool really does."},{id:"wheeler-sharpen-habit",topic:"Sharpen instead of swapping dull tools",keywords:["sharpen","dull","chisel","plane","habit"],answer:"If you own thirty chisels it is tempting to grab a fresh one when one gets dull. Own fewer tools and sharpen them — that habit makes every cut cleaner."},{id:"wheeler-rely-on-favorites",topic:"Develop a small trusted tool set",keywords:["favorite","core","essential","kit"],answer:"Experienced woodworkers return to the same plane, square, and chisels daily. Quality and familiarity beat a crowded rack of rarely used gadgets."},{id:"wheeler-tool-quality",topic:"Invest in quality core tools",keywords:["quality","brand","cheap","durable"],answer:"Your measuring tools, plane, and chisels should be the best you can afford. Cheap squares and dull irons cause errors that no skill can fix."},{id:"wheeler-jackknife-uses",topic:"The utility of a sharp pocket knife",keywords:["jackknife","knife","pocket","whittle","mark"],answer:"A sharp pocket knife handles quick trimming, marking, and light shaping when you are away from the bench. Keep it sharp and use it carefully."},{id:"wheeler-handsaw-basics",topic:"Using a handsaw effectively",keywords:["handsaw","saw","crosscut","rip","hand"],answer:"Let the saw do the work — short steady strokes, not heavy forcing. Support the work firmly and start the cut with a knifewall or light back stroke to stay on your line."},{id:"wheeler-crosscut-vs-rip",topic:"Crosscut vs rip hand saws",keywords:["crosscut","rip","saw","grain","teeth"],answer:"Crosscut saws have teeth shaped to sever fibers across the grain; rip saws chisel along the grain. Using the wrong saw makes cutting harder and rougher."},{id:"wheeler-bit-brace",topic:"The bit brace and auger bits",keywords:["brace","auger","drill","bit","hand"],answer:"A sharp brace and auger bit bores clean holes without electricity. Keep bits sharp and start with a light center punch so the spur does not wander."},{id:"wheeler-try-square",topic:"Using a try square",keywords:["square","try","right","angle","check","90"],answer:"A try square checks that edges are truly 90° to faces. Test frequently while planing and marking — catching a drift early saves rework."},{id:"wheeler-marking-gauge",topic:"Marking gauge for layout lines",keywords:["gauge","mark","scribe","layout","line"],answer:"Set the marking gauge to your exact dimension and scribe a crisp line along the grain. A scored line gives your chisel or saw a place to register."},{id:"wheeler-bench-hook",topic:"Bench hook for crosscutting",keywords:["bench hook","hook","crosscut","saw","hold"],answer:"A bench hook hooks against the bench front and holds work while you saw. It is one of the simplest and most useful shop jigs for short crosscuts."},{id:"wheeler-wooden-mallet",topic:"Wooden mallet for chisel work",keywords:["mallet","hammer","chisel","tap","drive"],answer:"Use a wooden mallet on chisel handles — it drives without damaging the handle or overdriving. Reserve a metal hammer for nails only."},{id:"wheeler-clamps-essential",topic:"Clamps are indispensable",keywords:["clamp","cramp","glue","hold","pressure"],answer:"You can never have too many clamps for glue-ups. Pipe clamps, hand screws, and F-clamps spread even pressure so joints close tight."},{id:"wheeler-hand-screws",topic:"Hand screw clamps",keywords:["hand screw","clamp","wood","glue","parallel"],answer:"Wooden hand screws grip odd shapes and spread pressure over a wide area. They are ideal for gluing panels and holding work to the bench."},{id:"wheeler-bench-vise",topic:"Workbench vise use",keywords:["vise","bench","hold","work","clamp"],answer:"A sturdy bench vise holds boards for planing, sawing, and chiseling. Protect finished surfaces with wooden jaw caps or scrap pads."},{id:"wheeler-plane-basics",topic:"Hand plane fundamentals",keywords:["plane","smoothing","jack","flatten","surface"],answer:"A sharp plane removes thin shavings to flatten and smooth wood. Adjust the iron for a fine cut and plane with the grain when possible to avoid tear-out."},{id:"wheeler-plane-grain-direction",topic:"Plane with the grain",keywords:["plane","grain","tearout","direction","smooth"],answer:"Plane in the direction the grain rises — when fibers look like they lean toward you, reverse direction. Tear-out means you are planing against the grain."},{id:"wheeler-jack-plane-role",topic:"Jack plane for rough work",keywords:["jack","plane","rough","stock","dimension"],answer:"Use a jack plane to remove saw marks and bring boards close to final thickness. Follow with a trying or smoothing plane for a finished surface."},{id:"wheeler-smoothing-plane",topic:"Smoothing plane for final surfaces",keywords:["smoothing","plane","finish","final","surface"],answer:"The smoothing plane takes whisper-thin shavings for a glassy surface before finishing. Keep the iron razor sharp and the mouth tight for best results."},{id:"wheeler-chisel-sizes",topic:"Choosing chisel widths",keywords:["chisel","width","size","mortise","pare"],answer:"A small set — 1/4', 1/2', 3/4', and 1' — covers most work. Match chisel width to the joint you are cutting for clean shoulders."},{id:"wheeler-sharpening-stones",topic:"Sharpening on oil or water stones",keywords:["sharpen","stone","oil","water","hone"],answer:"Hone bevels on flat stones until you feel a burr, then remove the burr on the flat back. Sharp tools are safer because they need less force."},{id:"wheeler-grinding-bevel",topic:"Grinding the primary bevel",keywords:["grind","wheel","bevel","angle","restore"],answer:"Use a grinder or coarse stone to restore a damaged edge, then hone on fine stones. Do not overheat the steel — dip in water if the edge blue."},{id:"wheeler-strop-finish",topic:"Stropping for a keen edge",keywords:["strop","leather","polish","edge","sharp"],answer:"A few strokes on a leather strop after honing removes the last burr and polishes the edge. It extends time between full sharpenings."},{id:"wheeler-annual-rings",topic:"Reading annual growth rings",keywords:["ring","annual","growth","end grain","log"],answer:"Each ring on the end of a board is one year of growth. Ring spacing tells you how fast the tree grew — tight rings often mean denser, stronger wood."},{id:"wheeler-sapwood-heartwood",topic:"Sapwood vs heartwood",keywords:["sap","heart","sapwood","heartwood","color"],answer:"Sapwood is the lighter outer wood that carried sap; heartwood is the darker inner core. Sapwood is often softer and accepts stain differently."},{id:"wheeler-medullary-rays",topic:"Medullary rays in oak and similar species",keywords:["ray","medullary","quarter","oak","figure"],answer:"Those flake patterns in quarter-sawn oak are medullary rays — natural structures that run from the pith outward. Quarter-sawing exposes this beautiful figure."},{id:"wheeler-grain-lines",topic:"Understanding grain direction on faces",keywords:["grain","direction","face","long","edge"],answer:"Grain lines on a board face show how the tree grew. Always note grain direction before planing, routing, or chiseling so your tools cut cleanly."},{id:"wheeler-shrinkage-across",topic:"Wood shrinks most across the grain",keywords:["shrink","warp","humidity","width","movement"],answer:"Wood moves little along its length but noticeably in width and thickness with humidity changes. Design joints and panels to allow that movement."},{id:"wheeler-shrinkage-length",topic:"Minimal lengthwise shrinkage",keywords:["length","shrink","long","grain","stable"],answer:"Along the length of a board, shrinkage is tiny enough to ignore for most furniture. Width and thickness are where seasonal movement matters."},{id:"wheeler-log-cracking",topic:"Why green logs crack",keywords:["crack","check","green","log","dry"],answer:"As a log dries, the outside shrinks faster than the inside, opening radial cracks. That is why lumber is sawn and stickered rather than left whole."},{id:"wheeler-plain-sawn",topic:"Plain-sawn lumber characteristics",keywords:["plain","flat","sawn","board","crown"],answer:"Plain-sawn boards show cathedral grain patterns and tend to cup toward the bark side as they dry. They are economical and fine for many uses."},{id:"wheeler-quarter-sawn",topic:"Quarter-sawn lumber benefits",keywords:["quarter","sawn","stable","ray","oak"],answer:"Quarter-sawn boards are cut radially from the log. They move less in width, stay flatter, and show striking ray figure in oak and similar species."},{id:"wheeler-rift-sawn",topic:"Rift-sawn lumber",keywords:["rift","sawn","straight","grain","stable"],answer:"Rift-sawn boards have straight, consistent grain lines with minimal figuring. They are stable and popular for legs and visible vertical members."},{id:"wheeler-center-board-best",topic:"Center boards stay flattest",keywords:["center","middle","board","flat","stable"],answer:"Boards cut through the center of a log shrink evenly on both faces and resist cupping better than outer boards. Ask for center stock on critical panels."},{id:"wheeler-split-vs-sawn",topic:"Split stock vs sawn stock",keywords:["split","rive","sawn","handle","grain"],answer:"Splitting wood along the grain guarantees straight fibers — ideal for axe handles and wedges. Sawing is faster but can leave short cross-grain weak spots."},{id:"wheeler-seasoning-basics",topic:"Why wood must be dry before use",keywords:["season","dry","moisture","green","warp"],answer:"Working wet wood means it will shrink after your project is built — opening joints, cracking panels, and twisting frames. Use lumber at working moisture content."},{id:"wheeler-air-drying",topic:"Air drying lumber",keywords:["air","dry","season","sticker","yard"],answer:"Stack boards outdoors under cover with stickers between each layer so air circulates. Good air drying takes months to years depending on thickness."},{id:"wheeler-kiln-drying",topic:"Kiln-dried lumber",keywords:["kiln","dry","moisture","lumber","yard"],answer:"Kiln drying speeds moisture removal in a controlled chamber. Most hardwood from lumberyards is kiln-dried to around 6–8% moisture for indoor furniture."},{id:"wheeler-no-fixed-season-time",topic:"Seasoning time varies",keywords:["time","year","season","how long","dry"],answer:"There is no magic 'one year per inch' rule that always applies. Thickness, species, climate, and stacking method all change drying time."},{id:"wheeler-test-moisture",topic:"Checking if wood is dry enough",keywords:["moisture","meter","dry","test","weight"],answer:"A moisture meter is the surest check. For furniture indoors, aim for 6–9%. Green wood feels cool and damp and is noticeably heavier."},{id:"wheeler-buying-lumber",topic:"Tips for buying lumber",keywords:["buy","lumber","yard","select","board"],answer:"Look straight down the length of each board for twist, bow, and cup. Reject boards with large knots on critical faces unless you can work around them."},{id:"wheeler-hardwood-softwood",topic:"Hardwood vs softwood explained",keywords:["hardwood","softwood","conifer","deciduous","species"],answer:"Hardwood comes from broad-leaved trees like oak and maple; softwood from conifers like pine and fir. The names describe botany, not always hardness."},{id:"wheeler-pine-uses",topic:"Working with pine",keywords:["pine","softwood","beginner","cheap","easy"],answer:"Pine is inexpensive, easy to cut, and forgiving for beginners. It dents easily and can be resinous — let fresh knots seal before finishing."},{id:"wheeler-oak-character",topic:"Oak for furniture and joinery",keywords:["oak","hardwood","strong","grain","quarter"],answer:"Oak is strong, splits along medullary rays beautifully when quarter-sawn, and takes stain well. Pre-drill screw holes and use sharp tools to avoid tear-out."},{id:"wheeler-maple-uses",topic:"Maple for hard-wearing surfaces",keywords:["maple","hard","dense","top","cutting"],answer:"Hard maple resists wear and polishes to a fine surface — great for tops, cutting boards, and turned legs. It can burn if router bits are dull."},{id:"wheeler-walnut-qualities",topic:"Walnut for fine work",keywords:["walnut","dark","fine","furniture","carve"],answer:"Walnut works easily, carves well, and needs little stain to look rich. It is a favorite for cabinets and visible joinery."},{id:"wheeler-mahogany-notes",topic:"Mahogany characteristics",keywords:["mahogany","stable","carve","fine","tropical"],answer:"Genuine mahogany is stable, works cleanly, and finishes beautifully. Verify the species — many woods are sold under similar names."},{id:"wheeler-cherry-aging",topic:"Cherry darkens with age and light",keywords:["cherry","darken","age","color","sun"],answer:"Cherry starts lighter and deepens to warm reddish brown with exposure to light. Finish samples on scrap and wait a week before judging color."},{id:"wheeler-basswood-carving",topic:"Basswood for carving",keywords:["basswood","lime","carve","soft","whittle"],answer:"Basswood is soft, fine-grained, and ideal for carving and whittling. It holds detail without fighting your tools."},{id:"wheeler-cedar-properties",topic:"Cedar for outdoor and chests",keywords:["cedar","aromatic","outdoor","rot","closet"],answer:"Cedar resists insects and decay naturally. It is soft — use it for closets, chests, and outdoor projects where its aroma and rot resistance help."},{id:"wheeler-workshop-location",topic:"Choosing a workshop space",keywords:["workshop","space","light","ventilation","location"],answer:"Pick a dry space with good light, ventilation, and power. Keep the floor clear of tripping hazards and store lumber flat off damp concrete."},{id:"wheeler-workbench-height",topic:"Workbench height",keywords:["bench","height","ergonomic","work","stand"],answer:"A bench around knuckle height when standing is a good starting point for hand tool work. Adjust with a lower platform if you do most work sitting."},{id:"wheeler-tool-rack",topic:"Storing tools safely",keywords:["store","rack","tool","organize","hang"],answer:"Hang saws and chisels where edges are protected and handles are easy to grab. Never toss sharp tools in a drawer loose."},{id:"wheeler-dust-control",topic:"Managing sawdust in the shop",keywords:["dust","sweep","vacuum","health","clean"],answer:"Sweep often and use dust collection on power tools. Fine wood dust is a health hazard — wear a mask when sanding and empty collectors regularly."},{id:"wheeler-lighting-shop",topic:"Good shop lighting",keywords:["light","lamp","see","shadow","bench"],answer:"Bright even lighting prevents layout errors and reduces eye strain. Add a task lamp at the bench for close chisel and marking work."},{id:"wheeler-first-aid",topic:"Keep a first aid kit handy",keywords:["first aid","cut","bandage","safety","shop"],answer:"Sharp tools mean occasional nicks. Keep bandages, antiseptic, and eye wash accessible. Know where the nearest phone is for emergencies."},{id:"wheeler-unplug-power-tools",topic:"Unplug tools when changing blades",keywords:["unplug","power","blade","bit","change"],answer:"Always disconnect power before swapping blades, bits, or belts. The switch can be bumped accidentally — treat every tool as if it could start."},{id:"wheeler-push-sticks",topic:"Push sticks on the table saw",keywords:["push stick","table saw","safety","kickback","guard"],answer:"Use push sticks and push blocks to keep hands past the blade line. Never reach over or behind a spinning blade to retrieve offcuts."},{id:"wheeler-eye-protection",topic:"Eye protection in the shop",keywords:["eye","goggles","safety","glasses","protection"],answer:"Wear impact-rated safety glasses for all cutting, sanding, and grinding. Regular prescription glasses are not enough protection from flying chips."},{id:"wheeler-hearing-protection",topic:"Hearing protection",keywords:["ear","hearing","plugs","muff","noise"],answer:"Power tools damage hearing over time. Use earplugs or muffs when running saws, routers, and sanders for more than brief cuts."},{id:"wheeler-measuring-twice",topic:"Measure twice cut once",keywords:["measure","twice","accuracy","mistake","layout"],answer:"Verify dimensions at the tool before every critical cut. Mark waste sides clearly so you do not cut the wrong side of the line."},{id:"wheeler-story-pole",topic:"Using a story pole",keywords:["story pole","stick","layout","repeat","dimension"],answer:"A story pole is a stick marked with all key dimensions for a project. Transfer marks from it to avoid repeated tape measure errors."},{id:"wheeler-knife-wall",topic:"Knifing a layout line",keywords:["knife","wall","mark","precise","chisel"],answer:"Score a layout line with a marking knife before sawing or chiseling. The knife wall gives your saw tooth a track and prevents grain tear-out past the line."},{id:"wheeler-pencil-vs-knife",topic:"Pencil marks vs knife lines",keywords:["pencil","knife","mark","thick","fine"],answer:"Pencils are fine for rough layout; use a knife for joinery lines where precision matters. Always cut to the waste side of a knifed line."},{id:"wheeler-gluing-basics",topic:"Wood glue fundamentals",keywords:["glue","adhesive","joint","bond","clamp"],answer:"Spread glue evenly on both mating surfaces, assemble promptly, and clamp until cured. Starved joints (too little glue) and glued-starved squeeze-out both weaken the bond."},{id:"wheeler-glue-consistency",topic:"Glue thickness for joints",keywords:["glue","thick","thin","cream","spread"],answer:"Glue should flow like cream — not so thick it will not penetrate pores, not so thin it runs everywhere. Warm cold glue slightly for easier spreading."},{id:"wheeler-glue-clamp-time",topic:"Clamp time for glued joints",keywords:["clamp","time","dry","glue","wait"],answer:"Leave clamps on at least 30–60 minutes for initial set and overnight for full strength. Do not stress the joint until the glue has fully cured."},{id:"wheeler-hide-glue",topic:"Hide glue for repairable joints",keywords:["hide glue","traditional","repair","reversible","hot"],answer:"Hot hide glue is traditional for fine furniture because it can be steamed apart for repairs. It requires a heated pot and has shorter open time."},{id:"wheeler-nailing-angle",topic:"Toenailing and angled nails",keywords:["toenail","angle","nail","diagonal","hold"],answer:"Driving nails at opposing angles locks boards together better than straight nailing. Alternate angles on each side of a joint for maximum grip."},{id:"wheeler-pilot-holes",topic:"Pilot holes for nails and screws",keywords:["pilot","pre-drill","split","hardwood","hole"],answer:"Drill a pilot hole slightly smaller than the nail or screw shank in hardwood and near board ends. It prevents splits and keeps the fastener straight."},{id:"wheeler-countersink-screws",topic:"Countersinking screw heads",keywords:["countersink","screw","flush","head","plug"],answer:"Countersink screw heads so they sit flush or below the surface. Fill with a wood plug or putty before finishing for an invisible fastener."},{id:"wheeler-screw-length",topic:"Choosing screw length",keywords:["screw","length","thread","grip","join"],answer:"Pick screws long enough for full thread engagement in the bottom piece but not so long they poke through. About two-thirds of the total thickness is a good guide."},{id:"wheeler-finishing-sequence",topic:"General finishing order",keywords:["finish","sand","stain","seal","coat"],answer:"Sand progressively finer, remove dust, apply stain if desired, then build finish coats. Sand lightly between coats with fine grit for a smooth build."},{id:"wheeler-sand-progression",topic:"Progressive sanding grits",keywords:["sand","grit","120","180","220","progress"],answer:"Start with grit that removes tool marks — often 120 or 150 — then step to 180 and 220 before finish. Jumping grits too fast leaves visible scratches."},{id:"wheeler-raise-grain",topic:"Raising grain before finish",keywords:["grain","raise","water","sand","prep"],answer:"Wipe the surface with a damp cloth, let it dry, then sand lightly with fine grit. This cuts raised fibers so the final finish feels smooth."},{id:"wheeler-oil-finish",topic:"Oil finishes on wood",keywords:["oil","linseed","tung","danish","natural"],answer:"Penetrating oils enhance grain and are easy to repair. Apply thin coats, wipe excess, and allow adequate drying between coats. They offer modest protection."},{id:"wheeler-shellac-uses",topic:"Shellac as a sealer",keywords:["shellac","seal","knot","bleed","coat"],answer:"Shellac blocks stain bleed from knots and makes a good barrier coat between dissimilar finishes. It dries fast and can be rubbed to a satin sheen."},{id:"wheeler-varnish-durability",topic:"Varnish for durable top coats",keywords:["varnish","polyurethane","durable","topcoat","protect"],answer:"Film finishes like varnish and polyurethane build a protective layer on tops and tables. Apply thin coats and sand lightly between for clarity."},{id:"wheeler-bending-kerf",topic:"Kerf bending for curves",keywords:["kerf","bend","curve","cut","flex"],answer:"Sawing closely spaced kerfs on the inside of a curve lets stock bend without steaming. Space kerfs evenly and do not cut through the outer face."},{id:"wheeler-steam-bending",topic:"Steam bending wood",keywords:["steam","bend","curve","box","lumen"],answer:"Steaming softens lignin so thin strips can bend around forms. Use straight-grained stock, bend while hot, and dry clamped to the form."},{id:"wheeler-repair-glue-joint",topic:"Repairing a failed glue joint",keywords:["repair","reglue","joint","open","fix"],answer:"Clean old glue from both surfaces with a scraper or sandpaper until bare wood shows. Reglue, clamp firmly, and the joint is often stronger than before."},{id:"wheeler-wood-filler",topic:"Wood filler for gaps",keywords:["filler","putty","gap","hole","grain"],answer:"Use filler tinted to match the wood for nail holes and small gaps. Large structural gaps need wood patches or reglued joints — filler alone is cosmetic."},{id:"wheeler-stain-test",topic:"Always test stain on scrap",keywords:["stain","test","scrap","color","sample"],answer:"The same stain looks different on every species and board. Sand a scrap from the project wood, stain it, and approve the color before touching the real piece."},{id:"wheeler-nail-set",topic:"Using a nail set",keywords:["nail set","set","below","surface","fill"],answer:"Drive finishing nails until a dimple remains, then set the head slightly below the surface with a nail set. Fill the hole before painting or staining."},{id:"wheeler-drawbore-peg",topic:"Drawbore pegging for tight joints",keywords:["drawbore","peg","mortise","tenon","pull"],answer:"Offset the peg hole slightly so driving a peg pulls a tenon tight into its shoulder. It is a traditional way to lock mortise-and-tenon joints without glue."},{id:"wheeler-wood-screw-brass",topic:"Brass screws in hardware",keywords:["brass","screw","hardware","corrosion","hinge"],answer:"Brass screws resist corrosion and suit hinges and visible hardware. They are soft — use a steel pilot screw first, then install the brass screw."},{id:"wheeler-cross-grain-screw",topic:"Avoid screws in end grain alone",keywords:["end grain","screw","weak","hold","cross"],answer:"Screws driven only into end grain pull out easily. Add a dowel, block, or redesign so threads bite into face or edge grain."},{id:"wheeler-hand-plane-cap",topic:"Cap iron and chip breaker",keywords:["cap iron","chip breaker","plane","tearout","adjust"],answer:"On bench planes, set the cap iron close to the edge to break chips and reduce tear-out on difficult grain. A few thousandths of an inch makes a big difference."},{id:"wheeler-saw-sharpening",topic:"When a handsaw needs sharpening",keywords:["sharpen","saw","dull","file","set"],answer:"If a saw takes more force or wanders off line, it needs filing and setting. A sharp saw cuts with light downward pressure and tracks your line."},{id:"wheeler-brace-auger-care",topic:"Caring for auger bits",keywords:["auger","bit","sharp","rust","brace"],answer:"Keep auger bits dry and sharp. A dull spur wanders and tears the entry hole. A small file restores the cutting lip on quality bits."},{id:"wheeler-rabbet-plane",topic:"Rabbet and shoulder planes",keywords:["rabbet","rebate","shoulder","plane","groove"],answer:"Shoulder planes trim tenon cheeks and rabbet shoulders right up to a scribed line. Their side reference face keeps cuts square to the edge."},{id:"wheeler-spokeshave-use",topic:"Using a spokeshave",keywords:["spokeshave","curve","shape","spoke","shave"],answer:"A spokeshave shapes curves and tapers like a plane for your hands. Skew it slightly for a slicing cut on difficult grain."},{id:"wheeler-drawknife-control",topic:"Drawknife for shaping",keywords:["drawknife","shave","beam","taper","rough"],answer:"A drawknife removes stock quickly on beams and chair parts. Work downhill with the grain and take thin cuts to stay in control."},{id:"wheeler-scraping-card",topic:"Cabinet scrapers for smooth surfaces",keywords:["scraper","card","burnish","smooth","tearout"],answer:"A properly burnished card scraper takes fine shavings where planes tear out. It is excellent for figured wood and between finish coats."},{id:"wheeler-awl-uses",topic:"Scratch awl for starting holes",keywords:["awl","scratch","start","hole","mark"],answer:"An awl marks hole centers and starts screw pilot holes accurately. Press or tap lightly — a wandering start ruins alignment."},{id:"wheeler-bevel-gauge",topic:"Sliding bevel for angles",keywords:["bevel","gauge","angle","miter","mark"],answer:"Set the sliding bevel to any angle and transfer it to stock for miters and roof pitches. Lock the blade firmly before marking."},{id:"wheeler-level-surface",topic:"Checking surfaces for wind",keywords:["wind","twist","flat","winding","stick"],answer:"Pair winding sticks across a board and sight across their top edges. Twisted boards show one stick higher — plane until both edges match."},{id:"wheeler-choose-lumber-width",topic:"Selecting board width for panels",keywords:["panel","width","glue","bookmatch","match"],answer:"Glue narrow boards into wide panels when single wide boards are unavailable. Alternate growth-ring direction to balance movement across the panel."},{id:"wheeler-nail-selection",topic:"Choosing nail size and type",keywords:["nail","size","penny","length","type"],answer:"Pick nail length so about two-thirds penetrates the bottom piece. Finishing nails have small heads for trim; common nails have larger flat heads for framing."},{id:"wheeler-screw-pilot-countersink",topic:"Pilot and countersink in one step",keywords:["pilot","countersink","combo","drill","screw"],answer:"A combination bit drills pilot, clearance, and countersink in one pass — fast and consistent for hinge screws and hardware."},{id:"wheeler-work-holding-dogs",topic:"Bench dogs and holdfasts",keywords:["dog","holdfast","bench","hold","planing"],answer:"Bench dogs in the top and a holdfast in a hole clamp boards for planing. They free both hands for the tool."},{id:"wheeler-stop-block",topic:"Stop blocks for repeat cuts",keywords:["stop","block","repeat","same","length"],answer:"Clamp a stop block to a fence when you need many pieces the same length. Measure once, cut many — but verify the first piece."},{id:"wheeler-waste-side-mark",topic:"Mark the waste side of a line",keywords:["waste","mark","X","cut","line"],answer:"Always mark which side of a line is waste before sawing or chiseling. A quick X on the scrap side prevents expensive mistakes."},{id:"wheeler-glue-starve",topic:"Avoiding starved glue joints",keywords:["starved","glue","dry","clamp","squeeze"],answer:"You want a thin even film on both surfaces and slight squeeze-out when clamped. Dry wood or too little glue leaves a weak starved joint."},{id:"wheeler-rubbed-joint",topic:"Rubbed glue joint without clamps",keywords:["rubbed","joint","glue","hand","panel"],answer:"For edge joints, warm the glue, rub the boards together until they resist sliding, and let them set on supports. Works well for thin panel glue-ups."},{id:"wheeler-pocket-hole-note",topic:"Modern pocket screws vs traditional joints",keywords:["pocket","screw","fast","strong","face"],answer:"Pocket screws pull face frames tight quickly without visible end grain fasteners. They are practical for shop cabinets though traditionalists prefer mortise and tenon."},{id:"wheeler-wood-toxicity",topic:"Wood dust and species sensitivity",keywords:["toxic","dust","mask","species","irritant"],answer:"Some woods irritate skin and lungs — rosewood, teak, and walnut among them. Use dust collection, gloves if needed, and ventilation when sanding exotic species."},{id:"wheeler-resaw-by-hand",topic:"Resawing thick stock by hand",keywords:["resaw","thick","veneer","frame saw","band"],answer:"For thin stock from thick boards, use a frame saw or bandsaw. Hand resawing is slow — mark both edges and work down the middle patiently."},{id:"wheeler-tool-restoration",topic:"Restoring old hand tools",keywords:["restore","rust","old","vintage","plane"],answer:"Rust on cast iron is removable with vinegar or electrolysis. Check flatness of plane soles and sharpen irons — vintage tools are often higher quality than new budget ones."},{id:"fairham-glued-joint-intro",topic:"The glued butt joint",keywords:["glue","butt","edge","panel","joint"],answer:"Edge-gluing boards face-to-face makes wide panels from narrow stock. Jointed edges must mate perfectly along their full length for an invisible seam."},{id:"fairham-rubbed-joint",topic:"Rubbed joint technique",keywords:["rubbed","glue","slip","hand","clamp"],answer:"Warm the glue, coat both edges, rub the boards together until they resist sliding, then leave them supported until set. No clamps needed on many panel joints."},{id:"fairham-glue-penetration",topic:"Glue penetration for strength",keywords:["glue","penetrate","pore","pine","hardwood"],answer:"Glue grips best in open-grained woods like pine. Dense tropical hardwoods may need the surface lightly toothed with a fine plane before gluing."},{id:"fairham-glue-white-pine",topic:"Hiding glue lines on light woods",keywords:["glue line","pine","sycamore","white","hide"],answer:"Mix a little white pigment into glue on pale woods so the seam does not show as a dark line after finishing."},{id:"fairham-panel-support",topic:"Supporting glued panels while drying",keywords:["support","panel","sag","warp","dry"],answer:"Never lean a glued panel against a wall without mid-span support — it can bow before the glue sets. Support the full width on battens until cured."},{id:"fairham-winding-sticks",topic:"Winding sticks for flat edges",keywords:["winding","stick","flat","twist","edge"],answer:"Place matched sticks on both ends of a board and sight across them. If one stick looks higher, the edge is twisted and needs more planing."},{id:"fairham-alternate-heart",topic:"Alternating heart side in panels",keywords:["heart","alternate","cup","panel","warp"],answer:"When edge-gluing boards, alternate growth-ring direction so the panel stays flatter as humidity changes."},{id:"fairham-quartered-stock",topic:"Quartered lumber for stability",keywords:["quarter","stable","panel","shrink","flat"],answer:"Quartered boards shrink mostly in thickness, not width — ideal for door stiles and any part that must stay straight."},{id:"fairham-grain-match",topic:"Matching grain in glued panels",keywords:["grain","match","book","panel","aesthetic"],answer:"Arrange boards so grain flows across the panel. Random grain directions look haphazard on fine furniture faces."},{id:"fairham-shooting-board",topic:"Shooting board for thin stock edges",keywords:["shooting","board","thin","edge","plane"],answer:"A shooting board guides the plane at 90° when jointing thin board edges. Alternate face-up and face-down passes to avoid a convex joint line."},{id:"fairham-hardwood-slip",topic:"Hardwood edge slip on softwood",keywords:["slip","edge","hardwood","pine","veneer"],answer:"Glue a thin hardwood strip on the front edge of a pine shelf so the visible edge matches finer work and resists dents."},{id:"fairham-halved-corner",topic:"Halved corner joint",keywords:["halved","corner","lap","frame","half"],answer:"Each piece loses half its thickness where they overlap at a corner. Strong for frames — glue and screw from the inside on shop work."},{id:"fairham-halved-t",topic:"Halved T joint",keywords:["halved","t","rail","stile","through"],answer:"The rail runs through the stile with half-laps on both pieces. Common in window frames and simple cabinet face frames."},{id:"fairham-oblique-halving",topic:"Oblique halving for braces",keywords:["oblique","halving","brace","diagonal","rack"],answer:"An angled half-lap brace prevents a frame from racking. Cut the angle carefully so shoulders seat tight."},{id:"fairham-dovetail-halving",topic:"Dovetail halving joint",keywords:["dovetail","halving","lap","lock","strain"],answer:"A dovetail-shaped half-lap locks the joint against pull-out. Use where an upper rail might be stressed outward."},{id:"fairham-mitre-halving",topic:"Mitred halving for visible frames",keywords:["mitre","halving","mirror","frame","show"],answer:"Combines a mitered face with halved strength behind. Used on mirror frames where the face must look clean."},{id:"fairham-cross-halving",topic:"Cross halving joint",keywords:["cross","halving","intersect","grid","lap"],answer:"Two pieces pass through each other at mid-span, each half-lapped. Useful for lattice and simple grid structures."},{id:"fairham-tee-halving",topic:"Tee halving joint",keywords:["tee","halving","t","cross","lap"],answer:"One piece notched halfway to receive a cross member at right angles. Quick and strong for internal framing."},{id:"fairham-stopped-dovetail-halving",topic:"Stopped dovetail halving",keywords:["stopped","dovetail","halving","hidden","edge"],answer:"The dovetail does not exit the bottom edge — cleaner appearance when the lower edge is visible."},{id:"fairham-three-piece-halving",topic:"Three-piece halving",keywords:["three","piece","third","lap","wheel"],answer:"Each of three pieces is one-third lapped where they meet — used in wheel hubs and pattern-making. Demands careful layout."},{id:"fairham-bridle-open",topic:"Open bridle joint",keywords:["bridle","open","corner","splice","frame"],answer:"An open slot in one piece receives the full thickness of the other — like an open mortise and tenon at a corner."},{id:"fairham-bridle-closed",topic:"Closed bridle joint",keywords:["bridle","closed","miter","corner","hood"],answer:"Similar to open bridle but with a closed hood on the corner piece for a neater outside appearance."},{id:"fairham-bridle-strength",topic:"When to use a bridle joint",keywords:["bridle","strong","frame","corner","racking"],answer:"Bridle joints resist racking in frames better than simple miters. They suit light framing and some table corners."},{id:"fairham-tongue-groove-basics",topic:"Tongue and groove joint",keywords:["tongue","groove","floor","panel","fit"],answer:"A tongue on one board fits a groove in the next — classic for flooring and panel construction. Allows seasonal movement along the groove."},{id:"fairham-tongue-groove-panel",topic:"T&G for floating panels",keywords:["tongue","groove","panel","float","door"],answer:"Door and cabinet panels sit in grooves without glue so they can expand and contract. Only the frame rails and stiles are glued."},{id:"fairham-groove-depth",topic:"Groove depth for tongues",keywords:["groove","depth","tongue","third","rule"],answer:"Make the groove about one-third of the stock thickness and match the tongue to fit snugly but not tight enough to split."},{id:"fairham-mortise-tenon-basics",topic:"Mortise and tenon overview",keywords:["mortise","tenon","joint","classic","frame"],answer:"A rectangular tenon on one piece fits a matching mortise in the other. It is the backbone of table, door, and chair joinery."},{id:"fairham-tenon-one-third",topic:"Tenon thickness rule",keywords:["tenon","third","thickness","mortise","rule"],answer:"A good starting point: tenon thickness is about one-third of the rail thickness, centered in the mortise. Adjust for thin stock."},{id:"fairham-barefaced-tenon",topic:"Barefaced tenon",keywords:["barefaced","tenon","flush","one","shoulder"],answer:"A tenon with only one shoulder — used when one face must stay flush with a thicker stile. Never use at an exposed frame corner."},{id:"fairham-stub-tenon",topic:"Stub or stump tenon",keywords:["stub","stump","tenon","blind","hidden"],answer:"The tenon does not pass through the stile — no visible end grain on the edge. Common on interior frame members."},{id:"fairham-haunched-tenon",topic:"Haunched tenon for doors",keywords:["haunch","tenon","door","groove","panel"],answer:"A short haunch fills the groove area beside the tenon so the stile stays strong and the panel groove stays continuous."},{id:"fairham-horn-on-stile",topic:"Horns on door stiles",keywords:["horn","stile","extra","clamp","wedge"],answer:"Leave extra length on stiles past the rails during glue-up to prevent splitting while wedging. Trim horns flush after the frame is set."},{id:"fairham-wedged-tenon",topic:"Wedging a through tenon",keywords:["wedge","tenon","through","lock","draw"],answer:"Drive tight wedges into a saw kerf in a through tenon to lock it permanently. Traditional on workbench and table joints."},{id:"fairham-twin-tenons",topic:"Twin tenons on wide rails",keywords:["twin","double","tenon","wide","rail"],answer:"Two tenons on a wide rail fit two mortises — stronger than one wide tenon and less likely to twist in the mortise."},{id:"fairham-drawbore-tenon",topic:"Drawbore mortise and tenon",keywords:["drawbore","peg","offset","pull","tight"],answer:"Drill the peg hole in the tenon slightly closer to the shoulder so a peg draws the joint tight. Excellent without modern clamps."},{id:"fairham-mitred-tenon",topic:"Mitred and moulded tenon",keywords:["mitre","tenon","moulding","cabinet","light"],answer:"Used in light cabinet work where mouldings must intersect cleanly on the face while a tenon carries the strength behind."},{id:"fairham-japanese-tenon",topic:"Self-wedging Japanese tenon",keywords:["japanese","self","wedge","tenon","lock"],answer:"A shaped tenon wedges itself as it enters the mortise — clever for knockdown or demonstration joints."},{id:"fairham-tenon-shoulder-fault",topic:"Common tenon shoulder mistakes",keywords:["shoulder","undercut","gap","tenon","shrink"],answer:"Undercut shoulders open when the stile shrinks. Saw shoulders square and pare carefully so they seat fully under pressure."},{id:"fairham-mortise-chop",topic:"Chopping a mortise by hand",keywords:["mortise","chop","chisel","waste","hand"],answer:"Drill or bore most waste, then chop the mortise walls square with a mortise chisel. Work from both faces on through mortises to avoid blow-out."},{id:"fairham-mortise-machine",topic:"Chain mortiser for production",keywords:["mortiser","chain","machine","production","shop"],answer:"A chain mortiser cuts rectangular mortises quickly in production shops. Hand chopping still teaches you what the machine should produce."},{id:"fairham-dowelling-basics",topic:"Dowel joint fundamentals",keywords:["dowel","pin","align","joint","round"],answer:"Dowels align and reinforce butt joints. Use a doweling jig or marking system so holes line up perfectly in both pieces."},{id:"fairham-dowel-groove",topic:"Dowel with groove for panels",keywords:["dowel","groove","shelf","pin","support"],answer:"Dowel pins through shelf standards into shelf ends — combined with a groove or pocket for hidden shelf support."},{id:"fairham-scarf-joint",topic:"Scarf joint for length",keywords:["scarf","splice","length","beam","angle"],answer:"Angled faces glued together lengthen a beam or plank. Long shallow scarfs are stronger than short steep ones."},{id:"fairham-scarf-fishing",topic:"Fished scarf with plates",keywords:["fish","scarf","plate","bolt","beam"],answer:"Metal fish plates or bolts reinforce scarf joints in structural timbers where maximum length is needed."},{id:"fairham-hinged-joint",topic:"Hinged joint types",keywords:["hinge","joint","leaf","pivot","door"],answer:"Hinges transfer load through a pin while allowing rotation. Match hinge size to door weight and use enough screws in solid wood."},{id:"fairham-rule-joint",topic:"Rule joint for drop leaves",keywords:["rule","joint","leaf","table","hinge"],answer:"A shaped rule joint lets a drop leaf hang level with the table top when raised. Requires paired rule-joint hinges and careful shaping."},{id:"fairham-dovetail-basics",topic:"Dovetail joint overview",keywords:["dovetail","pin","tail","drawer","box"],answer:"Interlocking wedge-shaped tails and pins resist pull-out — the classic drawer corner joint. Layout and sawing accuracy define the fit."},{id:"fairham-through-dovetail",topic:"Through dovetail",keywords:["through","dovetail","visible","pin","tail"],answer:"Tails and pins show on both faces. Strong and honest — common on tool chests and visible drawer sides."},{id:"fairham-half-blind-dovetail",topic:"Half-blind dovetail",keywords:["half","blind","dovetail","drawer","front"],answer:"Pins hide behind the drawer front so only the tails show from the side. Standard on fine drawer construction."},{id:"fairham-sliding-dovetail",topic:"Sliding dovetail",keywords:["sliding","dovetail","groove","shelf","guide"],answer:"A dovetail-shaped tongue slides into a matching groove — excellent for adjustable shelves and breadboard ends."},{id:"fairham-secret-dovetail",topic:"Secret mitered dovetail",keywords:["secret","miter","dovetail","hidden","corner"],answer:"Combines mitered appearance with hidden dovetail strength inside the corner. Demands careful layout but looks seamless."},{id:"fairham-dovetail-spacing",topic:"Spacing dovetails evenly",keywords:["spacing","dovetail","layout","pin","aesthetic"],answer:"Lay out pins and tails with dividers for even spacing. Wider tails on thick stock; finer pins on thin drawer sides."},{id:"fairham-dovetail-saw",topic:"Dovetail saw for joinery",keywords:["dovetail","saw","fine","rip","joinery"],answer:"A small stiff backsaw with fine rip teeth cuts accurate dovetail cheeks. Saw to the waste side of your knifed lines."},{id:"fairham-mitre-basics",topic:"Miter joint fundamentals",keywords:["miter","mitre","45","angle","corner"],answer:"Two 45° cuts form a 90° corner. Miters alone are weak — reinforce with splines, biscuits, or a hidden dovetail."},{id:"fairham-mitre-reinforce",topic:"Reinforcing miter joints",keywords:["miter","spline","biscuit","reinforce","corner"],answer:"Add a spline across the miter or use a biscuit or domino inside the joint. Glue alone on end grain is not reliable long term."},{id:"fairham-mitre-box",topic:"Miter box for hand cuts",keywords:["miter","box","saw","guide","angle"],answer:"A miter box guides your saw at fixed angles for trim and small frames. Check with a square — worn boxes drift from true 45°."},{id:"fairham-miter-clamp",topic:"Clamping mitered corners",keywords:["miter","clamp","band","corner","web"],answer:"Band clamps or corner web clamps apply even pressure on all four mitered corners at once. Tape works for small boxes while glue sets."},{id:"fairham-comb-joint",topic:"Comb or finger joint",keywords:["comb","finger","box","glue","surface"],answer:"Interlocking fingers maximize glue surface on box corners and board edges. Machines cut them fast; hand layout is good practice."},{id:"fairham-lap-joint-simple",topic:"Simple lap joint",keywords:["lap","overlap","half","quick","frame"],answer:"Overlapping pieces glued and screwed — fast for rough frames and temporary structures where appearance is secondary."},{id:"fairham-cross-lap",topic:"Cross lap at mid-span",keywords:["cross","lap","mid","grid","intersect"],answer:"Each piece is half-notched where they cross — used in lattice tops and simple shelving grids."},{id:"fairham-dado-joint",topic:"Dado joint for shelves",keywords:["dado","groove","shelf","cabinet","slot"],answer:"A groove cut across the grain receives a shelf or divider. Stop dados hide the groove end; through dados are simpler to cut."},{id:"fairham-rabbet-joint",topic:"Rabbet joint for boxes",keywords:["rabbet","rebate","box","back","corner"],answer:"A rabbet on one piece overlaps the end of another — quick box corners when combined with nails or screws."},{id:"fairham-rebated-mitre",topic:"Rebated miter joint",keywords:["rebated","miter","box","lid","corner"],answer:"A small rabbet adds glue surface and registration to a mitered box corner. Stronger than a plain miter alone."},{id:"fairham-housing-joint",topic:"Housed joint for shelves",keywords:["housing","dado","shelf","stopped","cabinet"],answer:"A stopped groove hides the shelf end inside the cabinet side — clean appearance on bookcases and cupboards."},{id:"fairham-t-bridle",topic:"T bridle on table rails",keywords:["t","bridle","table","rail","leg"],answer:"Table rails often use bridle or mortise-and-tenon joints at the legs. Match joint size to the loads the table will carry."},{id:"fairham-knuckle-joint",topic:"Knuckle joint for hinges",keywords:["knuckle","hinge","barrel","pin","pivot"],answer:"Interlocking cylinders form a knuckle — the mechanical heart of most butt hinges. Lubricate pins on outdoor gates occasionally."},{id:"fairham-feather-spline",topic:"Feather spline in a groove",keywords:["feather","spline","miter","slip","reinforce"],answer:"A thin slip of hardwood glued into matching grooves bridges a miter or butt joint across the grain."},{id:"fairham-biscuit-joint",topic:"Biscuit joint alignment",keywords:["biscuit","plate","align","panel","edge"],answer:"Compressed wood biscuits swell in glue-filled slots to align panel edges and reinforce miters. Fast and effective in modern shops."},{id:"fairham-pocket-screw-note",topic:"Pocket screws as a modern joint",keywords:["pocket","screw","face","frame","fast"],answer:"Angled pocket holes pull joints tight with screws — practical for face frames and carcases when traditional joints are not required."},{id:"fairham-glue-and-screw",topic:"Combining glue and screws",keywords:["glue","screw","both","clamp","hold"],answer:"Screws hold parts in alignment while glue cures; glue adds long-term strength screws alone lack. Do not rely on screws in end grain only."},{id:"fairham-paint-outdoor-joint",topic:"Painting outdoor lap joints",keywords:["paint","outdoor","lap","weather","seal"],answer:"On exterior half-laps, paint or seal all end grain before assembly — end grain drinks water and rots first."},{id:"fairham-joint-tolerance",topic:"Fit joints snug not forced",keywords:["fit","snug","tight","force","assembly"],answer:"A joint should close with hand pressure or light clamping. Forcing a too-tight joint splits the wood and starves the glue line."},{id:"fairham-dry-fit-first",topic:"Dry-fit before gluing",keywords:["dry","fit","test","clamp","glue"],answer:"Assemble joints without glue first to check fit and clamp clearance. Adjust shoulders and tenons before glue locks everything."},{id:"fairham-glue-open-time",topic:"Glue open assembly time",keywords:["open","time","glue","clamp","rush"],answer:"Work within the glue open time — do not spread glue on a large assembly until you are ready to close and clamp it immediately."},{id:"fairham-cramp-pressure",topic:"Even clamp pressure on joints",keywords:["clamp","pressure","even","warp","bow"],answer:"Use enough clamps along a panel glue-up to close every inch of the joint. Uneven pressure leaves voids and bows the panel."},{id:"fairham-cauls-distribute",topic:"Using cauls for even pressure",keywords:["caul","clamp","bow","distribute","panel"],answer:"Curved or padded cauls between clamps and work spread pressure across wide glue-ups and protect soft wood from clamp dents."},{id:"fairham-pin-nail-glue",topic:"Pin nails while glue sets",keywords:["pin","nail","glue","hold","brad"],answer:"Fine brads or pins hold alignment while glue dries on miters and small boxes. Set them below the surface or in hidden locations."},{id:"fairham-bridle-garden-gate",topic:"Bridle joints on gates",keywords:["gate","bridle","outdoor","frame","strong"],answer:"Open bridle corners on gates are strong and straightforward to maintain. Use rot-resistant wood and seal end grain well."},{id:"fairham-mortise-layout",topic:"Marking mortise and tenon from one gauge setting",keywords:["layout","gauge","mortise","tenon","mark"],answer:"Set mortise gauges once from the same stock thickness and transfer marks to every rail and stile — consistency prevents gaps."},{id:"fairham-shoulder-line",topic:"Cutting to the shoulder line",keywords:["shoulder","line","saw","chisel","tenon"],answer:"Saw cheeks down to the shoulder line, then chop waste with a chisel. A knifed shoulder line prevents tear-out past the joint face."},{id:"fairham-pegged-frame",topic:"Pegged timber frame",keywords:["peg","timber","frame","through","traditional"],answer:"Through tenons with hardwood pegs lock large timber frames. Drill peg holes after the joint is assembled for a tight fit."},{id:"fairham-loose-wedge-tenon",topic:"Loose wedge in a mortise",keywords:["loose","wedge","knockdown","tenon","removable"],answer:"A removable wedge tightens a through tenon for knockdown furniture — useful for pieces that must ship flat."},{id:"fairham-dovetail-drawer-fit",topic:"Fitting drawer dovetails",keywords:["drawer","fit","dovetail","slide","tight"],answer:"Drawers should slide smoothly without rocking. Fit tails snug on the sides and leave slight clearance on the bottom if needed."},{id:"fairham-mitre-trim",topic:"Mitered trim and moulding",keywords:["trim","miter","moulding","cope","corner"],answer:"Coping or mitering trim corners depends on the profile. Simple profiles miter; complex ones are often coped for a tight inside corner."},{id:"fairham-joint-for-task",topic:"Pick the joint for the job",keywords:["choose","joint","right","strength","appearance"],answer:"Match the joint to load, exposure, and visibility. A glued butt is fine for a back panel; a haunched tenon is better for a door rail."},{id:"fairham-halved-shelf-bracket",topic:"Halved joints on shelf brackets",keywords:["shelf","bracket","halving","wall","support"],answer:"Half-lapped brackets fold flat against a drop-leaf table or support shelving against a wall. Glue and screw for rigidity."},{id:"fairham-oblique-cross-halving",topic:"Oblique cross halving",keywords:["oblique","cross","angle","halving","non"],answer:"When two members meet at other than 90°, lay out the halving on a full-size drawing or with bevel gauge before cutting."},{id:"fairham-tongue-groove-floor",topic:"T&G flooring installation",keywords:["floor","tongue","groove","nail","expansion"],answer:"Face-nail through the tongue on wood floors, leaving expansion gap at walls. Never glue solid flooring to the subfloor across the width."},{id:"fairham-bridle-racking",topic:"Bridle joints prevent racking",keywords:["racking","bridle","diagonal","brace","frame"],answer:"Frames without diagonal bracing rack into parallelograms. Bridle or half-lap braces turn that movement into compression at the corners."},{id:"fairham-scarf-angle",topic:"Scarf angle for maximum glue area",keywords:["scarf","angle","glue","long","splice"],answer:"A long gentle scarf angle gives more glue surface than a short steep cut. Plane both faces perfectly flat before gluing."},{id:"fairham-hinge-placement",topic:"Hinge placement on doors",keywords:["hinge","place","door","gap","pivot"],answer:"Space hinges evenly on tall doors with an extra hinge if the door is heavy. A consistent reveal gap looks professional."},{id:"fairham-dovetail-pin-first",topic:"Cutting pins or tails first",keywords:["pin","tail","first","dovetail","method"],answer:"Either pins-first or tails-first works — pick one method and practice it. Pins-first is common when transferring to the tail board."},{id:"fairham-mitre-biscuit-align",topic:"Biscuits in mitered frames",keywords:["biscuit","miter","align","frame","register"],answer:"Biscuit slots in miters register corners during glue-up so they do not slide out of alignment under clamp pressure."},{id:"fairham-joint-sand-flush",topic:"Sanding joints flush after assembly",keywords:["sand","flush","joint","plane","level"],answer:"Plane or sand joints flush after glue-up, not before — slight proud edges sand away cleanly once the frame is rigid."},{id:"fairham-repair-open-miter",topic:"Fixing an open miter gap",keywords:["open","miter","gap","shim","fix"],answer:"Small miter gaps can be filled with colored wax or a sliver of matching wood. Large gaps mean recutting the joint."},{id:"fairham-glue-resistance",topic:"Glue as structural element",keywords:["glue","strength","joint","modern","design"],answer:"Modern PVA glues are stronger than wood fibers — a well-fitted glued joint often fails in the wood beside the glue line, not at the glue."},{id:"fairham-mortise-depth",topic:"Mortise depth vs tenon length",keywords:["depth","mortise","tenon","length","rule"],answer:"Mortise depth should leave a bit of room at the bottom; tenon length matches mortise depth minus 1/16' for glue squeeze-out space."},{id:"fairham-tenon-cheek",topic:"Parallel tenon cheeks",keywords:["cheek","parallel","mortise","fit","sliding"],answer:"Tenon cheeks must be parallel so the tenon slides in without rocking. Test fit with hand pressure before gluing."},{id:"fairham-bridle-saw-cut",topic:"Sawing bridle slot walls",keywords:["saw","bridle","slot","cheek","accurate"],answer:"Saw both walls of a bridle slot, then chisel the waste. A too-wide slot weakens the joint — pare cheeks carefully to the lines."},{id:"fairham-dowel-align-jig",topic:"Doweling jigs for alignment",keywords:["jig","dowel","align","hole","drill"],answer:"Commercial or shop-made doweling jigs keep hole spacing identical on both pieces. Misaligned dowels force joints open or split the wood."},{id:"fairham-lap-dovetail-scarf",topic:"Dovetailed lap for lengthening",keywords:["dovetail","lap","length","board","glue"],answer:"A dovetail-shaped lap splice resists pull better than a plain scarf on boards under tension along their length."},{id:"fairham-joint-expansion",topic:"Allowing movement in panel joints",keywords:["expansion","panel","groove","float","seasonal"],answer:"Never glue a solid wood panel into its groove on all four sides. Let it float in the groove while the frame is glued."},{id:"fairham-halved-moulded",topic:"Halving moulded members",keywords:["moulding","halving","profile","scribe","fit"],answer:"When half-lapping moulded stock, omit the profile in layout drawings and cut the flat bearing surfaces first for a tight fit."},{id:"fairham-carpentry-tie",topic:"Carpentry tie halving",keywords:["tie","joist","beam","angle","halving"],answer:"Angled tie pieces half-lapped to joists or beams resist diagonal loads in roof and floor framing."},{id:"fairham-puzzle-joint",topic:"Puzzle and trick dovetail joints",keywords:["puzzle","trick","dovetail","demonstration","exercise"],answer:"Interlocking puzzle joints are excellent layout exercises. They teach precision even though they are rarely used in furniture."},{id:"fairham-glued-mitre-box",topic:"Glued miter for small boxes",keywords:["box","miter","small","glue","tape"],answer:"Tape the outside of mitered box corners flat, fold them closed, and glue the inside — a simple clamp-free method for small work."},{id:"fairham-frame-racking-fix",topic:"Fixing a racked frame",keywords:["rack","square","frame","diagonal","measure"],answer:"Measure diagonals on a frame — equal diagonals mean square. Clamp across the long diagonal and glue a brace if racking persists."},{id:"fairham-joint-practice-order",topic:"Learning joints in sensible order",keywords:["learn","order","practice","halving","dovetail"],answer:"Start with halving and bridling, then mortise and tenon, then dovetails. Each joint teaches layout skills the next one builds on."},{id:"noyes-wedge-primitive",topic:"The wedge as the first wood tool",keywords:["wedge","split","primitive","force","grain"],answer:"A wedge splits wood along the grain by spreading force apart. Edge tools improved on this by letting you cut along a chosen path."},{id:"noyes-edge-two-actions",topic:"How cutting tools work",keywords:["edge","cut","wedge","shaving","tool"],answer:"Every cut has two actions: the sharp edge severs fibers, and the blade wedge pushes the shaving aside. Both must happen for a clean continuous cut."},{id:"noyes-straight-vs-sliding",topic:"Straight cut vs sliding cut",keywords:["straight","sliding","cut","chisel","plane"],answer:"Push a chisel straight in for mortising; slide it obliquely for easier paring. The sliding cut acts like a micro-saw and needs less force."},{id:"noyes-bevel-angle-soft-hard",topic:"Bevel angles for soft vs hard wood",keywords:["bevel","angle","soft","hard","chisel"],answer:"Use a lower cutting angle (around 25°) on soft woods and a steeper angle on hard woods so the edge supports itself under pressure."},{id:"noyes-firmer-chisel",topic:"Firmer chisel everyday use",keywords:["firmer","chisel","utility","mallet","pare"],answer:"The firmer chisel is the general-purpose chisel — sturdy enough for light mallet work and fine enough for paring. A good first chisel purchase."},{id:"noyes-paring-chisel",topic:"Paring chisel for fine work",keywords:["paring","chisel","thin","hand","control"],answer:"Long thin paring chisels are for hand pressure only — never hit them with a mallet. The beveled edges help reach into corners."},{id:"noyes-framing-chisel",topic:"Framing chisel for heavy work",keywords:["framing","chisel","heavy","timber","mallet"],answer:"Thick framing chisels take heavy mallet blows in timber framing. Socket handles absorb shock better than tang handles here."},{id:"noyes-mortise-chisel-thick",topic:"Mortise chisel thickness",keywords:["mortise","chisel","thick","lever","waste"],answer:"Mortise chisels are intentionally thick so you can lever waste out of deep mortises without the blade flexing or breaking."},{id:"noyes-chisel-motto",topic:"When in doubt use a chisel",keywords:["chisel","trim","fit","adjust","fine"],answer:"A sharp chisel trims tenon shoulders, cleans dados, and fine-tunes fit better than almost any other tool. Keep one within reach."},{id:"noyes-paring-grain",topic:"Paring with the grain",keywords:["pare","grain","chisel","smooth","direction"],answer:"Pare downhill with the grain for smooth surfaces. Paring uphill tears fibers — reverse the work or skew the chisel for a slicing cut."},{id:"noyes-dado-chisel-steps",topic:"Chiseling a dado in steps",keywords:["dado","chisel","groove","shelf","steps"],answer:"Saw the dado cheeks, then chisel out waste in layers — alternate inclined cuts from each side, then level the ridge in the middle."},{id:"noyes-end-grain-chisel",topic:"Chiseling end grain",keywords:["end","grain","chisel","perpendicular","splinter"],answer:"Take thin shavings on end grain and clamp work to a backup board to prevent blow-out on the back corner. A very sharp chisel is essential."},{id:"noyes-gouge-sweep",topic:"Gouge sweeps and uses",keywords:["gouge","sweep","curve","carve","hollow"],answer:"Gouges are labeled by sweep — shallow for gentle curves, deep for hollows. Push or mallet them like chisels following the grain."},{id:"noyes-drawknife-beam",topic:"Drawknife on a shaving horse",keywords:["drawknife","horse","shave","taper","chair"],answer:"Sit on a shaving horse and pull the drawknife toward you for controlled shaping of chair legs and tool handles."},{id:"noyes-spokeshave-detail",topic:"Spokeshave for fair curves",keywords:["spokeshave","fair","curve","adjust","iron"],answer:"Adjust the spokeshave iron for a fine cut on curved work. Skewing the tool reduces tear-out on figured grain."},{id:"noyes-hand-plane-types",topic:"Bench plane types explained",keywords:["bench","plane","jack","jointer","smooth"],answer:"Jack planes dimension rough stock, jointers straighten long edges, smoothing planes finish surfaces. Each has a role in the hand-tool sequence."},{id:"noyes-plane-iron-cap",topic:"Chip breaker on bench planes",keywords:["chip","breaker","cap","iron","tearout"],answer:"Set the cap iron close to the cutting edge to break chips early — essential for planing difficult or figured grain without tear-out."},{id:"noyes-block-plane",topic:"Block plane for end grain and trim",keywords:["block","plane","end","grain","trim","one hand"],answer:"A small block plane trims end grain, chamfers edges, and fits in one hand for quick jobs at the bench or on site."},{id:"noyes-router-plane",topic:"Router plane for grooves and dados",keywords:["router","plane","groove","dado","depth"],answer:"A router plane levels the bottom of grooves and dados to consistent depth after most waste is removed with a chisel."},{id:"noyes-rabbet-plane-hand",topic:"Rabbet plane by hand",keywords:["rabbet","plane","shoulder","step","groove"],answer:"A rabbet plane cuts an L-shaped step along an edge — the hand-tool ancestor of the router bit for joinery."},{id:"noyes-compass-plane",topic:"Compass plane for curves",keywords:["compass","plane","curve","arc","concave"],answer:"A compass plane has a flexible sole for convex or concave surfaces — rare today but useful for curved mouldings and boat work."},{id:"noyes-saw-set",topic:"Setting saw teeth",keywords:["set","saw","teeth","kerf","bend"],answer:"Saw set bends teeth slightly outward so the kerf is wider than the blade plate. Too much set makes wandering cuts; too little binds the saw."},{id:"noyes-rip-saw-teeth",topic:"Rip saw tooth pattern",keywords:["rip","teeth","chisel","grain","long"],answer:"Rip teeth act like tiny chisels splitting along the grain. Use a rip saw for cuts parallel to the grain on thick stock."},{id:"noyes-crosscut-teeth",topic:"Crosscut saw tooth pattern",keywords:["crosscut","teeth","knife","grain","across"],answer:"Crosscut teeth sever fibers like knives before the chip clears. Essential for clean cuts across the grain."},{id:"noyes-backsaw-stiff",topic:"Backsaw stiffness for joinery",keywords:["back","saw","stiff","dovetail","tenon"],answer:"The steel back keeps the blade rigid for precise joinery cuts. Dovetail and tenon saws are specialized backsaws with different tooth counts."},{id:"noyes-brace-bit-auger",topic:"Auger bit in a brace",keywords:["auger","brace","bit","bore","hole"],answer:"Auger bits in a brace bore large holes with a lead screw and cutting lip. The spur scores the circumference before the chip lifts."},{id:"noyes-gimlet-small",topic:"Gimlet for pilot holes",keywords:["gimlet","small","pilot","screw","start"],answer:"A gimlet drills tiny holes for screws in soft wood where a power drill would be overkill. Twist it slowly and keep it perpendicular."},{id:"noyes-bit-stock",topic:"Bit brace and interchangeable bits",keywords:["brace","stock","bit","ratchet","swing"],answer:"A ratcheting brace reaches holes near obstructions. Match bit type to the job — auger for wood, expansive for large diameters."},{id:"noyes-marking-knife-cut",topic:"Marking knife vs pencil",keywords:["marking","knife","pencil","layout","fine"],answer:"A marking knife severs fibers for a precise line your chisel can register in. Use pencils only for rough layout."},{id:"noyes-try-square-test",topic:"Testing with a try square",keywords:["try","square","test","90","check"],answer:"Check every planed edge against a known face with a try square. Small errors compound across a project."},{id:"noyes-gauge-mortise",topic:"Mortise gauge two pins",keywords:["mortise","gauge","two","pin","tenon"],answer:"A mortise gauge marks both sides of a mortise or tenon in one pass. Set it once from your stock thickness and lock firmly."},{id:"noyes-divider-scribe",topic:"Dividers for arcs and spacing",keywords:["divider","compass","arc","space","equal"],answer:"Dividers step off equal spaces and scribe arcs. Walk them along an edge to divide a line into equal parts without math."},{id:"noyes-rule-measure",topic:"Using a rule at the bench",keywords:["rule","ruler","measure","hook","end"],answer:"Hook rules on the end of a board for inside measurements. Measure from a knife line, not a pencil line, for accuracy."},{id:"noyes-bench-hook-cross",topic:"Bench hook for safe crosscuts",keywords:["bench","hook","saw","cross","safe"],answer:"The bench hook traps work against the bench while you saw — keeping fingers clear of the cut line on short pieces."},{id:"noyes-miter-box-hand",topic:"Hand miter box technique",keywords:["miter","box","hand","saw","trim"],answer:"Let the saw ride the miter box slots without forcing sideways pressure. Light strokes prevent binding in the kerf."},{id:"noyes-seasoning-why",topic:"Why seasoning matters",keywords:["season","dry","strength","weight","stable"],answer:"Drying wood reduces weight, increases strength, and prevents checking and decay. Working unseasoned stock courts warped projects."},{id:"noyes-sticker-stack",topic:"Sticker stacking lumber",keywords:["sticker","stack","air","dry","yard"],answer:"Place thin sticks between each layer of boards in a drying stack so air reaches every face. Align stickers vertically to avoid bowing."},{id:"noyes-kiln-vs-air",topic:"Kiln dry vs air dry",keywords:["kiln","air","moisture","percent","dry"],answer:"Kiln drying is faster and reaches lower moisture content than most air drying. Air-dried wood may still need acclimation indoors."},{id:"noyes-conifer-drying",topic:"Softwoods dry faster",keywords:["pine","fir","spruce","dry","fast"],answer:"Conifers have regular structure and dry more evenly than many hardwoods. They are often kiln-dried quickly for construction lumber."},{id:"noyes-thin-dries-fast",topic:"Thin stock dries faster",keywords:["thin","thick","dry","rate","board"],answer:"An inch board dries many times faster than a four-inch plank. Rip thick stock to rough width early to speed drying if air seasoning."},{id:"noyes-wood-moisture-indoor",topic:"Indoor furniture moisture content",keywords:["moisture","indoor","furniture","percent","humidity"],answer:"Furniture wood should match the humidity of the room where it will live — typically 6–9% moisture content in heated homes."},{id:"noyes-nail-cut-wire",topic:"Cut nails vs wire nails",keywords:["cut","wire","nail","wedge","hold"],answer:"Cut nails are wedge-shaped and grip strongly when driven with the wedge across the grain. Wire nails are cheaper and easier to drive."},{id:"noyes-nail-penny-size",topic:"Penny nail sizing",keywords:["penny","d","size","length","nail"],answer:"The 'd' penny system indicates nail length — a 6d nail is about 2 inches. Match length to joint thickness for good hold."},{id:"noyes-nail-angled-drive",topic:"Angled nail driving for grip",keywords:["angle","toenail","diagonal","hold","bind"],answer:"Drive nails at opposing angles where pieces meet — they work like dowels in tension and resist pull-out better than straight nails."},{id:"noyes-brad-finishing",topic:"Brad and finishing nails",keywords:["brad","finish","head","set","trim"],answer:"Small round-head brads set below the surface for trim and moulding. Fill holes before paint for an invisible finish."},{id:"noyes-screw-pilot-rule",topic:"Screw hole sizing rule",keywords:["pilot","clearance","screw","hole","slip"],answer:"Clearance hole in the top piece lets the screw pass freely; pilot hole in the bottom piece grips the threads. That draws pieces tight."},{id:"noyes-screw-lubricant",topic:"Soap on stubborn screws",keywords:["soap","wax","screw","drive","hardwood"],answer:"A little soap or wax on screw threads reduces friction in hardwood and helps prevent twisting off brass or small steel screws."},{id:"noyes-screw-plug-hide",topic:"Hiding screws with plugs",keywords:["plug","hide","screw","grain","match"],answer:"Bore a counterbore for the head, drive the screw, glue in a plug cut from scrap matched to grain direction, and trim flush."},{id:"noyes-lag-screw",topic:"Lag screws for heavy joints",keywords:["lag","coach","bolt","heavy","timber"],answer:"Lag screws are large hex-head screws for timber connections. Drill a full pilot hole and use a wrench — they exert enormous clamping force."},{id:"noyes-bolt-carriage",topic:"Carriage bolts in wood",keywords:["carriage","bolt","square","neck","timber"],answer:"The square neck under a carriage bolt head bites into wood and prevents spinning while you tighten the nut."},{id:"noyes-dowel-alignment",topic:"Dowels for alignment",keywords:["dowel","align","joint","drill","match"],answer:"Dowels keep butt joints from slipping during glue-up. Hole alignment must be perfect — use a jig or dowel centers to transfer marks."},{id:"noyes-corrugated-fastener",topic:"Corrugated fasteners",keywords:["corrugated","fastener","joint","frame","quick"],answer:"Corrugated nails bridge a joint from the side when face nailing is impossible. Drive so half the fastener sits in each piece."},{id:"noyes-glue-animal-modern",topic:"Animal glue and modern PVA",keywords:["animal","hide","pva","glue","repair"],answer:"Hide glue is reversible with heat and moisture — prized for antiques. PVA is stronger, easier, and standard for new furniture."},{id:"noyes-glue-clamp-pressure",topic:"Glue needs clamp pressure",keywords:["clamp","pressure","glue","void","film"],answer:"Clamps squeeze out excess glue and ensure intimate contact along the whole joint. Spring clamps alone are rarely enough on wide panels."},{id:"noyes-hinge-screw-length",topic:"Hinge screw length",keywords:["hinge","screw","length","pilot","door"],answer:"Hinge screws should bite deeply into solid wood or a plugged hole — short screws in thin stiles pull out under door weight."},{id:"noyes-lock-rail-mortise",topic:"Lock rail in door frames",keywords:["lock","rail","mortise","door","middle"],answer:"The lock rail is the horizontal member where the latch or lock sits — usually the widest rail in a paneled door frame."},{id:"noyes-panel-float",topic:"Floating panels in frames",keywords:["float","panel","groove","expand","season"],answer:"Panels fit in grooves without glue, free to move seasonally. The frame is glued; the panel is captured but not fixed."},{id:"noyes-breadboard-end",topic:"Breadboard end on tabletops",keywords:["breadboard","end","top","movement","peg"],answer:"A breadboard end caps end grain while allowing the main top to move. Peg the breadboard through slotted holes, not rigidly glued."},{id:"noyes-cross-grain-avoid",topic:"Avoid cross-grain construction traps",keywords:["cross","grain","trap","split","movement"],answer:"Never trap a wide solid board so it cannot move across the grain — tabletops split when screwed rigidly to a frame."},{id:"noyes-sanding-sequence",topic:"Sanding before finish",keywords:["sand","sequence","grit","prep","smooth"],answer:"Sand through progressively finer grits until scratches disappear. Always sand with the grain on the final passes before staining."},{id:"noyes-stain-oil-vs-water",topic:"Oil stains vs water stains",keywords:["oil","water","stain","raise","grain"],answer:"Oil stains are easy to apply evenly but may muddy fine grain. Water stains penetrate deeply and show grain clearly but raise fibers."},{id:"noyes-stain-test-scrap",topic:"Test stains on scrap wood",keywords:["stain","test","scrap","color","species"],answer:"Every species absorbs stain differently. Always test on the same wood as your project and view it after the finish coat dries."},{id:"noyes-ammonia-fume-oak",topic:"Ammonia fuming for aged oak",keywords:["ammonia","fume","oak","age","gray"],answer:"Exposing oak to ammonia fumes darkens and grays it like decades of aging. Ventilate heavily and fume in a sealed box away from metal."},{id:"noyes-shellac-sealer",topic:"Shellac as universal sealer",keywords:["shellac","seal","knot","bleed","barrier"],answer:"Dewaxed shellac seals knots, blocks tannin bleed, and isolates incompatible finishes. It dries in minutes between coats."},{id:"noyes-varnish-build",topic:"Building varnish coats",keywords:["varnish","coat","build","sand","between"],answer:"Apply thin varnish coats and sand lightly with fine grit between them. Thick single coats run and stay soft too long."},{id:"noyes-oil-rubbed-finish",topic:"Rubbed oil finish",keywords:["oil","rub","wipe","coat","natural"],answer:"Wipe-on oil finishes are forgiving for beginners. Apply thin coats, wipe dry after each, and build sheen gradually over days."},{id:"noyes-wax-over-shellac",topic:"Wax over shellac or varnish",keywords:["wax","paste","buff","sheen","maintain"],answer:"Paste wax over a cured film finish adds a soft sheen and makes dusting easier. Wax alone is not durable enough for tabletops."},{id:"noyes-raise-grain-water",topic:"Pre-raising grain before stain",keywords:["raise","grain","water","wipe","sand"],answer:"Dampen the wood lightly, let it dry, then sand with fine grit to knock down raised fibers. Stain and finish then feel smoother."},{id:"noyes-chemical-stain-chestnut",topic:"Chemical stains on chestnut and oak",keywords:["chemical","iron","acetate","stain","dark"],answer:"Solutions like iron acetate react with wood tannins for natural dark browns. Test strength on scrap — they penetrate deeply."},{id:"noyes-finishing-dust-free",topic:"Dust-free finishing area",keywords:["dust","finish","tack","cloth","clean"],answer:"Wipe the piece with a tack cloth between sanding and finishing. Airborne dust in finish coats is the main enemy of a glassy surface."},{id:"noyes-brush-quality",topic:"Quality brushes for finish",keywords:["brush","finish","bristle","foam","streak"],answer:"Good natural-bristle brushes lay varnish smoothly. Cheap foam brushes can leave bubbles — fine for shellac, less ideal for polyurethane."},{id:"noyes-spray-finish-note",topic:"Spray finishing basics",keywords:["spray","aerosol","HVLP","even","coat"],answer:"Thin even coats from a spray can or HVLP gun beat one heavy coat. Overlap passes and keep the gun moving to avoid runs."},{id:"noyes-safety-dust-lung",topic:"Wood dust and lung health",keywords:["dust","lung","mask","respirator","health"],answer:"Fine sanding dust is a long-term health risk. Wear a respirator rated for dust, not just a paper mask, during extended sanding."},{id:"noyes-safety-kickback",topic:"Table saw kickback awareness",keywords:["kickback","saw","splitter","paw","safety"],answer:"Kickback happens when the blade pinches the kerf and throws the work. Use a splitter, stand to the side, and never free-hand rip without a fence."},{id:"noyes-safety-router",topic:"Router safety",keywords:["router","bit","speed","direction","climb"],answer:"Feed the router against bit rotation on hand-held work to avoid climb cuts that jerk the tool. Unplug when changing bits."},{id:"noyes-measuring-diagonal",topic:"Diagonal measuring for square",keywords:["diagonal","square","frame","equal","check"],answer:"On a rectangular frame, equal diagonal measurements mean the corners are square. Adjust clamps along the long diagonal to pull it square."},{id:"noyes-story-stick-layout",topic:"Story stick for repeat layouts",keywords:["story","stick","layout","repeat","mark"],answer:"Mark all critical heights and widths on one stick, then transfer to each workpiece. Eliminates repeated measuring errors."},{id:"noyes-cutting-gauge",topic:"Cutting gauge for across-grain lines",keywords:["cutting","gauge","knife","cross","scribe"],answer:"A cutting gauge with a knife wheel scribes clean lines across grain where a pin gauge would tear fibers."},{id:"noyes-chalk-line",topic:"Chalk line for long layouts",keywords:["chalk","line","snap","long","straight"],answer:"Stretch a chalk line between two marks and snap it for a long straight reference on floors, panels, and sheet goods."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-oak",topic:"Oak properties for builders",keywords:["oak","strong","tannin","ring","porous"],answer:"Oak is strong and splits well for steam bending quarters. Its tannins react with steel and some finishes — use stainless or coated fasteners outdoors."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-maple",topic:"Maple hardness and use",keywords:["maple","hard","wear","floor","turn"],answer:"Hard maple resists denting — ideal for floors, butcher blocks, and turned legs. Soft maple is easier to work for painted casework."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-walnut",topic:"Walnut workability",keywords:["walnut","carve","rich","gunstock","fine"],answer:"Walnut planes and carves beautifully with a rich brown color. It is a top choice for gunstocks, cabinets, and visible joinery."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-mahogany",topic:"Mahogany stability",keywords:["mahogany","stable","carve","marine","fine"],answer:"Genuine mahogany is dimensionally stable and works without much fuss — historically prized for boats and fine furniture."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-pine",topic:"Pine and fir for construction",keywords:["pine","fir","spruce","construction","soft"],answer:"Softwoods like pine and fir dominate framing lumber. They nail easily, accept glue well, and are economical for shop projects."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-cedar",topic:"Cedar decay resistance",keywords:["cedar","rot","outdoor","aromatic","closet"],answer:"Cedar heartwood resists decay and insects naturally. Use it for closets, chests, and outdoor projects where rot matters."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-birch",topic:"Birch for plywood and turning",keywords:["birch","plywood","turn","even","grain"],answer:"Birch has fine even grain — common in plywood cores and turned items. It can blotch under stain without a pre-sealer."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-ash",topic:"Ash for tools and sports",keywords:["ash","strong","shock","handle","elastic"],answer:"Ash is elastic and shock-resistant — traditional for tool handles, baseball bats, and ladder rungs."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-cherry",topic:"Cherry for fine furniture",keywords:["cherry","age","color","fine","furniture"],answer:"Cherry machines well and deepens in color over time. It is a favorite for American period furniture reproductions."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-teak",topic:"Teak for marine use",keywords:["teak","oil","marine","outdoor","durable"],answer:"Teak’s natural oils resist water and rot — the standard for boat decks and outdoor furniture. Wear a mask — dust can irritate."},{id:"noyes-wood-species-rosewood",topic:"Rosewood caution",keywords:["rosewood","exotic","dust","irritant","dense"],answer:"Rosewood is dense and beautiful but dust can cause allergic reactions. Use excellent dust collection and ventilation."},{id:"noyes-logging-basics",topic:"From log to lumber overview",keywords:["log","lumber","mill","saw","process"],answer:"Logs are debarked, sawn into boards, edged, trimmed to length, and graded. Understanding mill steps helps you buy the right stock."},{id:"noyes-band-saw-mill",topic:"Band saw in modern mills",keywords:["band","saw","mill","kerf","thin"],answer:"Band saws make thin kerf cuts efficiently in modern mills — less waste than old circular sawmills."},{id:"noyes-waney-edge",topic:"Waney edge boards",keywords:["waney","bark","edge","live","rough"],answer:"Waney boards still carry the bark edge. They are rustic and economical — plane or rip the live edge if you need a straight reference."},{id:"noyes-grade-lumber",topic:"Lumber grading basics",keywords:["grade","select","common","defect","knot"],answer:"Higher grades have fewer knots and defects. Pick grade to match use — clear stock for visible faces, common grade for hidden structure."},{id:"noyes-power-drill-wood",topic:"Electric drill for woodworkers",keywords:["drill","power","pilot","hole","driver"],answer:"A variable-speed drill handles pilot holes, countersinks, and driving screws. Use sharp bits and back out chips in deep holes."},{id:"noyes-circular-saw-portable",topic:"Portable circular saw tips",keywords:["circular","saw","portable","guide","straight"],answer:"Clamp a straightedge guide for rip cuts with a circular saw. Set depth just below the work thickness for safer, cleaner cuts."},{id:"noyes-jigsaw-curve",topic:"Jigsaw for curves",keywords:["jigsaw","curve","scroll","blade","cut"],answer:"Use a narrow blade for tight curves and a coarse blade for fast straight cuts in thick stock. Support the work to reduce blade deflection."},{id:"noyes-tablesaw-fence",topic:"Table saw fence parallel to blade",keywords:["table","saw","fence","parallel","rip"],answer:"Check that the fence is parallel to the blade — binding causes kickback and burn marks. The fence can angle slightly away at the rear for safety."},{id:"noyes-router-table",topic:"Router table for profiles",keywords:["router","table","profile","edge","repeat"],answer:"A router table gives repeatable edge profiles and safer handling of small parts than hand-held routing."},{id:"noyes-planer-snipe",topic:"Avoiding planer snipe",keywords:["planer","snipe","feed","support","ends"],answer:"Support long boards at both ends as they enter and leave the planer to reduce snipe — shallow dips at board ends."},{id:"noyes-jointer-face-edge",topic:"Jointer face then edge",keywords:["jointer","face","edge","flat","square"],answer:"Joint one face flat, then joint one edge square to that face. Thickness planer references the flat face for parallel opposite face."},{id:"noyes-dust-collector",topic:"Dust collection on machines",keywords:["dust","collector","hose","CFM","health"],answer:"Connect each major machine to dust collection. Fine dust stays airborne longest — capture it at the source, not after it spreads."},{id:"noyes-glue-brush",topic:"Applying glue with a brush",keywords:["brush","glue","spread","even","tooth"],answer:"Use a disposable brush or notched spreader for even glue coverage. Missed dry spots are weak points in the joint."},{id:"noyes-clamping-caul",topic:"Cauls to protect soft wood",keywords:["caul","pad","clamp","dent","soft"],answer:"Place hardwood or MDF cauls between clamps and soft pine to distribute pressure and prevent clamp dents on the work face."},{id:"noyes-assembly-sequence",topic:"Glue-up assembly sequence",keywords:["assembly","sequence","glue","sub","frame"],answer:"Glue sub-assemblies first — a door frame before fitting the panel, a carcase before the back. Dry-fit the full sequence before opening glue bottles."},{id:"noyes-wood-filler-stain",topic:"Stainable wood filler",keywords:["filler","stain","hole","match","putty"],answer:"Use stainable filler for nail holes on finished surfaces. Regular putty without stain pigment stays light spots under dark stain."},{id:"noyes-steel-wool-between",topic:"Steel wool between coats",keywords:["steel","wool","rub","between","coat"],answer:"Fine steel wool between finish coats knocks down dust nibs and orange peel. Vacuum and tack cloth before the next coat."},{id:"noyes-rub-out-finish",topic:"Rubbing out a finish",keywords:["rub","out","pumice","rotten","stone","sheen"],answer:"After the final varnish coat cures, rub with pumice and rotten stone lubricated with oil or water for a piano-flat sheen."},{id:"noyes-carving-gouge-sharpen",topic:"Sharpening carving gouges",keywords:["carve","gouge","sharpen","inside","slip"],answer:"Use slip stones shaped to the gouge’s inside curve. A sharp inside bevel prevents crushing fibers in relief carving."},{id:"noyes-turning-basics",topic:"Wood turning on a lathe",keywords:["turn","lathe","round","spindle","bowl"],answer:"Mount stock securely between centers or on a faceplate. Take light cuts and keep tools sharp — dull tools cause catches and tear-out."},{id:"noyes-screw-thread-hold",topic:"Why screws fail in end grain",keywords:["end","grain","screw","thread","weak"],answer:"Threads in end grain pull out under load because they bite into short fibers. Redirect screws into face grain or add a hardwood block."},{id:"noyes-pilot-screw-hardwood",topic:"Pilot holes in hardwood",keywords:["pilot","hardwood","split","screw","depth"],answer:"Hardwood needs a pilot hole sized to the screw core, not the threads. Depth must exceed screw length to prevent bottoming and breakage."},{id:"noyes-wood-movement-tabletop",topic:"Allowing tabletop movement",keywords:["tabletop","movement","clip","slot","screw"],answer:"Attach tabletops with clips or screws in slotted holes in the apron — not rigidly glued — so seasonal width change does not crack the top."},{id:"noyes-veneer-hammer",topic:"Veneer hammer for hot glue",keywords:["veneer","hammer","hot","glue","press"],answer:"Traditional veneer work uses hot hide glue and a veneer hammer to squeegee and press sheets flat. Modern shops often use vacuum bags instead."},{id:"noyes-chip-carving",topic:"Chip carving technique",keywords:["chip","carve","knife","triangle","decorative"],answer:"Chip carving removes small triangular chips with a special knife for geometric decoration. Practice on basswood until cuts are clean and even."},{id:"noyes-work-across-grain-last",topic:"Plan cross-grain cuts last",keywords:["cross","grain","tear","last","sequence"],answer:"Do machining and planing with the grain first, then handle cross-grain end work with sharp tools and backup support to minimize tear-out."}],t=[{id:"expanded-oak-red-white",topic:"Red oak and white oak compared",keywords:["oak","red","white","open","closed","grain","hardness"],answer:"Red oak has open, porous grain that stains boldly; white oak has closed grain and better rot resistance for outdoor work. Both are hard and strong — white oak is the go-to for boats, barrels, and outdoor furniture."},{id:"expanded-maple-hard-soft",topic:"Hard maple vs soft maple",keywords:["maple","hard","soft","sugar","silver","cabinet"],answer:"Hard maple (sugar maple) is dense, wears well, and is prized for countertops and cutting boards. Soft maple works easier, costs less, and is fine for painted cabinets and secondary parts."},{id:"expanded-walnut-premium",topic:"Walnut for premium furniture",keywords:["walnut","dark","oil","premium","color"],answer:"Walnut offers rich brown color with straight or wavy grain and carves beautifully. An oil finish enhances its natural color — skip heavy stain and let the wood speak for itself."},{id:"expanded-cherry-aging-color",topic:"Cherry color change over time",keywords:["cherry","darken","sun","age","pink"],answer:"Fresh cherry looks pale pinkish brown and deepens to rich red-brown with light exposure over months. Finish a test board and wait a week before judging the final color."},{id:"expanded-pine-varieties",topic:"White, yellow, and ponderosa pine",keywords:["pine","white","yellow","ponderosa","softwood","knot"],answer:"White pine is soft with few knots — great for beginners. Yellow pine is harder and resinous. Ponderosa is common in the West with large knots — pick clear grades for visible work."},{id:"expanded-poplar-paint-grade",topic:"Poplar as paint-grade secondary wood",keywords:["poplar","paint","secondary","green","cheap"],answer:"Poplar is inexpensive, stable, and easy to machine — ideal for painted cabinet interiors and drawer sides. Heartwood can be greenish but disappears under paint."},{id:"expanded-hickory-hard",topic:"Hickory extreme hardness",keywords:["hickory","hard","floor","handle","tough"],answer:"Hickory is among the hardest domestic woods — excellent for flooring and striking tool handles. Use sharp tools and pre-drill every screw hole."},{id:"expanded-mdf-sheet-good",topic:"MDF strengths and limits",keywords:["mdf","medium","density","fiber","flat","paint"],answer:"MDF is perfectly flat with no grain — great for painted panels and jigs. It is heavy, soaks up moisture at edges, and screws need pilot holes or they strip easily."},{id:"expanded-plywood-grades",topic:"Plywood grades A through D",keywords:["plywood","grade","A","B","C","D","veneer"],answer:"Letter grades describe face veneer quality — A is nearly flawless, D allows large knots. Hardwood plywood has thin veneer faces; softwood ply is construction grade. Baltic birch has many thin plies and stays flat."},{id:"expanded-osb-not-furniture",topic:"OSB is structural not furniture grade",keywords:["osb","oriented","strand","structural","sheathing"],answer:"OSB is engineered for walls and subfloors — rough surface and swelling at edges make it unsuitable for furniture. Use plywood or solid wood for cabinets and shelves."},{id:"expanded-moisture-content-check",topic:"Checking wood moisture content",keywords:["moisture","meter","percent","dry","kiln"],answer:"Use a pin or pinless moisture meter on incoming lumber. Indoor furniture wood should read about 6–9% before building. Green wood feels cool and reads much higher."},{id:"expanded-movement-per-season",topic:"How much wood moves per season",keywords:["movement","inch","season","humidity","width"],answer:"A 12-inch wide solid board might move 1/8 inch or more across the grain between humid summer and dry winter. Design joints and panels to allow that movement instead of fighting it."},{id:"expanded-grain-planing-direction",topic:"Reading grain for hand planing",keywords:["grain","plane","direction","tearout","cathedral"],answer:"Look at the board face — if grain lines rise toward you like cat fur, plane the opposite direction. When the surface tears out, reverse direction or skew the plane for a slicing cut."},{id:"expanded-sawn-methods-compared",topic:"Quarter sawn, flat sawn, and rift sawn compared",keywords:["quarter","flat","rift","sawn","stability","figure"],answer:"Flat sawn shows cathedral arches and cups more. Quarter sawn is stable with ray fleck in oak. Rift sawn has straight grain lines with less figure — popular for legs and trim."},{id:"expanded-butt-joint-when",topic:"Butt joints and when they are fine",keywords:["butt","end","simple","weak","glue","nail"],answer:"A butt joint is two pieces end-to-end or edge-to-edge with no interlock — weakest alone but fine for back panels, temporary braces, or when captured in a groove. Add glue, screws, or nails for strength."},{id:"expanded-miter-coping",topic:"Miter joints and coping trim",keywords:["miter","45","coping","frame","trim"],answer:"Two 45° cuts make a 90° corner for picture frames and trim. Inside corners on moulding are often coped — one piece mitered, the other profile-cut to fit — for a tight joint even when walls are not square."},{id:"expanded-rabbet-joint-uses",topic:"Rabbet joints for cabinets",keywords:["rabbet","rebate","shelf","back","drawer"],answer:"A rabbet is an L-shaped notch along an edge — classic for cabinet backs, drawer bottoms, and glass panels. Cut with a table saw, router, or rabbet plane."},{id:"expanded-dado-shelf-support",topic:"Dado joints for shelf support",keywords:["dado","groove","shelf","router","table saw"],answer:"A dado runs across the grain to hold a shelf flush inside a carcase. Use a dado stack or router jig for consistent depth — typically one-third of the side thickness."},{id:"expanded-groove-with-grain",topic:"Groove joints running with the grain",keywords:["groove","plow","panel","bottom","drawer"],answer:"Grooves run parallel to grain to capture panels, drawer bottoms, or backs. A plow plane or router bit cuts them; stop grooves hide the ends inside the frame."},{id:"expanded-lap-joint-types",topic:"Full lap, half lap, and cross lap",keywords:["lap","half","cross","overlap","frame"],answer:"Lap joints overlap material — half lap removes half the thickness from each piece for a flush face. Cross lap joins two members at mid-span for grids and simple frames."},{id:"expanded-mortise-tenon-proportions",topic:"Mortise and tenon proportion rules",keywords:["mortise","tenon","third","rule","strongest"],answer:"Tenon thickness is often about one-third of the rail thickness, centered in the stile. Keep shoulders square and cheeks parallel — this is the strongest traditional frame joint."},{id:"expanded-wedged-tenon-drawbore",topic:"Wedged and drawbored mortise and tenon",keywords:["wedge","drawbore","peg","permanent","tenon"],answer:"Through tenons can be wedged or drawbored with offset peg holes to pull joints tight without clamps. Common in workbenches, doors, and timber framing."},{id:"expanded-dovetail-hand-router",topic:"Hand-cut dovetails vs router jigs",keywords:["dovetail","hand","router","jig","drawer"],answer:"Hand-cut dovetails show craftsmanship and need only a saw and chisel. Router jigs speed production drawers with uniform spacing. Both are strong — pick based on time and appearance goals."},{id:"expanded-half-blind-dovetail-drawer",topic:"Half-blind dovetails on drawer fronts",keywords:["half","blind","dovetail","drawer","front"],answer:"Half-blind dovetails hide pins behind the drawer front so only tails show from the side. Standard on fine furniture where the front must look clean."},{id:"expanded-sliding-dovetail-shelf",topic:"Sliding dovetail for shelves",keywords:["sliding","dovetail","shelf","case","lock"],answer:"A dovetail-shaped tongue slides into a matching groove — strong mechanical lock for shelves, dividers, and breadboard ends."},{id:"expanded-box-joint-jig",topic:"Box joints with a jig",keywords:["box","finger","joint","jig","strong"],answer:"Interlocking fingers give huge glue surface for boxes and drawers. A table saw or router jig keeps fingers even — layout matters more than fancy tools."},{id:"expanded-pocket-hole-modern",topic:"Pocket hole joints in modern shops",keywords:["pocket","hole","kreg","fast","face frame"],answer:"Angled pocket screws pull joints tight from inside — fast for face frames and carcases. Use coarse thread in softwood and fine in hardwood with correct screw length."},{id:"expanded-spline-miter",topic:"Spline reinforcement for miters",keywords:["spline","miter","reinforce","grain","align"],answer:"A thin strip glued into matching grooves bridges a miter across long grain — adds strength and alignment where end-grain glue alone is weak."},{id:"expanded-keyed-miter",topic:"Keyed miter joints",keywords:["keyed","miter","decorative","wedge","splined"],answer:"A visible key or spline across a miter adds decoration and strength — popular on box corners and picture frames."},{id:"expanded-knapp-joint-vintage",topic:"Knapp joint vintage machine dovetail",keywords:["knapp","vintage","machine","dovetail","antique"],answer:"The Knapp joint is a decorative machine-cut interlock from the late 1800s seen on antique drawers. Interesting historically — modern shops use standard dovetails or box joints instead."},{id:"expanded-glue-vs-mechanical",topic:"Glue alone vs mechanical fasteners vs both",keywords:["glue","screw","nail","both","joint"],answer:"Glue on long grain is very strong; end grain glue alone is weak. Screws and nails hold alignment and resist shock. Best practice: glue the joint and add mechanical backup where loads are high."},{id:"expanded-pva-yellow-white",topic:"Yellow vs white PVA wood glue",keywords:["pva","yellow","white","glue","aliphatic"],answer:"Yellow aliphatic glue is the shop standard — moderate open time and strong bond. White glue is similar but often slightly longer open time. Both clean up with water while wet."},{id:"expanded-titebond-levels",topic:"Titebond I, II, and III compared",keywords:["titebond","waterproof","resistance","I","II","III"],answer:"Titebond I is standard interior glue. II offers water resistance for kitchens and baths. III is waterproof for outdoor or wet environments — pick the lowest tier that meets your moisture exposure."},{id:"expanded-epoxy-gap-fill",topic:"Epoxy for gap filling and oily wood",keywords:["epoxy","gap","oily","teak","waterproof"],answer:"Two-part epoxy fills gaps and bonds oily or resinous woods where PVA struggles. Mix equal parts, work within pot life, and expect longer cure than yellow glue."},{id:"expanded-polyurethane-glue",topic:"Polyurethane glue expansion and cleanup",keywords:["polyurethane","gorilla","expand","foam","water"],answer:"PU glue foams as it cures and needs moisture to set — great for outdoor gaps but messy. Clamp firmly and scrape foam after it skins over; dried foam is hard to remove."},{id:"expanded-ca-glue-repair",topic:"CA glue for instant small repairs",keywords:["ca","super","glue","instant","activator"],answer:"Cyanoacrylate bonds small chips and cracks in seconds. Use thin CA for tight cracks and gel for gaps; activator spray speeds cure on dry wood."},{id:"expanded-contact-cement-veneer",topic:"Contact cement for veneer and laminate",keywords:["contact","cement","veneer","laminate","both sides"],answer:"Coat both surfaces, let dry to touch, then press together — no repositioning. Standard for plastic laminate counters and paper-backed veneer on large surfaces."},{id:"expanded-clamping-pressure-cauls",topic:"Clamping pressure and cauls",keywords:["clamp","pressure","caul","bow","even"],answer:"Clamp until you see even squeeze-out along the joint — snug, not crushing. Cauls spread pressure on curved or soft wood and prevent clamp dents."},{id:"expanded-glue-open-time",topic:"Glue open time and batch strategy",keywords:["open","time","assembly","batch","rush"],answer:"Spread glue only when ready to assemble — open time is limited. On large glue-ups, coat all surfaces quickly and enlist help so nothing skins over before clamping."},{id:"expanded-squeeze-out-cleanup",topic:"Cleaning glue squeeze-out",keywords:["squeeze","scrape","rag","cleanup","wet"],answer:"Scrape the bulk with a chisel when rubbery, then wipe with a damp rag before finish. Dried squeeze-out blocks stain and shows as pale spots."},{id:"expanded-end-grain-glue-size",topic:"End grain gluing and sizing",keywords:["end","grain","glue","weak","size","shellac"],answer:"End grain drinks glue like a straw leaving a starved joint. Size end grain with thin glue or dilute shellac, let dry, then glue normally for a stronger bond."},{id:"expanded-nail-types-compared",topic:"Common, box, finish nails and brads",keywords:["common","box","finish","brad","nail","head"],answer:"Common nails have large flat heads for framing. Box nails are thinner with smaller heads. Finish nails and brads have tiny heads meant to set below the surface on trim."},{id:"expanded-penny-system",topic:"Penny nail sizing explained",keywords:["penny","d","2d","16d","length","nail"],answer:"The 'd' penny size indicates length — 2d is about 1 inch, 8d about 2-1/2 inches, 16d about 3-1/2 inches. Match length so two-thirds of the nail sits in the bottom piece."},{id:"expanded-galvanized-nails",topic:"Galvanized nails for outdoor work",keywords:["galvanized","zinc","outdoor","rust","stain"],answer:"Zinc-coated nails resist rust in exterior work. Hot-dip galvanized is tougher than electro-plated. Avoid mixing uncoated steel with wet wood outdoors."},{id:"expanded-ring-shank-nails",topic:"Ring shank and spiral nail holding power",keywords:["ring","shank","spiral","hold","withdrawal"],answer:"Rings or spirals on shanks resist pull-out better than smooth nails — good for decking and subfloors where vibration loosens plain nails."},{id:"expanded-when-nail-vs-screw",topic:"When to nail instead of screw",keywords:["nail","screw","speed","shear","trim"],answer:"Nails are faster and excel in shear for framing and back panels. Screws give better withdrawal strength and removability. Use nails where speed matters and movement is small."},{id:"expanded-toe-nailing",topic:"Toe nailing technique",keywords:["toe","nail","angle","diagonal","stud"],answer:"Drive nails at opposing angles through the end of one board into another — locks joints without visible face fasteners. Standard for stud-to-plate connections in framing."},{id:"expanded-nail-split-prevent",topic:"Preventing splits when nailing",keywords:["split","blunt","pilot","hardwood","end"],answer:"Blunt the nail point with a hammer to crush fibers instead of wedging them apart. Pre-drill near ends and in hardwood — especially near board edges."},{id:"expanded-screw-anatomy",topic:"Wood screw heads, drives, and threads",keywords:["screw","head","phillips","torx","thread","flat"],answer:"Flat heads sit flush, round heads stand proud, pan heads suit washers. Phillips and Torx drives cam out less than slotted. Coarse threads grip softwood; fine threads suit hardwood and plywood."},{id:"expanded-screw-length-rule",topic:"Wood screw length rule of thumb",keywords:["screw","length","two thirds","penetration","join"],answer:"Choose length so full thread bites the bottom piece without poking through — about two-thirds of the screw in the second piece is a good starting point."},{id:"expanded-pilot-hole-sizing",topic:"Pilot and clearance hole sizing",keywords:["pilot","clearance","shank","thread","drill"],answer:"Drill clearance in the top piece for the shank and pilot in the bottom piece for the thread. That lets the screw pull pieces tight instead of fighting friction in the top board."},{id:"expanded-countersink-counterbore",topic:"Countersinking vs counterboring",keywords:["countersink","counterbore","plug","flush","head"],answer:"Countersinking creates a cone for a flat head to sit flush. Counterboring makes a flat pocket for a plug to hide the screw entirely on fine work."},{id:"expanded-drywall-screws-avoid",topic:"Why avoid drywall screws in wood furniture",keywords:["drywall","screw","brittle","bugle","wood"],answer:"Drywall screws are hard but brittle, snap under shear, and the bugle head splits wood. Use purpose-made wood screws with proper hardness and head shape."},{id:"expanded-pocket-screw-chart",topic:"Pocket hole screw length by thickness",keywords:["pocket","screw","1-1/4","2-1/2","coarse","fine"],answer:"Use 1-inch screws for 1/2-inch stock, 1-1/4 for 3/4-inch, 2-1/2 for 1-1/2-inch assemblies. Coarse thread for softwood, fine for hardwood — match jig setting to board thickness."},{id:"expanded-lag-screw-structural",topic:"Lag screws for structural connections",keywords:["lag","bolt","washer","timber","structural"],answer:"Lag screws are heavy hex-head screws for timber — drill a full pilot hole and use a washer under the head. Drive with a socket wrench, not a screwdriver."},{id:"expanded-screw-end-grain",topic:"Screw holding in end grain vs face grain",keywords:["end","grain","face","screw","weak","block"],answer:"Threads in end grain pull out easily under load. Angle screws into face grain, add a hardwood block, or use dowels when you must join into end grain."},{id:"expanded-hardware-wood-movement",topic:"Slotted holes for seasonal wood movement",keywords:["slot","elongated","movement","tabletop","clip"],answer:"Solid tops move with humidity — attach with clips or screws in slotted holes in the apron so the wood can slide. Never glue a wide panel flat to a rigid frame."},{id:"expanded-euro-cup-hinge",topic:"European cup hinges basics",keywords:["euro","cup","35mm","blum","overlay","inset"],answer:"35mm cup hinges clip into a bored hole — adjust depth, side, and height with screws after mounting. Pick overlay, half-overlay, or inset cups to match your door layout."},{id:"expanded-butt-hinge-mortise",topic:"Mortising butt hinges",keywords:["butt","hinge","mortise","door","reveal"],answer:"Lay out hinge leaves flush with the door and jamb edges, rout or chisel shallow mortises so the barrel sits proud of the face. Consistent reveal gaps look professional."},{id:"expanded-piano-hinge",topic:"Piano hinge continuous support",keywords:["piano","continuous","hinge","lid","bench"],answer:"A piano hinge runs the full edge — distributes weight on long lids and bench tops. Cut to length with a hacksaw and align carefully before drilling all holes."},{id:"expanded-drawer-slides-types",topic:"Side mount vs undermount drawer slides",keywords:["drawer","slide","undermount","extension","soft close"],answer:"Side mounts are easier to install; undermounts hide hardware for modern cabinets. Full-extension slides let you reach the back of the drawer; check weight ratings."},{id:"expanded-shelf-pin-32mm",topic:"Shelf pin holes and 32mm system",keywords:["shelf","pin","32mm","hole","spacing"],answer:"Adjustable shelf pins fit in 5mm holes — the 32mm system spaces holes vertically for European cabinet standards. Drill a grid with a jig for level shelves."},{id:"expanded-knockdown-hardware",topic:"Knockdown cam locks and confirmat screws",keywords:["knockdown","cam","confirmat","flat","pack"],answer:"Cam locks and confirmat screws assemble cabinets without glue so they ship flat. Follow the manufacturer bit size — confirmats need a stepped drill bit."},{id:"expanded-optimizer-lumber",topic:"DoveDesign lumber optimizer (1D)",keywords:["optimizer","lumber","1d","cut","nesting","waste"],answer:"Open the Optimizer tab, choose Lumber mode, set your stock lengths and kerf, then click Optimize Cuts. The diagram shows which parts fit on each board and how much waste remains."},{id:"expanded-optimizer-sheet",topic:"DoveDesign sheet optimizer (2D)",keywords:["optimizer","sheet","2d","plywood","panel","layout"],answer:"In Sheet mode, enter your sheet size and panel list, lock grain if needed, then run Optimize Sheets. Color-coded layouts show panel placement and total sheet count."},{id:"expanded-rip-crosscut-saws",topic:"Rip saw vs crosscut saw tooth geometry",keywords:["rip","crosscut","teeth","grain","handsaw"],answer:"Rip teeth chisel along the grain like tiny chisels; crosscut teeth sever fibers like knives. Using the right saw makes hand sawing faster and leaves a cleaner edge."},{id:"expanded-back-saw-types",topic:"Dovetail saw vs tenon saw",keywords:["back","saw","dovetail","tenon","stiff"],answer:"Dovetail saws have finer teeth for small joinery; tenon saws have coarser teeth for larger cheeks. The steel back keeps the blade straight for precise cuts."},{id:"expanded-coping-saw-curves",topic:"Coping saw for curves and interior cuts",keywords:["coping","saw","curve","interior","blade"],answer:"A coping saw turns tight curves and removes waste in pierced work. Tension the blade so it pings — loose blades wander and break."},{id:"expanded-card-scraper",topic:"Card scraper final surface prep",keywords:["card","scraper","burnish","shaving","no sandpaper"],answer:"A burnished card scraper takes fine shavings and can replace sanding on difficult grain. It needs no dust collection and leaves a glassy surface when sharp."},{id:"expanded-cabinet-scraper",topic:"Cabinet scraper for large surfaces",keywords:["cabinet","scraper","panel","tabletop","burnish"],answer:"Larger scrapers cover tabletops and panels faster than sandpaper. Bow the blade slightly with thumb pressure to control the cut depth."},{id:"expanded-block-plane-uses",topic:"Block plane for end grain and chamfers",keywords:["block","plane","end","grain","chamfer","one hand"],answer:"A small block plane trims end grain, eases sharp edges, and fits one hand for quick adjustments at the bench."},{id:"expanded-bench-plane-numbers",topic:"Bench planes No. 4, 5, and 7 roles",keywords:["no","4","5","7","smoother","jack","jointer"],answer:"No. 4 smooths final surfaces, No. 5 (jack) removes material quickly, No. 7 joints long edges straight. Match plane length to the job — longer planes straighten better."},{id:"expanded-shoulder-plane",topic:"Shoulder plane for square tenon shoulders",keywords:["shoulder","plane","tenon","cheek","square"],answer:"A shoulder plane has a blade flush with the sides to trim tenon cheeks and rabbets right up to a scribed line without tilting."},{id:"expanded-router-plane-depth",topic:"Router plane for consistent groove depth",keywords:["router","plane","dado","depth","bottom"],answer:"After chiseling most of a dado, a router plane levels the bottom to uniform depth — essential for shelves that sit flat."},{id:"expanded-chisel-bench-vs-mortise",topic:"Bench chisel vs mortise chisel",keywords:["bench","mortise","chisel","thick","pare"],answer:"Bench chisels pare and chop light mortises. Mortise chisels are thick to lever out waste without bending. Match tool to the cut width."},{id:"expanded-mallet-striking",topic:"Wooden mallet for chisels and assembly",keywords:["mallet","strike","chisel","assemble","wood"],answer:"A wooden or rawhide mallet drives chisels without mushrooming steel handles. Heavier mallets suit deep mortising; lighter ones suit dovetail chopping."},{id:"expanded-marking-gauge-types",topic:"Marking gauge and mortise gauge",keywords:["marking","gauge","mortise","pin","knife"],answer:"A single pin marks lines parallel to an edge. A mortise gauge has two pins to lay out both sides of a mortise or tenon in one pass."},{id:"expanded-combination-square",topic:"Combination square uses",keywords:["combination","square","90","45","depth","gauge"],answer:"Check 90° and 45° angles, mark parallel lines, and set depth with the sliding head. A reliable square is the foundation of accurate layout."},{id:"expanded-sliding-bevel",topic:"Sliding bevel for transferring angles",keywords:["sliding","bevel","angle","miter","transfer"],answer:"Lock any angle and transfer it to stock for roof pitches, tapered legs, and custom miters. Check tightness before marking — slipping loses accuracy."},{id:"expanded-marking-knife-accuracy",topic:"Marking knife beats pencil for joinery",keywords:["marking","knife","accurate","line","joint"],answer:"A knife severs fibers for a precise line your saw or chisel can register in. Always cut to the waste side of a knifed line."},{id:"expanded-drawknife-stock",topic:"Drawknife for fast stock removal",keywords:["drawknife","shave","beam","rough","curve"],answer:"Pull the drawknife toward you to peel thick shavings on rounded work. Take light cuts — deep bites are hard to control and can split the wood."},{id:"expanded-brace-bit-holes",topic:"Brace and bit for large holes",keywords:["brace","bit","auger","hand","hole"],answer:"A hand brace with auger bits bores large holes without electricity. The lead screw pulls the bit in — keep both hands on the brace and start perpendicular."},{id:"expanded-eggbeater-drill",topic:"Eggbeater hand drill control",keywords:["eggbeater","hand","drill","small","pilot"],answer:"The eggbeater drill offers controlled speed for small pilot holes and brass screws. Easier to feel binding than a power drill on delicate work."},{id:"expanded-clamp-types-guide",topic:"F, pipe, bar, spring, band, and toggle clamps",keywords:["f","clamp","pipe","bar","spring","band","toggle"],answer:"F and pipe clamps glue panels. Bar clamps reach long spans. Spring clamps hold templates lightly. Band clamps squeeze mitered frames. Toggle clamps fix jigs to the bench."},{id:"expanded-workbench-setup",topic:"Workbench height, vise, and holdfasts",keywords:["workbench","height","vise","holdfast","dog"],answer:"Bench height near your knuckles when standing suits hand planing. A front vise grips boards; bench dogs and holdfasts anchor work for planing and chiseling."},{id:"expanded-waterstones-sharpening",topic:"Waterstones grits and flattening",keywords:["waterstone","grit","1000","8000","flatten"],answer:"Progress through grits — 1000 to establish the edge, 4000–8000 to polish. Flatten stones regularly on diamond plate or sandpaper on glass so edges stay straight."},{id:"expanded-strop-honing",topic:"Strop and honing compound polish",keywords:["strop","honing","compound","polish","edge"],answer:"A few strokes on a leather strop with honing compound removes the last burr and extends time between full sharpenings."},{id:"expanded-sharpening-angles-chisel",topic:"Sharpening angles for chisels and planes",keywords:["angle","25","30","bevel","chisel","plane"],answer:"Primary bevel around 25° with a micro-bevel at 30° suits most bench work. Harder woods benefit from slightly steeper angles to support the edge."},{id:"expanded-table-saw-guide",topic:"Table saw safe and accurate use",keywords:["table","saw","fence","blade","kickback","splitter"],answer:"Set blade height barely above the work. Keep the fence parallel, use a splitter, and stand to the side. Push sticks are mandatory past the blade — never free-hand rips without a fence."},{id:"expanded-miter-saw-guide",topic:"Miter saw angles and stop blocks",keywords:["miter","saw","chop","bevel","compound","stop"],answer:"Use detents for common angles and a stop block clamped to the fence for repeat lengths. Let the blade reach full speed before lowering — do not rush small pieces without clamping."},{id:"expanded-router-handheld",topic:"Handheld router depth and climb cut danger",keywords:["router","handheld","climb","depth","pass"],answer:"Take shallow passes — about 1/8 inch in hardwood. Feed against bit rotation to avoid climb cuts that jerk the tool. Unplug when changing bits."},{id:"expanded-router-table-guide",topic:"Router table fence and featherboards",keywords:["router","table","fence","featherboard","direction"],answer:"Feed work against bit rotation so the fence pulls stock in. Featherboards hold work down and against the fence. Use a starting pin on curved starts."},{id:"expanded-router-bits-types",topic:"Router bit types and uses",keywords:["straight","roundover","chamfer","rabbet","flush","dovetail","bit"],answer:"Straight bits cut grooves; roundover and chamfer ease edges; flush-trim follows templates; dovetail bits cut drawer joints with a jig. Match shank size to your collet."},{id:"expanded-jigsaw-guide",topic:"Jigsaw blades and tearout control",keywords:["jigsaw","blade","tpi","scroll","tearout"],answer:"Higher TPI leaves cleaner cuts in wood; lower TPI cuts faster. Downstroke blades reduce chip-out on laminate faces. Support work close to the cut to reduce blade deflection."},{id:"expanded-bandsaw-guide",topic:"Band saw TPI, drift, and resawing",keywords:["bandsaw","tpi","drift","resaw","tension"],answer:"Narrow blades turn tight curves; wide blades resaw straight. Compensate for drift when fence resawing. Tension until the blade plucks like a guitar string."},{id:"expanded-drill-press-guide",topic:"Drill press speed and Forstner bits",keywords:["drill","press","speed","forstner","brad","depth"],answer:"Slow speed for large bits, faster for small. Forstner bits cut flat-bottom holes; brad-point bits locate accurately in wood. Set depth stop for consistent shelf pin holes."},{id:"expanded-ros-sander",topic:"Random orbital sander grit sequence",keywords:["random","orbital","sander","grit","swirl"],answer:"Progress 80–120–150–180–220 without skipping grits. Let the tool weight do the work — pressing causes swirl marks. Connect dust collection for health and visibility."},{id:"expanded-belt-sander-guide",topic:"Belt sander aggressive stock removal",keywords:["belt","sander","aggressive","moving","tip"],answer:"Keep the sander moving — holding still digs trenches. Belt sanders flatten and rough-shape fast; finish with an orbital sander. Mind the cord and balance so you do not tip onto edges."},{id:"expanded-planer-snipe-tips",topic:"Thickness planer snipe and passes",keywords:["planer","snipe","pass","thickness","marks"],answer:"Take light passes — 1/16 inch or less in hard wood. Support long boards at infeed and outfeed to reduce snipe. Roller marks mean dull blades need service."},{id:"expanded-jointer-order",topic:"Jointer face then edge workflow",keywords:["jointer","face","edge","flat","square"],answer:"Joint one face flat, then joint one edge square to that face. The planer references the flat face for parallel thickness — never skip face jointing."},{id:"expanded-pocket-hole-jig",topic:"Pocket hole jig setup and clamping",keywords:["pocket","hole","jig","collar","clamp"],answer:"Set the drill guide collar to your stock thickness and clamp the jig firmly so it cannot shift. Pocket screws draw joints tight — verify screw length chart before driving."},{id:"expanded-biscuit-joiner",topic:"Biscuit joiner slot sizes 0, 10, 20",keywords:["biscuit","joiner","0","10","20","align"],answer:"Biscuits align panel edges and add glue surface — size 0 for narrow frames, 20 for wide panels. Register the fence on a flat face for flush alignment."},{id:"expanded-scroll-saw-guide",topic:"Scroll saw blade tension and inside cuts",keywords:["scroll","saw","tension","pierce","stack"],answer:"Blade teeth point down — tension until it sings. Drill a pilot hole for inside cuts, thread the blade, and re-tension. Stack identical thin pieces with tape for duplicate shapes."},{id:"expanded-lathe-basics",topic:"Wood lathe tools and speed",keywords:["lathe","gouge","skew","speed","rpm"],answer:"Keep the tool rest close and move tools smoothly — never jam. Large diameters turn slower; small spindles faster. Roughing gouge shapes, skew chisel refines, parting tool cuts depth."},{id:"expanded-track-saw-guide",topic:"Track saw guide rail and splinter control",keywords:["track","saw","plunge","rail","splinter"],answer:"The guide rail replaces a table saw fence on sheet goods. A scoring pass or splinter strip reduces chip-out on veneer faces."},{id:"expanded-oscillating-tool",topic:"Oscillating multi-tool uses",keywords:["oscillating","multi","flush","cut","sand"],answer:"Flush-cut blades trim plugs and door jambs; sanding pads reach corners. Gentle pressure — forcing slows cutting and overheats blades."},{id:"expanded-nail-gun-compressor",topic:"Compressor PSI and nail gun types",keywords:["compressor","psi","brad","finish","framing","nailer"],answer:"Set PSI per gun manual — typically 70–120. Brad guns shoot thin pins; finish guns use 15 or 16 gauge; framing guns use large clipped nails. Clear jams with the air disconnected."},{id:"expanded-dust-collection-shop",topic:"Shop dust collection and health",keywords:["dust","collection","cfm","micron","hepa","vac"],answer:"Capture dust at the source with a collector or shop vac. Fine wood dust is a serious health risk — use N95 minimum for sanding, and HEPA for fine finishing dust."},{id:"expanded-sanding-never-skip",topic:"Sanding grit sequence never skip grits",keywords:["sand","grit","sequence","skip","scratch"],answer:"Each grit removes the scratches of the previous one. Jumping from 80 to 220 leaves deep scratches that show under finish."},{id:"expanded-raising-grain-finish",topic:"Raising grain before finishing",keywords:["raise","grain","water","220","smooth"],answer:"Wipe with a damp cloth, let dry, then sand lightly with 220 grit. This cuts raised fibers so the finished surface feels smooth to the touch."},{id:"expanded-gel-vs-liquid-stain",topic:"Gel stain vs liquid stain",keywords:["gel","liquid","stain","blotching","control"],answer:"Gel stain sits on the surface and reduces blotching on pine and cherry. Liquid stain penetrates deeper for bold color on open-grained woods like oak."},{id:"expanded-wood-conditioner",topic:"Stain conditioner for blotchy woods",keywords:["conditioner","blotch","pine","cherry","pre"],answer:"Pre-stain conditioner partially seals absorbent areas so stain absorbs evenly. Apply to pine, cherry, and maple before oil-based stain."},{id:"expanded-danish-oil-beginner",topic:"Danish oil for beginners",keywords:["danish","oil","wipe","easy","beginner"],answer:"Danish oil wipes on easily, enhances grain, and repairs with another coat. Protection is modest — fine for tables that get coasters and care."},{id:"expanded-blo-rag-safety",topic:"Boiled linseed oil and rag disposal fire risk",keywords:["linseed","oil","rag","fire","spontaneous"],answer:"Oily rags can spontaneously combust as they dry. Spread rags flat to dry or soak in water in a sealed metal can before disposal."},{id:"expanded-tung-oil-finish",topic:"Tung oil hardness and waterproofing",keywords:["tung","oil","hard","waterproof","coat"],answer:"Pure tung oil builds a harder film than boiled linseed over multiple thin coats. Allow adequate dry time between coats — it cures slower than Danish oil."},{id:"expanded-shellac-sealer-coat",topic:"Shellac as fast sealer",keywords:["shellac","seal","knot","dewaxed","barrier"],answer:"Dewaxed shellac seals knots and blocks tannin bleed. It dries in minutes and accepts most topcoats after light scuff sanding."},{id:"expanded-lacquer-spray",topic:"Lacquer spray and ventilation",keywords:["lacquer","spray","fume","fast","repair"],answer:"Lacquer dries fast and rubs out beautifully but needs spray equipment and excellent ventilation. It is repairable with new coats melting into old."},{id:"expanded-poly-oil-vs-water",topic:"Oil-based vs water-based polyurethane",keywords:["polyurethane","oil","water","amber","clear"],answer:"Oil-based poly adds warm amber tone and long cure. Water-based stays clear and cleans with water but raises grain more — sand between coats."},{id:"expanded-varnish-outdoor",topic:"Varnish for outdoor durability",keywords:["varnish","outdoor","uv","slow","marine"],answer:"Spar varnish flexes with wood movement and includes UV inhibitors for outdoor use. Expect slower dry times and more coats than indoor poly."},{id:"expanded-milk-paint",topic:"Milk paint distressed look",keywords:["milk","paint","voc","distress","bonding"],answer:"Milk paint is non-toxic and gives an antique matte look. Use a bonding agent on sealed surfaces so it adheres — it chips deliberately for distressed styles."},{id:"expanded-wax-topcoat-only",topic:"Paste wax as topcoat only",keywords:["wax","paste","buff","repair","not durable"],answer:"Wax over cured film finish adds sheen and easy renewal. Wax alone offers little protection on tabletops — always use over shellac, lacquer, or poly."},{id:"expanded-apply-method-compare",topic:"Spray vs brush vs wipe-on finish",keywords:["spray","brush","wipe","apply","method"],answer:"Spraying gives the flattest film but needs equipment. Brushing is accessible but may show strokes. Wiping builds thin even coats ideal for oils and Danish oil."},{id:"expanded-between-coat-scuff",topic:"Between-coat scuff sanding",keywords:["between","coat","320","400","scuff","nib"],answer:"Lightly scuff cured coats with 320–400 grit or gray pad to remove dust nibs. Vacuum and tack cloth before the next coat — do not sand through the film."},{id:"expanded-end-grain-seal-stain",topic:"Sealing end grain before stain",keywords:["end","grain","seal","blotch","stain"],answer:"Brush dilute shellac or conditioner on end grain before staining the faces — end grain drinks stain darker and looks blotchy without sealing first."},{id:"expanded-board-feet-formula",topic:"Board feet formula explained",keywords:["board","feet","formula","144","thickness"],answer:"Board feet = (thickness in inches × width in inches × length in feet) ÷ 12, or all inches divided by 144. Lumberyards price hardwood by the board foot."},{id:"expanded-waste-factor-solid",topic:"Adding 15–20% waste factor",keywords:["waste","factor","15","20","percent","extra"],answer:"Buy 15–20% extra solid wood for knots, defects, and miscuts. Complex projects with many small parts need more — simple boxes need less."},{id:"expanded-story-pole-layout",topic:"Story pole replaces repeated measuring",keywords:["story","pole","layout","stick","mark"],answer:"Mark all key dimensions once on a stick, then transfer marks to each workpiece. One mistake on the pole is easier to fix than ten tape measure errors."},{id:"expanded-cut-list-workflow",topic:"Cut list rough then final dimension",keywords:["cut","list","rough","final","oversize"],answer:"Rough-cut parts slightly long and wide, then mill flat and dimension to final size. This handles bow and twist before you commit to finished lengths."},{id:"expanded-lumber-s4s-rough",topic:"S4S vs rough sawn lumber buying",keywords:["s4s","rough","surfaced","mill","thick"],answer:"Rough lumber costs less but you must flatten and thickness it yourself. S4S (surfaced four sides) is ready to dimension — you pay for mill work in the price."},{id:"expanded-nominal-actual-list",topic:"Nominal vs actual lumber sizes",keywords:["nominal","actual","2x4","1x6","dimension"],answer:"A 2×4 is actually about 1-1/2 × 3-1/2 inches. A 1×6 is about 3/4 × 5-1/2. Always design and cut to actual dimensions, not nominal names."},{id:"expanded-tape-fractions-knife",topic:"Reading a tape measure and knifing marks",keywords:["tape","measure","fraction","knife","mark"],answer:"Learn eighths and sixteenths on the tape — mark with a knife or awl for joinery, pencil for rough layout only."},{id:"expanded-diagonal-square-cabinet",topic:"Squaring cabinets with diagonals",keywords:["diagonal","square","cabinet","equal","clamp"],answer:"Measure corner to corner on a rectangular carcase — equal diagonals mean square. Clamp across the long diagonal and tweak until they match before glue dries."},{id:"expanded-shelf-sag-rule",topic:"Shelf sag span rule of thumb",keywords:["sag","span","shelf","3/4","support"],answer:"A 3/4-inch shelf spanning more than about 30–36 inches without support may sag under books. Add a center divider, thicker stock, or edge banding for stiffness."},{id:"expanded-floating-panel-design",topic:"Designing floating panels for movement",keywords:["floating","panel","groove","expand","design"],answer:"Capture panels in grooves without glue so they slide seasonally. The frame is glued; the panel floats — critical for solid wood doors and tabletops."},{id:"expanded-assembly-order-plan",topic:"Planning assembly order before glue",keywords:["assembly","order","sub","glue","sequence"],answer:"Glue sub-assemblies first — face frame before carcase back, drawers after case is square. Dry-fit the full sequence with clamps in place before opening glue."},{id:"expanded-drawer-clearance-fit",topic:"Drawer side clearance for smooth slide",keywords:["drawer","clearance","slide","1/16","fit"],answer:"Leave about 1/16 inch total side clearance for wooden drawers — more in humid climates. Test fit before finishing; slides need manufacturer-specified gaps."},{id:"expanded-door-reveal-hinge",topic:"Door reveal margins and hinge placement",keywords:["reveal","door","hinge","gap","margin"],answer:"Consistent 1/16 to 1/8 inch reveals around doors look professional. Place hinges 3–4 inches from top and bottom on cabinet doors — add a third on tall doors."},{id:"expanded-cabinet-proportion",topic:"Cabinet proportion and rule of thirds",keywords:["proportion","golden","thirds","design","balance"],answer:"Divide height into thirds for pleasing drawer and door sizes. Slightly heavier bases and balanced negative space look better than equal random divisions."},{id:"expanded-face-frame-vs-frameless",topic:"Face frame vs frameless cabinets",keywords:["face","frame","frameless","euro","overlay"],answer:"Face-frame cabinets have a hardwood front frame — traditional American style. Frameless (European) rely on thick box sides and full-overlay doors for a modern look."},{id:"expanded-finish-inside-outside",topic:"Finishing inside vs outside surfaces",keywords:["finish","inside","outside","cabinet","interior"],answer:"Finish exterior and visible interior surfaces — shelf tops you see, drawer boxes you touch. Unseen carcase interiors can get one sealer coat or none to save time."},{id:"expanded-sketch-to-cutlist",topic:"From sketch to cut list",keywords:["sketch","cut","list","parts","breakdown"],answer:"Label every part on your sketch with finished dimensions and grain direction. List parts grouped by thickness and species for efficient milling at the saw."},{id:"expanded-prototype-cheap-wood",topic:"Prototype in cheap wood first",keywords:["prototype","cheap","pine","poplar","test"],answer:"Build a fit-check version in poplar or plywood before cutting expensive hardwood. Jigs and complex joinery earn their keep on the second build."},{id:"expanded-beginner-design-mistakes",topic:"Beginner design mistakes to avoid",keywords:["beginner","mistake","design","movement","square"],answer:"Common traps: ignoring wood movement, skipping square checks, wrong screw length, and finishing before final fit. Build flat, check square often, and dry-fit twice."},{id:"expanded-safety-eye-always",topic:"Eye protection always in the shop",keywords:["eye","goggles","safety","always","chips"],answer:"Wear impact-rated safety glasses for every cut, route, and sand. Prescription glasses are not safety glasses — chips come from unexpected angles."},{id:"expanded-safety-hearing",topic:"Hearing protection threshold",keywords:["hearing","ear","muff","plugs","noise"],answer:"Sustained noise above about 85 dB damages hearing permanently. Wear muffs or plugs when running saws, routers, and sanders for more than brief cuts."},{id:"expanded-safety-dust-n95",topic:"Dust masks N95 and P100 for finishing",keywords:["n95","p100","mask","dust","respirator"],answer:"Paper dust masks are insufficient for fine wood dust. Use N95 minimum for sanding; P100 or organic vapor cartridges for spray finishing."},{id:"expanded-safety-push-stick",topic:"Push sticks when they are required",keywords:["push","stick","table","saw","narrow"],answer:"Use a push stick whenever your hand would pass within a few inches of the blade — narrow rips and short pieces especially. Make push sticks from plywood scraps."},{id:"expanded-safety-featherboard",topic:"Featherboards for fence pressure",keywords:["featherboard","fence","hold","kick","make"],answer:"Featherboards press stock against the fence and table, freeing your hands. Make them from resilient hardwood strips or buy plastic versions with slots."},{id:"expanded-safety-blade-guard",topic:"Blade guards when to use them",keywords:["guard","blade","splitter","safety","remove"],answer:"Keep the guard and splitter on the table saw whenever possible. If removed for dado work, replace them before ripping — most accidents happen on unguarded cuts."},{id:"expanded-safety-kickback-stance",topic:"Table saw kickback causes and stance",keywords:["kickback","stance","splitter","pawls","bind"],answer:"Kickback happens when the kerf pinches the blade or a cut-off is thrown. Stand to the side, use a splitter, and never reach behind the blade."},{id:"expanded-safety-router-climb",topic:"Router climb cut risk",keywords:["climb","cut","router","direction","feed"],answer:"Feed against bit rotation on handheld routing — feeding with rotation makes the router run away. Climb cuts are for controlled CNC or table setups only."},{id:"expanded-safety-finish-vent",topic:"Finishing ventilation and flash point",keywords:["ventilation","fume","flash","point","spray"],answer:"Finish in a ventilated space away from flames. Solvents have low flash points — no water heaters or furnaces igniting vapor in enclosed shops."},{id:"expanded-safety-rag-combustion",topic:"Spontaneous combustion from oily rags",keywords:["rag","combustion","fire","oil","linseed"],answer:"Crumpled oily finish rags generate heat as they dry and can ignite. Lay flat to dry outdoors or store in a water-filled metal container."},{id:"expanded-safety-first-aid-shop",topic:"Shop first aid basics",keywords:["first","aid","splinter","cut","eye","wash"],answer:"Keep bandages, tweezers, and eye wash accessible. Flush eyes 15 minutes for dust or finish splash — seek medical help for deep cuts or punctures."},{id:"expanded-safety-clothing-loose",topic:"Safe clothing near spinning tools",keywords:["clothing","sleeve","glove","loose","spinning"],answer:"No loose sleeves, dangling cords, or jewelry near rotating tools. Do not wear gloves on table saws or lathes — they catch and pull hands in."},{id:"expanded-safety-focus-rush",topic:"Focus and avoiding rushed cuts",keywords:["focus","rush","distraction","tired","stop"],answer:"Fatigue and distractions cause accidents. If you feel rushed or angry, step away — the project waits; fingers do not grow back."},{id:"expanded-ash-flex-steam",topic:"Ash for steam bending and handles",keywords:["ash","steam","bend","handle","elastic"],answer:"White ash bends well with steam and absorbs shock — ideal for tool handles, ladder rungs, and bent chair parts. Straight grain is essential for strength."},{id:"expanded-birch-paint-plywood",topic:"Birch for paint and plywood cores",keywords:["birch","paint","plywood","even","stable"],answer:"Birch is fine-grained and stable — it paints smoothly and forms the core of many hardwood plywoods. Seal before stain or it blotches."},{id:"expanded-teak-glue-challenge",topic:"Teak gluing and oily surface prep",keywords:["teak","glue","oil","wipe","epoxy"],answer:"Natural oils in teak resist PVA glue. Wipe with acetone immediately before gluing, or use epoxy. Use fresh glue and clamp firmly — do not let the surface re-oil before assembly."},{id:"expanded-mahogany-work-stable",topic:"Mahogany workability for case pieces",keywords:["mahogany","case","stable","carve","classic"],answer:"Mahogany machines cleanly, holds detail, and stays relatively stable — a classic choice for drawers, doors, and raised panels in traditional furniture."},{id:"expanded-cedar-closet-outdoor",topic:"Cedar for closets and outdoor projects",keywords:["cedar","closet","outdoor","rot","aromatic"],answer:"Cedar repels moths and resists decay — line closets and chests with it. It is soft, so use it where dents are acceptable or on exterior projects."},{id:"expanded-self-tapping-screws",topic:"Self-tapping screws in sheet metal and wood",keywords:["self","tapping","thread","sheet","metal"],answer:"Self-tapping screws cut their own threads — common in metal and some composite boards. In solid wood, a pilot hole still prevents splits near edges."},{id:"expanded-hardwood-softwood-meaning",topic:"What hardwood and softwood really mean",keywords:["hardwood","softwood","deciduous","conifer","botanical"],answer:"Hardwood means from broad-leaved trees (oak, maple); softwood from conifers (pine, fir). Balsa is a hardwood but very soft — the names describe botany, not always hardness."},{id:"expanded-contact-cement-laminate",topic:"Laminating with contact cement",keywords:["laminate","counter","contact","press","roll"],answer:"Roll contact cement on both surfaces, wait until dry to the touch, then align and press with a J-roller from the center out to avoid bubbles."},{id:"expanded-toggle-clamp-jigs",topic:"Toggle clamps for jigs and fixtures",keywords:["toggle","clamp","jig","fixture","hold"],answer:"Toggle clamps snap down fast for repetitive jig work — mount on drill press tables and router fences to hold identical parts safely."},{id:"expanded-spiral-upcut-downcut",topic:"Spiral upcut vs downcut router bits",keywords:["spiral","upcut","downcut","chip","blow"],answer:"Upcut bits pull chips up — good for deep grooves but can fray top faces. Downcut bits push chips down for clean top edges on veneer and melamine."},{id:"expanded-dado-stack-table-saw",topic:"Dado stack on the table saw",keywords:["dado","stack","width","chipper","shelf"],answer:"Stack chippers and outer blades to match groove width for shelves and tenons. Use the arbor length rating — never exceed the saw manual limit."},{id:"expanded-forstner-overlap",topic:"Overlapping Forstner holes for mortises",keywords:["forstner","overlap","mortise","drill","clean"],answer:"Drill overlapping Forstner holes, then chisel mortise walls square — faster than mortising by hand for many through mortises in thick stock."},{id:"expanded-zero-clearance-insert",topic:"Zero clearance throat plate",keywords:["zero","clearance","insert","tearout","saw"],answer:"A custom zero-clearance insert supports fibers right at the kerf — less tear-out on crosscuts and splinter-free plywood cuts."},{id:"expanded-crosscut-sled",topic:"Crosscut sled for square ends",keywords:["crosscut","sled","square","miter","fence"],answer:"A shop-made crosscut sled runs in both miter slots for perfectly square ends and safe repeat cuts wider than a miter gauge allows."},{id:"expanded-rip-fence-alignment",topic:"Aligning the table saw rip fence",keywords:["rip","fence","parallel","blade","measure"],answer:"Measure fence to blade front and rear at the same tooth — they should match within a few thousandths. Slight toe-out at the rear reduces binding."},{id:"expanded-chop-saw-stand",topic:"Miter saw stand and material support",keywords:["miter","stand","support","long","stock"],answer:"Support long stock at infeed and outfeed the same height as the saw table — sagging ends bind the blade and ruin cuts."},{id:"expanded-router-edge-guide",topic:"Router edge guide for dados",keywords:["edge","guide","router","dado","parallel"],answer:"An edge guide runs along a straight reference to cut parallel grooves without a table — set offset carefully and make multiple shallow passes."},{id:"expanded-bandsaw-blade-tension",topic:"Band saw blade tension test",keywords:["tension","bandsaw","pluck","flutter","track"],answer:"Tension until the blade resists sideways push about 1/4 inch. Too loose drifts; too tight stresses wheels. Release tension when idle overnight."},{id:"expanded-drill-speed-chart",topic:"Drill press speed by bit size",keywords:["speed","rpm","drill","large","small"],answer:"Large bits need slow speed (hundreds of RPM); small bits can run faster. Burning smell means slow down or sharpen the bit."},{id:"expanded-sander-edges-tip",topic:"Sanding edges without rounding",keywords:["edge","sand","round","block","sharp"],answer:"Use a sanding block backed by cork or rubber to avoid rounding sharp edges. Light pressure on profiles preserves crisp joinery lines."},{id:"expanded-jointer-push-pad",topic:"Push blocks on the jointer",keywords:["jointer","push","block","pad","safety"],answer:"Keep fingers away from the cutterhead with push blocks and pads — never joint narrow stock shorter than the infeed table without a sled."},{id:"expanded-pocket-hole-joinery",topic:"When pocket holes make sense",keywords:["pocket","hole","face","frame","cabinet"],answer:"Pocket holes excel at face frames, shop cabinets, and repairs where speed beats tradition. Hide holes on the inside face away from view."},{id:"expanded-biscuit-alignment",topic:"Biscuits for alignment not structure",keywords:["biscuit","align","panel","edge","glue"],answer:"Biscuits mainly align panel glue-ups — the swollen biscuit adds some strength but alignment is the main win on edge joints."},{id:"expanded-scroll-stack-cutting",topic:"Stack cutting on the scroll saw",keywords:["stack","scroll","tape","identical","pattern"],answer:"Tape identical thin pieces together and cut once — saves time on duplicate brackets and inlay parts. Keep stack height within blade capacity."},{id:"expanded-lathe-faceplate-bowl",topic:"Faceplate turning for bowls",keywords:["faceplate","bowl","lathe","grain","mount"],answer:"Mount bowl blanks on a faceplate with screws into waste wood — grain orientation affects tear-out on the rim. Keep tool rest close for hollowing."},{id:"expanded-track-saw-breakdown",topic:"Track saw for breaking down sheet goods",keywords:["track","sheet","plywood","breakdown","portable"],answer:"A track saw replaces a circular saw and straightedge for breaking down plywood on site — one setup cut for accurate cabinet sides."},{id:"expanded-fein-oscillating",topic:"Oscillating tool flush cuts",keywords:["fein","oscillating","flush","trim","plunge"],answer:"Metal flush-cut blades trim dowels and plugs flush without scratching surrounding finish — gentle pendulum motion, no forcing."},{id:"expanded-framing-nailer",topic:"Framing nailer vs finish nailer",keywords:["framing","nailer","gauge","15","16","18"],answer:"Framing guns shoot large nails for walls; finish guns use 15 or 16 gauge for trim; brad guns use 18 gauge for thin moulding without splitting."},{id:"expanded-cyclone-separator",topic:"Cyclone separator for shop vac",keywords:["cyclone","separator","vac","chip","filter"],answer:"A cyclone drops heavy chips before they reach the filter — keeps suction strong and extends shop vac bag life on router tables and sanders."},{id:"expanded-waterborne-poly-tips",topic:"Water-based poly application tips",keywords:["water","based","poly","raise","grain"],answer:"Water-based poly raises grain more than oil — sand with 220 after first coat. Use synthetic bristle or foam; never shake the can (bubbles)."},{id:"expanded-gel-stain-pine",topic:"Gel stain on pine and softwoods",keywords:["gel","stain","pine","softwood","even"],answer:"Brush gel stain on pine in thin coats — wipe evenly for uniform color without the blotchy patches liquid stain causes on softwood."},{id:"expanded-tung-pure-vs-dark",topic:"Pure tung oil vs tung oil finish products",keywords:["pure","tung","product","dark","poly"],answer:"Read labels — many 'tung oil' products contain varnish and dryers. Pure tung cures slowly but builds a natural water-resistant film over many coats."},{id:"expanded-shellac-flake-mix",topic:"Mixing shellac from flakes",keywords:["shellac","flake","pound","cut","denatured"],answer:"Dissolve shellac flakes in denatured alcohol — a 2-pound cut is versatile. Mix only what you need weekly; shellac spoils in the jar over months."},{id:"expanded-lacquer-retarder",topic:"Lacquer retarder for hot weather",keywords:["lacquer","retarder","blush","humidity","slow"],answer:"Add retarder in humid conditions to slow dry and prevent blushing (white haze). Thin coats beat one heavy wet coat that runs."},{id:"expanded-paste-wax-over-poly",topic:"Paste wax over cured polyurethane",keywords:["paste","wax","poly","buff","sheen"],answer:"After poly has cured a week or more, buff paste wax for a soft sheen and easier dusting — not a substitute for durable top coats on heavy-use tables."},{id:"expanded-artist-pigment-repair",topic:"Artist pigments for color matching",keywords:["pigment","repair","touch","up","toner"],answer:"Mix dry artist pigments into shellac or lacquer for spot repairs on antiques. Build color slowly on a test stick matching the aged surrounding finish."},{id:"expanded-waste-sheet-plywood",topic:"Waste factor for plywood projects",keywords:["waste","plywood","sheet","15","layout"],answer:"Nest parts on paper first — plywood waste is often 10–20% depending on part sizes. Save offcuts for jigs and drawer bottoms."},{id:"expanded-rough-mill-order",topic:"Milling order: rip, joint, plane, crosscut",keywords:["mill","order","rip","joint","plane"],answer:"Rough rip oversize, joint one face and edge, plane to thickness, then crosscut to final length. This order minimizes twist and snipe."},{id:"expanded-pencil-gauge-line",topic:"Gauge line vs pencil for dovetails",keywords:["gauge","pencil","dovetail","baseline","knife"],answer:"Knife the baseline at the tail and pin roots — a pencil line is too thick and lets tails shift when chopping."},{id:"expanded-reveal-overlay-doors",topic:"Overlay vs inset door reveals",keywords:["overlay","inset","reveal","door","cabinet"],answer:"Full overlay doors cover most of the face frame with minimal reveal. Inset doors sit flush inside the opening with even gaps all around — harder to build, classic look."},{id:"expanded-toe-kick-design",topic:"Toe kick height and recess",keywords:["toe","kick","base","cabinet","recess"],answer:"Standard toe kick is about 4 inches high and 3 inches deep — allows feet under cabinets while hiding the base structure."},{id:"expanded-crown-miter-spring",topic:"Crown moulding spring angle",keywords:["crown","spring","angle","miter","compound"],answer:"Crown sits at a spring angle against the wall and ceiling — use compound miter settings or a jig rather than plain 45° on flat."},{id:"expanded-wood-filler-vs-dowel",topic:"Structural repair vs wood filler",keywords:["filler","structural","dowel","patch","glue"],answer:"Filler is cosmetic only — structural gaps need a glued wood patch or dutchman. Do not rely on filler to carry load or hold screws."}],a=[{id:"ma-ash-grain-pattern",topic:"Ash grain pattern and figure",keywords:["ash","grain","figure","olive","wavy","sports","tool","handle"],answer:"Ash has a bold open grain similar to oak but with a lighter, cream color. Straight-grained ash is preferred for tool handles because the fibers absorb shock. Olive ash has dark brown heartwood streaks that make it a premium figured wood for furniture. The wide growth rings make ash excellent for steam bending into curved chair parts."},{id:"ma-walnut-regional",topic:"American black walnut regional variation",keywords:["walnut","black","american","region","color","light","dark","appalachian"],answer:"American black walnut varies dramatically by region — Appalachian trees often produce darker, richer heartwood, while Midwest and West Coast trees can be lighter brown. Trees grown in the open tend to have more figured grain than forest-grown straight-grained trees. Color also varies within a single log, with outer sapwood being cream to tan while heartwood ranges from chocolate to purple-brown."},{id:"ma-walnut-sapwood",topic:"Using walnut sapwood in furniture",keywords:["walnut","sapwood","cream","heartwood","contrast","steamed"],answer:"Walnut sapwood is pale cream and is often cut away, but some designers use the sapwood-to-heartwood contrast as a design element. Commercially, walnut logs are often steamed to darken the sapwood closer to heartwood color. If you want uniform color, steam-dried walnut is the way to go; if you want contrast, air-dried unsteamed boards show the full range."},{id:"ma-cherry-blotch",topic:"Cherry blotching with stain",keywords:["cherry","blotch","stain","conditioner","pre-stain","uneven"],answer:"Cherry blotches badly with oil-based stains because its pores are very fine and absorb unevenly. A pre-stain wood conditioner (or a thin wash coat of shellac) seals the surface evenly before stain. Many woodworkers skip stain entirely on cherry — the natural color deepens beautifully with just an oil or clear varnish finish and UV exposure over months."},{id:"ma-curly-maple",topic:"Curly maple figure and how it forms",keywords:["curly","maple","figure","tiger","fiddleback","chatoyance","wave"],answer:"Curly maple (also called tiger maple or fiddleback maple) has wavy grain that creates a 3D chatoyance — it appears to ripple as you change viewing angle. The curls are caused by undulating wood fibers, possibly from wind stress or genetic factors. It machines fine but is prone to tearout, so take light passes and plane from multiple directions. The figure is most visible under a clear or light tinted finish — heavy stains mask it."},{id:"ma-birdseye-maple",topic:"Birdseye maple rarity and working",keywords:["birdseye","maple","eyes","figure","rare","turning"],answer:`Birdseye maple has small circular "eyes" scattered throughout the face grain, caused by dormant buds that never fully developed. It's not a separate species — it occurs in sugar maple, occasionally soft maple. The eyes are only visible on the flatsawn face; quartersawn birdseye loses the pattern. It planes well but the tiny eyes can pop out with aggressive cuts — use sharp tools and light passes.`},{id:"ma-quartersawn-oak-ray",topic:"Quartersawn oak ray fleck appearance",keywords:["quartersawn","oak","ray","fleck","medullary","silver","figure"],answer:'Quartersawn oak exposes the medullary rays as broad, lustrous silver or tan flecks on the face — this is the "silver grain" prized in Arts & Crafts furniture. The rays run perpendicular to the annual rings; quartersawing cuts across them to expose their full width. Ray fleck size varies — white oak has larger, more dramatic rays than red oak. Quartersawn oak also moves less across its width, making it more dimensionally stable for tabletops and doors.'},{id:"ma-riftsawn-legs",topic:"Riftsawn lumber for table and chair legs",keywords:["riftsawn","rift","leg","vertical","straight","consistent","grain"],answer:"Rift-sawn boards are cut at roughly 30–60° to the annual rings, producing straight, consistent grain lines on all four faces with no ray fleck. This makes rift-sawn stock ideal for table legs and chair legs where you want grain to look the same on every visible face. It's the most wasteful cutting method and therefore the most expensive, but the visual result on legged furniture is unmatched."},{id:"ma-flatsawn-cathedral",topic:"Flatsawn cathedral grain appearance",keywords:["flatsawn","cathedral","arch","grain","plain","sawn","most","common"],answer:"Flatsawn (also called plain-sawn) lumber shows the classic cathedral arch grain patterns on the face — the annual rings curve across the width. It's the most common and economical cut because it yields the widest boards from a log. Flatsawn boards move more in width than quartersawn and are more prone to cupping, but the bold figure is desirable for tabletops and case sides."},{id:"ma-ambrosia-maple",topic:"Ambrosia maple coloring and working",keywords:["ambrosia","maple","beetle","worm","track","streaks","character"],answer:"Ambrosia maple is soft maple with gray-brown streaks and tracks caused by the ambrosia beetle, which bores through the log and introduces a fungus that stains the wood. The result is character figure prized by modern rustic designers. The wood itself is structurally sound — the staining doesn't compromise strength. It finishes beautifully with a clear finish, and the streaks look striking with an oil or hardwax-oil finish."},{id:"ma-spalted-wood",topic:"Spalted wood — beauty and caution",keywords:["spalted","zone","line","fungus","rot","stabilize","safety"],answer:"Spalted wood has dark zone lines and color patches caused by competing fungi staining the wood fibers. The lines and patterns are unique to each piece. Working spalted wood requires care — advanced spalting means the wood is partially rotted and crumbly, making it dangerous to turn or mill. Mildly spalted wood is fine; heavily punky areas should be stabilized with penetrating epoxy before machining. Always wear a P100 respirator — spalted wood dust contains live fungal spores."},{id:"ma-live-edge",topic:"Working with live edge slabs",keywords:["live","edge","slab","bark","natural","wane","flatten"],answer:"Live edge slabs retain the natural edge of the tree, sometimes including bark. Before finishing, decide whether to remove the bark (it often falls off eventually) and clean out the cambium layer underneath. Flatten wide slabs with a router sled or a wide drum sander before surfacing — hand planes alone aren't practical on large slabs. Seal the live edges heavily with finish to prevent checking from uneven moisture exchange."},{id:"ma-crotch-figure",topic:"Crotch figure in wood",keywords:["crotch","figure","feather","plume","cathedral","premium","veneer"],answer:"Crotch figure comes from the junction where a trunk splits into two major branches — the wood fibers swirl in dramatic plume or feather patterns. Crotch wood is almost always sold as veneer because the sections are small and the grain is so wild it can't be planed without tearing. It makes spectacular tabletop centers and door panels. Expect to pay a premium — good crotch veneer is expensive and in limited supply."},{id:"ma-purpleheart",topic:"Purpleheart color, stability, and working",keywords:["purpleheart","purple","tropical","color","fade","turning","hard"],answer:"Purpleheart starts as a gray-brown when freshly cut and turns vivid purple within hours of air and light exposure. Over years of UV exposure, it fades to brown — protect it with a UV-resistant finish. It's extremely hard (Janka ~1860) and very stable, making it excellent for cutting boards, furniture accents, and tool handles. It's resinous and can be tough on saw blades; sharp carbide is essential. It glues well once the surface oils are removed with acetone."},{id:"ma-padauk-color",topic:"Padauk color change over time",keywords:["padauk","red","orange","fade","brown","uv","finish","protect"],answer:"Padauk is a vivid red-orange when freshly cut — one of the most striking colors in woodworking. Like purpleheart, it fades significantly with UV exposure and will turn a deep brick-red to brown-red over years. A UV-filtering varnish or oil slows the fade but can't stop it entirely. It's moderately hard, machines well, and glues well if you wipe the surface with acetone before applying glue to remove surface oils."},{id:"ma-wenge",topic:"Wenge characteristics and safety",keywords:["wenge","splinter","pore","fill","black","stripe","pain","grain"],answer:"Wenge is a dark brown/black African hardwood with coarse, open grain and dramatic dark streaks. It's very hard and produces vicious splinters — always wear gloves when handling rough stock. The large pores need grain filler before applying film finishes; without it, the finish sinks into the pores and looks blotchy. Its bold grain makes it striking as a design accent, though it's challenging to work by hand."},{id:"ma-bloodwood",topic:"Bloodwood color and stability",keywords:["bloodwood","red","bright","stable","accent","turning","hard"],answer:"Bloodwood is a deep scarlet red tropical hardwood from South America — similar to padauk in color but more stable with less color fading. It's very dense and hard, takes a high natural polish, and is popular for turning, inlay, and furniture accents. The dust can irritate skin and respiratory system; wear a respirator. It glues well and accepts finishes without the oil-removal step needed for teak or padauk."},{id:"ma-sapele",topic:"Sapele ribbon stripe figure",keywords:["sapele","ribbon","stripe","interlocked","grain","mahogany","substitute"],answer:"Sapele is an African hardwood often used as a mahogany substitute, with a rich reddish-brown color and pronounced ribbon stripe figure on quartersawn faces. The interlocked grain produces the ribbon effect but also causes tearout when planing — always plane with a sharp, finely set blade. It's a great choice for door panels, cabinet faces, and veneered surfaces where you want mahogany-like figure at a lower cost."},{id:"ma-african-vs-genuine-mahogany",topic:"African mahogany vs genuine (Honduran) mahogany",keywords:["mahogany","african","honduran","genuine","khaya","swietenia","compare"],answer:"Genuine (Honduran) mahogany (Swietenia macrophylla) is CITES-listed and rare — expect to pay a premium. African mahogany (Khaya) is widely available, similar in color and workability, but with more interlocked grain that can cause tearout. Genuine mahogany has finer, straighter grain and a more even pore structure. Both finish beautifully with oil or varnish and are excellent furniture woods. For most shop work, African mahogany is the practical choice."},{id:"ma-redwood-outdoor",topic:"Redwood for outdoor furniture and decking",keywords:["redwood","outdoor","rot","resistant","deck","fence","tannin","straight"],answer:`Redwood contains natural tannins and oils that resist rot, insects, and weathering, making it ideal for outdoor furniture, decking, and garden structures. It's lightweight and easy to work with hand tools. The straight grain means minimal warping and splitting. Use stainless or hot-dipped galvanized fasteners — redwood tannins react with regular steel and leave black stains. Heartwood is far more resistant than sapwood; look for "all-heart" grades for outdoor use.`},{id:"ma-douglas-fir",topic:"Douglas fir for structural and decorative work",keywords:["douglas","fir","structural","beam","strong","hard","softwood","span"],answer:"Douglas fir is one of North America's strongest softwoods — commonly used in structural applications like beams, joists, and house framing. Clear vertical-grain Douglas fir is beautiful for furniture, showing tight, straight grain lines. It's harder and stiffer than most pines, and heavy enough that large pieces are physically demanding to handle. Finishing is easy, though the resin channels need attention on stained work — wiping with naphtha before staining helps."},{id:"ma-eastern-cedar",topic:"Eastern red cedar aromatic properties",keywords:["eastern","red","cedar","aromatic","closet","moth","chest","aroma","lining"],answer:"Eastern red cedar has a distinctive aromatic smell from natural oils that repel moths and insects, making it the traditional choice for cedar chests and closet linings. The oils diminish over years, but lightly sanding the surface revives the aroma. It's soft, which means it dents easily in furniture applications — use it as a liner, not a structural member. The purple-red heartwood with white sapwood makes beautiful contrasting panels."},{id:"ma-butternut",topic:"Butternut wood characteristics",keywords:["butternut","white","walnut","soft","carve","light","grain"],answer:"Butternut (also called white walnut) is a soft hardwood with open grain similar to black walnut but much lighter in weight and color — a warm tan-brown. It carves beautifully and is one of the best carving woods in North America. It's too soft for furniture tops or high-wear surfaces but excellent for carved panels, drawer fronts, and accent pieces. Butternut is susceptible to butternut canker disease, making large clear logs increasingly rare."},{id:"ma-black-locust",topic:"Black locust hardness and rot resistance",keywords:["black","locust","hard","dense","rot","outdoor","yellow","heavy"],answer:"Black locust is one of North America's hardest and most rot-resistant hardwoods — it outlasts redwood and cedar in ground contact and was historically used for fence posts and ship pegs. The yellow-green heartwood is extremely dense (Janka ~1700) and difficult to machine. It's underappreciated in furniture work; the color mellows to a warm tan and the wood machines to a fine surface. Smaller diameters make wide clear boards rare and expensive."},{id:"ma-sycamore",topic:"Sycamore lacy figure",keywords:["sycamore","lacewood","lace","ray","figure","interior","interlocked"],answer:`American sycamore has prominent medullary rays that, when quartersawn, produce a "lacewood" pattern similar to Australian lacewood. The rays appear as light tan patches against a pinkish-brown background. It's prone to interlocked grain and can be challenging to plane cleanly, but produces a beautiful turned bowl or veneered panel. It was historically used for butcher blocks because it doesn't split from the end grain impacts of chopping.`},{id:"ma-elm-interlocked",topic:"Elm and its interlocked grain challenge",keywords:["elm","interlocked","grain","tough","crack","bend","chairleg","burl"],answer:"American elm has severely interlocked, cross-grain structure that makes it nearly impossible to split — which is why it was the traditional choice for wagon wheels, wheel hubs, and chair seats that needed to resist splitting. This same interlocked grain makes planing extremely difficult, with tearout in multiple directions. Elm burls are prized for turning and veneered panels. Dutch elm disease has made large clear elm rare; reclaimed elm from old buildings is a good source."},{id:"ma-osage-orange",topic:"Osage orange hardness and rot resistance",keywords:["osage","orange","hedge","apple","hardest","bow","yellow","dense"],answer:"Osage orange (hedge apple or bodark) is one of North America's hardest and most decay-resistant woods — fence posts can last 50+ years in the ground. The heartwood is bright yellow and oxidizes to golden-brown. It was the premier wood for Native American bows. It's so dense and hard that it dulls tools quickly and can be dangerous to machine — secure work carefully, use carbide, and expect to sharpen often."},{id:"ma-ipe-decking",topic:"Ipe for decking and outdoor structures",keywords:["ipe","decking","hardwood","tropical","dense","oil","finish","pre-drill"],answer:"Ipe (Brazilian walnut) is one of the densest commercial lumbers available — it sinks in water. It's exceptionally rot-resistant and holds up for 25+ years as decking without treatment. Its density means you must pre-drill every fastener hole to prevent splitting and burning screws. It's too oily for most glues and films — use penetrating oil finishes only. The dark brown color fades to silver-gray without maintenance, which many designers prefer."},{id:"ma-sitka-spruce",topic:"Sitka spruce for musical instruments",keywords:["sitka","spruce","guitar","top","resonance","stiffness","weight","ratio"],answer:"Sitka spruce has the highest stiffness-to-weight ratio of any commercial wood, making it the standard for guitar soundboards, violin tops, and other instrument tops. Quarter-sawn Sitka with tight, straight grain and minimal runout is preferred — it transmits vibration efficiently. The same properties make it useful for airplane spars historically. For furniture, it's rarely used due to its softness, but as an acoustic material it's unrivaled."},{id:"ma-longleaf-pine",topic:"Longleaf pine reclaimed and new growth",keywords:["longleaf","pine","heart","virgin","reclaimed","dense","resin","old","growth"],answer:"Old-growth longleaf pine is one of the hardest pines — the centuries-old trees grew slowly and have dense, resin-saturated heartwood far harder than modern plantation pine. Much of it is now reclaimed from old warehouses and factories. New-growth longleaf is being reforested and is available from sustainable sources, though it lacks the density of old-growth. The golden-orange heart pine takes a beautiful finish and holds fasteners extremely well."},{id:"ma-alder",topic:"Alder for cabinets and staining",keywords:["alder","west","coast","cabinet","paint","stain","fine","grain","inexpensive"],answer:"Red alder is the primary commercial hardwood of the Pacific Northwest — inexpensive, light, with fine uniform grain that accepts stain very evenly, making it popular for kitchen cabinets. It's softer than maple or oak (Janka ~590) so it dents more easily, but it machines beautifully and has minimal blotching compared to pine or cherry. It's an excellent paint-grade wood and one of the best choices for stained cabinetry at a budget price."},{id:"ma-janka-hardness",topic:"Janka hardness scale explained",keywords:["janka","hardness","scale","rating","comparison","pound","ball","test"],answer:"The Janka hardness test measures the force in pounds-force (lbf) needed to embed a steel ball halfway into the wood surface. Common reference points: balsa is around 100, pine 380–870, red oak 1290, hard maple 1450, hickory 1820, Brazilian walnut 3684. Higher numbers mean more dent resistance for flooring and tabletops, but also more tool wear and harder machining. Janka numbers help compare species objectively when choosing material for a project."},{id:"ma-ring-porous",topic:"Ring-porous vs diffuse-porous wood",keywords:["ring","porous","diffuse","oak","maple","pore","grain","stain"],answer:"Ring-porous woods (oak, ash, elm, hickory) have large pores concentrated in the early wood (spring growth), creating bold, open grain. Diffuse-porous woods (maple, cherry, birch, walnut) have small pores evenly distributed, creating finer, more uniform grain. Ring-porous woods show strong grain patterns under stain; diffuse-porous woods stain more evenly. Knowing the type helps predict how a species will take finish and how visible the grain will be."},{id:"ma-tannin-effects",topic:"Tannin content and its effects on finishing",keywords:["tannin","oak","walnut","iron","stain","black","chemical","react"],answer:"High-tannin woods (oak, walnut, chestnut, mahogany) react chemically with iron and steel, causing black stains at fastener locations and wherever water carries dissolved iron. Always use stainless or hot-dipped galvanized fasteners in tannin-rich woods. Tannins also interfere with certain adhesives and can bleed through water-based finishes, causing discoloration. Seal high-tannin wood with shellac before applying water-based topcoats."},{id:"ma-silica-tropical",topic:"Silica in tropical hardwoods dulling tools",keywords:["silica","teak","ipe","tropical","dull","carbide","blade","edge"],answer:"Many tropical hardwoods — teak, ipe, iroko, afrormosia — contain silica deposits that rapidly dull steel and even carbide cutting tools. You'll notice blades that dull in minutes rather than hours. Use carbide-tipped tools and expect to sharpen or replace blades more often. A blade dulled on silica-rich wood will often feel sharp by touch but cut poorly — the silica abrades the microscopic cutting edge rather than chipping it visibly."},{id:"ma-baltic-birch",topic:"Baltic birch plywood in depth",keywords:["baltic","birch","void","ply","cabinet","drawer","shop","grade","russia","finland"],answer:"Baltic birch plywood comes from Russia and Finland and is manufactured with thin, void-free birch plies throughout — unlike domestic plywood which may have softwood inner plies and voids. It's available in 5x5 sheets (1525×1525mm) and comes in metric thicknesses (6mm, 12mm, 18mm). It's the best choice for drawer boxes, cabinet carcases, and jig-making. The edge grain has a beautiful stacked-ply appearance that many woodworkers leave exposed rather than banding."},{id:"ma-mdo-plywood",topic:"MDO plywood for painting and signs",keywords:["mdo","medium","density","overlay","paint","sign","smooth","exterior"],answer:"MDO (Medium Density Overlay) plywood has a resin-fiber surface bonded to each face, creating an extremely smooth, paint-ready surface. It's designed for exterior signs, concrete forms, and painted panels. Unlike MDF, MDO has a structural plywood core so it holds fasteners and handles moisture better. If you need a perfectly smooth painted surface that resists moisture, MDO is superior to MDF for cabinets going in humid environments."},{id:"ma-melamine-board",topic:"Melamine coated board for cabinet interiors",keywords:["melamine","coated","board","particleboard","interior","white","cabinet","shelf"],answer:"Melamine board is particleboard or MDF with a melamine resin film laminated to the surface. It comes in white, colors, and wood-grain prints. It's the standard for modern cabinet interiors — the surface is easy to clean, doesn't need finishing, and resists most household chemicals. Cut it with a fine-tooth saw blade to minimize chip-out on the laminate surface. The particleboard core doesn't hold fasteners as well as plywood — use knock-down hardware designed for it."},{id:"ma-bending-plywood",topic:"Bending plywood for curved work",keywords:["bending","plywood","kerfed","flexible","curve","form","bend","radius"],answer:"Flexible bending plywood (also called wiggle board or flexply) has thin plies all running in one direction, allowing it to bend easily across the grain direction. It comes in two orientations — bends lengthwise or widthwise. Stack two layers with opposing grain directions and glue over a form to make a rigid curved panel. It's ideal for curved cabinet doors, reception desks, and curved stair risers."},{id:"ma-phenolic-plywood",topic:"Phenolic (dark brown) plywood for jigs",keywords:["phenolic","dark","brown","slippery","jig","template","flat","smooth"],answer:"Phenolic plywood has a dark brown resin overlay that makes the surface extremely hard, flat, and slippery. It's a favorite for router table tops, jig bases, and shooting boards because workpieces slide smoothly across it. It's also very flat and dimensionally stable. The surface dulls router bits faster than MDF but holds up to heavy use without wearing. It comes in 4x8 sheets and is available from industrial lumber suppliers."},{id:"ma-hardboard",topic:"Hardboard (Masonite) uses in the shop",keywords:["hardboard","masonite","thin","panel","back","template","drawer","bottom"],answer:`Hardboard is dense pressed wood fiber panel, sold as 1/8" or 1/4" sheets. Tempered hardboard has oil added and is harder and slightly water-resistant. Common uses: cabinet backs, drawer bottoms, templates for routing, dust panels on chair frames, and covering workbench tops for a smooth sacrificial surface. It's cheap but doesn't hold fasteners well — rely on dado grooves or construction adhesive to secure it in place.`},{id:"ma-cost-tiers-domestic",topic:"Cost tiers for domestic hardwoods",keywords:["cost","price","expensive","cheap","domestic","hardwood","budget","value"],answer:"Budget tier: poplar, soft maple, alder — $3–5 per BF. Mid-tier: red oak, ash, birch, hard maple — $5–8 per BF. Premium domestic: walnut, cherry, white oak — $8–15 per BF. Figured wood (curly, birdseye, quilted) commands double to triple the figure-grade premium on top of the base price. Prices vary significantly by region and yard — walnut is cheaper in the Midwest where it's local, and oak is cheaper in the East."},{id:"ma-cost-tiers-exotics",topic:"Cost tiers for exotic hardwoods",keywords:["exotic","tropical","cost","price","expensive","teak","ebony","per","board","foot"],answer:"Entry-level exotics: sapele, sipo, okoume, meranti — similar prices to mid-tier domestics. Mid-tier exotics: mahogany, teak, purpleheart, padauk — $10–20 per BF. Premium exotics: bubinga, wenge, bocote, ziricote — $20–40 per BF. Ultra-premium: ebony, cocobolo, lignum vitae — $40–100+ per BF and often only available in small sizes. CITES restrictions on certain species (rosewood, ebony) affect availability and legal import status."},{id:"ma-wood-movement-rates",topic:"Wood movement rates by species comparison",keywords:["movement","seasonal","shrinkage","radial","tangential","rate","species","compare"],answer:"Wood moves tangentially (parallel to rings) about twice as much as radially (perpendicular to rings). Quartersawn is more stable because the wood is cut radially. High-movement species: beech, sycamore, red oak. Medium movement: hard maple, cherry, walnut, white oak. Low movement: teak, mahogany, quartersawn white oak. The ratio of tangential to radial shrinkage also affects whether wood cups — low ratios (close to 1:1) are more stable like mahogany; high ratios (2:1+) like beech tend to cup more."},{id:"ma-equilibrium-moisture",topic:"Equilibrium moisture content (EMC) and wood movement",keywords:["emc","equilibrium","moisture","content","humidity","rh","target","indoor"],answer:"Wood naturally adjusts its moisture content to balance with the surrounding relative humidity — this is its equilibrium moisture content (EMC). At 40-50% RH (typical heated home), EMC is around 7-9%. At 70% RH (garage in summer), EMC is around 13-15%. Wood needs to be at its EMC for its final environment before you build — if you install furniture at 15% MC in a 8% MC home, it will shrink and crack. Use a moisture meter and acclimate lumber for weeks in the shop before milling."},{id:"ma-wood-toxicity",topic:"Wood dust toxicity and allergens by species",keywords:["toxicity","allergen","dust","sensitize","poison","reaction","species","health"],answer:'Some woods cause sensitization — repeated exposure creates allergic reactions that worsen over time. High-risk: cocobolo, rosewood, mahogany, teak, ebony, Western red cedar. Medium risk: walnut (contains juglone), oak, pine (resinous). Even "safe" species cause irritation with fine dust. Always wear a P100 half-face respirator for exotic woods, not just an N95. Once sensitized, even small exposures can trigger reactions. Keep your shop vacuumed and use dust collection at the source.'},{id:"ma-bookmatch",topic:"Bookmatching panels for symmetry",keywords:["bookmatch","book","match","sequential","veneer","panel","symmetric","mirror"],answer:"Bookmatching means opening two consecutive slices from the same log like pages of a book — the grain mirrors symmetrically across the joint. It creates a dramatic butterfly pattern on figured wood. For solid wood, use consecutive boards from the same log and orient them grain-side-down together, then flip one open. Glue the joint with careful alignment. Bookmatch panels are striking on cabinet doors, tabletops, and speaker cabinets."},{id:"ma-veneer-application",topic:"Applying veneer with contact cement or PVA",keywords:["veneer","contact","cement","pva","glue","roller","substrate","iron","bag"],answer:"Contact cement gives an instant bond — apply to both surfaces, let dry, then press together (no repositioning). PVA with vacuum press or cauls gives more control — apply to substrate only, then place veneer, press firmly, and clamp for 30 minutes to several hours. A household iron with a damp cloth can activate hide glue on pre-glued veneer. Keep veneer flat by humidifying slightly if it's curled — pressing curled veneer risks it cracking or telegraphing through."},{id:"ma-rotary-vs-sliced-veneer",topic:"Rotary-cut vs sliced veneer differences",keywords:["rotary","sliced","veneer","cut","lathe","peel","figure","match"],answer:"Rotary-cut veneer peels around a spinning log like unrolling a roll of paper — it produces wide sheets with wild grain patterns, used mainly for plywood face veneers. Flat-sliced veneer is sliced like salami from a half log, producing sheets that show the true grain figure. Quartersawn-sliced gives ribbon stripe on appropriate species. For matching and bookmatching decorative panels, always specify flat-sliced or quartersawn-sliced veneer — rotary-cut won't match."},{id:"ma-humidity-shop-control",topic:"Controlling humidity in the shop for lumber storage",keywords:["humidity","shop","control","dehumidifier","storage","acclimate","rh","wood"],answer:"Ideally store and work lumber at the humidity of the room it's destined for — typically 35–55% RH for interior furniture. In humid climates, use a dehumidifier in summer; in dry climates, add a humidifier in winter. Sticker-stack lumber with small wood strips between layers to allow air circulation. Never store lumber on a concrete floor — wick moisture up from below. A $30 digital hygrometer lets you monitor shop RH and catch humidity swings before they warp your lumber."},{id:"ma-bluestain-pine",topic:"Bluestain fungus in pine lumber",keywords:["bluestain","blue","stain","fungus","pine","discolor","structural","beetle"],answer:"Bluestain (sap stain) is a fungal discoloration in pine sapwood — it appears as blue-gray streaking and is introduced by bark beetles. It's purely cosmetic; bluestained pine is structurally identical to unstained pine. For painted or rustic work it doesn't matter at all. For natural or stained work, bluestain will show through clear finishes. Many designers embrace it as a character feature, especially in reclaimed or beetle-kill pine."},{id:"ma-mineral-streaks",topic:"Mineral streaks in cherry and other hardwoods",keywords:["mineral","streak","cherry","walnut","gray","discolor","stain","natural"],answer:"Mineral streaks are gray, dark green, or dark brown discolorations in wood caused by mineral deposits absorbed during tree growth. Common in cherry, hard maple, and soft maple. They're natural — not decay or defect — but some buyers consider them downgrade. Under a clear finish they're often an interesting feature; under stain they may read differently than the surrounding wood. Avoid selecting boards with mineral streaks if you need consistent stain color."},{id:"ma-through-dovetail-detail",topic:"Through dovetail proportions and layout",keywords:["through","dovetail","tail","pin","ratio","layout","proportion","angle"],answer:"Through dovetails are fully visible from both faces — the tails on one board interlock with pins on the other. The traditional ratio is 1:6 for hardwoods (less angle) and 1:8 for softwoods (more angle). Lay out tails first, then use them to scribe the pins directly — never trust transferred measurements. Half-pins at the ends are essential to close the corners neatly. The joint's mechanical resistance to pulling apart comes from the trapezoidal tail shape, not the glue."},{id:"ma-half-blind-dovetail",topic:"Half-blind dovetails for drawer fronts",keywords:["half","blind","dovetail","drawer","front","hidden","concealed","rabbet"],answer:'Half-blind dovetails conceal the joint from the front face while remaining visible from the side — the classic choice for drawer fronts. The tails stop short of the front face by about 1/8"–1/4", leaving a thin wall that hides the joint. This thin wall is the most delicate part to chop — work from both the side and the face, never taking out too much at once. The joint is significantly more challenging to cut by hand than a through dovetail.'},{id:"ma-full-blind-dovetail",topic:"Full-blind (secret mitered) dovetail",keywords:["full","blind","mitered","secret","dovetail","invisible","box","corner"],answer:"The secret mitered dovetail hides both faces behind a mitered corner — from outside the box you see only a clean miter; inside, the dovetail structure is visible. It's one of the most difficult joints in hand woodworking. The miter must be cut after the dovetails are fitted, and the mitered sections need to align perfectly. It's used in fine boxes and cabinets where even the inside joint matters aesthetically."},{id:"ma-sliding-dovetail-detail",topic:"Sliding dovetail joint setup and fit",keywords:["sliding","dovetail","shelf","divider","fit","sneak","snug","router"],answer:"A sliding dovetail has a trapezoidal tenon that slides into a matching groove — used for attaching shelves, dividers, or breadboards. The fit must be snug but not so tight the joint seizes. Cut the groove first, then sneak up on the tenon size in test cuts until it slides with light hand pressure. A tiny amount of wax on the tenon eases assembly. Glue only the first inch or two to allow seasonal movement on wide panels."},{id:"ma-mortise-tenon-proportions",topic:"Mortise and tenon proportioning rules",keywords:["mortise","tenon","proportion","rule","third","thickness","width","length"],answer:`The classic rule: tenon thickness is one-third the stock thickness. Tenon width is no more than five times its thickness to limit racking. Tenon length should be at least 2/3 of the mortised member's width — a stub tenon less than 1" long has little mechanical strength. For a 3/4" thick rail, the tenon is 1/4" thick. For a 4" wide rail, use twin tenons rather than one very wide tenon to manage wood movement.`},{id:"ma-haunched-tenon",topic:"Haunched tenon for panel grooves",keywords:["haunched","tenon","haunch","groove","panel","door","frame","fill"],answer:"A haunched tenon has a notched shoulder — the haunch fills the groove that runs through the stile for the floating panel. Without the haunch, an ugly gap would appear at the top or bottom rail where the groove extends past the tenon. The haunch is typically square (full thickness of the tenon) and fills the groove depth exactly. This is the standard joint for frame-and-panel doors where the groove is run on the router table before assembly."},{id:"ma-wedged-tenon",topic:"Wedged through tenon for permanent joints",keywords:["wedged","tenon","kerf","fox","wedge","through","permanent","splay"],answer:"A wedged through tenon has kerfs sawn in the end of the tenon; after assembly, wedges are driven in to splay the tenon and lock it permanently in the mortise. Fox-wedging does this blind — the wedges compress as the tenon seats, with no way to disassemble without breaking it. Straight wedging in a through tenon creates a visible decorative detail on the outside face. The angle of the wedge should match the splay it creates in the mortise walls."},{id:"ma-drawbore-detail",topic:"Drawbore technique for tight mortise and tenon",keywords:["drawbore","draw","bore","offset","pin","peg","pull","tight","clampless"],answer:'Drawboring pulls a loose mortise and tenon joint tight using a misaligned peg hole. Drill through the mortise walls first, assemble dry, then mark and drill the tenon hole offset 1/16" toward the shoulder. Drive a tapered wooden peg (often dry oak) through — the offset forces the tenon to draw tight against the shoulder. The joint assembles without clamps and is permanently locked. Traditional timber framing uses drawbored joints throughout for this reason.'},{id:"ma-bridle-joint-detail",topic:"Bridle joint for T and corner connections",keywords:["bridle","joint","T","corner","mortise","open","slotted","gate","frame"],answer:"The bridle joint (open mortise and tenon) has a slot cut into one member and a fork on the other — the fork wraps around the slotted member. It's faster to cut than a traditional mortise and tenon and very strong in bending. It's the go-to joint for frame corners, gate corners, and T-connections on garden furniture. Cut the slot with a tenon saw and chisel, then use the slot to scribe the fork shoulders for a perfect fit."},{id:"ma-finger-joint-jig",topic:"Box joint jig for the table saw",keywords:["box","finger","joint","jig","table","saw","router","spacing","consistent"],answer:"A box joint jig indexes the workpiece by one finger width per cut, producing perfectly spaced interlocking fingers. The jig has a key the same width as the cut — after each pass, you move the board over by resting the last slot against the key. The key-to-blade distance must equal one finger width exactly. Make a few test cuts in scrap to dial in the spacing before cutting good material. The fit should be snug but not forced — about the same feel as a good drawer fit."},{id:"ma-scarf-joint-types",topic:"Scarf joint types and angle requirements",keywords:["scarf","joint","angle","length","splice","long","grain","tension","compression"],answer:"A scarf joint splices two boards end-to-end. A plain glued scarf needs a slope ratio of at least 1:8 (ideally 1:12) to have enough long-grain glue area for good strength. Mechanical scarfs add wedges, keys, or bolts for structural applications like timber frames. A fished scarf uses side plates on both faces bolted through. For furniture stretchers, a simple 1:10 glued scarf is invisible and nearly as strong as a single piece if the grain is perfectly parallel."},{id:"ma-lap-joint-types",topic:"Lap joint variations for frames and boxes",keywords:["lap","joint","half","cross","corner","middle","dado","rabbet"],answer:"Lap joints overlap two pieces with half the thickness removed from each — they're fast and strong enough for many applications. Corner lap (end lap) works for box corners. Cross lap joins two pieces crossing at any point. Middle lap connects a rail to the middle of another rail. The dado and rabbet are essentially specialized laps. Lap joints have more long-grain glue area than a butt joint but less mechanical resistance than a mortise and tenon under racking loads."},{id:"ma-biscuit-sizes",topic:"Biscuit joiner slot sizes and uses",keywords:["biscuit","joiner","plate","size","0","10","20","align","strength"],answer:'Biscuit joiners cut football-shaped slots for compressed beech biscuits that swell when glue contacts them. Size 0 is the smallest — for narrow stock 1/2"–3/4". Size 10 is medium — standard for most 3/4" panels. Size 20 is large — for thicker stock and frames. Biscuits are primarily alignment aids in furniture work; they add little structural strength in face grain. They do a better job in edge-to-face joints like shelf dadoes. Space them every 6–8" on long glue-ups.'},{id:"ma-domino-vs-biscuit",topic:"Festool Domino vs biscuit joiner comparison",keywords:["domino","festool","biscuit","compare","strength","loose","tight","tenon","mortise"],answer:"The Domino creates a floating mortise and oval tenon using a plunging oscillating bit — much stronger than a biscuit. Dominoes come in loose and tight tenon lengths; loose allows panel movement, tight locks the joint. The Domino is faster and more precise than a traditional mortise and tenon for frame work. The machine itself costs 5–10 times more than a biscuit joiner. For most hobby shops, a biscuit joiner plus pocket screws covers 90% of Domino use cases at a fraction of the cost."},{id:"ma-pocket-hole-engineering",topic:"Pocket hole joint engineering and limits",keywords:["pocket","hole","strength","limit","shear","tension","screw","kreg"],answer:`Pocket hole joints excel at face-frame assembly, carcass backs, and table apron-to-leg connections. They're strong in shear (face frame connections, drawer assembly) but weak in tension (face-pulling loads). Never rely on pocket screws alone for chair joints — they'll pull loose under repeated stress. The screws need to engage enough material — a 3/4" board needs a longer screw than the standard setup; consult the pocket hole manufacturer's chart. Clamp the joint while driving screws to prevent offset.`},{id:"ma-cam-lock-hardware",topic:"Cam lock (confirmat) knock-down hardware",keywords:["cam","lock","confirmat","knock","down","flat","pack","rta","euronut","barrel"],answer:"Knock-down cam lock connectors let furniture be assembled and disassembled repeatedly. The cam (eccentric bolt head) locks into a barrel nut in the adjoining panel. Confirmat screws are a simpler alternative — coarse-thread screws designed for particleboard that drive directly into the edge. Both require accurately located holes; a drilling jig is essential. Knock-down hardware is used in RTA (ready-to-assemble) furniture and shop fixtures where you need to reconfigure later."},{id:"ma-dowel-jig",topic:"Dowel jigs for accurate hole alignment",keywords:["dowel","jig","alignment","drill","accurate","guide","self-centering"],answer:"Dowel joints need precisely aligned holes or the joint will be offset and rack during assembly. Self-centering dowel jigs automatically locate in the center of the stock thickness — fast for edge-to-face joints. Transfer punches (dowel centers) let you drill one board, then mark the mating board by pressing them together. For cabinet face frames, a self-centering jig with depth stop is fastest. Grooved dowels let excess glue escape and reduce hydraulic pressure during assembly."},{id:"ma-krenov-style-joint",topic:"Wedged through tenon as design element",keywords:["krenov","wedge","tenon","visible","design","through","aesthetic","craft"],answer:"The visible wedged through tenon — popularized by James Krenov — turns a structural joint into a decorative feature. The tenon extends through the mortised piece and is wedged with a contrasting wood species, the wedge visible on the outside face. This signals craft and intentionality. The mortise must be cut with slightly tapered sides to allow the splayed tenon to pull the joint tight. The wedge itself should be dense, fine-grained hardwood."},{id:"ma-loose-tenon-router",topic:"Loose tenon joints cut with a router",keywords:["loose","tenon","router","mortise","festool","lamello","strong","fast"],answer:"A loose (floating) tenon system cuts identical mortises in both mating pieces, then inserts a separate tenon strip to fill both. The Festool Domino is the premium tool for this; a plunge router with a spiral bit and fence works just as well. Mill loose tenon stock from straight-grained hardwood to fit your mortise snugly. This approach is faster than cutting integral tenons and just as strong — the joint is essentially a double mortise with a floating tenon."},{id:"ma-rabbet-joint-variations",topic:"Rabbet joint for case backs and box corners",keywords:["rabbet","rebate","groove","back","panel","box","corner","lid"],answer:"A rabbet (rebate) is an L-shaped cut along an edge or end — the most versatile case-making joint. Used for cabinet backs (rabbet cut in the case sides receives the back panel), box corners (rabbeted box corner hides end grain), and drawer backs (a rabbet on the drawer side receives the back). Cut rabbets on the table saw with a dado stack or a straight bit in the router table. A backing board prevents tearout on the exit side."},{id:"ma-tongue-groove-variations",topic:"Tongue and groove joint variations",keywords:["tongue","groove","flooring","panel","frame","floating","glue","align"],answer:"Tongue and groove joints interlock a projecting tongue into a matching groove — they align panels and provide mechanical resistance to racking. In floating panels (frame-and-panel doors), the panel slides in the groove unglued to allow movement. In solid wood flooring, T&G provides alignment with no glue — the floor floats on the subfloor. For glued T&G panels, glue only the first few inches to allow movement. Keep tongue thickness at 1/3 the stock thickness."},{id:"ma-spline-miter",topic:"Spline reinforcement for miter joints",keywords:["spline","miter","corner","reinforce","glue","kerf","slot","plywood"],answer:"A spline is a thin strip of wood or plywood inserted into a matching slot sawn across a miter joint. It dramatically increases the long-grain glue area and provides mechanical resistance to the joint opening. Cut the spline slot on the table saw with a jig that holds the mitered corner at 45°. Use plywood for the spline (cross-grain resists splitting) or a short-grain solid spline cut from scrap. Splines are standard on frame joints and small box miters."},{id:"ma-keyed-miter",topic:"Keyed miter joint as visible decoration",keywords:["keyed","miter","key","butterfly","box","corner","inlay","contrast"],answer:"A keyed miter has a contrasting wood key inserted across the corner after assembly. The joint is assembled and fully cured, then slots are sawn across the corner on the table saw using a V-block jig. Contrasting keys (walnut keys in maple, for example) are glued in and trimmed flush. The keys are structural and decorative — they add real strength while signaling the maker's intent. Space keys evenly and use an odd number for best visual balance."},{id:"ma-rule-joint",topic:"Rule joint for drop-leaf tables",keywords:["rule","joint","drop","leaf","table","cove","roundover","hinge","knuckle"],answer:"The rule joint is a matched cove and roundover between a drop-leaf table top and its leaf. When the leaf drops, the curved profiles rotate against each other cleanly, hiding the gap. The hinge is mortised below the joint pivot point — its knuckle aligns with the center of the roundover radius. If the hinge is set at the wrong location, the joint will bind or gap when swinging. The router makes cutting the profiles straightforward; getting the hinge placement right is the harder part."},{id:"ma-breadboard-end",topic:"Breadboard ends for tabletop flatness",keywords:["breadboard","end","tabletop","movement","slot","peg","flat","warp"],answer:"Breadboard ends cap the end grain of a solid wood tabletop to keep it flat and protect the end grain. Because the top moves seasonally across its width and the breadboard is glued perpendicular to the grain, the joint must allow movement. Glue only the center peg; elongate the outer peg holes as slots to let the top move. The breadboard should be slightly shorter than the top's narrowest seasonal width to avoid it projecting in dry conditions."},{id:"ma-bridle-T-joint",topic:"T-bridle joint for stretchers and rails",keywords:["T","bridle","stretcher","rail","table","frame","open","slot"],answer:"The T-bridle (stub mortise and tenon bridled) uses an open slot cut into one member to accept a two-shouldered tenon from another. It's used where a rail meets the middle of another rail — like a stretcher-to-stretcher connection. The slot is cut all the way through on the face, making it easier to clean than a traditional mortise. It's weaker in tension than a closed mortise but adequate for compression-loaded stretchers and framework joints."},{id:"ma-pinned-tenon",topic:"Pinning a mortise and tenon for permanence",keywords:["pin","peg","oak","tenon","mortise","timber","frame","permanent","round"],answer:"Pegging a glued mortise-and-tenon joint adds mechanical reinforcement and is the standard in timber framing. Drill through the assembled joint and drive a seasoned hardwood peg (traditionally riven oak) that is slightly larger than the hole — it wedges in as you drive it and compresses the wood fibers for a self-tightening fit. Pre-bore the tenon peg hole slightly offset toward the shoulder (drawbore) to pull the joint tight. Saw the peg flush and the surface is clean."},{id:"ma-butterfly-key",topic:"Butterfly (bowtie) key for stabilizing cracks",keywords:["butterfly","bowtie","key","crack","check","stabilize","inlay","slab"],answer:"Butterfly keys (bowties) are hourglass-shaped inlays driven across a crack to lock it and prevent further splitting. Make the key from dense hardwood — it should be slightly fatter than the routed pocket so it presses in. Rout the pocket by tracing the key shape with a marking knife, then chop and rout to depth. The key should sit slightly proud, then be planed flush after the glue cures. Contrasting species make a dramatic design feature on live-edge slabs."},{id:"ma-glue-mortise-strategy",topic:"Where to glue in a mortise and tenon",keywords:["glue","mortise","tenon","where","apply","squeeze","out","long","grain"],answer:"Apply glue to the mortise walls (all four), to both tenon faces, and to the shoulders. Avoid putting glue on the end grain of the tenon — end grain absorbs glue but provides almost no strength. Too much glue creates hydraulic lock; back-chamfer the tenon end slightly to let excess squeeze out. Squeeze-out inside a deep mortise is hard to clean — use a small brush or pipe cleaner to apply glue precisely inside the mortise rather than globbing it on the tenon."},{id:"ma-box-joint-strength",topic:"Box joints vs dovetails in strength",keywords:["box","finger","joint","dovetail","strength","compare","glue","area"],answer:"Box joints (finger joints) have more long-grain glue surface area than dovetails of the same finger count, making them potentially stronger in pure glue-joint tests. Dovetails resist mechanical pull-out (no glue needed to prevent the joint from opening in one direction) while box joints rely entirely on glue. In practice, both are more than strong enough for box and drawer construction. Box joints are faster to cut with a jig; dovetails signal hand craftsmanship."},{id:"ma-cope-stick-joint",topic:"Cope and stick router bit joint for doors",keywords:["cope","stick","router","bit","frame","panel","door","quick","profile"],answer:"Cope and stick router bit sets cut both the frame profile and the panel groove in one pass (stick cut), then cope the rail ends to match (cope cut). The rail ends interlock with the stile profile for a strong, fast frame-and-panel joint. You must use both bits from the matched set — mix brands and the profiles won't mate. The joint has no real mechanical strength on its own (no tenon shoulders for racking resistance), so many woodworkers add a dowel or Domino at each rail-stile joint."},{id:"ma-coping-saw-curves",topic:"Coping trim profiles for inside corners",keywords:["cope","cope","trim","moulding","inside","corner","45","profile","butt"],answer:"Coping an inside corner means cutting the profile of one trim piece so it overlaps the face of the other — rather than mitering two pieces at 45°. A coped joint stays tight even as the room expands and contracts; miters open at inside corners. To cope: miter the piece at 45° first, then use a coping saw to cut along the revealed profile line. Undercut slightly (angle the saw back a few degrees) for a tighter front edge fit against the mating piece."},{id:"ma-dado-depth",topic:"Dado joint depth and strength",keywords:["dado","groove","depth","shelf","half","third","weak","strength"],answer:"A dado (housing joint) supports a shelf from below by capturing its end in a slot. Depth should be 1/3–1/2 of the thickness of the housed piece — never more than half, or you weaken the shelving unit significantly. A stopped dado (the slot doesn't run the full width) hides the joint from the front. Use a dado stack for clean, flat-bottomed dados on the table saw. The shelf should slide in snugly with hand pressure — not forced, not sloppy."},{id:"ma-double-tenon",topic:"Twin tenons for wide rails",keywords:["twin","double","tenon","wide","rail","movement","apron","table"],answer:'When a rail is wider than about 3"–4", a single tenon across the full width will conflict with seasonal wood movement — the wide tenon would need to allow the full movement of the wide rail. Twin tenons (two narrower tenons side by side with a gap between) solve this: each tenon is narrower and the gap between them accommodates movement. Twin tenons also provide more surface area and better resist racking than one wide tenon.'},{id:"ma-mortise-order",topic:"Mortise before tenon cutting order",keywords:["mortise","first","tenon","order","fit","chop","cut","sequence"],answer:"Always cut the mortise first, then fit the tenon to the mortise — not the other way around. Mortises are harder to change once cut; tenons are easy to sneak up on with a shoulder plane or a few extra table saw passes. A tenon that is slightly too thick can be trimmed; a mortise that is slightly too large can't be easily reduced. Mark the mortise from your actual chisel width to set dimensions."},{id:"ma-loose-fit-joint",topic:"How tight should a mortise and tenon be",keywords:["fit","tight","loose","snug","hand","pressure","mortise","tenon","dry"],answer:"A well-fitted mortise and tenon should slide together with firm hand pressure — not pounding, but not loose either. If it drops in under its own weight, it's too loose. If it requires mallet blows dry, it will crack the mortise when glue swells the wood. Test the fit dry before gluing; a joint that's slightly too tight will become impossible to assemble with wet glue adding friction. Shoot for: firm push by hand, comes apart with a sharp rap from the heel of your hand."},{id:"ma-japanese-joinery",topic:"Japanese joinery principles and complexity",keywords:["japanese","joinery","complex","interlocking","no","glue","timber","wood","frame"],answer:"Japanese joinery uses complex interlocking geometry cut without glue or metal fasteners. Traditional examples include the kanawa tsugi (scarfed splice) and the shachi sen (wedged timber joint). The joints are self-locking under load and are designed for disassembly and repair. Learning Japanese joinery develops deep geometry and hand-tool skills. For furniture work, simplified Japanese joints (the sliding dovetail, wedged through tenon) offer a manageable introduction to the principles."},{id:"ma-no4-plane",topic:"No. 4 bench plane for smoothing",keywords:["no4","number","4","smoother","plane","final","surface","prep"],answer:'The No. 4 smoothing plane is the classic final-step hand plane — 9–10" long, single iron, takes very fine shavings to leave a glass surface. Set the cap iron close to the cutting edge (1/16" or less) to reduce tearout on figured grain. A freshly honed iron should produce shavings thin enough to see light through. The No. 4 is the most versatile bench plane for a beginning hand tool woodworker.'},{id:"ma-no5-jack-plane",topic:"No. 5 jack plane for stock removal",keywords:["no5","jack","plane","stock","removal","roughing","camber","fast"],answer:'The No. 5 jack plane (14–15" long) is the workhorse — used to flatten, remove mill marks, and rough-dimension stock. Its iron is often cambered (curved edge, not straight) so it takes heavier gouging cuts without leaving straight track marks. It bridges high spots on bowed stock where a shorter plane would follow the wave. For stock over 6" wide, the jack works the wood down to near-flat before the jointer or a longer trying plane takes over.'},{id:"ma-no7-jointer-plane",topic:"No. 7 jointer plane for long edges",keywords:["no7","jointer","plane","long","edge","joint","flat","22","inch"],answer:'The No. 7 jointer plane (22") is the longest common bench plane, used to true long edges for glue joints and flatten large panels. Its length bridges low spots that shorter planes would follow, skimming only the high points. For glue-joint preparation, a jointed edge should show a light gap in the middle (1/32") so clamp pressure closes the joint firmly at the ends — a technique called a "sprung joint." The No. 7 is heavy and tiring to use, but irreplaceable for edge jointing without a power jointer.'},{id:"ma-block-plane-uses",topic:"Block plane uses and setup",keywords:["block","plane","end","grain","chamfer","trim","low","angle","bevel","up"],answer:'Block planes are small (6–7"), single-handed, and have the bevel facing up — the low angle (12° bed) makes them ideal for end grain. Use them for chamfering edges, trimming flush plugs and dowels, fitting drawer faces, and shooting miters. The adjustable mouth (on better versions) controls tearout — tighter for finish work, open for faster cuts. A block plane rides comfortably in an apron pocket and is useful for dozens of trim and fitting tasks.'},{id:"ma-router-plane",topic:"Hand router plane for consistent depth",keywords:["router","plane","groove","dado","hinge","mortise","consistent","depth","hand"],answer:"The hand router plane has a blade that extends below the sole to cut flat-bottomed grooves, dados, and recesses to a precise, consistent depth. It's invaluable for trimming hinge mortises, refining machine-cut dados, and cleaning up stub tenon shoulders. Set depth by clamping the blade at the desired projection — the flat sole registers on the surrounding surface, not the cut. A hand router plane does things a power router can't: it can reach into a stopped groove and trim incrementally without tearout risk."},{id:"ma-shoulder-plane",topic:"Shoulder plane for trimming tenon shoulders",keywords:["shoulder","plane","tenon","trim","square","rabbet","edge","accurate"],answer:"The shoulder plane has an iron the full width of the body, so it can plane right up to a shoulder without leaving a ledge. It's the precise tool for trimming tenon shoulders square and trimming rabbets. Set it to take a very thin shaving and work the shoulder from both faces toward the center to prevent tearout at the edges. A good-fitting tenon often needs just a few shoulder plane strokes to tune a gap-free joint."},{id:"ma-compass-plane",topic:"Compass plane for curved surfaces",keywords:["compass","curved","plane","concave","convex","adjust","radius","hull"],answer:"The compass plane has a flexible sole that can be adjusted to both convex and concave curves. It's used for chair seats, boat hull planking, coopered stave joints, and any curved surface too large to sand efficiently. Adjust the sole to match the curve of the work, then take light passes. On concave surfaces, the plane rocks slightly side to side — keep passes consistent in direction to avoid high spots. Good compass planes hold their curve setting accurately; cheap ones flex inconsistently."},{id:"ma-card-scraper-use",topic:"Card scraper technique and sharpening",keywords:["card","scraper","burnish","burr","hook","sharp","shaving","figure","tearout"],answer:"The card scraper removes whisker-thin shavings and is often the best tool for figured wood where a plane causes tearout. To sharpen: file the edge square, hone on a stone, then turn a hook with a burnishing rod held at 5–10° above horizontal. The hook (burr) is the cutting edge — when shavings stop and dust appears, the hook is gone. Flex the card slightly while scraping — the center of the flex is the cutting zone. Keep the scraper moving to avoid heat buildup that blurs your thumbs."},{id:"ma-cabinet-scraper",topic:"Cabinet scraper vs card scraper",keywords:["cabinet","scraper","handle","flat","back","holder","large","surface"],answer:"A cabinet scraper is a thicker plate of steel mounted in a handle — the Preston-style has an adjustment screw to flex the blade for optimal cutting. It works identically to a card scraper but reduces thumb fatigue over large surfaces. The Lie-Nielsen No. 80 and Veritas cabinet scrapers are the classic examples. Use a cabinet scraper to flatten areas too large for hand-held card scraping and for final prep before finishing on solid wood surfaces."},{id:"ma-marking-gauge-types",topic:"Marking gauge, cutting gauge, mortise gauge",keywords:["marking","gauge","cutting","mortise","pin","wheel","knife","fence","set"],answer:"A marking gauge scribes a line parallel to an edge. A cutting gauge has a knife blade rather than a pin, cutting cleanly across grain for shoulder lines. A mortise gauge has two adjustable pins to scribe both sides of a mortise in one stroke — set the gap to your mortise chisel width. Wheel-type gauges (Veritas, Japanese) stay sharp longer than pin types. Always score from the reference face so the gauge fence bears firmly on the datum surface."},{id:"ma-sliding-bevel-use",topic:"Sliding bevel for transferring angles",keywords:["sliding","bevel","angle","transfer","dovetail","mortise","protractor","set"],answer:"The sliding bevel (bevel gauge) sets to any angle and locks there — you use it to transfer angles from one piece to another without measuring. Set it from a protractor, a known angle, or directly from the work. For dovetails, set the bevel to the desired ratio (1:6 or 1:8) using a simple geometric method: mark 6 or 8 units along the grain and 1 unit across the edge, connect with the bevel, and lock. The sliding bevel is also useful for setting blade tilts on the table saw and bandsaw."},{id:"ma-winding-sticks-use",topic:"Winding sticks for detecting twist",keywords:["winding","stick","twist","wind","flat","parallel","sight","panel"],answer:"Winding sticks are parallel straight sticks placed across opposite ends of a board. Sight from one end across the two sticks — if they appear parallel, the board is flat; if one end is higher, the board is in wind (twisted). The sticks amplify the twist optically. Mark the high corners with chalk and plane them down until the sticks appear perfectly level with each other. Inlay contrasting strips on one stick to make the misalignment easier to see."},{id:"ma-rip-saw-technique",topic:"Hand rip saw technique and tooth geometry",keywords:["rip","saw","tooth","angle","file","set","stroke","grain","hand"],answer:"Rip saws have teeth filed at 90° across the face (like tiny chisels), optimized for cutting with the grain by paring fibers. The efficient stroke angle is 45°–60° to the workpiece. Start the cut by pulling to establish a kerf, then push strokes do the cutting. A sharp rip saw removes a surprising amount of material quickly. Dull rip saws require more force and wander; have them filed by a saw sharpener or learn to file and set teeth yourself."},{id:"ma-crosscut-saw-technique",topic:"Crosscut saw tooth geometry and use",keywords:["crosscut","saw","tooth","knife","bevel","file","angle","clean"],answer:"Crosscut saws have teeth beveled to knife across fibers, producing a clean crosscut without splintering. Western-style crosscut saws cut on the push stroke; Japanese crosscut saws (ryoba) cut on the pull stroke with teeth that fold cleanly. For fine joinery crosscuts (tenon shoulders, dovetail baselines), use a dovetail saw or a fine-toothed Japanese saw. The critical thing is starting accurately — use a knife wall or guide block rather than a pencil line."},{id:"ma-dovetail-saw-detail",topic:"Dovetail saw characteristics and alternatives",keywords:["dovetail","saw","thin","fine","kerf","back","spine","joint","control"],answer:'A dovetail saw is a small back saw with a thin plate (0.020"–0.025" kerf) and fine teeth (15–20 TPI). The stiff spine keeps the cut straight without needing much hand pressure. For through dovetails, a 20 TPI dovetail saw leaves a clean, thin kerf with minimal waste. Japanese dozuki saws are a fine alternative with very thin plates and pull-cutting action. Whatever you choose, the saw must be sharp — a dull saw drifts and requires pressure that wanders the cut.'},{id:"ma-mortise-chisel-heavy",topic:"Mortise chisels for heavy paring work",keywords:["mortise","chisel","thick","heavy","lever","mallet","square","back"],answer:'Mortise chisels have thick blades and robust handles designed to withstand mallet blows and levering out waste chips. The thick cross-section resists sideways flex during paring. Common widths: 1/4", 5/16", 3/8", 1/2". Always work to a scribed gauge line, chop halfway down, flip the board, and chop from the other side to meet in the middle. Never lever against the finished mortise wall — lever against the waste side to protect the layout lines.'},{id:"ma-paring-chisel-detail",topic:"Paring chisel for fine fitting work",keywords:["paring","chisel","thin","long","hand","pressure","dovetail","hinge","fit"],answer:`Paring chisels are thin, long, and driven by hand pressure only (never a mallet) — they're for fine fitting, cleaning dovetail corners, and trimming hinge mortises. A 1/8" paring chisel reaches into dovetail corners; a wide 1" is excellent for cleaning up flat mortise walls and tenon shoulders. Keep paring chisels at a lower bevel angle (15°–20°) than bench chisels for easier slicing. Never use a mallet on a paring chisel — the thin blade isn't designed for it.`},{id:"ma-bench-chisel-set",topic:"Bench chisel selection for a starter set",keywords:["bench","chisel","set","starter","size","1/4","1/2","3/4","1"],answer:`A practical starter chisel set: 1/4", 1/2", 3/4", and 1" bench chisels cover the vast majority of joinery work. The 1/4" is for small mortises and corner work; the 1/2" handles most mortises; the 3/4" and 1" are for paring and fitting wide joints. Buy a mid-tier set (Stanley 750 or equivalent, or a two-cherries set) rather than big-box chisels — cheap chisels hold an edge for minutes. Avoid complete sets of 10 — you'll use 4 chisels 90% of the time.`},{id:"ma-coping-saw-use",topic:"Coping saw for curves and interior cutouts",keywords:["coping","saw","blade","curve","interior","pierce","scroll","fretwork"],answer:"A coping saw has a thin blade tensioned in a C-frame, allowing curves and interior cuts (pierce through a drilled hole and reassemble the saw). The blade can be rotated in the frame for cutting in any direction. It's the hand-tool version of a scroll saw. Tension matters — too loose, the blade wanders; too tight, it snaps. Japanese-style kugihiki saws with flexible blades are often used for flush-cutting through tenons and dowels."},{id:"ma-drawknife-spokeshave",topic:"Drawknife and spokeshave for shaped work",keywords:["drawknife","spokeshave","chair","leg","curve","shaping","green","wood"],answer:"The drawknife pulls toward you to hog off stock quickly — used for green woodworking, shaping chair legs and rungs, and rough-profiling curved work. The spokeshave is like a narrow-soled plane with handles on both sides, refined for smoothing curves after the drawknife. Flat-soled spokeshaves work convex curves; round-soled spokeshaves work concave. Chair makers rely on both to shape legs, stretchers, and back slats efficiently."},{id:"ma-hand-saw-starting",topic:"Starting a hand saw cut accurately",keywords:["start","saw","cut","knife","notch","guide","pull","stroke","chisel"],answer:"To start a hand saw accurately: knife the line first (don't use pencil for joinery), then use your thumbnail or a guide block to register the saw. Pull two or three light strokes toward you to establish a kerf notch, then switch to push strokes. For crosscuts with no guide, place your thumb knuckle against the saw blade as a fence. Always check that the saw is vertical using the reflection from the side of the plate — a slight reflection error reveals lean."},{id:"ma-hand-plane-grain-direction",topic:"Planing with grain direction — reading the arrows",keywords:["plane","grain","direction","tearout","uphill","downhill","arrow","read"],answer:'Plane in the direction the grain runs "downhill" — look at the edge of the board and observe the grain lines. If they slope up from left to right, plane right to left (going with the slope). Planing against the grain lifts fibers rather than slicing them, causing tearout. On quartersawn and figured wood, grain direction changes — reduce depth of cut, use a tighter mouth, or use a card scraper instead. When in doubt, take a test cut and observe whether shavings roll smoothly or fibers tear.'},{id:"ma-hand-plane-setup",topic:"Setting up a bench plane for the first time",keywords:["plane","setup","flatten","sole","frog","chip","breaker","lateral","adjust"],answer:'New bench planes often need the sole flattened — rub on a sheet of 120 grit paper on a flat surface (granite plate or glass) in figure-8 patterns. Flatten the back of the iron on your sharpening stones before establishing the bevel. Set the chip breaker close to the edge (1/16") for smooth hardwood work. Adjust the frog forward for a tighter mouth. Final check: sight down the sole from the toe — the iron should be visible as a fine, even sliver across the full width.'},{id:"ma-scratch-stock",topic:"Scratch stock for custom profiles",keywords:["scratch","stock","profile","moulding","custom","file","scraper","tool"],answer:"A scratch stock is a homemade tool: a steel scraper filed to the desired profile, mounted in a notched wood handle. Drag it along the edge of a board with even pressure to produce a consistent moulding profile. You can make any profile you want — bead, cove, ogee, or complex combinations — by filing the scraper to shape. It works slowly but with total control and zero tearout. Excellent for small mouldings on curved work where routers can't safely reach."},{id:"ma-hand-saw-maintenance",topic:"Hand saw care and when to have it resharpened",keywords:["hand","saw","sharpen","set","tooth","maintain","file","joint"],answer:"Modern panel saws with hardened teeth (coated gray) can't be resharpened with a file — replace them when dull. Traditional hand saws with soft steel teeth are jointed, shaped, set, and filed on a regular cycle. Signs a saw needs work: it requires more effort, drifts in the cut, or leaves a rough surface. Basic maintenance: wipe the blade with an oily rag after use to prevent rust. Hang saws on the wall (tooth-up) rather than stacking them — contact dulls and bends teeth."},{id:"ma-mallet-types",topic:"Wooden mallet vs rubber mallet for chisels",keywords:["mallet","wooden","rubber","dead","blow","chisel","joinery","assembly"],answer:"Traditional wooden mallets have heavy lignum vitae or beech heads that deliver crisp, controlled blows to chisel handles without rebounding energy back into your arm. Rubber/dead-blow mallets are good for assembly — their sand-filled heads reduce rebound that could knock a joint loose. Never use a steel hammer directly on a chisel handle — you'll mushroom the end. For mortise work, a weight of 16–20 oz is comfortable; heavier mallets are tiring for extended chopping."},{id:"ma-marking-knife-types",topic:"Marking knife types and what to look for",keywords:["marking","knife","bevel","single","double","japanese","line","accurate"],answer:"A single-bevel marking knife (flat back, angled front) registers directly against a square or template — the flat back sits flush against the guide. A double-bevel knife can't do this; it rides up on the bevel and moves the line outward. Good marking knives are stiff (no flex) and hold a keen edge. Many woodworkers use a Japanese laminated blade — hard steel edge, soft steel body — that sharpens easily and holds longer than standard steel."},{id:"ma-story-pole-practice",topic:"Making and using a story pole",keywords:["story","pole","stick","layout","repeat","measure","transfer","kitchen","cabinet"],answer:'A story pole is a thin stick (1/4" x 2" typically) on which you mark all the key dimensions of a project directly — no numbers, just marks and labels. For a kitchen cabinet run, mark every cabinet width, shelf position, door gap, and hardware location. Transfer these marks directly to the stock rather than re-measuring each time. Story poles eliminate cumulative tape measure error and speed up repetitive layout in large projects. Mark the stick with a marking knife for precision.'},{id:"ma-travisher",topic:"Travisher for hollowing chair seats",keywords:["travisher","chair","seat","hollow","windsor","round","curved","compass"],answer:'A travisher is a curved-sole spokeshave-like tool used to hollow the seat of Windsor and slab-seat chairs. Its convex sole curves in two planes, allowing it to work in all directions across a hollowed seat. Work from the edges toward the center, then refine with a card scraper. The hollow depth in a Windsor seat is typically 3/4"–1" at the deepest point. A travisher in skilled hands produces a smooth hollow in 20 minutes; a grinder and sanding drum take longer and are harder to control.'},{id:"ma-dividers-spacing",topic:"Using dividers for even spacing and proportions",keywords:["dividers","compass","spacing","divide","even","dovetail","shelf","pin"],answer:"Dividers (wing compasses) transfer distances without arithmetic. To divide a space into equal parts: set the dividers to your best guess, walk them across the space, and adjust by the error divided by the number of steps — repeat until they land exactly. Use dividers to space dovetails evenly, lay out shelf pin holes, transfer mortise positions from story poles, and mark circles for turning centers. Keep a second pair set to your most-used increment (like 32mm)."},{id:"ma-spokeshave-setup",topic:"Setting up and using a spokeshave",keywords:["spokeshave","setup","adjust","blade","flat","round","chair","rung"],answer:"Spokeshave blades are tiny — sharpen them like a plane iron on a stone, keeping the bevel flat. The cap iron screw controls blade depth; use a fine screwdriver to set it. Push-style spokeshaves need the blade to protrude just a whisker. Pull-style cut on the pull stroke. Always work with the grain on convex curves. On concave surfaces, you often need to work from both directions. A round-soled spokeshave (for concaves) and flat-soled (for convex) are the two essential types."},{id:"ma-hand-tool-shop-layout",topic:"Setting up a hand tool friendly shop",keywords:["hand","tool","shop","bench","height","layout","quiet","light","space"],answer:"A hand tool shop needs less space and less noise than a power tool shop. Bench height is critical — your bench top should be at your first knuckle when you stand with arms at your sides. Good lighting from the side (raking light) reveals surface defects. A solid workbench that doesn't move under heavy planing is non-negotiable. Organize tools on the wall above the bench — the fewer steps between tool and bench, the faster you work."},{id:"ma-shaving-horse",topic:"Shaving horse for green woodworking",keywords:["shaving","horse","drawknife","green","wood","foot","pedal","clamp","free"],answer:"A shaving horse is a foot-operated clamping bench that holds work for the drawknife — your foot pressure on the pedal drives a pivoting head that clamps the workpiece. Releasing foot pressure frees the work instantly for repositioning. It's ideal for shaping chair spindles, tool handles, and rungs from green (unseasoned) wood. Green wood is much easier to shape than dry wood. Build your own shaving horse — they're simple construction projects with dozens of available plans."}],o=[{id:"mb-table-saw-blade-height",topic:"Table saw blade height for ripping and dadoing",keywords:["table","saw","blade","height","rip","expose","set","above"],answer:'For ripping, set the blade 1/8"–1/4" above the stock thickness — just enough to clear the top of the board. Higher blades kick back more aggressively; lower blades produce more heat and burning. For dado cuts, set the dado stack to exactly the depth you need and test on scrap. Never expose more blade than necessary — the exposed arc above the work is the kickback zone.'},{id:"mb-table-saw-fence-setup",topic:"Setting a table saw fence parallel to the blade",keywords:["fence","parallel","blade","table","saw","dial","indicator","toe","in"],answer:`A fence parallel to the blade produces clean rips; a fence that's toed in at the back (toward the blade) causes burning and kickback. Measure from a fixed tooth at the front and rear of the blade to the fence — both measurements should be identical. Some woodworkers prefer 1/64" of toe-out (fence slightly farther from blade at rear) to help guide the wood away from the blade. Use a dial indicator for precision on production work.`},{id:"mb-table-saw-crosscut",topic:"Crosscuts on the table saw with miter gauge",keywords:["crosscut","miter","gauge","table","saw","square","sled","accurate"],answer:"The miter gauge's small fence doesn't support long boards well — use a crosscut sled for longer pieces. Set the miter gauge or sled to exactly 90° using a reliable square, then test-cut two pieces and check them back to back for gaps. A fence extension screwed to the miter gauge helps support wider panels. Never use the rip fence as a length stop for crosscuts without a stop block that the workpiece clears before reaching the blade — otherwise the offcut can pinch and kick."},{id:"mb-dado-stack-setup",topic:"Setting up a dado stack on the table saw",keywords:["dado","stack","chipper","shim","width","flat","bottom","table","saw"],answer:'A dado stack combines outer blades with inner chippers and shims to cut wide, flat-bottomed grooves in one pass. Outside blades set the kerf edges; chipper blades are 1/8" wide each and fill in between. Shims (paper-thin to 1/16") fine-tune the total width. Always test the dado width and depth on scrap first — chippers packed out of balance cause vibration. A sacrificial zero-clearance throat plate prevents tearout on dado edges.'},{id:"mb-table-saw-zero-clearance",topic:"Zero-clearance insert for the table saw",keywords:["zero","clearance","insert","throat","plate","tearout","support","veneer"],answer:'A zero-clearance insert (ZCI) has the saw blade rise through it, leaving no gap around the blade. It supports the wood fibers right up to the cut, eliminating tearout on the bottom face. Make one from 1/4" MDF or hardboard: lower the blade, set the blank over the blade slot, clamp firmly, and slowly raise the spinning blade through it. Make a new one for each blade angle and dado width you use regularly.'},{id:"mb-bandsaw-resawing",topic:"Resawing on the bandsaw — blade and technique",keywords:["bandsaw","resaw","blade","fence","TPI","drift","wide","veneer"],answer:'Resawing means cutting a thick board into thinner slabs through its width. Use a 3/4"–1" wide blade with 2–3 TPI (few teeth, large gullets to clear sawdust). Drift — the tendency of the blade to wander from a parallel line — must be accounted for by setting your fence at the drift angle rather than parallel to the table. Feed slowly; forcing the feed causes blade deflection and wavy cuts. A single-point fence (a board clamped to the table at the drift angle) works better than a full fence for resawing.'},{id:"mb-bandsaw-blade-tension",topic:"Bandsaw blade tension and tracking",keywords:["bandsaw","blade","tension","track","crown","wheel","vibration","flutter"],answer:'Proper tension eliminates blade flutter and produces straight cuts. The "flutter test": spin the blade with power off, tap the flat of the blade — it should ping, not thud. Most manufacturers under-tension — err toward more tension on wide blades. Tracking (blade centering on the wheels) is adjusted with the upper wheel tilt knob; center the blade on the crown of the rubber tire. Blade guides (above and below the table) control side-to-side movement — set them 1/32" from the blade without touching.'},{id:"mb-jointer-grain-direction",topic:"Jointer grain direction and tearout prevention",keywords:["jointer","grain","direction","tearout","feed","cutter","head","climb"],answer:'Feed the jointer so the cutter head rotates "into" the wood fibers (not lifting them). Look at the board edge — grain lines that slope down from right to left mean feed right to left. If you get tearout despite correct grain direction, try a shallower depth of cut (1/32" instead of 1/16") or take the final pass with a very sharp, freshly honed hand plane instead. Heavily figured or interlocked grain may never plane cleanly on a jointer — alternate the feed direction and use a hand plane for the final surface.'},{id:"mb-jointer-snipe",topic:"Jointer snipe and how to avoid it",keywords:["jointer","snipe","dip","end","start","infeed","outfeed","table","set"],answer:"Jointer snipe is a deeper cut at the start or end of a board caused by the board tipping into the cutter head before or after it's fully supported. Prevent it by supporting the outfeed end of long boards with a roller stand, and applying downward pressure on the outfeed table (not the infeed) as soon as enough of the board has passed the knives. Add an inch to your rough lengths to sacrifice the sniped ends during final crosscutting."},{id:"mb-planer-snipe",topic:"Thickness planer snipe prevention",keywords:["planer","snipe","thick","end","feed","roller","lift","prevent"],answer:"Planer snipe is a slightly deeper cut at the very start and end of a board, caused by the feed rollers releasing the board before the second roller engages it. Minimize it: plane boards slightly longer than needed and cut off the sniped ends. Running multiple boards end-to-end through the planer (snipe only happens at the true first and last board). On some planers, slightly lifting the trailing end of a board while it exits reduces snipe on that end."},{id:"mb-drill-press-forstner",topic:"Forstner bits on the drill press",keywords:["forstner","bit","drill","press","flat","bottom","hinge","cup","overlay","speed"],answer:'Forstner bits cut flat-bottomed holes with a clean edge, making them ideal for cup hinge holes (35mm Forstner), shelf pin holes, and dowel holes. Run at the correct speed — large Forstner bits need slow speeds: 1/2" at ~1000 RPM, 1" at ~500 RPM, 1-1/2" at ~250 RPM. Let the bit cool between cuts in hard woods. Back up the exit face with scrap to prevent tearout. A drill press is essential — Forstner bits in a hand drill wander dangerously.'},{id:"mb-lathe-speeds",topic:"Wood lathe speeds for different diameters",keywords:["lathe","speed","rpm","diameter","turn","faceplate","spindle","safe"],answer:'Lathe speed scales inversely with diameter — larger pieces must spin slower for safe surface speeds. Rough rule: 6,000 ÷ diameter in inches = safe max RPM. A 6" bowl should run no faster than ~1000 RPM; a 1" spindle can run up to 3000+. Start every piece at the lowest speed and listen for vibration or imbalance before increasing. An out-of-balance blank at high speed is extremely dangerous — attach it firmly and check balance before powering up.'},{id:"mb-lathe-tools",topic:"Wood lathe turning tools and when to use them",keywords:["lathe","gouge","skew","parting","scraper","spindle","bowl","turning","tool"],answer:"Spindle work uses gouges and skew chisels to shape between centers. Bowl gouges have a deep flute for aggressive interior cuts and work from the outside in. Parting tools define shoulders and tenons. Scrapers remove fine amounts but need the edge on-center or below on the rest. Learn the spindle roughing gouge first — it's forgiving and fast for cylinders. Never use a spindle roughing gouge on a faceplate — it can catch and be flung dangerously."},{id:"mb-lathe-faceplate",topic:"Faceplate turning vs between centers",keywords:["faceplate","chuck","lathe","bowl","between","centers","spindle","attach"],answer:"Between-centers (spindle) turning holds the work on the headstock drive spur and tailstock center — used for table legs, chair rungs, tool handles, and long spindles. Faceplate turning mounts work directly on the headstock for bowls, platters, and hollow forms. A 4-jaw scroll chuck is more versatile than a plain faceplate — it grips a tenon turned on the blank and allows the work to be reversed for finishing the bottom."},{id:"mb-scroll-saw-technique",topic:"Scroll saw technique for tight curves",keywords:["scroll","saw","blade","tension","speed","curve","fret","inside","cut"],answer:"Scroll saws use thin blades in a reciprocating frame for intricate curves and inside cuts. Blade tension is critical — too loose and the blade bows in curves; too tight and it breaks. Feed rate must match the curve tightness — slow down for tight turns. For inside cuts (like fretwork letters), drill a blade entry hole, thread the blade through, and reconnect. Stack multiple sheets of thin material with tape to cut identical pieces in one pass."},{id:"mb-router-climb-cut",topic:"Router climb cutting risks and when to use it",keywords:["router","climb","cut","direction","pullout","control","profile","edge"],answer:'Climb cutting moves the router in the same direction as the bit rotation — the bit self-propels through the cut, pulling the router forward. It can eliminate tearout on certain grain directions. The danger: the router surges forward suddenly and is extremely hard to control, especially with large bits. Only climb cut on light finishing passes (1/16" or less) on the router table, never on a handheld router. Normal cutting direction (against rotation) is always safer.'},{id:"mb-router-bit-speeds",topic:"Router bit speeds — larger bits slower",keywords:["router","speed","bit","rpm","large","panel","raiser","safe","sfm"],answer:'Larger router bits must run at lower RPM to keep the rim speed (surface footage) safe. A 1/2" straight bit runs fine at 24,000 RPM. A 3" panel-raising bit should run no faster than 10,000–12,000 RPM — the large diameter means very high rim speed even at moderate RPM. Running large bits too fast creates vibration, burning, and risk of bit failure. Most modern variable-speed routers allow dial-down to 10,000 RPM for large profile bits.'},{id:"mb-router-table-fence",topic:"Router table fence setup and featherboards",keywords:["router","table","fence","featherboard","split","opening","bit","guard"],answer:"The router table fence halves position on either side of the bit, with an opening no wider than necessary. A featherboard upstream of the bit presses the workpiece against the fence for consistent depth. For profiling, the outfeed fence half must be advanced slightly to compensate for the stock removed — just like a jointer outfeed table. The bit guard sits on the fence to deflect chips and protect fingers from the spinning bit above the table."},{id:"mb-router-template",topic:"Template routing for repeat parts",keywords:["template","routing","pattern","flush","trim","bearing","guide","repeat"],answer:'Template routing uses a flush-trim or pattern bit with a bearing that rides against a template. The template is the exact shape you want; the bit reproduces it in the workpiece. Attach the template with double-sided tape, carpet tape, or toggle clamps. For inside curves, you need a pin router or to use the top bearing. Always rough-cut the workpiece close to shape first (within 1/8") to reduce the load on the router bit. Spiral upcut bits leave cleaner edges than straight bits on template work.'},{id:"mb-jigsaw-tearout",topic:"Jigsaw blade selection and tearout control",keywords:["jigsaw","blade","tearout","reverse","TPI","downstroke","veneer","cut"],answer:"Jigsaw tearout happens on the upstroke because the blade cuts on the upstroke in most jigsaws. To get a clean top surface, place the good face down (tearout appears on the top, which becomes the back). Alternatively use reverse-tooth blades that cut on the downstroke, leaving the visible face clean. Fine-tooth blades (10–12 TPI) produce smoother cuts than coarse blades. Score the cut line with a knife before cutting veneered panels to prevent surface splintering."},{id:"mb-circular-saw-technique",topic:"Circular saw technique for straight cuts",keywords:["circular","saw","fence","guide","straight","edge","plunge","cut","rip"],answer:"A circular saw with a good fence guide is nearly as accurate as a track saw for ripping sheet goods. Clamp a straight edge (or factory edge of another plywood sheet) as a guide, account for the offset between the blade and saw base, and run the base against the guide. Keep the saw moving at a consistent feed — stopping causes burning. Always support the off-cut side so the sheet doesn't collapse onto the blade as the cut finishes."},{id:"mb-track-saw-technique",topic:"Track saw for breaking down sheet goods",keywords:["track","saw","guide","rail","splinter","guard","plunge","sheet","plywood"],answer:"Track saws (like Festool TS55) glide along a guide rail and produce table-saw quality rip cuts in sheet goods on the floor or a workbench. The anti-splinter strip on the rail edge eliminates tearout on the top face. Plunge capability lets you start a cut in the middle of a panel (for sink openings). Tracks can be spliced for long cuts. The main limitation vs a table saw: you bring the tool to the stock, not the stock to the tool — awkward for multiple identical rip cuts."},{id:"mb-random-orbit-sander",topic:"Random orbit sander technique",keywords:["random","orbit","sander","swirl","pressure","grit","sequence","cross","scratch"],answer:`Random orbit sanders combine spinning and orbiting motion to eliminate cross-grain scratches — but only if you don't press too hard (which defeats the random motion) and don't skip grits. Move slowly across the surface (1"/second) and keep the sander flat. Start at 80 or 100 grit for stock removal, then 120, 150, and 180 or 220 before finish. Check your work by raking light across the surface — 80-grit scratches are invisible until the finish magnifies them.`},{id:"mb-belt-sander-use",topic:"Belt sander for aggressive stock removal",keywords:["belt","sander","aggressive","coarse","flatten","direction","grain","scratch"],answer:"Belt sanders remove stock very fast — they can easily sand through a veneer or create low spots. Use them for initial flattening of glued panels, removing mill marks, and final shaping of thick curved parts. Run parallel to the grain to minimize cross-grain scratches. Apply even, light pressure — the machine's weight is enough. Cross-grain belt sanding (at 45°) can flatten bowed panels faster but leaves deep scratches that require additional sanding to remove."},{id:"mb-cnc-basics",topic:"CNC router basics for woodworkers",keywords:["cnc","router","g-code","toolpath","bit","depth","pass","feed","rate"],answer:'A CNC router moves a spinning bit in X, Y, and Z axes to cut shapes from CAD files. Key parameters: feed rate (how fast the bit moves), plunge rate (how fast it goes down), and depth per pass (how deep each cutting pass goes). For 3/4" plywood, a 1/4" upcut spiral bit at 100 in/min with 1/4" depth-per-pass is a safe starting point. Upcut bits clear chips well but can tearout the top surface — downcut bits leave clean tops but pack chips in the cut.'},{id:"mb-cnc-spoilboard",topic:"CNC spoilboard and work holding",keywords:["cnc","spoilboard","mdf","vacuum","clamp","holddown","screw","tabbed"],answer:"The CNC spoilboard is a sacrificial MDF layer between the machine bed and your workpiece — the bit can cut slightly into it without damaging the machine. Resurface the spoilboard flat periodically. Work holding options: screws around the perimeter, double-sided tape, T-nuts in the spoilboard, or vacuum hold-down. For through-cuts in panels, leave tabs (small uncut bridges) to keep the workpiece from shifting; break tabs off after machining."},{id:"mb-oscillating-tool",topic:"Oscillating multi-tool for flush cuts and demo",keywords:["oscillating","multi","tool","flush","cut","undercut","door","trim","demo"],answer:"Oscillating multi-tools (Fein, Milwaukee, DeWalt) make flush cuts, undercut door casings, remove old caulk, and trim in tight spaces. For flush-cutting dowels or through tenons, the oscillating saw is safer than a chisel and faster than a hand saw. The blades dull quickly on hardwood — keep spares. For undercutting door casings to fit flooring, a long reach blade with a flat base attachment produces a consistent, accurate undercut."},{id:"mb-drill-press-mortise",topic:"Drilling out mortises on the drill press",keywords:["drill","press","mortise","forstner","chisel","clean","efficiency","overlap"],answer:"Drill a series of overlapping Forstner bit holes to rough out a mortise quickly — remove most of the waste by drilling before touching a chisel. Mark the mortise on the layout lines, drill the end holes first, then overlap holes between them. The chisel work is then just cleaning the flat bottom and squaring the corners. A mortise attachment for the drill press guides a square chisel around a drill bit, making perfectly clean mortises in one pass."},{id:"mb-router-bit-types",topic:"Router bit types and their uses",keywords:["router","bit","straight","spiral","flush","trim","roundover","cove","rabbet","profile"],answer:'Straight bits cut dados and grooves. Spiral upcut bits clear chips out of the cut for deep grooves. Flush-trim bits have a bearing to follow a template. Roundover and chamfer bits profile edges. Cove bits cut a concave profile. Rabbet bits cut stepped edges for cabinet backs. Profile bits (ogee, roman ogee, classical) produce decorative mouldings. Carbide-tipped bits outlast high-speed steel; solid carbide spiral bits last even longer. Always use 1/2" shank bits in 1/2" collet routers — they run truer and safer.'},{id:"mb-router-depth-setting",topic:"Setting router bit depth accurately",keywords:["router","depth","set","adjust","rule","block","stack","shim","accurate"],answer:'To set router bit depth without a depth gauge: place the router on a flat surface, lower the bit to the surface, set the depth stop, then back it off the desired depth measurement. A stack of feeler gauges or drill bits can serve as a depth block. For a 1/4" deep dado, use a 1/4" drill bit as a spacer under the depth stop. Fine-adjust plunge routers by loosening the micro-adjust nut, turning, and relocking — each mark on the fine-adjust is typically 1/32".'},{id:"mb-power-miter-saw",topic:"Miter saw angles for polygons and frames",keywords:["miter","saw","angle","polygon","frame","hexagon","octagon","formula","90"],answer:"Each miter on an n-sided polygon is cut at 90° ÷ n. For a 4-sided frame: 90° ÷ 4 = 22.5° each side (45° total corner). Hexagon: 90° ÷ 6 = 15°. Octagon: 90° ÷ 8 = 11.25°. For a picture frame, a 45° miter is exactly half of 90°. To check: add all the miter angles around the perimeter — they must equal 360°. Cut one test piece of each angle, assemble dry, and check for gaps before cutting good material."},{id:"mb-compound-miter",topic:"Compound miter for crown moulding and angle joints",keywords:["compound","miter","crown","angle","bevel","tilt","chart","spring"],answer:"Compound miters set both the miter angle and the saw blade tilt simultaneously — used for cutting crown moulding flat on the saw table and for angled joints in frames. Crown moulding compound angles depend on the spring angle of the moulding. A 38° spring angle needs a 33.9° miter and 31.6° bevel. Charts are available for all common spring angles. Alternatively, stand the crown upside-down against the saw fence at its spring angle and cut a simple 45° miter — easier but requires a taller fence."},{id:"mb-surface-prep-sequence",topic:"Surface preparation sequence before finishing",keywords:["surface","prep","sand","scrape","raise","grain","grit","sequence"],answer:"Machine-sanded wood: start at 100 or 120 grit to remove machine marks, then 150, 180, 220. Hand-planed wood: start at 150 or 180 — plane marks are finer than machine marks. Stop at 150 for open-grained porous woods that will get an oil finish; stop at 220 for dense woods or film finishes. Always sand with the grain for the final grit. Remove all dust with a vacuum and tack cloth before applying any finish."},{id:"mb-raising-grain",topic:"Raising the grain before water-based finishes",keywords:["raise","grain","water","based","whisker","sand","220","between"],answer:"Water raises wood grain — any water-based finish will create a rough surface on the first coat even on well-sanded wood. To prevent this, wet the wood with clean water, let it dry completely, then sand lightly with 220 grit to knock down the raised whiskers. The first coat of finish will then go on and dry smooth. Subsequent coats also need 320-grit scuff sanding between coats to remove dust nibs and maintain a flat surface."},{id:"mb-dewaxed-shellac",topic:"Dewaxed vs waxed shellac",keywords:["shellac","dewaxed","waxed","seal","topcoat","compatibility","blonde","amber"],answer:"Shellac contains natural wax. Dewaxed shellac has the wax removed and can be used as a sealer under any topcoat — it bonds to everything and everything bonds to it. Waxed shellac has the wax retained; subsequent coats of oil-based finishes may not adhere well over it. Zinsser SealCoat is a premixed dewaxed shellac. Blonde shellac gives minimal color; orange/amber adds warmth. Mix your own from dry flakes for fresher, longer-lasting finish than pre-mixed products."},{id:"mb-shellac-mixing",topic:"Mixing shellac flakes — cut and shelf life",keywords:["shellac","flake","mix","cut","pound","alcohol","ratio","shelf","fresh"],answer:`Shellac cut is the ratio of dry flakes (in pounds) to alcohol (in gallons). A 2-lb cut means 2 lbs of flakes dissolved in 1 gallon of denatured alcohol. For brushing, a 2-lb cut is standard. For wiping on thin coats, a 1-lb cut works better. Mix only what you'll use in a few months — shellac in solution has a shelf life of 6 months to 1 year. Old shellac won't dry hard. Always check the shellac "sell by" or mix date; fresh shellac dries in 30 minutes.`},{id:"mb-boiled-linseed-oil",topic:"Boiled linseed oil — properties and safety",keywords:["boiled","linseed","oil","blo","dry","time","rag","fire","penetrating","finish"],answer:"Boiled linseed oil (BLO) penetrates wood fibers and hardens through oxidation, providing some protection and bringing out grain figure. It dries slowly (24–48 hrs per coat) and produces a matte, low-sheen finish. BLO-soaked rags are a serious spontaneous combustion hazard — spread them flat outside to dry completely before disposal. BLO builds finish slowly (6–10 coats for meaningful protection) and produces a softer finish than varnish or poly; it's better as a base treatment than a sole finish."},{id:"mb-danish-oil-properties",topic:"Danish oil — what is it and best uses",keywords:["danish","oil","wiping","varnish","blend","easy","beginner","penetrating"],answer:"Danish oil is a proprietary blend of oil and varnish — it penetrates like an oil but builds a thin film like varnish. The exact formula varies by brand. It's one of the easiest finishes to apply — wipe on, let soak, wipe off excess. 3–4 coats provide moderate protection. It's not as durable as polyurethane but is much more forgiving to apply. Danish oil is a good first finish for beginners and is ideal for carved pieces where brush application is difficult."},{id:"mb-tung-oil",topic:"Pure tung oil vs tung oil finish products",keywords:["tung","oil","pure","finish","mineral","spirit","diluted","blo","compare"],answer:`Pure tung oil (from the tung nut) is a slow-drying penetrating finish harder than linseed oil when fully cured. Most "tung oil finish" products at the hardware store contain little or no actual tung oil — they're diluted alkyd varnish. Pure tung oil requires multiple coats and takes days to cure. It's naturally food-safe when cured. For a genuine tung oil look, Waterlox and pure tung oil from specialty suppliers are the real products — read labels carefully.`},{id:"mb-hardwax-oil",topic:"Hardwax oil finish for floors and furniture",keywords:["hardwax","oil","osmo","rubio","floor","furniture","matte","repair","easy"],answer:"Hardwax oil (brands: Osmo Polyx, Rubio Monocoat) combines penetrating oil with natural waxes — it soaks in and hardens to leave a flat, natural-looking surface. It's very popular for floors and modern furniture. Apply thin — a very thin coat is far more effective than a thick one, which stays sticky. One or two coats is sufficient. Spot repairs are possible by reapplying locally without refinishing the whole surface, which is a major advantage over film finishes."},{id:"mb-nitro-lacquer",topic:"Nitrocellulose lacquer — pros and cons",keywords:["nitrocellulose","lacquer","spray","guitar","fast","dry","brittle","amber"],answer:"Nitrocellulose lacquer sprays beautifully, dries in minutes, and is the traditional finish for guitars and vintage furniture. It's reversible — new coats bond chemically to old ones, making repairs seamless. Downsides: it's flammable and requires excellent ventilation, it yellows amber over time, and it's not very durable (chips and crazes). Modern CAB-acrylic lacquers are clearer (less amber) and slightly tougher. Both are spray-only for best results — brushing lacquer has retarders added but is still fast."},{id:"mb-conversion-varnish",topic:"Conversion varnish for commercial durability",keywords:["conversion","varnish","catalyzed","acid","cure","hardener","durable","spray"],answer:"Conversion varnish (catalyzed varnish) is a two-component finish mixed with an acid catalyst — it cross-links to a very hard film that resists water, solvents, and abrasion far better than oil-based poly. It's the standard finish in commercial cabinet shops. You must spray it (brushing rarely works). Pot life is limited (8–48 hours after mixing). The catalyst is hazardous — wear full respirator and gloves. Once cured, conversion varnish is exceptionally durable."},{id:"mb-wiping-varnish",topic:"Wiping varnish — easy film finish for amateurs",keywords:["wiping","varnish","diluted","poly","danish","oil","wipe","thin","coat"],answer:`Wiping varnish is oil-based varnish diluted 50% with mineral spirits — thin enough to wipe on and off like an oil but builds a real varnish film over multiple coats. It's forgiving: no runs, no brush marks. Apply with a lint-free cloth, wipe off excess after 5 minutes, let cure overnight, sand lightly with 320 grit, and repeat 4–6 times. The result is a thin, satin varnish film with an "in the wood" look. You can make your own by thinning any oil-based poly.`},{id:"mb-waterbased-poly",topic:"Water-based polyurethane application tips",keywords:["water","based","polyurethane","poly","brush","bubbles","fast","dry","grain"],answer:"Water-based poly dries in 2 hours vs 8 for oil-based, which is convenient — but the fast dry time creates problems. Don't overbrush or you'll drag up previous coats. Apply with a good synthetic bristle brush in long, even strokes. Bubbles: apply thinner coats, use a foam brush, or add a few drops of Floetrol to extend open time. Water-based poly raises grain on the first coat — sand 220 grit between coats. The finish is very clear (no amber), making it ideal over light woods and stains."},{id:"mb-oil-based-poly",topic:"Oil-based polyurethane for durability and warmth",keywords:["oil","based","polyurethane","amber","warm","durable","brush","dry","slow"],answer:"Oil-based polyurethane adds a warm amber glow — enhancing walnut and cherry beautifully — and is more durable than water-based formulas. Dry time is 8–12 hours between coats; full cure takes 30 days. Apply with a good quality natural bristle brush; synthetic brushes streak. Thin the first coat 10–15% with mineral spirits for better penetration. Three coats with 320-grit sanding between produces an excellent surface. Best avoided on very light woods (maple, ash) where amber tinting is unwanted."},{id:"mb-spray-finishing",topic:"Spray finishing basics — HVLP vs airless",keywords:["spray","finish","hvlp","airless","gun","pressure","viscosity","tip","atomize"],answer:'HVLP (High Volume, Low Pressure) guns atomize finish at low air pressure, producing fine droplets with minimal overspray — ideal for furniture. Airless sprayers use high pressure with no air — faster for large surfaces but harder to dial in for furniture finishes. Thin the finish to the right viscosity (test with a viscosity cup — water-thin for HVLP, slightly thicker for airless). Hold the gun 6–8" from the surface, move in even passes at 1 ft/sec, 50% overlap between passes.'},{id:"mb-fisheye-finish",topic:"Fisheye in finish — causes and fix",keywords:["fisheye","finish","silicone","contamination","oil","repel","crater","repair"],answer:"Fisheye appears as craters or circular repelled areas in finish — caused by silicone contamination (from furniture polish, aerosol lubricants, or hand lotion). The finish can't wet the contaminated surface. Fix: let dry completely, wash the surface with naphtha or mineral spirits, sand 220, apply a sealer coat with fisheye eliminator additive, then topcoat. Prevention: ban silicone products from your finishing area. Even tiny amounts of silicone in the air can contaminate bare wood."},{id:"mb-blush-lacquer",topic:"Blush in lacquer — causes and fix",keywords:["blush","lacquer","milky","humid","white","moisture","trapped","fix"],answer:"Blush is a milky white haze in lacquer caused by moisture trapped in the film as it dries — usually occurs in high humidity. Fix: add retarder (lacquer retarder or slow thinner) to slow the drying, allowing moisture to escape before the film skins over. Alternatively, spray in lower humidity or heat the shop slightly. A mild blush sometimes clears as the lacquer fully cures over days. Severe blush must be sanded off and recoated."},{id:"mb-orange-peel-finish",topic:"Orange peel in sprayed finish — causes and fix",keywords:["orange","peel","texture","atomize","spray","pressure","thin","rub","out"],answer:"Orange peel is a dimpled texture in sprayed finish resembling citrus skin — caused by poor atomization (pressure too low), finish too thick (needs thinning), or too-fast drying (gun too close). Fix the application: increase air pressure, thin the finish slightly, or slow the movement. If it's already cured, wet-sand with 400–600 grit and rub out with polishing compound. On fine furniture, flatting and buffing out orange peel is a normal step in achieving a glass finish."},{id:"mb-runs-drips-finish",topic:"Runs and drips in finish — prevention and repair",keywords:["run","drip","sag","finish","thick","coat","brush","spray","fix","sand"],answer:"Runs happen when too much finish is applied at once — gravity pulls the excess down before it skins over. Prevention: apply thin coats, brush only up-and-down on vertical surfaces, keep edges moving. For fresh runs, brush them out immediately with a dry brush. For cured runs: let the finish fully harden, then sand flat with 400 grit wrapped around a hard block, feather into surrounding finish, and recoat. On brush finishes, keep a wet-edge and never go back over partially dried finish."},{id:"mb-dye-stain",topic:"Dyes vs pigment stains for wood color",keywords:["dye","pigment","stain","transparent","pop","figure","opaque","NGR","color"],answer:"Dyes penetrate wood fibers and produce transparent, vivid color — they accentuate figure because the dye goes deeper into the pores. Pigment stains sit on the surface and in the pores, partially obscuring figure while providing more opaque color. Use dyes when you want to enhance figure; use pigment stains when you want more uniform, opaque color. NGR (non-grain-raising) dyes use alcohol carriers and don't raise grain. Mix dyes in water to raise grain, let dry, sand, then apply a second dye coat for best penetration."},{id:"mb-gel-stain",topic:"Gel stain for blotch-prone woods",keywords:["gel","stain","pine","birch","blotch","even","thick","apply","wipe"],answer:"Gel stain is thick — it sits on the surface rather than penetrating, which is exactly why it works on blotchy woods (pine, cherry, birch, maple). The thick gel can't penetrate unevenly because it doesn't penetrate much at all. Apply generously, work into the grain, and wipe off excess. Build color slowly with multiple thin coats. Gel stain is harder to apply on vertical surfaces (it sags) and inside corners (it pools). It's the go-to for a cherry-look on pine or cherry without conditioner."},{id:"mb-wash-coat",topic:"Wash coat to control stain penetration",keywords:["wash","coat","shellac","thin","seal","stain","blotch","pine","control"],answer:"A wash coat is a very diluted finish (typically 1-lb cut shellac or 10% oil-based poly in mineral spirits) that partially seals the wood surface to control stain penetration. On blotch-prone woods, it limits how much stain soaks in, preventing the dark/light mottling. Apply it after raising the grain and final sanding, let dry, then apply stain on top. The wash coat also works as a de-nibbing coat under veneer to prevent sand-through."},{id:"mb-toning",topic:"Toning finishes to even out color",keywords:["toning","color","shellac","spray","unify","blend","panel","even"],answer:"Toning adds color to the finish itself (rather than the wood) by dissolving dye or pigment into the topcoat. Sprayed toner can unify color variation between boards in a panel, blend sapwood to heartwood, or add subtle color without the blotchy risk of direct staining. Apply toner in light passes — too much obscures the grain figure. A toned finish looks best when you can still see the wood texture clearly."},{id:"mb-glazing",topic:"Glazing for antique and distressed finishes",keywords:["glaze","antique","distress","gel","pigment","highlight","shadow","dark","brush"],answer:'Glazing applies a translucent pigmented layer between coats of finish to add depth, highlight carvings, and create aged effects. Apply glaze over a sealed surface, work it into profiles and corners with a brush, then wipe back the flats to leave color only in recesses. Seal with a topcoat when dry. The "dirty" look in raised panel doors and carved furniture often comes from brown or black glaze pushed into the corners and profiles.'},{id:"mb-rubbing-out",topic:"Rubbing out a finish to a gloss or satin sheen",keywords:["rub","out","finish","gloss","satin","pumice","rottenstone","compound","flat"],answer:"Rubbing out flattens the final topcoat to a perfectly even sheen — from the same gloss finish you can produce matte, satin, or high gloss depending on how you rub it. Let the finish cure hard (2–4 weeks for oil-based). Wet-sand with 400, 600, 800 grit paper using soapy water. Follow with automotive rubbing compound on a foam pad. Finish with polishing compound for glass-smooth high gloss. Mineral spirits and 0000 steel wool produce satin; automotive compound produces gloss."},{id:"mb-paste-wax-topcoat",topic:"Paste wax as a topcoat and between coats",keywords:["paste","wax","topcoat","buff","johnson","renaissance","carnauba","final"],answer:"Paste wax (Johnson's, Briwax, Renaissance Wax) applied over a cured hard finish adds a soft sheen and a sacrificial protective layer that can be renewed without stripping. It's NOT a primary finish — wax alone offers very little protection. Apply thin, let haze, buff with a cloth or rotary buffer. On furniture, rewax annually in high-wear areas. Carnauba wax is harder and more heat-resistant; beeswax is softer and more natural-looking. Don't apply wax if you intend to apply more finish coats — wax prevents adhesion."},{id:"mb-between-coats-sanding",topic:"Between-coat sanding for film finishes",keywords:["between","coat","sand","320","scuff","adhesion","nib","flat","smooth"],answer:"Light sanding between finish coats removes dust nibs, levels brush marks, and improves adhesion for the next coat. Use 320 or 400 grit — you're just scuffing, not removing the finish. The surface should be uniformly dull after scuffing; shiny spots mean you missed them. Remove all dust before recoating. Don't sand between coats of lacquer (it bonds chemically); do sand between coats of varnish, poly, and waterborne finishes that rely on mechanical adhesion between coats."},{id:"mb-finish-compatibility",topic:"Finish compatibility — what can go over what",keywords:["compatibility","finish","layer","over","poly","shellac","lacquer","oil","order"],answer:"General rule: oil first (if any), then shellac as sealer, then any topcoat. Shellac goes over everything and everything goes over shellac. Oil-based finishes go over oil, shellac, or oil-based varnish. Water-based finishes go over water-based or dewaxed shellac (not over oil or waxed shellac without testing first). Never apply lacquer over an oil-based sealer — it wrinkles. Never apply polyurethane over pure oil that hasn't fully cured — it stays soft for months."},{id:"mb-milk-paint-finishing",topic:"Milk paint and chalk paint for furniture",keywords:["milk","chalk","paint","flat","matte","distress","wax","seal","furniture"],answer:"Milk paint (real or modern) produces a very flat, porous surface with an antique look. Real milk paint bonds permanently to bare wood and is hard to remove; modern milk paint can be used over existing finishes. Apply in thin coats — it dries fast (30 minutes). Seal with wax (traditional) or oil for a natural finish. Chalk paint (Annie Sloan style) is similar but bonds to nearly any surface. Both can be sanded, distressed, and dry-brushed to create aged furniture effects."},{id:"mb-finish-outdoor",topic:"Finishing outdoor wood furniture",keywords:["outdoor","exterior","finish","teak","oil","spar","varnish","uv","weather"],answer:"Outdoor furniture needs UV protection and water resistance. Options: spar varnish (flexible, UV-resistant alkyd), penetrating teak oil (needs reapplication every year), exterior water-based poly (2–3 season life), or epoxy prime with spar topcoat (longest lasting). Any outdoor film finish will eventually peel — penetrating finishes are easier to maintain because they don't peel. Reapply penetrating finishes before the wood weathers to gray and starts to check."},{id:"mb-titebond-types-comparison",topic:"Titebond I, II, and III in-depth comparison",keywords:["titebond","1","2","3","waterproof","type","outdoor","I","II","III"],answer:"Titebond I (original) has the longest open time (~5 min) and makes the strongest joints in pure wood-to-wood tests. It fails at about 150°F so it's not for objects near heat. Titebond II is water-resistant (Type II ANSI) — fine for occasional moisture but not submersion; the slight difference from Type I rarely matters. Titebond III is fully waterproof (Type III ANSI) but has shorter open time and slightly lower dry-strength than I. For furniture, Titebond I or II is ideal. Use III only when genuine waterproofing is required."},{id:"mb-hide-glue-hot",topic:"Hot hide glue — preparation and use",keywords:["hot","hide","glue","pot","protein","reversible","temperature","gram","bloom"],answer:"Hot hide glue (rabbit skin or pearl) must be dissolved in water and heated to 140–145°F in a double boiler. Too hot degrades it; too cool it gels on contact. Bloom strength (192–251 gram bloom) affects assembly time — higher bloom = shorter working time. Apply quickly to both surfaces, assemble and clamp within 30–60 seconds. Hot hide glue is the traditional choice for antique furniture because it's reversible with heat and water — invaluable for instruments and heirloom pieces that will need future repair."},{id:"mb-liquid-hide-glue",topic:"Liquid hide glue convenience and tradeoffs",keywords:["liquid","hide","glue","old","brown","convenient","open","time","reversible"],answer:"Liquid hide glue (like Old Brown Glue) contains a urea or glycerin retarder that keeps it liquid at room temperature — no heating required. Open time is much longer than hot hide glue (15–20 minutes). It's still reversible with heat and water. Strength is slightly lower than hot hide glue, and it has a shelf life of about 1 year after opening. Ideal for repairs, instrument building, and anyone who wants the advantages of hide glue without the glue pot and timing pressure."},{id:"mb-epoxy-types",topic:"Slow vs fast curing epoxy — when to use each",keywords:["epoxy","slow","fast","cure","five","minute","gap","fill","potlife","thick"],answer:"5-minute epoxy cures fast but is brittle, has minimal penetration, and provides a weaker bond than slower epoxies. Use it only for quick fixes that won't be stressed. Slow-cure epoxy (30 min to 2 hr pot life) penetrates better, cures harder, and fills gaps more reliably. For gap-filling on end grain or porous woods, thin slow-cure epoxy slightly with its own solvent for better penetration. West System and System Three are quality boat-grade epoxies that work well in furniture applications."},{id:"mb-ca-glue-types",topic:"CA glue viscosities — thin, medium, thick",keywords:["CA","cyanoacrylate","thin","medium","thick","gap","penetrate","accelerator","second"],answer:"CA (cyanoacrylate) glue comes in three viscosities. Thin CA is water-like — it wicks into tight joints by capillary action and is great for closing splits and stabilizing loose joints. Medium CA is the general-purpose type — workable for most gluing tasks. Thick CA (gel) fills gaps and is ideal for porous surfaces or larger gaps. Accelerator (kicker) speeds any CA to instant cure — useful for one-sided applications. CA joints are very brittle under impact — don't rely on CA for structural furniture joints."},{id:"mb-polyurethane-glue",topic:"Polyurethane glue — expansion and cleanup",keywords:["polyurethane","glue","gorilla","expand","foam","water","activate","cleanup"],answer:"Polyurethane glue (Gorilla Glue, PL Premium) cures by reacting with moisture — slightly dampen one surface before assembly. It foams and expands as it cures, filling gaps but also creating ugly brown foam squeeze-out that's hard to clean. Let foam squeeze-out fully cure (rock hard), then chisel or scrape it off. Polyurethane glue is excellent for bonding dissimilar materials (wood to metal, plastic, masonry) but offers no advantage over PVA for standard wood-to-wood gluing."},{id:"mb-contact-cement-types",topic:"Contact cement — solvent vs water based",keywords:["contact","cement","solvent","water","laminate","veneer","formica","toxic"],answer:"Solvent-based contact cement is stronger, more waterproof, and bonds faster than water-based. It's extremely flammable and toxic — only use it with excellent ventilation, no open flames. Water-based contact cement is safer and lower-odor but requires longer dry time and slightly less aggressive initial bond. Both work by coating both surfaces, letting dry until not tacky, then pressing together for an instant permanent bond. Bond is immediate on contact — position pieces carefully before pressing."},{id:"mb-open-time-strategy",topic:"Managing glue open time during complex glue-ups",keywords:["open","time","glue","complex","slow","batch","temperature","cold","rush"],answer:"A complex glue-up with many joints can exhaust your glue open time before all joints are assembled and clamped. Strategies: rehearse the assembly dry with clamps already staged, use slow-setting PVA (Titebond Extend has 8+ min open time), use hot hide glue then add hot water to buy time, or break the assembly into sub-assemblies glued in stages. Cold temperatures (50–60°F) extend open time significantly. Never rush a glue-up — a joint that closes 30 seconds too late will have a glue-starved joint."},{id:"mb-clamping-pressure",topic:"Correct clamping pressure for glue joints",keywords:["clamp","pressure","squeeze","out","gap","too","much","too","little"],answer:`The right clamping pressure produces a thin, continuous bead of squeeze-out along the entire joint — this confirms full coverage and sufficient pressure. Too little pressure leaves gaps. Too much pressure starves the joint by squeezing all the glue out (a "starved joint" is stronger than it looks but weaker than optimal). For PVA, you don't need massive force — 100–150 psi is fine for most joints. More clamps applying light pressure beats fewer clamps applying excessive force.`},{id:"mb-squeeze-out-cleanup",topic:"Cleaning up glue squeeze-out timing",keywords:["squeeze","out","cleanup","timing","wet","rubbery","stain","finish"],answer:"Timing glue cleanup matters. Wet cleanup with a damp cloth spreads diluted glue into the grain — invisible now, but it blocks stain and finish later. Better: let squeeze-out harden to a rubbery gel (30–45 min for PVA) then peel or slice it off cleanly with a chisel. For interior corners, a glue chisel (or a sharpened stick) gets into the corner. Any glue residue in the grain will show as a lighter spot under stain — check with naphtha before finishing."},{id:"mb-gap-filling-glue",topic:"Gap filling in wood joinery — best approaches",keywords:["gap","fill","joint","sawdust","epoxy","glue","filler","structural","cosmetic"],answer:"Structural gaps in load-bearing joints need real solutions — wood shims, re-cutting, or epoxy fills only (not sawdust fillers). Cosmetic gaps on exterior surfaces can be filled with colored epoxy, walnut wood filler, or the wood's own sawdust mixed with CA glue. Sawdust-and-CA filler matches the color closely but sands differently and may resist finish. Pre-mixed wood fillers (Timbermate, Famowood) sand and take finish better. Color-match the filler to the finished wood, not the raw wood."},{id:"mb-glue-temp-requirements",topic:"Temperature requirements for wood glue",keywords:["temperature","cold","freeze","glue","apply","shop","winter","minimum"],answer:"Most PVA wood glues require minimum application temperature of 50–55°F for the glue itself AND the wood. Cold glue is thick and doesn't penetrate well. Cold wood causes glue to chill too quickly before it can form a proper bond. PVA that has frozen is permanently ruined — shake it; if it separates, discard it. In cold shops, bring glue inside overnight and use it at room temperature even if the shop is cold — the working time drops but the bond is better than applying cold glue to cold wood."},{id:"mb-glue-reversibility",topic:"Reversible vs permanent adhesives for antiques and instruments",keywords:["reversible","hide","glue","repair","antique","instrument","epoxy","permanent"],answer:"For antique furniture and musical instruments that will need future repair, use reversible adhesives — hide glue (hot or liquid) is the classic choice. It releases with heat (120–140°F) and moisture. PVA can sometimes be released with steam but often tears wood fibers. Epoxy, cyanoacrylate, and polyurethane are essentially permanent — joints can be broken but the surfaces are damaged. Using epoxy on a valuable antique makes all future repairs far harder."},{id:"mb-rubbed-joint",topic:"Rubbed butt joint without clamps",keywords:["rubbed","joint","rub","flat","hide","glue","clamp","less","veneer"],answer:"A rubbed joint applies hide glue to both flat surfaces, then slides them against each other while pressing firmly. The heat from friction activates the glue and the molecular contact creates a strong bond without clamps. It works on perfectly flat mating surfaces — any gap prevents contact and the joint fails. This technique is used for attaching veneers, building up tabletops from narrow boards, and joining thin cabinet back panels. Modern PVA doesn't work well for rubbed joints — use hot hide glue."}],i=[{id:"mc-wood-screw-thread",topic:"Wood screw thread types — coarse vs fine",keywords:["screw","coarse","fine","thread","type","holding","grain","sheet","solid"],answer:"Coarse-thread screws have wider, deeper threads that cut aggressively into solid wood and softwood — better holding power in face grain. Fine-thread screws suit hardwood and machine applications. Self-tapping screws have a sharp point that cuts without a pilot hole in softwood. For solid hardwood, always pre-drill to avoid splitting — the clearance hole should match the shank diameter and the pilot hole match the core diameter."},{id:"mc-pilot-hole-size",topic:"Pilot hole sizing for wood screws",keywords:["pilot","hole","clearance","size","bit","screw","chart","hardwood","split"],answer:`The pilot hole drill bit should match the screw's root (core) diameter — the solid metal between the threads. The shank clearance hole (in the top board) matches the full shank diameter so the screw can pull the boards together. A common guide: for #8 screws, use a 5/64" bit for softwood pilot, 7/64" for hardwood pilot, and 11/64" for the clearance hole. If in doubt, drill a test hole in scrap — the screw should drive in with moderate hand pressure but not spin freely.`},{id:"mc-countersink-counterbore",topic:"Countersink vs counterbore differences",keywords:["countersink","counterbore","flat","oval","head","plug","flush","recessed"],answer:"A countersink creates a conical recess for flat-head or oval-head screws that sit flush with the surface. A counterbore creates a cylindrical pocket deep enough to accept the whole screw head below the surface, leaving room for a wood plug. Counterbores are used when you want to conceal the screw entirely. Combination drill-and-countersink bits do both the pilot hole and countersink in one step — very convenient for face frames and cabinet assembly."},{id:"mc-wood-plug-hiding",topic:"Hiding screw heads with wood plugs",keywords:["plug","screw","hide","counterbore","match","grain","sand","flush"],answer:"Counterbore the screw hole, drive the screw, cut a plug with a plug cutter from the same board (matching grain direction and figure), glue it in with the grain aligned, and sand flush after the glue cures. The plug will be nearly invisible if grain and color match. For a deliberate decorative plug, use contrasting wood (walnut plugs in maple). Plugs aligned with the grain disappear; plugs with end grain showing or cross-grain don't — always orient them correctly."},{id:"mc-pocket-screw-length",topic:"Pocket screw length selection by material thickness",keywords:["pocket","screw","length","thickness","chart","3/4","1/2","1.5","kreg"],answer:`Pocket screw length must be calibrated to the material thickness — too short and it won't reach the mating piece; too long and it blows through. Kreg's guide: 3/4" material uses a 1-1/4" screw; 1" material uses a 1-1/2" screw; 1-1/2" material uses a 2-1/2" screw. Fine-thread screws for hardwood; coarse-thread for softwood and sheet goods. Always set the pocket hole jig's depth collar to match the material thickness or the screw will be angled incorrectly.`},{id:"mc-structural-screw",topic:"Structural screws for heavy connections",keywords:["structural","screw","simpson","sdw","grip","rite","heavy","lag","load"],answer:"Structural screws (GRK, Simpson SDS, FastenMaster HeadLOK) are engineered fasteners with greater shear and withdrawal values than standard construction screws. They self-countersink, don't need pilot holes in most applications, and are rated for structural connections. Use them for stair stringers, deck ledgers, beam-to-post connections, and workbench assembly. They're far faster to install than lag bolts (no pre-drilling required) and often stronger for the same size."},{id:"mc-european-hinge-adjustment",topic:"European cup hinge adjustment — in, out, up, down",keywords:["european","hinge","cup","adjust","side","height","depth","overlay","inset"],answer:"European (cup) hinges have three adjustments. Side-to-side: the lateral screw moves the door left or right within the opening — typically ±2mm. Up and down: sliding the hinge on the mounting plate slot. In and out (depth): moves the door toward or away from the case face — adjusts the gap reveal. Make adjustments with the door hung — one screw at a time. Most hinges can be adjusted without removing the door. Set all hinges to have even reveals (gaps) all around the door."},{id:"mc-hinge-cup-sizes",topic:"Cup hinge cup size and overlay type",keywords:["cup","hinge","35mm","26mm","overlay","full","half","inset","boring"],answer:"Standard European cup hinges use a 35mm cup bored 13mm deep into the door back. Smaller 26mm cups exist for thin cabinet doors. Overlay type determines how much of the face frame the door covers: full overlay covers almost all of the case side; half overlay is used on interior partitions where two doors share a divider; inset hinges require a door that fits inside the face frame opening. Choose overlay type first when ordering hinges — it determines the hinge arm geometry."},{id:"mc-drawer-slide-types",topic:"Drawer slide types — undermount vs side mount",keywords:["drawer","slide","undermount","side","mount","soft","close","full","extension"],answer:"Side-mount slides attach to the side of the drawer box and the cabinet side — simple to install, widely available. Undermount slides attach to the drawer bottom and clip under the front of the drawer — completely hidden in the closed position for a clean look. Full-extension slides allow the drawer to extend completely out of the cabinet for full access. Soft-close slides use a dampened mechanism to close silently in the last inch. Undermount slides with soft close are the current industry standard for quality kitchens."},{id:"mc-figure-8-table-clip",topic:"Table clips and figure-8 fasteners for tops",keywords:["figure","8","table","clip","Z","clip","movement","allowance","slot","seasonal"],answer:'Figure-8 fasteners, Z-clips, and tabletop clips attach a solid wood top to an apron while allowing seasonal movement. They sit in a slot or rabbet in the apron, with one tab screwed to the top. As the top expands and contracts, the clip slides or pivots in the slot. Never screw a solid wood top rigidly in multiple places along the grain — it will crack at the joints or buckle. Space fasteners 8–10" apart; elongate slots perpendicular to the grain direction for maximum movement.'},{id:"mc-shelf-pins",topic:"Shelf pin hole systems and 32mm spacing",keywords:["shelf","pin","hole","32mm","system","spacing","jig","drill","cabinet"],answer:"The 32mm system spaces shelf pin holes exactly 32mm apart in vertical rows — it's the European production standard. A 5mm drill bit (for standard shelf pins) is used with a drilling jig. Typically drill two rows on each cabinet side, set in 37mm from the front and back edges. The advantages: holes align perfectly across multiple cabinets, and the shelf pin math simplifies into multiples of 32. Many router-bit and dado-stack jigs produce 32mm spacing automatically."},{id:"mc-bed-bolt",topic:"Bed bolts for knock-down bed construction",keywords:["bed","bolt","rail","post","knock","down","assemble","disassemble","strong"],answer:"Bed bolts (barrel nuts) pull bed rails tightly against the headboard and footboard posts for a strong, removable joint. The bolt threads into a barrel nut set in the post, and the bolt head is recessed in the rail end with access through the rail face. Tighten with a box wrench or dedicated bed bolt key. The joint gets tighter the more load the bed carries. Pre-drill the bolt and barrel nut holes with a dedicated jig — alignment is critical for the bolt to thread cleanly."},{id:"mc-piano-hinge",topic:"Piano hinge continuous support for lids and boxes",keywords:["piano","hinge","continuous","lid","box","full","length","support","evenly"],answer:"Piano hinges (continuous hinges) run the full length of a lid or door, distributing load evenly along the entire joint. They prevent warping in thin lid material by fully supporting the entire edge. Cut piano hinge to length with a hacksaw or snips, and file the cut end smooth. Mortise them flush for a clean look or surface-mount for utility installations. Piano hinges on box lids often need a chain or lid support to keep them from falling flat and breaking off."},{id:"mc-magnetic-catch",topic:"Magnetic catches and cabinet door hardware",keywords:["magnetic","catch","door","cabinet","close","hold","latch","strike"],answer:"Magnetic catches use a magnet in the cabinet and a steel strike plate on the door back. The catching strength varies (250g to 2kg) — heavier doors need stronger catches. Position the catch at the top or bottom of the door away from the hinge side for the most leverage. Roller catches (a small roller that snaps over a strike) are an alternative for overlay doors. Touch-latch systems let you open the door by pushing it — useful for handle-free modern cabinets."},{id:"mc-drawer-pulls-placement",topic:"Drawer pull placement and consistency",keywords:["drawer","pull","handle","placement","center","consistent","layout","jig"],answer:"Drawer pulls should be placed consistently — centered left-to-right and at a consistent height relative to the drawer front (typically centered top-to-bottom for small drawers, or at the top third for tall drawers). Make a simple drill jig from scrap for consistent hole placement across all drawers. Mark one drawer front carefully and use it as the template. European pulls with two screws must be centered on the hole spacing — note whether it's a 96mm, 128mm, or 160mm center-to-center."},{id:"mc-knockdown-hardware-types",topic:"Knock-down hardware for flat-pack furniture",keywords:["knock","down","rta","cam","lock","confirmat","minifix","barrel","nut"],answer:"Common knock-down hardware: cam-lock (barrel nut + cam bolt) for panel-to-panel connections; confirmat screws for edge-to-face connections in particleboard; cross-dowels (barrel nuts) with machine bolts for stronger connections in solid wood. All these allow assembly and disassembly without tools damage. The key is accurate hole placement — use a drilling jig or CNC. Assemble and disassemble more than three times and the particleboard core starts to degrade around the holes."},{id:"mc-screw-end-grain",topic:"Why screws in end grain fail and alternatives",keywords:["end","grain","screw","hold","weak","cross","dowel","alternative","pocket"],answer:"Screws driven into end grain hold at roughly 40% of the strength compared to face or edge grain — the fibers run parallel to the screw shaft and pull out easily. For stronger end-grain connections, angle the screw toward face grain (toe-nailing), use cross-dowels that bear on face-grain walls, or use epoxy to fill the hole before driving the screw. Pocket hole screws that angle through a face into the end grain of another piece work better than straight end-grain screwing."},{id:"mc-board-feet-formula",topic:"Board feet formula in full detail",keywords:["board","feet","formula","calculate","thickness","width","length","bf"],answer:'Board feet = (T × W × L) ÷ 12, where T is thickness in inches, W is width in inches, and L is length in feet. Example: a 4/4 board (1" thick) × 6" wide × 8 feet long = (1 × 6 × 8) ÷ 12 = 4 board feet. Hardwood lumber is always sold by board foot at the rough thickness — a 4/4 board is roughly 1" rough-sawn. Buy 15–20% extra for waste, defects, and milling loss.'},{id:"mc-linear-feet-vs-bf",topic:"Linear feet vs board feet — when each applies",keywords:["linear","feet","board","feet","difference","molding","trim","sell","price"],answer:"Linear feet measures only length — used for mouldings, trim, and lumber sold by the running foot. Board feet measures volume (thickness × width × length) — used for dimensional lumber and hardwood. A 1×6×8' board is 8 linear feet but 4 board feet. When estimating trim, calculate linear feet; when estimating hardwood furniture material, calculate board feet. Big-box stores sell 1×3, 1×4, 1×6 pine by linear feet at a fixed width — hardwood yards price by board foot regardless of width."},{id:"mc-sheet-good-yield",topic:"Sheet good yield calculation for cabinet projects",keywords:["sheet","plywood","yield","parts","lay","out","nest","optimize","waste"],answer:`A 4×8 sheet of plywood yields 32 sq ft. Rough rule: a standard base cabinet case uses about 1.5–2 sheets of 3/4". Layout matters — try to orient all grain the same direction and minimize crosscuts. For planning, add 10–15% waste for cutting errors and offcuts. DoveDesign's cut list panel shows board feet and sheet counts automatically based on your design. Draw out your cut layout on graph paper for large orders to minimize sheet count before purchasing.`},{id:"mc-miter-angle-polygons",topic:"Miter angles for polygon frames",keywords:["miter","angle","polygon","formula","hexagon","octagon","pentagon","frame","sides"],answer:"Miter angle per cut = 90° ÷ number of sides. Square (4 sides): 22.5° per cut, 45° total corner. Pentagon (5): 18°. Hexagon (6): 15°. Octagon (8): 11.25°. These are for flat regular polygons. Cut all pieces the same length (short point to short point for miters) to get equal sides. If pieces vary in length, the interior angles still hold but the polygon won't close — check all lengths are identical before cutting final material."},{id:"mc-taper-calculation",topic:"Calculating taper for furniture legs",keywords:["taper","calculation","leg","width","start","end","length","ratio","formula"],answer:'A tapered leg requires calculating the taper angle or drop per inch of length. Formula: taper per inch = (start width - end width) ÷ length. Example: 2" top, 1" bottom, 28" long = 1" taper ÷ 28" = 0.0357" taper per inch. Set your taper jig to this ratio. For even four-sided tapers, taper two opposite faces first, then rotate 90° and taper the other two — the reference face for the second two cuts is the already-tapered face, not the original.'},{id:"mc-golden-ratio",topic:"Golden ratio in furniture proportions",keywords:["golden","ratio","phi","proportion","rectangle","furniture","aesthetic","1.618"],answer:`The golden ratio (1:1.618 or φ) describes proportions found aesthetically pleasing across many cultures. For furniture: a table top might be 30"×48.5" (1:1.618), or a bookcase 18" deep × 29" wide (1:1.618). To find the golden ratio for any dimension: multiply by 1.618 for the longer dimension, or divide by 1.618 for the shorter. It's a starting point, not a rule — successful furniture design regularly violates it. But when a piece "looks right" and you can't say why, the proportions are often close to φ.`},{id:"mc-rule-of-thirds",topic:"Rule of thirds in cabinet door and panel design",keywords:["rule","thirds","panel","door","proportion","upper","lower","rail","divider"],answer:"The rule of thirds divides a rectangle at 1/3 and 2/3 intervals. For a cabinet door, placing the horizontal rail at the 1/3 point from the top (or bottom) looks more dynamic than centering it. A chest with three drawers looks better with a proportioned height progression (3:4:5 or similar) than equal-height drawers. Divide a wall unit into thirds — tall open section, shorter cabinet section, and base — for visual interest. The rule prevents the monotony of exactly halved proportions."},{id:"mc-wood-movement-formula",topic:"Calculating seasonal wood movement",keywords:["movement","formula","percent","species","change","MC","width","calculate"],answer:'Movement = width × (MC change ÷ 100) × species coefficient. Example: 12" wide hard maple panel, moving from 14% MC (summer) to 7% MC (heated winter) = 7% MC change. Maple tangential coefficient ≈ 9.9. Movement = 12 × (7 ÷ 100) × 9.9 = 0.083 inches ≈ 5/64" per foot. A 24" wide maple panel could move almost 3/8" seasonally — that gap must be accounted for in panel float and tabletop attachment. Species coefficients are in every woodworking reference; quartersawn is always about half the tangential value.'},{id:"mc-dovetail-ratio",topic:"Dovetail angle ratios for hardwood and softwood",keywords:["dovetail","angle","ratio","1:6","1:8","hardwood","softwood","slope","marking"],answer:"The conventional dovetail slope ratio for hardwoods is 1:6 — for every 6 units along the grain, the tail sides splay 1 unit. For softwoods (pine, cedar), use 1:8 — a shallower angle that reduces the risk of short grain snapping off the softwood pins. Steeper angles (1:4 or 1:5) look bold but are weaker. Lay out the ratio geometrically on paper or use a sliding bevel — mark 6 (or 8) units along the baseline and 1 unit up, connect for the slope. Set the bevel to this line and scribe all tails from it."},{id:"mc-drawer-height-progression",topic:"Drawer height progression for visual balance",keywords:["drawer","height","progression","series","stack","balance","visual","proportion"],answer:'A stack of identical-height drawers looks static. Use a progression: the top drawer is shortest, with each drawer below slightly taller (arithmetic or geometric progression). Example: 4" / 5" / 6" / 7" or using a 1.15× multiplier between drawers. The heaviest, largest items go in the lowest, tallest drawer — practical and visually weighted to the base. Survey furniture catalogs to internalize proportions that read as "right" before designing your own progression.'},{id:"mc-diagonal-squaring",topic:"Diagonal measurement for squaring carcases and frames",keywords:["diagonal","square","carcase","frame","measure","equal","check","winding"],answer:"Equal diagonals mean a rectangle is square — measure corner to corner in both directions. If diagonals are equal, the frame is square; if one is longer, push the longer-diagonal corners toward each other while clamping. This works for any rectangle regardless of size. Check before the glue sets — once cured, correcting a racked carcase requires cutting apart joints. On large carcases, a steel tape is accurate enough; for small boxes, use the same diagonal stick both ways."},{id:"mc-trammel-points",topic:"Trammel points for large circles and arcs",keywords:["trammel","point","circle","arc","large","radius","mark","layout","stick"],answer:"Trammel points are metal tips clamped to a wooden beam, acting as a large compass for circles and arcs too large for a standard compass. Set the two points the desired radius apart, anchor one point at the center, and scribe the arc with the other. Make your own trammel from a 1×2 strip with a nail at one end and a pencil or knife at the desired radius. Router circle jigs work the same way — pivot nail at center, router at the radius."},{id:"mc-compound-angle-chart",topic:"Compound miter angles for splayed boxes and picture frames",keywords:["compound","miter","splay","angle","tilted","bevel","table","saw","tilt"],answer:"Splayed sides (like a planter box or a tray with angled sides) require compound miters — the miter saw tilts in two planes simultaneously. The exact angles depend on both the splay angle and the number of sides. For a 4-sided box with 10° splay: bevel = arctan(cos(45°) × tan(10°)) ≈ 7.1°; miter = arctan(sin(45°) / cos(10°)) ≈ 44.3°. Woodworking apps and compound miter charts provide these values — don't calculate by hand. Always cut test pieces in scrap before committing to good material."},{id:"mc-percent-waste",topic:"Estimating waste percentage for projects",keywords:["waste","percent","overage","buy","extra","defect","kerf","cut","estimate"],answer:"Buy 15–20% more lumber than your cut list requires to account for defects, bad cuts, and kerf waste. For figured or highly figured lumber, buy 25–30% extra because yields are lower. For sheet goods, buy 10% over the optimized sheet count. For mouldings and trim, buy 10–15% linear feet extra for miter waste and bad cuts. Leftover stock is always useful for test cuts and small projects; running out means a trip back to the lumber yard and risk of not matching color or grain."},{id:"mc-pythagorean-woodworking",topic:"3-4-5 triangle for checking square in the shop",keywords:["3","4","5","triangle","square","layout","right","angle","pythagorean"],answer:"The 3-4-5 triangle (Pythagorean relationship) creates a perfect right angle: if one leg is 3 units, another is 4 units, and the hypotenuse is 5 units, the corner is exactly 90°. Use any multiples — 6-8-10 or 12-16-20 work equally well. To check a large structure or slab foundation for square, measure 3 feet on one edge, 4 feet on the perpendicular edge, and the diagonal should be exactly 5 feet. For smaller work, any reliable framing square works better."},{id:"mc-metric-imperial-convert",topic:"Converting between metric and imperial in woodworking",keywords:["metric","imperial","convert","inch","mm","centimeter","32mm","fraction"],answer:'1 inch = 25.4mm exactly. Common conversions: 3/4" = 19mm, 1/2" = 12.7mm, 1/4" = 6.35mm, 1/8" = 3.175mm. The 32mm cabinet system uses: 37mm setback for shelf pins, 16mm panel thickness (5/8"), 18mm (3/4"). Most European hardware is in mm; most US lumber is in fractions of inches. Keep a conversion chart at the bench — mental arithmetic between the two systems is error-prone.'},{id:"mc-fibonacci-sequence",topic:"Fibonacci sequence in furniture design",keywords:["fibonacci","sequence","golden","proportion","shelf","height","rail","design"],answer:"The Fibonacci sequence (1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 21...) produces proportions that approach the golden ratio. Use consecutive Fibonacci numbers as dimension ratios — 5:8 for a table width to depth, 8:13 for a bookcase height to width, 3:5 for drawer heights in a two-drawer chest. These ratios feel natural and well-proportioned because human visual perception is sensitive to the golden ratio. Use it to set heights, widths, and panel divisions rather than defaulting to round numbers."},{id:"mc-shaker-design",topic:"Shaker style design principles",keywords:["shaker","style","simple","tapered","leg","mortise","tenon","honest","design"],answer:"Shaker furniture is defined by simplicity, honesty of materials, and utility. Features: square or slightly tapered legs (no carving), frame-and-panel construction with mortise-and-tenon joinery, minimal surface decoration, and natural wood finishes (milk paint or linseed oil). Cherry and maple are the most historically accurate species. The aesthetic rejects ornamentation as dishonest — every element must serve a functional purpose. Shaker proportions are usually classic: tall, narrow cabinet doors and simple turned or carved pulls."},{id:"mc-arts-crafts-design",topic:"Arts and Crafts furniture design elements",keywords:["arts","crafts","mission","stickley","through","tenon","quartersawn","oak","pegged"],answer:"Arts and Crafts furniture (Mission style) celebrates exposed joinery and structural honesty. Key features: through tenons pegged with ebony or contrasting wood, quartersawn white oak for its ray-fleck figure, wide corbels and stretchers, flat surfaces with minimal moulding, and leather or canvas upholstery. Hardware is hammered copper or hand-forged iron. The style emerged as a reaction to Victorian excess — craftsmanship and material quality are the decoration."},{id:"mc-mid-century-design",topic:"Mid-century modern furniture design",keywords:["mid","century","modern","tapered","leg","thin","plywood","organic","1950","1960"],answer:"Mid-century modern (1940s–1960s) features: thin, tapering legs (often angled outward), clean horizontal lines, organic curves on chairs and sofas, extensive use of bent plywood (Eames), teak and walnut as preferred species, and minimal ornamentation. Hardware is often completely hidden. The aesthetic was influenced by post-war optimism and new materials (molded plywood, fiberglass). To achieve the style: thin profiles, light footprint legs, and natural oil finishes rather than heavy polys."},{id:"mc-traditional-period-design",topic:"Traditional and period furniture design elements",keywords:["traditional","period","cabriole","ogee","carved","detail","bracket","foot"],answer:"Traditional furniture (Queen Anne, Chippendale, Federal) features cabriole legs with ball-and-claw or pad feet, carved details on crests and aprons, ogee bracket feet on case pieces, broken pediment tops, and rich mahogany or cherry with shellac or varnish finishes. The style emphasizes elaborate detail and visual complexity. Period furniture requires strong carving skills, advanced joinery, and deep knowledge of historical proportions — a demanding but deeply rewarding area of woodworking."},{id:"mc-contemporary-mixed-materials",topic:"Contemporary furniture with mixed materials",keywords:["contemporary","mixed","steel","glass","concrete","wood","modern","contrast"],answer:"Contemporary furniture mixes materials expressively — thick walnut slabs on welded steel bases, concrete tabletops on wood frames, glass shelves in wooden cases. The contrast between raw metal or concrete and warm wood is the main aesthetic statement. For woodworkers, the challenge is making clean connections between materials — steel legs bolt to wood through properly sized through-holes with barrel nuts, or the steel is welded to a flat plate that screws to the wood from underneath."},{id:"mc-farmhouse-style",topic:"Farmhouse style furniture characteristics",keywords:["farmhouse","rustic","painted","apron","table","bench","knotty","pine","white"],answer:"Farmhouse style embraces imperfection — knotty pine, rough-sawn oak, wide farmhouse tables with breadboard ends, apron tables painted white or gray, and bench seating. Joinery is honest and simple — mortise-and-tenon apron-to-leg connections, visible hardware, and face-frame cabinet construction. Distressing and aging techniques (milk paint chipping, wire brushing, light sanding edges) are common. This style rewards the use of less-than-perfect lumber that would be rejected for fine furniture."},{id:"mc-scandinavian-design",topic:"Scandinavian (Scandi) furniture design",keywords:["scandinavian","danish","swedish","nordic","light","simple","beech","functional"],answer:"Scandinavian design combines simple forms with excellent craftsmanship and functional purpose. Features: blonde woods (beech, ash, birch), clean simple profiles, natural finishes (oil, soap, wax — no heavy lacquer), ergonomic attention to human proportions, and modest ornamentation. Danish furniture icons (Hans Wegner, Finn Juhl) use steam-bending for chair backs and complex leg-to-seat angles. The style rewards precision joinery and thoughtful ergonomics over decorative complexity."},{id:"mc-cabriole-leg",topic:"Cabriole leg construction techniques",keywords:["cabriole","leg","S","curve","knee","ankle","pad","foot","bandsaw","carve"],answer:"The cabriole leg is an S-curved leg found in Queen Anne and Chippendale furniture. Cut the rough shape on the bandsaw in two passes — cut one face, tape the offcut back, rotate 90°, and cut the second face. This produces a perfect blank that can then be carved and smoothed. The knee (upper curve), shank, and foot are refined with spokeshave, rasps, and scrapers. The pad foot is turned on the lathe or shaped with rasps. Proportioning the leg is the critical skill — study originals carefully."},{id:"mc-table-proportions",topic:"Table proportions — height, width, and apron rules",keywords:["table","height","proportion","apron","top","overhang","clearance","knee","leg"],answer:'Standard dining table height is 28"–30". Desk/work height: 28"–29". Coffee table: 16"–18". The apron underside should be at least 24"–25" from the floor for knee clearance at a dining table. Top overhang beyond apron: 1"–2" standard (more looks clunky; less risks hitting the apron with your legs). Leg-to-leg span (inside measure) at a four-person dining table should be at least 24" for two seats per side. A table top at least 36" wide seats two across comfortably.'},{id:"mc-chair-ergonomics",topic:"Chair ergonomics — seat angle, back angle, height",keywords:["chair","ergonomics","seat","angle","back","rake","height","comfort","design"],answer:'Dining chair seat height: 17"–18" from floor. Seat depth: 15"–17". Seat angle (rake): 2°–5° downward from front to back. Back angle from vertical: 5°–10°. Back height: 14"–18" for mid-back, 32"+ for high-back. Arm height (if present): 7"–8" above seat. These are starting points — vary them for target users (children need different dimensions). Make a full-size cardboard mockup before building a chair — adjustments to angles are much easier before cutting wood.'},{id:"mc-negative-space",topic:"Negative space in furniture design",keywords:["negative","space","void","opening","shelving","visual","light","airy","frame"],answer:"Negative space — the open areas through and around a piece — is as important as the solid wood parts. Thick legs without negative space between them look heavy; open stretcher arrangements look lighter. Bookcase backs recessed into the shelf rather than flush create a visual frame. Open cabinet sections alternating with closed ones give rhythm. Evaluate furniture design by flipping the silhouette upside down — the negative shapes should be as considered as the positive ones."},{id:"mc-grain-matching-design",topic:"Grain matching for tabletops and panels",keywords:["grain","match","tabletop","panel","direction","figure","book","sequence"],answer:"For a glued-up tabletop, use sequential boards from the same log (or at least the same species and figure character) and arrange them for best visual match. Try all possible arrangements before gluing — bark side always up or always down was traditional advice (now debated), but keeping grain direction consistent for planing matters. Mark the boards before breaking the arrangement. Boards from the same log opened bookmatched give the most dramatic matched top."},{id:"mc-leg-to-top-ratio",topic:"Leg size to top thickness visual proportion",keywords:["leg","size","top","thickness","ratio","proportion","visual","thick","thin"],answer:'A common guideline: table leg size should be roughly equal to the top thickness in visual weight. A 1.5" top looks good on 1.5"–2" square legs; a massive 2.5" thick slab demands chunkier legs or a heavy structural base. Thin tapered legs look best under delicate tops. Breaking the rule intentionally can be design-forward — a thick slab on thin steel legs creates visual tension. When in doubt, make scale cardboard models before committing to wood.'},{id:"mc-case-proportions",topic:"Casework proportions — height, width, and depth ratios",keywords:["casework","cabinet","proportion","height","width","depth","ratio","design"],answer:'Well-proportioned case pieces follow some loose guidelines. Width:height should rarely exceed 1:2 (a very tall, narrow case) or be less than 1:0.6 (a squat, wide case). Depth is typically 14"–18" for bookshelves, 23"–24" for kitchen base cabinets, and 12" for wall cabinets. Hanging wall cabinets proportioned too deep look top-heavy. Break wide casepieces into visual vertical sections (using pilasters or varied door widths) to avoid monotony.'},{id:"mc-knots-working-around",topic:"Knots — tight vs loose and how to work around them",keywords:["knot","tight","loose","intergrown","encased","crack","circle","plan"],answer:"Tight (intergrown) knots are solidly connected to surrounding wood and can be left in place — they're a character feature in rustic work. Loose (encased) knots may fall out; stabilize them with thin CA glue or epoxy, or plan your cut list to place them in waste. Dead knots (darker, often surrounded by a black ring) signal a dead branch — the wood around them is weaker. On visible surfaces, orient knots where they're least objectionable or cut around them entirely by adjusting your layout."},{id:"mc-checks-splits-prevention",topic:"Checks and splits — causes and prevention",keywords:["check","split","crack","end","grain","seal","dry","fast","surface"],answer:"Wood checks (cracks) when surface fibers dry faster than the interior, creating tension that tears across the fibers. Prevent checking in slabs and live-edge pieces by sealing end grain with end-grain sealer, wax, or even latex paint immediately after cutting. For boards in storage, sticker-stack with good airflow and cover the ends and top — not the sides. In the shop, don't leave boards in direct sun or near a heat source for extended periods."},{id:"mc-reaction-wood",topic:"Reaction wood — tension wood and compression wood",keywords:["reaction","tension","compression","wood","softwood","hardwood","bow","stress","release"],answer:"Trees on slopes or in wind develop reaction wood — wood with internal stresses to keep the tree growing upright. In softwoods, reaction wood is on the lower side of leaning branches (compression wood) — it's darker, denser, and often has abnormal growth. In hardwoods, reaction wood is on the upper side (tension wood) — it's lighter, weak in compression, and furry after cutting. Reaction wood releases stress as you cut it — boards spring and bind saw blades. Cut extra length and expect to flatten more than usual."},{id:"mc-tearout-prevention",topic:"Tearout prevention techniques",keywords:["tearout","prevent","sharp","back","bevel","downcut","score","blade","plane"],answer:"Tearout happens when wood fibers are lifted instead of cut. Prevention: keep tools sharp (sharp tools slice, dull tools tear); plane in the correct grain direction; score a knife line before routing or sawing across grain; use a backing board when drilling through (drill press or clamp scrap below); use a zero-clearance insert on the table saw; take lighter cuts on figured wood with a tight plane mouth. On the router table, run a final light climb cut to eliminate tearout from the standard direction if needed."},{id:"mc-cupping-flattening",topic:"Cupping causes and how to flatten cupped boards",keywords:["cupping","cup","cup","warp","flatten","plane","wet","moisture","caul"],answer:"Boards cup across their width when one face dries faster than the other (the faster-drying face becomes concave). To flatten: for mild cupping, wet the concave face with a damp cloth, place it concave-side-down on a flat surface, and let it flatten overnight under weight. Then joint the convex face flat first on the jointer, then thickness plane. For severe cupping, handplane the convex face first to reduce it, then joint and plane. Store boards standing on edge or fully supported to prevent cupping during storage."},{id:"mc-bowing-fixing",topic:"Bow and crook in lumber — should you fix it",keywords:["bow","crook","warp","long","flat","mill","waste","reject","joint"],answer:"Bow (curve along the length of the face) and crook (curve along the edge length) are removed by milling. Joint the face first — the bow means only the high points contact the jointer in the first pass. Repeated light passes bring the board to flat. If the bow is severe, the waste to flatten it will significantly reduce thickness; calculate whether the resulting board is thick enough for your purposes. Buying rough-sawn stock thicker than needed gives you more room to flatten bowed boards."},{id:"mc-twisting-fixing",topic:"Twist (wind) in lumber and how to remove it",keywords:["twist","wind","winding","stick","diagonal","plane","diagonal","face","check"],answer:"Twist (wind) means opposite corners of the board are not in the same plane. Use winding sticks to identify the high corners. Mark the high corners and plane diagonally across the face (at 45° to the length) to remove the high corners first, then work toward flat with strokes parallel to the grain. The jointer removes twist only if you can get one face fully supported on the table — with severe twist, it rocks, and the jointer makes it worse. Hand plane twist first before using the jointer."},{id:"mc-drilling-blowout",topic:"Preventing blowout when drilling through wood",keywords:["blowout","drill","exit","through","backing","clamp","forstner","spade","brad"],answer:"When a drill bit exits wood, it pushes the last few fibers out rather than cutting them, creating a ragged exit hole (blowout). Prevention: clamp a piece of scrap wood tightly against the exit face and drill through both. On the drill press, use a sacrificial backer on the table. Slow feed rate and sharp bits help. For the cleanest exit hole, drill from both sides, meeting in the middle — requires accurate center marking. Forstner bits blowout less than spade bits; brad-point bits less than twist drills."},{id:"mc-chipout-crosscuts",topic:"Preventing chipout on crosscuts",keywords:["chipout","crosscut","veneered","plywood","score","blade","back","zero","clearance"],answer:`Crosscutting veneered plywood or hardwood produces chipout on the exit face. Prevention: zero-clearance insert in the table saw (supports fibers right up to the blade); score the cut line with a knife before sawing; use a fine-tooth blade (60+ teeth for 10" blade); apply blue painter's tape along the cut line; use a circular saw with a track (fine blade, scored tape on exit). On the miter saw, back the cut with a sacrificial fence attachment.`},{id:"mc-end-grain-staining",topic:"End grain absorbing stain too darkly",keywords:["end","grain","stain","dark","absorb","seal","pre-coat","control"],answer:"End grain is extremely absorbent — stain soaks in 5–10x more than face grain, turning end grain dramatically darker. To equalize: apply a diluted coat of finish (shellac, 10% poly) or end grain sealer, let dry, sand lightly, then stain. Some end grain darkening is acceptable and expected, but untreated end grain on a stained piece looks jarring. Test your sealing strategy on scrap cut from the same board before working on the actual piece."},{id:"mc-grain-direction-milling",topic:"Reading grain direction before milling",keywords:["grain","direction","milling","jointer","planer","read","fiber","uphill","downhill"],answer:`Before running a board through the jointer or planer, look at the edge to determine grain direction. Fibers that slope "downhill" in the direction you're feeding will be cut cleanly. Fibers that slope "uphill" in the feed direction will be lifted and torn. Flip the board if needed — most boards have at least one direction where the grain runs favorably. On boards with reversing grain, reduce depth of cut to 1/32" or less and accept that one section will tearout regardless — hand plane it after machining.`},{id:"mc-punky-wood",topic:"Working with punky (partially decayed) wood",keywords:["punky","soft","rot","stabilize","epoxy","firming","consolidant","pen","turning"],answer:"Punky wood has partially decayed, crumbly fibers. Small areas can be stabilized with thin penetrating epoxy (System Three SilverTip or similar) — flood the area, let it soak in, and reapply until the wood firms up. For pen and small turning blanks, commercial wood stabilizing resins (vacuum-pressure impregnation) produce a very firm blank from highly punky material. Machining stabilized punky wood requires sharp tools — it's abrasive from the epoxy. Never use structurally punky wood in load-bearing applications."},{id:"mc-interlocked-grain-challenge",topic:"Working with interlocked grain woods",keywords:["interlocked","grain","elm","sapele","tearout","handplane","scraper","direction"],answer:'Interlocked grain reverses direction every few inches — the wood fibers literally corkscrew around the tree. Any planing direction will tear out in some zones. Strategies: take very light cuts (0.001"–0.003" plane depth) with a very sharp, tightly set plane; use a high cutting angle on the plane iron (50°–55° instead of 45°); use a card scraper instead of a plane for final surface prep; or sand with progressive grits rather than planing at all. Accept that these woods require more finishing time.'},{id:"mc-nail-pops",topic:"Nail pops in face-framed cabinets",keywords:["nail","pop","brad","finish","face","frame","show","move","seasonal"],answer:"Nail pops occur when the wood shrinks and the fastener stays in place, pushing a small bump above the surface. Prevention: use screws or pocket screws instead of brads for face frames; keep the wood at equilibrium moisture content before assembling; use small finish brads (not larger ring-shank nails) only to hold while glue sets. If nails pop after installation, drive them below the surface with a nail set, fill with putty, and refinish. In a heated interior, seasonal shrinkage is unavoidable — design accordingly."},{id:"mc-lumber-grades",topic:"Hardwood lumber grades — FAS, Select, Common",keywords:["grade","FAS","select","common","1","2","face","yield","clear","better"],answer:`FAS (Firsts and Seconds) is the highest hardwood grade — boards 6"+ wide, 8'+ long, with 83%+ clear face area. Select is nearly FAS quality in shorter boards. #1 Common has 66%+ clear yield — good for furniture with cutting optimization. #2 Common has 50%+ clear — economical for rustic work and smaller parts. For furniture, #1 Common often offers the best value — the lower price more than offsets the extra cutting time. FAS is worth the premium only for wide, long, clear parts you can't get from lesser grades.`},{id:"mc-quartersawn-quarter",topic:"What 4/4, 5/4, 6/4 lumber thickness means",keywords:["4/4","5/4","6/4","8/4","quarter","rough","actual","thickness","lumber"],answer:'4/4 lumber is nominally 1" thick rough-sawn (actually 1–1-1/8"). After surfacing, it typically yields 13/16"–7/8". 5/4 gives about 1-1/16" surfaced, 6/4 gives about 1-5/16", 8/4 gives about 1-3/4". The fractions refer to 1/4" increments of rough-sawn thickness. Buy extra thickness for heavily bowed stock that needs significant milling. Specify "S2S" (surfaced two sides) if you want the yard to plane both faces; "rough" or "rough sawn" means you mill it yourself.'},{id:"mc-moisture-meter",topic:"Using a moisture meter for lumber",keywords:["moisture","meter","reading","percent","MC","pin","pinless","species","correction"],answer:"A pin-type moisture meter drives two probes into the wood; a pinless meter uses electromagnetic fields to read moisture without penetrating. Pin meters are more accurate at a specific depth; pinless meters scan a larger area quickly. Target moisture content for interior furniture: 6–8% in dry climates, 7–9% in moderate climates. Most meters need a species correction factor since different woods have different electrical resistance — use the correction table in the manual. Take multiple readings along the board."},{id:"mc-air-drying-rates",topic:"Air drying rates for different species and thicknesses",keywords:["air","dry","time","rate","year","inch","thickness","sticker","rule"],answer:`The traditional rule: one year of air drying per inch of thickness. This varies significantly: softwoods and lighter hardwoods (poplar, butternut) dry faster; dense hardwoods (oak, hickory, walnut) dry slower. A 4/4 (1") walnut board needs 1–2 years minimum; 8/4 (2") needs 3–4 years. Proper stickering (3/4" dry sticks every 16"–24"), good airflow, shaded storage, and sealed end grain all speed the process and reduce checking. Check with a moisture meter before using — don't guess by time alone.`},{id:"mc-kiln-dried-types",topic:"Kiln drying methods — conventional, dehumidification, RF",keywords:["kiln","dried","conventional","dehumidifier","radio","frequency","method","fast","slow"],answer:"Conventional kiln drying uses forced hot air and humidity control — the standard for commercial lumber. Dehumidification kilns work at lower temperatures and are common in small custom operations. Radio frequency (RF) kilns use microwave-like energy to dry from the inside out — very fast (days vs months) but can cause checking if not carefully controlled. Air-dried lumber is often considered superior for stability by some craftspeople — slower drying allows stresses to equalize gradually."},{id:"mc-acclimatizing-lumber",topic:"Acclimatizing lumber to the shop before use",keywords:["acclimate","acclimatize","shop","humidity","moisture","days","weeks","sticker","indoor"],answer:"Bring lumber into your shop and sticker it (stack with spacers) for at least 2 weeks — 4 weeks or more is better, especially for 6/4+ stock. The wood will adjust its moisture content to match the shop environment. Check with a moisture meter when you start and at the end of the acclimation period — when the reading stabilizes, the wood has equalized. Never mill and immediately build — wood milled cold or from a humid outdoor environment will move significantly in the first week inside."},{id:"mc-milling-sequence",topic:"Milling sequence for dimensioning lumber",keywords:["mill","sequence","order","face","joint","edge","thickness","crosscut","flatten","first"],answer:"The correct milling sequence: (1) flatten one face on the jointer (reference face); (2) joint one edge square to the flat face (reference edge); (3) thickness-plane the opposite face parallel to the reference face; (4) rip to final width on the table saw with the reference edge against the fence; (5) crosscut to length. Never skip steps or change the order — each step depends on the reference surfaces created by the previous. Mark reference face and edge with chalk before starting."},{id:"mc-reading-end-grain",topic:"Reading end grain to identify cuts and species",keywords:["end","grain","read","rings","pore","species","identify","quartersawn","plain"],answer:`End grain tells the whole story. Annual rings running roughly parallel to the face = flatsawn (cathedral grain on face). Rings running perpendicular to the face = quartersawn (straight grain on face). Dense, small uniform pores = diffuse-porous (maple, cherry). Large distinct early-wood pores = ring-porous (oak, ash). Color, pore size, and ray width help identify species. A reference guide (Hoadley's "Identifying Wood") with a hand lens is the most reliable field identification tool.`},{id:"mc-buying-figured",topic:"Tips for buying figured wood at the lumber yard",keywords:["figured","buy","selection","flash","chatoyance","lighting","wet","choose","yard"],answer:"Figured wood hides in a dry lumber stack — take a damp sponge and wet the face to reveal figure. The moisture simulates a finish and makes curly, quilted, and ray fleck pop clearly. Bring a small LED flashlight and rake it across the surface at various angles — chatoyance (3D ripple effect) is angle-dependent. Pull the board fully out of the rack and sight down its length for bow and twist. Buying figured wood requires physically selecting at the yard; online purchasing is a gamble."},{id:"mc-sawyer-direct",topic:"Buying lumber direct from a sawyer",keywords:["sawyer","direct","portable","mill","fresh","green","low","cost","custom"],answer:"Buying directly from a local sawyer gives access to unusual species, large slabs, fresh-sawn lumber, and custom-cut dimensions at lower cost than lumber yards. The tradeoff: the lumber is usually green (unseasoned) and you must dry it yourself — years, not weeks. Some sawyers sell air-dried lumber if you're willing to wait for their stock to season. Local Facebook groups, Craigslist, and state woodworking guild forums are good sources. Bring your moisture meter and a flashlight."},{id:"mc-rough-vs-s4s",topic:"Rough sawn vs S2S vs S4S lumber",keywords:["rough","S2S","S4S","surfaced","dressed","mill","ready","four","two","sides"],answer:"Rough sawn lumber comes straight from the mill — irregular surfaces, possibly still air-drying. S2S (surfaced 2 sides) has both faces planed flat but edges are still rough. S4S (surfaced 4 sides) has faces and edges planed and is ready to use at nominal thickness. Rough sawn from a hardwood dealer is the best value but requires your own milling. S4S from a home center is convenient but expensive per board foot and limited to a few species. S2S is a good middle ground from a hardwood dealer."},{id:"mc-plywood-buying",topic:"Buying plywood — what to check before purchasing",keywords:["plywood","buy","check","flat","void","delaminate","warp","face","core","quality"],answer:"Before buying a plywood sheet, hold it vertical and sight along the face for bow — slight bow is common and usually works itself flat when fastened. Check the face veneer for patching (small football-shaped patches indicate lower grade). Look at the edge for voids in the inner plies — many domestic sheets have voids in cheaper grades. Flex the sheet slightly and listen for delamination sounds. Choose BB or better grade for visible cabinet exteriors; CD or BC for cabinet backs and carcases."},{id:"mc-lumber-species-identify",topic:"Identifying common wood species at the lumber yard",keywords:["identify","species","smell","color","pore","ring","grain","oak","maple","cherry"],answer:`Quick identification clues: Red oak — very open pores, pinkish tan, distinct ring-porous pattern. Maple — very tight grain, white to cream, heavy. Cherry — fine grain, pinkish when fresh, darkens fast, often has gum pockets. Walnut — dark chocolate brown heartwood with distinct grain. Pine — prominent resin canals, soft, yellow-white. Many species are best identified by a combination of color, grain pattern, smell (pine is resinous, cherry has a distinctive scent), and end grain pore structure. Hoadley's "Identifying Wood" is the standard reference.`},{id:"mc-wide-slab-sources",topic:"Sourcing wide solid wood slabs for tabletops",keywords:["slab","wide","tabletop","source","live","edge","local","online","price"],answer:'Wide slabs come from tree removal services, local sawyers, specialty slab dealers, and online marketplaces (Etsy, Hardwood Market, local sawmill Facebook groups). Local tree services are gold — when a large urban tree is removed, contact the owner or service before the log hits the chipper. Slab prices vary wildly: a basic 2" walnut slab might be $30–50/linear foot; figured or exotic slabs can reach $200–400/linear foot. Always see large slabs in person before buying — photos hide defects.'}],r=[{id:"md-waterstone-grits",topic:"Waterstone grit sequence for sharpening",keywords:["waterstone","grit","220","1000","4000","8000","sequence","sharpen","plane","chisel"],answer:"Waterstone sharpening follows a progression from coarse to fine. Damaged or very dull edges start at 220 or 400 grit to reshape the bevel. The 1000 grit removes the previous scratches and refines the edge. The 4000 grit polishes the bevel further. The 6000–8000 grit produces the final keen edge. Each step should fully remove all scratches from the previous stone. Skip a grit and you waste time on fine stones that can't erase the scratches from two grits back."},{id:"md-oilstone-types",topic:"Oilstones — India, Arkansas, and synthetic",keywords:["oilstone","India","Arkansas","coarse","medium","fine","oil","honing"],answer:"Oilstones are the traditional American sharpening medium. India stones are aluminum oxide — coarse, medium, or fine grades for initial sharpening and bevel refinement. Arkansas stones are natural novaculite — soft Arkansas for medium work, hard Arkansas for final polishing, black Arkansas (translucent) for a near-mirror edge. Use honing oil (mineral oil or petroleum-based) to float swarf off the surface. Oilstones cut slowly compared to waterstones but stay flat longer and work without water."},{id:"md-diamond-plates",topic:"Diamond sharpening plates — advantages and uses",keywords:["diamond","plate","sharpen","fast","coarse","flat","stones","chisel","plane"],answer:"Diamond plates cut faster than waterstones or oilstones and don't dish (hollow out). Use them for initial bevel grinding (coarse diamond), flattening waterstones and oilstones, and sharpening carbide. They require water or no lubricant at all (dry). The cutting surface is nickel-plated diamond particles — they wear over time and eventually stop cutting fast. Good diamond plates last years; cheap ones degrade in months. Inexpensive diamond paddles work well for flattening bench plane backs and quick touch-ups."},{id:"md-strop-compound",topic:"Leather strop and honing compound for a keen edge",keywords:["strop","leather","compound","honing","chromium","oxide","green","polish","burr"],answer:`Stropping on leather with honing compound (chromium oxide "green chrome" is the standard) removes the final microscopic burr and polishes the edge to a razor sharpness. Drag the bevel at the sharpening angle AWAY from the edge (spine leading) — pulling toward the edge rolls the burr instead of removing it. 10–20 strokes per side on charged leather is enough. A well-stropped chisel or plane iron can shave end grain cleanly — that's the test for sharp. Strop regularly during use to extend time between full sharpening cycles.`},{id:"md-bevel-angles",topic:"Bevel angle selection for different tools and tasks",keywords:["bevel","angle","degrees","chisel","plane","carving","paring","bench","grind"],answer:"Bevel angles vary by tool and task. Paring chisels: 15°–20° for easy slicing. Bench chisels: 25°–30° for general joinery. Mortise chisels: 30°–35° for lever strength. Bench plane irons: 25°–30° primary, sometimes 35° for hardwoods. Block plane: 20°–25° (bevel up, so effective cutting angle is bed angle + bevel angle). Carving gouges: 10°–15° for softwood, 20°–25° for hardwood. Steeper angles are more durable; lower angles are keener but nick more easily on hard or abrasive woods."},{id:"md-hollow-grind",topic:"Hollow grind vs flat grind for sharpening",keywords:["hollow","grind","flat","wheel","bench","grinder","back","bevel","advantage"],answer:"A hollow grind (from a bench grinder wheel) produces a concave bevel — only the edge and the heel touch the stone during honing. This makes honing faster because less steel touches the stone. A flat grind (from a flat grinding wheel or abrasive sheet) produces a flat bevel that fully contacts the stone — slower to hone but produces a stronger edge (no thin heel that can chip). Both work well; hollow grinds are popular for hand tools, flat grinds for chisels that do heavy mortising work."},{id:"md-micro-bevel",topic:"Micro bevel technique for faster touch-ups",keywords:["micro","bevel","secondary","hone","quick","touch","up","angle","degree"],answer:'A micro bevel raises the honing angle 2°–5° above the primary bevel angle and creates a tiny secondary bevel at the very edge. The advantage: you only need to touch the small micro bevel on the fine stone for quick touch-ups between heavy sharpening sessions — far less steel to remove. Lift the tool slightly higher on the stone to engage only the micro bevel. When the micro bevel gets wide (more than 1/16"), re-grind the primary bevel to reset the process.'},{id:"md-back-bevel",topic:"Back bevel on plane irons for high-angle cutting",keywords:["back","bevel","plane","high","angle","tearout","figured","steep","effective"],answer:"A back bevel adds a small bevel on the flat back of a plane iron — if the primary bevel is 25° and you add a 5° back bevel, the effective cutting angle becomes 30°. Higher effective cutting angles reduce tearout in figured or interlocked grain. On bevel-up planes (low angle, block, shoulder), back bevel is the standard way to increase cutting angle. On bevel-down (bench) planes, a steeper primary bevel is easier than a back bevel. A 50°–55° effective angle handles most difficult grain."},{id:"md-honing-guides",topic:"Honing guides vs freehand sharpening",keywords:["honing","guide","jig","freehand","angle","consistent","beginner","Veritas","Eclipse"],answer:"Honing guides (Veritas MK.II, Eclipse) hold the tool at a consistent angle across the stone, removing the skill requirement for freehand technique. They're excellent for beginners and for maintaining exact consistent bevel angles. Freehand sharpening is faster once mastered, more adaptable to odd-shaped tools, and requires no setup time. Start with a guide while learning; transition to freehand as you develop muscle memory for the angle. Carving tools almost always need freehand technique — guides don't accommodate gouges."},{id:"md-flattening-stones",topic:"Flattening sharpening stones — why and how",keywords:["flatten","stone","dish","hollow","nagura","lapping","diamond","flat","glass"],answer:"Waterstones dish (hollow out) in the middle quickly with regular use. A dished stone creates a convex bevel on your tools — the opposite of what you want. Flatten regularly (every 3–5 sessions) by rubbing on a diamond plate, wet-dry sandpaper on a flat glass plate, or a dedicated lapping plate. Use circular or figure-8 motions and check flatness with a straightedge. A flat stone is fundamental to good sharpening results — no amount of skill compensates for a dished stone."},{id:"md-grinding-primary-bevel",topic:"Grinding the primary bevel on a bench grinder",keywords:["grind","primary","bevel","bench","grinder","wheel","blue","overheat","temper","cool"],answer:`Use a white aluminum oxide wheel (8" × 1") at 3450 RPM with a tool rest set to the bevel angle. Move the tool smoothly side to side to keep the bevel uniform and prevent grooving the wheel. Quench in water frequently — if the steel turns blue, you've overheated and destroyed the temper at that point. Keep a bowl of cool water at the grinder. The edge should produce sparks that fall toward you (not over the top of the tool) when grinding correctly. Dress the wheel often to keep it flat and cutting freely.`},{id:"md-carving-gouge-sharp",topic:"Sharpening carving gouges — inside and outside bevel",keywords:["carving","gouge","sharpen","slipstone","inside","outside","burr","strop"],answer:"Carving gouges require sharpening both the outside bevel (on a waterstone, rolling the gouge across its curve as you move forward) and removing the wire edge on the inside (with a curved slipstone or rounded strop). The outside bevel should be polished to 8000 grit; the inside just needs the burr removed with a few strokes. Sharp carving gouges cleanly slice end grain and leave a burnished, not torn, surface. Test sharpness by paring end grain — it should pare cleanly with no effort."},{id:"md-when-to-regrind",topic:"When to hone vs when to regrind the bevel",keywords:["regrind","hone","micro","bevel","wide","nick","chip","dull","decide"],answer:`Hone (sharpen on fine stones only) when the edge is dull from normal use — the micro bevel has widened. Regrind (reshape on a coarse stone or grinder) when there's a chip in the edge, the bevel has become too convex from repeated honing, or the micro bevel is more than 1/8" wide. A quick test: if you can sharpen to a keen edge in under 2 minutes on a 1000 grit stone, just hone. If it takes much longer with little improvement, it's time to regrind the primary bevel.`},{id:"md-sharpness-tests",topic:"Testing sharpness — multiple methods",keywords:["sharp","test","paper","hair","arm","thumb","light","reflect","end","grain"],answer:"Several sharpness tests: arm hair test — a truly sharp edge shaves arm hair cleanly. Thumbnail test — drag the edge lightly across a fingernail; it should grip, not slide. Paper test — slice newspaper; a sharp edge cuts cleanly, a dull edge tears. Reflecting light test — look at the edge under a light; a sharp edge reflects nothing (invisible), a dull edge reflects a bright thin line. End grain test — pare end grain; sharp tools leave a shiny, smooth surface. For furniture tools, the end grain test is the most practical real-world indicator."},{id:"md-japanese-water-stones",topic:"Japanese natural water stones vs synthetic",keywords:["japanese","natural","water","stone","awasedo","nakayama","synthetic","toishi"],answer:"Natural Japanese finishing stones (awasedo, nakayama) produce extremely fine edges but are expensive ($100–$1000+), variable in quality, and require careful storage to prevent cracking. Synthetic Japanese stones (King, Naniwa, Shapton) are consistent, affordable, and excellent quality — used by most professional woodworkers. Shapton Kuromaku and Naniwa Chosera are considered among the best synthetic options. Natural stones are prized mainly by high-end woodworkers, knife makers, and collectors; synthetics are the practical choice for a working shop."},{id:"md-face-vise-setup",topic:"Face vise setup and use on a workbench",keywords:["face","vise","bench","front","left","right","dog","screw","clamp"],answer:'The face vise is mounted on the front-left corner of the bench for right-handers (front-right for left-handers). Its jaws clamp work for planing, sawing, and chiseling. Wide vises (7"+ jaw width) support wide panels. A wooden jaw liner (hardwood laminate on the inner vise jaw) prevents marking workpieces. Many face vises have a quick-release mechanism to adjust width rapidly. Set the inner jaw face flush with the bench top — the bench top and vise top form one flat reference plane.'},{id:"md-leg-vise",topic:"Leg vise advantages for hand tool work",keywords:["leg","vise","parallel","guide","crisscross","large","hold","traditional"],answer:`A leg vise mounts on the front leg and uses a large wooden jaw that travels parallel to the bench leg — typically 24" tall or more. The parallel guide (a wooden arm or crisscross mechanism below the vise) keeps the jaw parallel to the leg as it opens. Leg vises can hold very wide or irregular work that won't fit in a standard face vise. They're the traditional European workbench vise and are making a strong comeback among hand tool workers. Building your own leg vise from a hardware kit is a satisfying first project.`},{id:"md-tail-vise",topic:"Tail vise and wagon vise for panel work",keywords:["tail","vise","wagon","end","bench","dog","panel","planing"],answer:"The tail vise (or wagon vise) is at the right end of the bench and is used with bench dogs — round or square pegs in holes along the bench top and the vise. Clamp long boards or wide panels between the bench dog in the vise and another dog further along the bench top. The work lies flat on the bench and is clamped from the side rather than from below, keeping the surface clear for planing. Tail vises are complex to build; a simpler alternative is a Moxon vise for panel flattening."},{id:"md-moxon-vise",topic:"Moxon vise for dovetail and joint work",keywords:["moxon","vise","portable","twin","screw","dovetail","top","clamp","low"],answer:"The Moxon vise is a simple twin-screw wooden vise that clamps to the front of the workbench with holdfasts or clamps. Its high profile raises the work to a comfortable hand-sawing height — ideal for dovetail and other detailed joinery. Build one from hardwood and hardware store threaded rod in an afternoon. Sit the Moxon vise on the bench to raise work for dovetailing; remove it when bench space is needed. Many woodworkers consider the Moxon essential for comfortable, accurate hand joinery."},{id:"md-holdfast-use",topic:"Holdfasts for quick clamping to the bench",keywords:["holdfast","bench","hole","anvil","quick","hammer","clamp","shaft"],answer:`A holdfast is a metal shaft (often L-shaped) that drops into a hole in the bench top — a smart tap with a mallet locks it fast via wedging action. Tap the side to release instantly. They're extremely fast for positioning and repositioning work on the bench. Holdfasts need holes exactly matched to the shaft diameter (3/4" for most Gramercy and Crucible holdfasts) and a bench top at least 3" thick for good grip. They're one of the most satisfying traditional shop tools to use.`},{id:"md-clamp-types",topic:"Clamp types for different woodworking tasks",keywords:["clamp","types","parallel","pipe","bar","F","spring","band","Bessey"],answer:"Parallel jaw clamps (Bessey, Jet) apply even pressure along the full jaw width — best for panel glue-ups, less racking than bar clamps. Pipe clamps use standard plumbing pipe as the beam — inexpensive and infinitely extendable. Bar clamps are lighter than pipe clamps but limited to their bar length. F-clamps (C-clamps with sliding bar) are fast and useful for clamping assemblies to the bench. Spring clamps are quick for light-duty tacking while other clamps set. Band clamps (strap clamps) wrap around irregular shapes and polygon frames."},{id:"md-crosscut-sled",topic:"Building and using a crosscut sled",keywords:["crosscut","sled","table","saw","square","accurate","stop","block","jig"],answer:"A crosscut sled runs in the table saw miter slots on runners, carrying work past the blade with precision and support. The key: the fence must be exactly perpendicular to the blade. Calibrate by testing: cut a known-square piece of MDF in half, flip one piece, and check for any gap at the joint — any gap doubles the error. Adjust by shimming the fence. Add a stop block for repeatable lengths. A well-made crosscut sled is more accurate and safer than a miter gauge for crosscutting solid wood."},{id:"md-tenon-jig",topic:"Tenon jig for table saw tenon cutting",keywords:["tenon","jig","table","saw","vertical","hold","fence","shoulder","cheek"],answer:"A tenon jig holds the workpiece vertically against a fence and rides along the rip fence to cut tenon cheeks. The cheek cuts run with the grain in a vertical orientation — safer and cleaner than horizontal cheek cuts with a dado stack. After cheek cuts, lay the piece flat to cut the shoulders with a crosscut sled. Commercial tenon jigs (Kreg, Woodpeckers) are robust and accurate; building your own from scrap is a common shop project. Test each tenon for fit in a test mortise before final cuts."},{id:"md-box-joint-jig",topic:"Box joint jig construction and setup",keywords:["box","joint","jig","key","spacing","router","table","saw","index"],answer:"The box joint jig consists of a fence with a key (a small wooden or metal pin the same width as the joint fingers) attached to the miter gauge or router table fence. Cut the first slot, place it over the key, cut the next slot, and so on. Key placement relative to the blade determines finger spacing. The most common method: cut the first slot at the blade, then move the fence so the slot is exactly one finger-width from the blade (using the key). Minor adjustments correct for tight or loose fitting joints."},{id:"md-taper-jig",topic:"Taper jig for cutting tapered legs",keywords:["taper","jig","leg","table","saw","set","angle","shopmade","sliding"],answer:"A taper jig holds stock at an angle to the saw blade for ripping a taper. Commercial taper jigs have two arms that pivot and lock at the desired angle. Shop-made taper jigs are a notched board with a stop at the end — the notch determines the taper. For a four-sided taper, taper two faces first, rotate 90°, and rest the tapered face against the jig for the second two cuts. Make a test cut in scrap to confirm the taper angle before cutting finished legs."},{id:"md-circle-cutting-jig",topic:"Router circle jig for round tabletops",keywords:["circle","jig","router","round","tabletop","radius","pivot","pin","trammel"],answer:'A circle-cutting jig mounts to the router base with a pivot pin that sits at the center of the circle. The radius from pin to bit equals the circle radius. Drill a small hole at the center of your blank, seat the pivot pin, and rout in a clockwise direction in multiple shallow passes. A router circle jig produces perfect circles impossible to achieve any other way. Alternatively, bandsaw close to the line first and use the router jig only for the final 1/8" — this puts less load on the bit and gives a cleaner edge.'},{id:"md-doweling-jig",topic:"Self-centering doweling jig setup",keywords:["doweling","jig","self","centering","align","drill","guide","hole","accurate"],answer:"Self-centering doweling jigs have jaws that grip the stock and automatically center the drill guide on the stock thickness regardless of width — ideal for edge-to-face joints and rail-to-leg connections. Lock the jig at the correct position along the board (mark your center line), drill to depth with the appropriate bit. Repeat on the mating piece with the jig in the same position. The key: always register the jig from the same face on both pieces so holes align even if the jig isn't perfectly centered."},{id:"md-vacuum-clamping",topic:"Vacuum clamping for router template work",keywords:["vacuum","clamp","hold","template","pod","cup","pump","flat","bottom"],answer:`Vacuum clamping uses atmospheric pressure (~14.7 psi) to hold flat workpieces without clamps obstructing the surface. A vacuum pump (or venturi venturi) evacuates air from a pad or pod under the workpiece. Works best on flat, non-porous material — porous wood needs a sealed face or a vacuum bag. Holding force = 14.7 psi × contact area in sq. in. A 6"×6" pad provides 529 lbs of holding force — more than sufficient for routing operations. Add a veneer or MDF face to the workpiece if it's porous.`},{id:"md-featherboard-function",topic:"Featherboard function and placement",keywords:["featherboard","pressure","fence","blade","table","saw","router","spring","hold"],answer:"A featherboard applies spring pressure to push the workpiece against the fence or table surface — preventing it from drifting and catching. It must be placed BEFORE the blade or bit (never at the blade or after) — a featherboard at the blade would trap the cut piece and cause kickback. Position it so the fingers flex back when the stock pushes past. Commercial featherboards clamp to the table with T-bolts; shop-made versions use a notched board clamped to the fence. Use one on the fence and optionally one on the table surface for router table work."},{id:"md-shooting-board",topic:"Shooting board for accurate edges and miters",keywords:["shooting","board","edge","plane","square","miter","45","accurate","thin"],answer:"A shooting board is a flat platform with a fence at 90° (or 45°) to the running surface. A hand plane rides on its side along the shooting board to true up the end of a board perfectly square or at a precise 45°. Essential for accurate miter joints where gaps are unacceptable. The bench plane rides on the shooting board sole, making a shearing cut across the grain — the square fence registers the workpiece. Shooting board miters can be fit to a knife-line accuracy not possible with any power tool."},{id:"md-bench-hook",topic:"Bench hook for one-handed crosscutting",keywords:["bench","hook","crosscut","hand","saw","secure","one","hand","seat","stop"],answer:"A bench hook is a simple shop-made device: a flat board with a cleat on the bottom that hooks over the bench front, and a cleat on top that acts as a back stop for the workpiece. Rest the work against the top cleat and saw on the near side — the bench hook keeps the work from moving. The bottom cleat keeps the hook on the bench. Make several in different sizes. The bench hook works with no clamping — just hook it over the bench edge and you're ready to saw."},{id:"md-kickback-mechanics",topic:"Table saw kickback — mechanics and prevention",keywords:["kickback","table","saw","riving","knife","anti","pawl","splitter","fence","cause"],answer:"Kickback happens when a board gets pinched between the blade and the fence (or fence and riving knife) and the spinning blade launches it toward the operator at 100+ mph. Prevention: always use the riving knife (keeps the kerf open behind the blade), never stand directly behind the blade, never use the fence and miter gauge simultaneously, keep the blade height just above the stock. A stock that veers into the blade (because the fence is slightly toe-in at the back) is a kickback setup — fence must be parallel to the blade."},{id:"md-riving-knife",topic:"Riving knife vs splitter — what is the difference",keywords:["riving","knife","splitter","difference","follow","blade","SawStop","modern"],answer:"A riving knife follows the blade as it tilts — it stays behind the blade at all bevel angles and at all blade heights. A fixed splitter is only in the correct position at a specific blade height and doesn't move with blade tilt. Riving knives are the modern standard on all European and newer North American table saws. If your saw has only a fixed splitter, use it anyway — it's far better than nothing. Never remove the riving knife or splitter for dado cuts without a dado guard."},{id:"md-push-stick-design",topic:"Push stick design and when to use it",keywords:["push","stick","design","narrow","rip","blade","guard","hand","safe","distance"],answer:'A push stick keeps your hands away from the table saw blade for narrow rips (under 6" wide) and anytime a piece requires your hand to pass near the blade. The notch-style push stick contacts the rear edge of the board and pushes through the cut. A push block (like a Grr-Ripper) provides downward pressure and side pressure simultaneously — better control. Make several push sticks from scrap and replace them when they get nicked. Always reach for a push stick rather than your fingers when a cut gets tight.'},{id:"md-router-safety-detail",topic:"Router safety — bit installation and speed",keywords:["router","safety","bit","collet","speed","large","starter","pin","guard"],answer:'Install bits with at least 3/4" of shank in the collet — never shallow-seated. Tighten with two wrenches (not one). Unplug before changing bits. For freehand routing, secure the workpiece firmly — two hands on the router, no exceptions. Large bits (over 1.5" diameter) need speeds under 16,000 RPM. Always rout against the bit rotation (conventional direction) unless doing a final light climb cut. Wear eye protection — routers launch chips at high velocity. Ear protection is mandatory — routers are extremely loud.'},{id:"md-fine-dust-health",topic:"Fine wood dust health dangers",keywords:["dust","fine","micron","10","lung","cancer","sensitize","health","long","term"],answer:"Particles below 10 microns (invisible to the eye) penetrate deeply into lungs and are the most dangerous. Regular shop dust collectors filter down to 1–5 microns typically; cyclone separators help capture fine particles before the filter. Many wood species are carcinogenic with long-term exposure (walnut, oak, certain tropical species). Sensitization develops over time — years of exposure can lead to asthma and allergic reactions that worsen. A basic dust collector removes visible dust; fine dust requires a filter rated to 1 micron or better, plus respiratory protection."},{id:"md-respirator-types",topic:"Respirator types for woodworking",keywords:["respirator","N95","P100","half","face","HEPA","OV","finish","spray","dust"],answer:"N95 filters particles ≥0.3 microns and blocks 95% — adequate for light sanding on non-toxic species. P100 filters 99.97% of particles including the finest wood dust and is the minimum for heavy production sanding, toxic species, and finishing operations. For spray finishing, add OV (organic vapor) cartridges to the P100 half-face respirator — the particulate filter alone doesn't remove vapor. Half-face respirators with P100+OV combination cartridges cover both dust and finish vapors in one unit. Disposable N95 masks are inconvenient but better than nothing."},{id:"md-spontaneous-combustion",topic:"Spontaneous combustion of oily rags — the real risk",keywords:["spontaneous","combustion","rag","oily","fire","danish","linseed","tung","dispose"],answer:"Oily rags (linseed oil, danish oil, tung oil) can self-ignite through exothermic oxidation as the oil cures — no external flame required. A pile of oil-soaked rags can reach ignition temperature in under an hour. Every year shops burn down from this. Always: spread oil-soaked rags flat on a non-combustible surface outside to dry completely before disposal. Or submerge in water in a metal can with a lid. Never ball them up or throw them in a trash bin while still wet with oil. Water-based finishes don't carry this risk."},{id:"md-dust-collector-cfm",topic:"Dust collector CFM requirements for shop machines",keywords:["dust","collector","cfm","volume","shop","machine","table","saw","planer","require"],answer:'CFM (cubic feet per minute) determines whether a dust collector can keep up with chip production. Table saw: 400–700 CFM. Jointer (8"): 400 CFM. Planer (13"): 500–800 CFM. Bandsaw: 350 CFM. Router table: 300 CFM. These are minimums — bigger is better. A 1-1/2 HP shop vac produces ~100–150 CFM — adequate for routers and sanders but not planers or table saws. A 1.5 HP dedicated dust collector provides ~600–800 CFM with proper hose sizing. Hose length and elbows reduce CFM — minimize runs and bends.'},{id:"md-hearing-protection-nrr",topic:"Hearing protection NRR ratings for woodworking",keywords:["hearing","protection","NRR","decibel","earmuff","earplug","reduce","noise"],answer:"NRR (Noise Reduction Rating) measures how many decibels a hearing protector reduces. A router runs ~100 dB; 85+ dB causes hearing damage with sustained exposure. NRR 33 earplugs reduce by ~16 dB in real use (the formula: NRR - 7) ÷ 2 for field performance). For very loud tools, double up — earplugs under earmuffs. Most woodworking requires NRR 25–33 protection. Never run a table saw, jointer, planer, or router without hearing protection — one hour a day over years causes permanent irreversible damage."},{id:"md-bandsaw-safety",topic:"Bandsaw safety considerations",keywords:["bandsaw","safety","guard","blade","tension","crack","weld","speed","curve"],answer:"Keep the upper blade guard close to the workpiece — just above the work. Never reach around a moving blade. If the blade drifts off a cut, stop and restart rather than twisting the work to compensate (blade weld failure can happen). Slow feed on curves — forcing a turn wider than the blade TPI allows causes blade buckling. Check blade welds periodically for stress cracks at the weld point. The bandsaw is generally safer than the table saw but still demands full attention; most bandsaw injuries happen to fingers reaching near the blade to adjust work."},{id:"md-chisel-safety",topic:"Chisel safety — direction and hand placement",keywords:["chisel","safety","direction","hand","behind","guard","controlled","slip"],answer:"Never put your non-holding hand in front of the chisel cutting direction — if it slips, the blade goes toward that hand. Clamp the work so both hands are on the chisel. Pare across a corner away from your body, not toward it. Keep chisels sharp — dull chisels require force that causes slipping. Store chisels with their edges protected (a tool roll, rack with edge guards, or individual blade covers). Never leave a chisel edge-up on the bench where it can be accidentally grasped edge-first."},{id:"md-oily-shop-rag-storage",topic:"Safe storage of shop rags and cloths",keywords:["rag","storage","metal","can","water","fire","safe","lid","dispose"],answer:"The safest method for used finishing rags: keep a metal can with a tight-fitting lid filled with water. Drop rags into the water immediately after use — the water prevents the oxidation reaction that causes spontaneous combustion. Dispose of the can contents (now harmless, water-soaked rags) at a hazardous waste collection site or let the rags fully dry outside spread flat, then dispose in regular trash. A $25 Justrite safety can is a lifetime investment against shop fires."},{id:"md-table-saw-stance",topic:"Body positioning at the table saw",keywords:["stance","table","saw","position","body","kickback","line","stand","feet"],answer:"Never stand directly behind the blade or in line with the blade — this is the kickback danger zone. Stand to the left of the blade line (for right-handed operators) so a kickback event fires to your right, not into your body. Keep your left arm behind your body to avoid having it in the kickback path when feeding narrow stock. Keep feet shoulder-width apart, balanced but mobile. Never stretch beyond comfortable reach — walk around for long boards rather than leaning over the blade."},{id:"md-jointer-pushblock",topic:"Jointer push blocks and finger injury prevention",keywords:["jointer","push","block","finger","guard","hand","clear","blade","over"],answer:"The jointer outfeed section is the danger zone — fingers can reach the cutter head as the board passes. Use push blocks that straddle the fence and table to keep hands clear of the cutter head. Never back-feed (pull wood back over the cutter head). Use featherboards to maintain consistent fence pressure. Keep the guard over the non-working side of the cutter head. Jointers account for a high percentage of serious woodworking injuries — treat them with full respect and use push blocks for every pass."},{id:"md-cabinet-face-frame",topic:"Face frame cabinet construction details",keywords:["face","frame","cabinet","construction","rail","stile","overlay","inset","pocket"],answer:"Face frame cabinets have a solid wood frame (stiles and rails) glued and screwed to the front of a plywood or particleboard box. The frame creates a finished front, hides the box construction, and provides a robust mounting surface for hinges and drawer slides. Stiles are the vertical frame members; rails are horizontal. Pocket screws are the fastest assembly method for face frames. Overlay doors and inset doors are both possible — inset requires the box and frame to be built to tighter tolerances."},{id:"md-frameless-cabinet",topic:"Frameless (European) cabinet construction",keywords:["frameless","european","32mm","box","cabinet","overlay","full","efficiency","quick"],answer:'Frameless cabinets have no face frame — the door and drawer fronts overlap the box sides completely (full overlay). The box is built from 3/4" plywood or particleboard with dado-and-rabbet joints. The 32mm hole system spaces hinge holes, shelf pin holes, and drawer slide mounting holes on a 32mm grid. Frameless construction is faster, requires less wood, and provides maximum interior access. Hinges must be European cup hinges (adjustable, concealed). The interior is completely accessible with drawers open, unlike face frame cabinets.'},{id:"md-cabinet-back-options",topic:"Cabinet back options — dado vs rabbet vs surface mount",keywords:["cabinet","back","dado","rabbet","surface","mount","1/4","plywood","square"],answer:"Three main approaches for cabinet backs. Dado into the sides: strongest, keeps back flush with sides, allows the back to add racking resistance. Rabbet into the back edge of the sides: fast, back overlaps the sides slightly. Surface mount: just screw a plywood panel to the back of the assembled box — easiest but adds depth and looks less finished. For furniture-grade work, dado the back into all four sides and glue it in for maximum rigidity. For shop cabinets, surface mount is quick and adequate."},{id:"md-drawer-construction",topic:"Drawer box construction — sizing and materials",keywords:["drawer","box","size","clearance","height","width","sides","bottom","plywood"],answer:'Size a drawer box to the opening: width = opening width minus clearance for slides (check slide specs — undermount usually need 1/2" less than opening, side mount need slide thickness × 2 less). Height = opening height minus 1/2"–3/4" for clearance and bottom thickness. Drawer bottom: 1/4" plywood in a groove cut 1/4"–3/8" from the bottom edge. Side material: 1/2" Baltic birch or hardwood is traditional; 5/8" particleboard is commercial standard. The bottom slides in dry (no glue) to allow movement, but can be pinned from below at the back.'},{id:"md-drawer-dovetail-layout",topic:"Laying out drawer dovetail spacing",keywords:["drawer","dovetail","layout","spacing","even","pin","tail","half","pin","end"],answer:'For a classic drawer front dovetail layout: begin and end with half-pins (narrower than the tails, typically the same width as your chisel). Divide the remaining space into an odd or even number of equal spaces for tails. Traditional ratios: tails about twice as wide as pins. Space tails evenly using dividers (walk them across until they divide equally). The number of tails depends on drawer width — about one per 1-1/2" is a reasonable guide. Mark all tails on one drawer front, then use it as a template for identical drawers.'},{id:"md-piano-bench-construction",topic:"Bench (seating) construction principles",keywords:["bench","seating","seat","apron","leg","stretcher","joint","height","strength"],answer:'A seat bench needs to resist significant racking forces from side loads and people leaning. Mortise-and-tenon apron-to-leg joints are the historical standard. Stretchers (rails near the floor) tie the legs together and dramatically increase resistance to racking. Seat height for dining: 17"–18". Seat depth: 14"–16". Add a wedge-tenon or drawbore peg through any exposed through tenon for maximum strength. Seat width per person: 20"–24". Check that the bench clears a dining table apron — the seat edge must be reachable without hitting the apron.'},{id:"md-chair-joinery-stress",topic:"Chair joinery for stress and longevity",keywords:["chair","joinery","stress","load","racking","dovetail","wedge","angle","spindle"],answer:"Chairs are the most structurally demanding furniture — they carry dynamic loads and rack in all directions. Mortise-and-tenon with drawbore pegs or wedged through tenons at the back posts. Round tenons (turned) in round mortises for spindles and rungs — the round tenon can't rack. Angled joints (where the rear legs splay back) are the hardest: mortises must be cut at compound angles to match the leg geometry. Glue every joint; chairs assembled with pocket screws alone will fail within years under normal use."},{id:"md-windsor-chair",topic:"Windsor chair construction overview",keywords:["windsor","chair","spindle","turned","seat","bow","rung","green","wood"],answer:"Windsor chairs combine a solid slab seat (scooped with a travisher) with turned spindles, bent steam-bent bows, and turned leg-and-rung bases. Traditionally built with multiple species: white pine seat (soft for seat carving), steam-bent ash or oak for the bow, turned oak or hickory for legs. Green wood (unseasoned) spindles and rungs are turned oversize, then dried — when glued into drilled holes in the dry seat and posts, the dried wood expands with moisture and locks the joint permanently. An elegant, zero-glue joinery system."},{id:"md-tabletop-movement",topic:"Allowing wood movement in tabletops",keywords:["tabletop","movement","attach","clip","slot","season","expand","contract","solid"],answer:'A solid wood tabletop 24" wide might move 3/8"–1/2" seasonally. The top must be attached to the apron in a way that allows this movement in width — NOT along the length (minimal movement in that direction). Figure-8 fasteners, Z-clips, wooden clips in apron slots, or bed bolt-style slotted wooden buttons all work. Never glue or rigidly screw a solid top in multiple places along the grain — it will crack at the glue joints or at the fastener holes when seasonal movement is blocked.'},{id:"md-table-apron-joinery",topic:"Table apron to leg joinery options",keywords:["apron","leg","joinery","mortise","tenon","pocket","screw","table","corner"],answer:'The strongest apron-to-leg joint for tables: mortise-and-tenon, glued and possibly pinned. The tenon extends about 2/3 through the leg, with a 1/4" gap between mating tenons at a corner for a corner block or pocket screw reinforcement. Pocket screws alone are adequate for light-use tables but fail over years under stress. Corner blocks (triangular blocks glued into the inside corner) reinforce the joint and help prevent racking. Metal corner brackets are a functional but less attractive alternative.'},{id:"md-box-construction",topic:"Small box construction techniques",keywords:["box","lid","fit","hinge","miter","rabbet","small","jewelry","trinket"],answer:"Small boxes use mitered corners (reinforced with splines or keys), finger joints, or rabbet and dado construction. Build the box as a complete unit, then cut the lid off with a thin saw blade — this ensures perfect lid alignment. For small hinges, mortise them flush for a clean line. The lid-to-box fit should be snug but open smoothly with light pressure — test the fit before applying finish. Line the box interior with felt, thin suede, or flocked material; apply this before the final assembly step if access is limited."},{id:"md-lid-fitting",topic:"Fitting box and chest lids for a smooth reveal",keywords:["lid","fit","reveal","even","gap","hinge","offset","overhang","chest"],answer:'A well-fitted lid has even gaps all around — typically 1/16"–1/8" for a finished box. Shoot the lid to fit with a hand plane; work on the ends first, then the long edges. Hinge placement affects alignment — offset hinges (surface or mortised) position the pivot differently. Piano hinge on large lids distributes the load evenly and prevents the lid from racking. Lid supports (chain, table leaf hinges, or pneumatic supports) prevent the lid from falling flat and putting stress on the hinges.'},{id:"md-bookcase-shelving",topic:"Bookcase and shelving construction decisions",keywords:["bookcase","shelf","fixed","adjustable","dado","pin","sag","span","load"],answer:'Fixed shelves dadoed into sides are strongest and prevent racking; adjustable shelves on pins are more versatile. For span limits: 3/4" plywood sags noticeably over 36" under book loads; 3/4" solid maple lasts a bit longer. Solutions: edge banding (solid wood front edge adds rigidity), solid wood shelves, thicker stock (1" or more), or center dividers. A 5mm shelf pin in each of four holes provides about 50 lbs per shelf — adequate for most home library loads.'},{id:"md-workbench-design",topic:"Workbench top thickness and vise placement",keywords:["workbench","top","thickness","vise","placement","dog","hole","spacing","mass"],answer:'Workbench top thickness: 3"–4" for a heavy hand tool bench (mass dampens vibration), 2"–2.5" for a lighter combination bench. Vise placement: face vise at the left front corner, leg vise at the left front leg, tail vise at the right end. Dog hole spacing: every 6"–8" across the top in a line parallel to the front edge. The bench dog holes align with the tail vise dog for panel clamping. Workbench height: your palm-to-floor distance is a common guide for hand planing.'},{id:"md-workbench-mass",topic:"Why mass matters in a workbench",keywords:["workbench","mass","heavy","vibration","walk","rattle","stable","weight"],answer:`A heavy bench stays put during planing — it doesn't walk across the shop floor. Mass absorbs the impact of mallet blows and crosscut saws without bouncing or rattling. A laminated hardwood top (maple, beech, oak) at 4" thick weighs 150–250 lbs just for the top. Leg joinery should be mortise-and-tenon for rigidity — a wobbly bench is the bane of accurate hand tool work. If your bench moves during use, add weight (an undershelf of concrete blocks works in a pinch) or improve the leg joinery.`},{id:"md-cabinet-door-fitting",topic:"Fitting cabinet doors for even reveals",keywords:["cabinet","door","fit","reveal","gap","plane","sand","consistent","even"],answer:'Even reveals (the gap between the door edge and cabinet opening) require careful fitting. Start with the door 1/16" oversize in each dimension. Hang the door on one hinge, mark where it binds, and shim to check gap before fixing the second hinge. Plane or sand the door edges on a shooting board for final fitting — work from one edge, hang, check, adjust. Target 1/16"–3/32" reveals all around for face frame inset doors. Frameless full-overlay doors use European hinge adjustment instead of door edge trimming.'},{id:"md-kitchen-cabinet-layout",topic:"Kitchen cabinet standard heights and depths",keywords:["kitchen","cabinet","height","depth","base","wall","upper","standard","clearance"],answer:`Standard kitchen dimensions: base cabinets 34.5" tall (with 1.5" countertop = 36" finished). Base cabinet depth: 24" (23.5" box + door). Wall (upper) cabinets: 12"–13" deep, typically 30" or 42" tall, mounted at 54" from floor (18" clearance above counter). Distance from counter to bottom of upper cabinet: 18" minimum (15" in pantry areas where taller items store on counter). These are standards, not rules — adjust for the specific user's height and functional needs.`},{id:"md-floating-shelves",topic:"Floating shelf construction with hidden brackets",keywords:["floating","shelf","hidden","bracket","hardware","sleeve","cleat","blind"],answer:'Floating shelves appear to hover without visible support. Methods: metal cantilever brackets bolted into studs with the shelf sleeved over them (commercial system); a wall-mounted cleat with a matching routed channel in the shelf back; or heavy-duty blind shelf pins in a drilled shelf edge. Studs are critical for load capacity — only the stud-mounted bracket carries the load. For solid wood floating shelves, cut slightly short (1/8"–1/4") to allow seasonal wood movement across the width without the shelf binding against the wall.'},{id:"md-entertainment-center",topic:"Entertainment center design and AV equipment clearances",keywords:["entertainment","center","tv","av","ventilation","cable","depth","clearance","heat"],answer:`Design entertainment centers with ventilation for AV equipment — amplifiers and receivers generate significant heat. Open backs or ventilation slots in cabinet backs and tops prevent heat buildup. TV depth (if recessed): measure the TV's screen-to-back-of-mount depth carefully. Cable management: plan channels in vertical members from the start — adding them after construction is much harder. Component depth: 24" is standard for current AV equipment, but confirm against your specific gear before building.`},{id:"md-murphy-bed",topic:"Murphy (wall) bed construction basics",keywords:["murphy","bed","wall","fold","piston","spring","hardware","cabinet","counterbalance"],answer:"Murphy beds use counterbalance hardware (pistons or springs) to offset the weight of the mattress so the bed folds up and down effortlessly. Buy a hardware kit first and build the case to the kit's exact dimensions — each manufacturer specifies the case dimensions for their spring system. Mount the unit into studs or with heavy-duty lag bolts into blocking between studs — Murphy beds in use carry 300–500 lbs. Side cabinets and shelving units attached to the Murphy case stabilize the whole unit."},{id:"md-outdoor-furniture",topic:"Outdoor furniture construction principles",keywords:["outdoor","furniture","teak","cedar","stainless","lap","joint","drain","recess"],answer:"Outdoor furniture must drain and dry quickly to prevent rot. Design with drainage: avoid horizontal surfaces that pond water (angle flat surfaces slightly), use open joints rather than fully closed dado joints that trap moisture. Use rot-resistant species (teak, ipe, western red cedar, black locust) or pressure-treated lumber. Fasten with stainless steel or hot-dipped galvanized fasteners — regular steel rusts and stains the wood. Joinery must tolerate seasonal movement more extreme than indoor furniture (40–80% RH range in many climates)."},{id:"md-bed-frame-construction",topic:"Bed frame construction for strength and assembly",keywords:["bed","frame","rail","post","mattress","platform","slat","support","bolt"],answer:'Bed frames must support 500–800 lbs of combined load. Queen and king beds need a center support leg from the mid-rail to the floor. Rail-to-post connections: bed bolts (barrel nuts), mortise-and-tenon with bed bolts, or heavy metal rail-to-post brackets. Platform beds with a slat system: slats should be 3"–4" wide hardwood, spaced 3" maximum. Cover each slat with non-slip fabric to prevent mattress sliding. Build beds to be disassemble-able for moving — drawbore pegs or bolted connections only, no permanent glue at rail-to-post.'},{id:"md-toy-chest-safety",topic:"Toy chest safety requirements",keywords:["toy","chest","lid","support","hinge","ventilation","safety","child","finger"],answer:`Toy chests present entrapment and finger-pinch hazards. Use a lid support that holds the lid open at any angle and prevents sudden drop (spring-loaded lid supports or piano hinge with a lid stay chain). Ventilation holes are required by consumer safety standards — drill 1/2" holes in the front near the top if the lid seals tightly. Rounded edges on all corners. Hinges must allow a child's fingers to avoid the pinch zone. Paint or finish with non-toxic, child-safe finishes — check the manufacturer's label specifically.`},{id:"md-cutting-board-design",topic:"Cutting board construction — end grain vs edge grain",keywords:["cutting","board","end","edge","grain","glue","food","safe","warp","rubber","feet"],answer:`End grain cutting boards expose the wood fibers' open ends — knives slip between fibers rather than cutting across them, preserving the blade edge longer and self-healing small cuts. They're thick (1.5"–3") to prevent warping. Edge grain boards are thinner, lighter, and easier to build. Both need glues rated as food-safe when cured (Titebond III, food-safe epoxy). Finish with mineral oil and beeswax — never linseed oil, danish oil, or any curing finish. Rubber feet prevent slipping and lift the board for airflow.`},{id:"md-speaker-cabinet",topic:"Speaker cabinet construction — wood and joinery",keywords:["speaker","cabinet","enclosure","MDF","bracing","joint","joint","resonance"],answer:`Speaker enclosures need dense, rigid walls to minimize resonance — MDF is standard because it's inert acoustically. Void-free 3/4" MDF is the choice for most speaker builders. Dados and rabbets at corners are structural; glue all joints with PVA and add internal corner braces. Dadoed braces inside the enclosure at the midpoint break up internal standing waves and add rigidity. Veneered MDF gives a furniture appearance with the acoustic properties of MDF. Laminate all seams with silicone or wood filler before veneer to prevent telegraph.`}],s=[{id:"me-bocote",topic:"Bocote — striking figure and working notes",keywords:["bocote","striped","mexican","rosewood","figure","dark","brown","line"],answer:"Bocote is a Mexican hardwood with bold dark brown stripes and swirling grain on a golden-tan background. It's moderately hard, finishes beautifully with oil, and turns to a glassy surface. The interlocked grain causes some tearout — take light passes and use sharp tools. It's popular for knife handles, inlay, guitar backs, and small accent pieces where the figure shows best."},{id:"me-zebrawood",topic:"Zebrawood — appearance and workability",keywords:["zebrawood","stripe","african","parallel","contrast","coarse","grain"],answer:"Zebrawood has pale yellow-brown background with dark brown parallel stripes — among the boldest patterned hardwoods available. The coarse, interlocked grain causes significant tearout when planing. Use sharp tools and a scraper for final surfacing. The bold pattern can overwhelm a piece — use zebrawood as an accent rather than primary surface. It machines well with carbide and finishes nicely with oil or wiping varnish."},{id:"me-bubinga",topic:"Bubinga characteristics and use",keywords:["bubinga","african","rosewood","pink","red","heavy","drum","furniture"],answer:"Bubinga is a large African tree producing wide, stable boards with pinkish-red to reddish-brown color. It's quite heavy (similar to hard maple) and machines well with sharp carbide tools. Wavy, interlocked grain creates a beautiful pomele figure on some logs. It's popular for tabletops, workbench tops, and drum shells because of its stability and attractive color. It can cause skin irritation in some people — wear gloves when sanding."},{id:"me-lignum-vitae",topic:"Lignum vitae — densest commercial wood",keywords:["lignum","vitae","dense","hard","self","lubricating","oily","bearing","sinker"],answer:"Lignum vitae is the world's densest commercial wood — it sinks in water and self-lubricates due to natural resins. Historically used for ship bearings, mallets, and croquet balls. It's nearly impossible to work with hand tools; carbide is required. Today it's expensive and limited to specialty applications like ship propeller shaft bearings, bowls, and tool handles. Its extraordinary hardness means turned surfaces need almost no finish."},{id:"me-cocobolo",topic:"Cocobolo beauty and extreme allergen risk",keywords:["cocobolo","rosewood","allergen","sensitize","oil","color","red","orange","knives"],answer:"Cocobolo is a Central American rosewood with stunning orange-red to purple-red color and intricate grain. It's one of the most allergenic woods known — even people with no prior sensitivities can develop severe reactions from dust or handling the oiled wood. Always wear gloves, a P100 respirator, and eye protection. The natural oils make gluing difficult — wipe with acetone before gluing. Its beauty makes it a prized choice for knife handles, guitar headstocks, and small decorative pieces."},{id:"me-ebony-types",topic:"Ebony species — Gaboon, Macassar, African",keywords:["ebony","gaboon","macassar","black","stripe","piano","key","inlay","rare"],answer:"Gaboon ebony is solid jet-black and the classic ebony for piano keys, fingerboards, and decorative inlay. Macassar ebony has dramatic black-and-tan striping and is often more available than solid black. African ebony (Grenadilla) is used for woodwind instruments. All ebony is CITES-regulated, rare, and very expensive. It machines to a natural polish and needs almost no finish — oil enhances the black depth. Small sizes (pen blanks, turning squares) are more accessible than large boards."},{id:"me-olive-wood",topic:"Olive wood figure and working",keywords:["olive","wood","mediterranean","wavy","yellow","tan","brown","fragrant","turning"],answer:"Olive wood has a warm golden to tan color with dramatic wavy dark streaks, a distinctive fragrant smell when cut, and very dense, fine grain. It's excellent for turning, small boxes, and utensils. The interlocked, wavy grain causes tearout — sharp tools and a light touch are essential. Olive wood is available mostly in small sizes from Mediterranean trees. It finishes beautifully with oil and has excellent natural resistance to moisture, making it traditional for kitchen utensils and cutting boards."},{id:"me-fruitwood",topic:"Apple, pear, and cherry fruitwood characteristics",keywords:["apple","pear","fruitwood","small","turning","carving","tight","grain","dense"],answer:"Fruitwoods (apple, pear, plum, quince) share common traits: very tight, fine grain with minimal figure, warm pinkish-tan to reddish-brown color, and excellent workability for carving and turning. They're available only in small sizes because orchard trees are rarely large. Pear has the finest, most uniform grain and was historically used for rulers and precision instruments. Apple turns to a smooth, near-burnished surface. Source them from orchardists when old trees are removed — excellent urban salvage wood."},{id:"me-beech-steam",topic:"Beech for steam bending and tool handles",keywords:["beech","steam","bend","chair","german","tool","handle","lathe","stiff"],answer:"Beech is the classic European steam-bending wood — the dense, straight-grained fibers bend more reliably than almost any other species. Traditional Windsor chairs in Europe used beech for the legs and arm bows. It's also the standard wood for hand planes, work bench tops, and European hand tools because of its toughness and stability under mallet blows. Beech moves significantly with humidity changes, so it's less ideal for fine furniture that must stay flat."},{id:"me-hornbeam",topic:"Hornbeam — the hardest European hardwood",keywords:["hornbeam","hard","european","plane","workbench","mallet","axle","wearing"],answer:"Hornbeam (also called ironwood or musclewood) is the hardest European deciduous hardwood, used historically for plane soles, mallet heads, and gear teeth. The very fine, dense grain takes extreme wear without denting. It's difficult to find as sawn lumber but beloved by traditional toolmakers. American hornbeam (blue beech) is similar in properties but smaller. If you want to build a wooden-soled hand plane or a heavy mallet, hornbeam is the premium choice."},{id:"me-cypress-outdoor",topic:"Bald cypress for outdoor use",keywords:["bald","cypress","outdoor","rot","swamp","boat","stable","knot","knee"],answer:"Bald cypress is a softwood with excellent rot resistance from natural oils (cypressene), making it historically important for boat building, exterior siding, and outdoor furniture in the American South. Old-growth cypress is exceptionally resistant; second-growth may have less oil and resistance. It machines easily, takes paint and stain well, and is relatively lightweight. Reclaimed cypress from old buildings or water-logged logs is especially prized for its density and figure."},{id:"me-teak-aging",topic:"Teak color change and weathering",keywords:["teak","silver","gray","age","weather","oil","refresh","maintain","outdoor"],answer:"New teak is golden-brown with a slightly oily feel. Without treatment, UV exposure turns teak silver-gray within a season — a look many designers actively choose for outdoor teak furniture. To maintain the golden color, apply teak oil annually (after cleaning with teak cleaner to remove dirt and oxidation). To restore weathered gray teak, clean with oxalic acid-based teak brightener, sand lightly, then oil. The gray weathered look requires zero maintenance and is structurally fine — it's purely aesthetic preference."},{id:"me-mesquite",topic:"Mesquite for furniture and turning",keywords:["mesquite","southwest","dense","hard","figured","crack","small","board","texas"],answer:"Mesquite is a dense, hard Southwestern hardwood with rich golden-brown to reddish-brown color, often with dramatic figure, knots, and natural voids. It's very heavy and hard on tools. Available mainly in smaller dimensions because mesquite trees are rarely large and straight. The high figure and natural character (voids, crotches) suit rustic and contemporary furniture and turning. Fill voids with tinted epoxy for a distinctive look."},{id:"me-sassafras",topic:"Sassafras characteristics and aroma",keywords:["sassafras","aromatic","light","soft","tea","root","furniture","reclaimed"],answer:"Sassafras has a distinctive root beer or tea-like aromatic smell from natural safrole oils. It's a light, moderately soft hardwood with coarse grain similar to white ash. Historically used for furniture, boats, and barrels. The aroma fades after years of use but is strong when freshly cut. It's relatively uncommon as sawn lumber today — find it from local sawyers and urban tree sources. Light, relatively low density makes it comfortable to work with hand tools."},{id:"me-catalpa",topic:"Catalpa — soft, light, and rot resistant",keywords:["catalpa","light","soft","rot","outdoor","boat","coarse","open","grain"],answer:"Catalpa is surprisingly rot-resistant for such a soft, lightweight wood. It's been used historically for fence posts and railroad ties precisely because of this combination of low density and high durability. The coarse, open grain and bold growth rings give it a rustic character. It finishes nicely for outdoor furniture and is increasingly popular in the Southeast for benches and garden furniture. It's faster-growing than most rot-resistant species, making it more sustainable."},{id:"me-LVL-glulam",topic:"LVL and glulam engineered lumber",keywords:["LVL","laminated","veneer","glulam","engineered","beam","span","structural","shop"],answer:"LVL (Laminated Veneer Lumber) is made from thin veneers with all grain running parallel — essentially a very precise plywood-like beam. It's straighter, more uniform, and stronger than sawn lumber for the same dimension. Glulam (glued laminated timber) stacks dimension lumber with alternating grain orientations for very large beams. Both are used for long-span beams and structural shop applications where solid wood would be too heavy, too expensive, or not available in the required size. Glulam beams can be beautiful left exposed."},{id:"me-reclaimed-wood-processing",topic:"Processing reclaimed lumber safely",keywords:["reclaimed","barn","wood","nail","metal","detector","mill","old","growth"],answer:"Old barn wood and reclaimed lumber contains hidden nails, screws, and metal from previous lives — they will destroy carbide blades and potentially be ejected at high speed. Always sweep boards with a strong magnet or handheld metal detector before milling. Mark any suspect areas. Use cheaper blades for the first rough milling pass. Reclaimed wood is often dry and stable (decades of seasoning) but may have embedded grit, paint, or surface contamination that dulls tools quickly. The payoff is character-rich, old-growth dense wood unavailable new."},{id:"me-pallet-wood",topic:"Pallet wood — what it is and safety",keywords:["pallet","wood","HT","MB","heat","treated","methyl","bromide","safe","paint"],answer:`Shipping pallets marked "HT" are heat-treated and safe to use for woodworking. Pallets marked "MB" were treated with methyl bromide pesticide — avoid these entirely. Most modern US pallets are HT. Pallet wood is usually low-grade mixed hardwood (oak, maple, poplar) that's rough-sawn but surprisingly dry. Expect significant nail holes, surface grit, and rough edges — plan for extra milling. The rustic character is prized for furniture; the material is essentially free. Run through a metal detector first.`},{id:"me-cork-natural",topic:"Cork as a woodworking material",keywords:["cork","stopper","wall","floor","gasket","compressible","natural","bark"],answer:"Cork is harvested from the bark of cork oak trees without killing the tree — a sustainable material. In woodworking, cork sheet is used as drawer and shelf liners, tool handle wraps, and acoustic dampening in speaker cabinets. It's easily cut with a knife and glued with contact cement. For cabinet interiors, cork shelf liners prevent dishes and glasses from sliding. Cork is also used as the sacrificial surface on shooting boards and hand router plane bases."},{id:"me-bamboo-material",topic:"Bamboo as a woodworking material",keywords:["bamboo","grass","floor","cutting","board","strand","woven","hard","flat"],answer:"Technically a grass, bamboo is used in woodworking as flooring, cutting boards, and sheet material. Strand-woven bamboo is extremely hard (Janka ~1380 or higher) — nearly as hard as hard maple. Flat-pressed bamboo is softer and lighter. Bamboo is dimensionally stable, grows rapidly (sustainable), and takes finishes well. For shop use, bamboo sheets are available as a plywood alternative. The glue lines between strands can be visible — embrace them as part of the look or select for minimal layering."},{id:"me-tusk-tenon",topic:"Tusk tenon for removable joints",keywords:["tusk","tenon","wedge","removable","key","drawbore","disassemble","mortise"],answer:"A tusk tenon passes through the mortise and locks with a removable wedge-shaped key (the tusk) that passes through a slot in the projecting tenon. Tightening the key tightens the joint; removing it allows disassembly. Used historically for workbenches, sawhorses, and any furniture that needed to be portable. The key slot is angled so that the wedge drives the joint tight. Cut the slot farther from the shoulder than it needs to be, then trim to fit so the wedge pulls the joint fully closed."},{id:"me-coopering",topic:"Coopering — stave construction for cylinders",keywords:["coopered","stave","cylinder","barrel","drum","angle","bevel","glue","circle"],answer:"Coopering assembles narrow staves with angled edges to form cylinders or curved shapes — think barrels, wooden drums, and coopered cabinet doors. Each stave edge is beveled at an angle that depends on the diameter and number of staves: bevel angle = 90° ÷ number of staves. Dry-fit all staves with a band clamp before gluing — the joints must close evenly all the way around. A caul made from pipe insulation or a bent metal band helps apply even pressure during glue-up."},{id:"me-bent-lamination",topic:"Bent lamination for curved parts",keywords:["bent","lamination","curve","thin","strip","form","glue","chair","rail"],answer:'Bent lamination stacks thin strips of wood (1/8"–1/4" thick) glued together over a curved form. The thin strips bend easily without breaking; the glue locks them in the curved shape permanently. The form must be built to the inside radius of the finished piece. Apply glue to every face, stack the strips, and clamp firmly over the form for several hours. The spring-back (slight straightening as the blank is removed from the form) must be anticipated — build the form slightly tighter than the final radius to compensate.'},{id:"me-kerf-bending",topic:"Kerf bending for curves without lamination",keywords:["kerf","bend","cut","curve","plywood","radius","calculate","spacing","panel"],answer:'Kerf bending makes a straight panel flexible by sawing a series of parallel cuts nearly through the thickness. The remaining web of wood (typically 1/8"–3/16") bends while the uncut face provides a clean outer surface. Calculate spacing: the closer the kerfs, the tighter the possible bend radius. Test with a strip of the actual material to find the minimum radius before committing. Kerf-bent plywood is used for curved cabinet doors, stair risers, and architectural millwork. The kerf side faces inward (away from view).'},{id:"me-angled-mortise",topic:"Laying out angled mortises for chair legs",keywords:["angled","mortise","chair","leg","compound","angle","splay","rake","layout"],answer:"Chair legs typically splay outward in two directions simultaneously — splay (front-to-back) and rake (side-to-side) — requiring compound-angled mortises in the seat. Use a sliding bevel set to each angle, a drill press tilted to the correct side-to-side angle with the workpiece shimmed for front-to-back angle, or a dedicated chair mortising jig. Traditional chairmakers often used a reference board and sight lines to set angles empirically rather than calculating them trigonometrically."},{id:"me-round-tenon-round-mortise",topic:"Round tenon in round mortise for chair rungs",keywords:["round","tenon","mortise","chair","rung","spindle","turned","drill","auger"],answer:"Chair rungs and spindles use round tenons (turned on the lathe or shop-turned with a dowel former) in round mortises (drilled with a Forstner or auger bit). The tenon should be sized to enter the mortise with firm hand pressure — not pounding. Green wood traditions size the tenon slightly oversize and dry it (which shrinks the tenon); the dry tenon is then glued into a moister mortise that swells slightly, creating a locked joint without relying entirely on glue."},{id:"me-floating-panel-sizing",topic:"Floating panel groove and panel sizing",keywords:["floating","panel","groove","movement","size","gap","door","frame","allowance"],answer:`For a floating panel (like a cabinet door panel) that isn't glued, the panel must be sized smaller than the groove length to allow seasonal movement. Allowance: panel width = groove length minus (panel width × movement coefficient × MC change). A simpler field rule: leave 1/8" gap per foot of panel width for panels moving into the groove season. Never fill the gap with caulk or glue — the panel must be free to move. Center the panel in the frame before assembly so it has equal expansion room in both directions.`},{id:"me-pocket-hole-thin",topic:'Pocket holes in thin material — under 3/4"',keywords:["pocket","hole","thin","1/2","5/8","short","screw","Kreg","setting"],answer:`For material thinner than 3/4", most pocket hole jigs have a secondary setting. Kreg's guide: 1/2" material uses a 1" screw and specific drill depth setting; 5/8" uses a 1-1/4" screw. If you use the 3/4" setting on 1/2" material, the screw will blow through the face. Always consult the pocket hole jig chart and use the exact drill depth collar setting for the material thickness. Test the setup on scrap before committing to the actual workpiece.`},{id:"me-tongue-groove-sizing",topic:"Tongue and groove sizing rules",keywords:["tongue","groove","size","ratio","depth","width","panel","loose","fit"],answer:`Tongue thickness: 1/3 of the total stock thickness. For 3/4" stock, that's a 1/4" tongue. Groove depth: slightly deeper than the tongue is long (1/16" extra) so the tongue doesn't bottom out before the shoulder seats. Groove width: tongue thickness plus a few thousandths clearance for glue or movement. For floating panels, size the groove to allow the tongue to move freely — it shouldn't be glued. A snug-sliding fit without binding is correct.`},{id:"me-biscuit-near-edge",topic:"Biscuit placement near board ends and edges",keywords:["biscuit","near","edge","end","distance","minimum","splinter","blow","out"],answer:'Keep biscuit slots at least 2" from the end of a board — slots too close to ends allow the biscuit to pop through when the board is under clamp pressure. Size #10 biscuits need 2" minimum from the end; #20 need 2.5". On edge joints (face-to-face glue ups), biscuits provide alignment but add no real strength. Space them 8–12" apart for best alignment. On miter joints, biscuits can reinforce the miter but must be placed precisely perpendicular to the miter face.'},{id:"me-glue-starved-joint",topic:"Starved glue joints and how to avoid them",keywords:["starved","glue","joint","too","little","dry","weak","penetrating","open","grain"],answer:"A starved joint has insufficient glue — either too little applied or too much squeezed out by excessive clamp pressure. It looks fully assembled but is weak. Signs: very little or no squeeze-out, joint opens at light stress, or dry line visible at joint. Prevention: apply sufficient glue to cover both mating surfaces completely, use moderate clamp pressure (light bead of squeeze-out all the way around means correct pressure), and don't leave joints unclamped too long after spreading glue on porous end grain."},{id:"me-mortise-tenon-table-corner",topic:"Mitered mortise and tenon for table corners",keywords:["mitered","mortise","tenon","table","corner","long","depth","maximize","miter"],answer:`At a table corner, two apron rails meet at the same leg. Each needs a mortise, and the two mortises can't overlap inside the leg. A mitered tenon (the tenon end is cut at 45°) allows both tenons to extend deeper into the leg and come close together without intersecting. This maximizes glue area and mechanical strength at the corner. The diagonal miter at the tenon end is cut after the shoulder cuts. Mark the miters carefully so they clear each other by at least 1/8".`},{id:"me-slot-mortise-jig",topic:"Router mortising jig for consistent mortises",keywords:["router","mortise","jig","plunge","consistent","repeat","fence","stop"],answer:"A shop-made router mortising jig clamps to the workpiece and guides the router with two fences (for side-to-side centering) and stop blocks (for length). Plunge the router in the center first, then work toward the ends to avoid climbing cuts at the stop blocks. Spiral upcut bits clear chips efficiently in deep mortises. Routing mortises produces flat walls and a consistent depth automatically — better than hand-chisel mortises for batch production. Clean the rounded corners with a chisel or round the tenon corners to match."},{id:"me-japanese-plane",topic:"Japanese kanna (hand plane) setup and use",keywords:["japanese","kanna","pull","plane","laminated","chipbreaker","setup","hollow","back"],answer:"Japanese planes cut on the pull stroke, which many find more controllable for fine work. The laminated iron (hard steel welded to soft backing steel) sharpens easily and holds an edge extremely well. The back of the iron has a hollow (ura) that must be maintained by occasional flattening on a waterstone — this ensures only the cutting edge and corners contact the stone. Planes are adjusted by tapping the body to advance the blade and tapping the iron laterally for alignment. Setup is more complex than Western planes but the result is exceptional."},{id:"me-japanese-chisel",topic:"Japanese nomi (chisels) characteristics",keywords:["japanese","nomi","chisel","laminated","ura","hollow","back","hard","steel"],answer:"Japanese chisels (nomi) use the same laminated construction as Japanese plane irons — hard steel cutting edge, soft steel body. The hollow ura (hollow back) makes flattening the back fast and keeps it flat during use. Japanese bench chisels are driven with a round-headed hammer (genno) — the steel hoop on the handle prevents mushrooming. They're typically available in specific widths (3mm through 36mm) and hold an edge longer than most Western chisels at similar or lower sharpening cost."},{id:"me-japanese-saws",topic:"Japanese pull saws (ryoba, dozuki, kataba)",keywords:["japanese","saw","ryoba","dozuki","kataba","pull","thin","kerf","accurate"],answer:'Japanese saws cut on the pull stroke, which keeps the thin plate in tension rather than compression — allowing extremely thin kerfs. Ryoba saws have two edges: rip teeth on one, crosscut on the other. Dozuki saws have a stiffening spine (like a Western backsaw) and very fine teeth for joinery cuts. Kataba are single-edge saws without a spine, allowing deeper cuts. Japanese saw kerfs are 1/32"–1/16" — significantly thinner than Western backsaws, removing less material and making cuts easier to correct.'},{id:"me-wooden-planes",topic:"Wooden bodied planes vs metal planes",keywords:["wooden","plane","metal","infill","body","warm","glide","adjust","traditional"],answer:"Wooden-bodied planes are lighter, warm to the touch, and glide more smoothly on some woods — the wood-on-wood friction is lower than metal-on-wood. They're adjusted by tapping with a mallet (to advance the iron) or tapping the heel (to retract). Without a chip breaker adjustment screw, they're harder to set precisely but master craftsmen prefer them for speed of adjustment once mastered. Infill planes (wooden body with metal sole, British tradition) combine the smoothness of wood with the mass of metal for exceptional surface prep."},{id:"me-burnisher-technique",topic:"Burnisher technique for card scrapers",keywords:["burnisher","technique","angle","hook","scraper","card","steel","rod","oval"],answer:"A burnisher is a hardened smooth rod (often oval or round cross-section) used to turn the hook on a card scraper. After jointing and honing the scraper edge square, draw the burnisher along the edge at 90° two or three times (this consolidates and smooths the edge). Then tilt the burnisher 5–10° and make 2–3 strokes along each face to turn the tiny hook. The hook must be uniform all the way across — an uneven hook produces ridges. A fine oval-section burnisher gives more control than a round one."},{id:"me-toothing-plane",topic:"Toothing plane for veneer work",keywords:["toothing","plane","veneer","glue","roughen","substrate","tooth","score"],answer:"A toothing plane has a serrated (toothed) iron that scores parallel grooves in a surface rather than taking a smooth shaving. It's used to roughen substrate surfaces before applying veneer with hide glue or contact cement — the grooves create mechanical tooth for better adhesion. It also removes any wax or silicone contamination that would prevent glue adhesion. Run it diagonally in both directions for maximum tooth. It's also useful for preliminary flattening of difficult, reversing-grain boards before final smooth planing."},{id:"me-inshave",topic:"Inshave for chair seat hollowing",keywords:["inshave","chair","seat","hollow","scorp","bent","gouge","curved","draw"],answer:"The inshave (scorp) is a two-handled draw tool with a curved blade used for hollowing chair seats and inside curved surfaces. Unlike the travisher (which is a spokeshave), the inshave uses a drawknife-style grip and cuts with the grain across the seat hollow. Use a push-pull motion across the grain to rough out the hollow quickly, then follow with the travisher for final shaping. The curved blade radius should loosely match the desired hollow depth. Available from chairmaking suppliers."},{id:"me-adze-basics",topic:"Adze for hollowing and rough shaping",keywords:["adze","hollow","flat","chair","seat","rough","texture","log","shape"],answer:"An adze is an axe-like tool with the blade perpendicular to the handle, used for hollowing large areas — chair seats, canoe hulls, and troughs. The flat adze is for flatter surfaces; the gutter adze has a rounded blade for deeper hollows. Swing it in controlled arcs, working across the grain. The adze removes material very fast — follow up with a travisher and scrapers for final surfacing. Always secure the workpiece firmly and be aware of your foot position on the downswing."},{id:"me-panel-gauge",topic:"Panel gauge for wide marking",keywords:["panel","gauge","wide","board","rip","fence","mark","layout","long"],answer:`A panel gauge is an extended marking gauge with a long beam (12–24") that allows scribing lines parallel to the edge across wide boards — too wide for a standard mortise gauge. It's used to mark rip lines on wide planks and to scribe panel grooves on cabinet sides. Make a shop-built version from a hardwood beam and fence with a wedge and knife or pin. The key is a secure lock — the fence must not shift during a long scribing stroke.`},{id:"me-hand-tool-set-priorities",topic:"Hand tool starter set priorities for new woodworkers",keywords:["starter","set","hand","tool","priority","buy","first","begin","essential"],answer:`Start with: a No.5 jack plane for rough work, a No.4 smoother for final prep, a set of 4 bench chisels (1/4", 1/2", 3/4", 1"), a crosscut and a rip handsaw (or a ryoba Japanese saw covering both), a combination square, a marking gauge, a marking knife, and a wooden mallet. Add a shoulder plane when you start doing mortise and tenon work. This set handles 80% of hand tool furniture work. Don't buy a set of 20 chisels before you can sharpen one.`},{id:"me-try-square-check",topic:"Checking and calibrating a try square",keywords:["try","square","check","accurate","calibrate","line","edge","reliable"],answer:"All squares drift out of true over time — check yours regularly. Place the stock against a known-flat reference edge and scribe a line with a sharp knife. Flip the square end-for-end (same face) against the same edge and scribe a second line from the same starting point. If the square is true, both lines coincide. If they diverge, the square is out by half the divergence at the knife tip. The best combination squares can be adjusted; fixed try squares can sometimes be gently bent back into true, or replace them."},{id:"me-table-saw-blade-types",topic:"Table saw blade types — rip, combination, crosscut, ATB",keywords:["blade","rip","combination","crosscut","ATB","carbide","tooth","count","type"],answer:"Rip blades have 24–30 large, flat-top teeth optimized for cutting parallel to grain. Crosscut blades have 60–80 small, ATB (alternate top bevel) teeth for clean grain-crossing cuts. Combination blades (40–50 teeth in groups of 5, with a raker tooth) handle both reasonably well — the compromise most shops use. For the cleanest sheet good cuts, an 80-tooth ATB blade is ideal. For production ripping, a 24-tooth blade is faster and cooler. Match blade selection to the most frequent task; buy the specialized blade when rip or crosscut quality becomes the priority."},{id:"me-sawstop-technology",topic:"SawStop flesh detection technology",keywords:["sawstop","flesh","detect","brake","cartridge","signal","safety","trigger"],answer:"SawStop table saws detect flesh contact through electrical capacitance — the blade carries a small electrical signal; touching it with a finger changes the signal, triggering an aluminum brake cartridge that stops the blade in 5 milliseconds. The blade drops below the table simultaneously. Typical result: a small nick rather than a lost finger. The brake cartridge ($70–90) is destroyed in a triggering event and must be replaced. Wood conducts electricity poorly — wet, green, or treated wood can sometimes trigger a false stop. A legitimate tool for production shops and woodworking educators."},{id:"me-jointer-outfeed",topic:"Jointer outfeed table height adjustment",keywords:["jointer","outfeed","table","height","set","coplanar","cutter","head","flat"],answer:"The jointer outfeed table must be exactly level with the highest point of the cutter head arc. Too low and the board drops off the outfeed table end and produces a slight hollow at the board end. Too high and the board hits the outfeed table and stops. To set: rotate the cutter head by hand to the top position, lay a metal straightedge across the outfeed table to the cutter, and adjust the outfeed table up or down until the straightedge just barely grazes the highest carbide point. Check and readjust whenever knives are replaced."},{id:"me-spiral-cutter-head",topic:"Spiral/helical cutter head vs straight knives",keywords:["spiral","helical","cutter","head","planer","jointer","quiet","tearout","carbide"],answer:"Spiral (helical) cutter heads have dozens of small square carbide inserts arranged in a helix around the cylinder. They cut more quietly, produce far less tearout on difficult grain (each small insert takes a shearing cut at an angle), and individual carbide inserts are easily indexed to a fresh edge when dull. Straight knife heads (2–4 long knives) are cheaper and simpler but noisier and produce more tearout. Upgrading to a spiral head is one of the highest-impact investments for a jointer or planer that handles figured wood."},{id:"me-bandsaw-blade-guide",topic:"Setting bandsaw blade guides correctly",keywords:["bandsaw","guide","bearing","block","clearance","side","back","thrust"],answer:'Bandsaw blade guides sit above and below the table on both sides of the blade and the back. Side guides (bearing or cool blocks) are set to just clear the blade width without touching — 0.004" clearance (the thickness of a piece of paper) is about right. The back thrust bearing contacts only when wood is fed against the blade — it should have a hair of clearance when no wood is present. Guides too tight cause blade heat and metal fatigue; too loose allows wandering. Readjust guides when changing blade widths.'},{id:"me-drill-press-table",topic:"Shop-built drill press table with fence",keywords:["drill","press","table","shop","built","fence","stop","mdf","auxiliary"],answer:'The standard drill press table is too small and lacks a fence. Build an auxiliary table from 3/4" MDF clamped or bolted to the cast iron table. Add a sacrificial insert in the center that can be replaced when drill-through holes accumulate. Build a sliding fence that adjusts with a T-track and knob-locks. Add a stop block to the fence for repeat-hole drilling at the same distance from the edge. A good drill press table transforms a fussy machine into a production-ready workhorse for shelf pin holes, mortises, and doweling.'},{id:"me-router-collet-size",topic:'Router collet sizes — 1/4" vs 1/2" shank',keywords:["router","collet","1/4","1/2","shank","vibration","runout","strength","bit"],answer:'1/2"-shank bits run truer and with less vibration than 1/4"-shank bits because the larger shank has more bearing contact in the collet. For a router with a 1/2" collet, always use 1/2"-shank bits for larger profiles — panel raisers, large roundovers, and flush-trim bits especially. 1/4"-shank bits are fine for small bits (1/4" straight, small roundovers) and are the only option in trim routers. Never reduce a 1/2" collet with an adapter — the fit is imprecise and bit concentricity suffers.'},{id:"me-fixed-vs-plunge-router",topic:"Fixed base vs plunge base router — choosing",keywords:["fixed","plunge","router","base","choose","edge","table","groove","start"],answer:"Fixed-base routers have the motor locked at a set depth — ideal for router table use and edge routing where you plunge in from the end of the board. Plunge-base routers have a spring-loaded column that allows plunging into the middle of a workpiece — essential for starting mortises and through-holes in the center of a panel. Many routers have interchangeable bases (fixed and plunge) for versatility. For router table use, fixed is simpler and easier to set. For handheld mortising and groove work, plunge is necessary."},{id:"me-palm-router-uses",topic:"Palm (trim) router — best applications",keywords:["palm","trim","router","small","light","edge","flush","chamfer","one-handed"],answer:'Palm routers (compact trim routers) are lightweight (under 2 lbs), one-hand operable, and ideal for light-duty edge routing, chamfering, flush-trimming laminate or veneer edges, and inlay routing. They typically accept only 1/4"-shank bits and have limited depth adjustment range. Not suitable for large profile bits or heavy production work — the light motor bogs down. For furniture work, a palm router with a roundover bit handles the majority of edge-profiling quickly and precisely.'},{id:"me-drum-sander",topic:"Drum sander for consistent thickness sanding",keywords:["drum","sander","thickness","thin","veneer","wide","consistent","sandpaper","roll"],answer:`A drum sander (wide belt or open-end drum) sands boards to consistent thickness without the snipe risk of a thickness planer. It's ideal for very thin stock (under 3/8") that a planer can't safely process, and for figured wood prone to tearout under planer knives. Feed boards slightly diagonal to minimize sanding pattern. Take light passes (0.005"–0.010" per pass) — too much removes the drum paper quickly and burns the wood. Change sandpaper rolls before they stop cutting — dragging dull abrasive causes heat.`},{id:"me-spindle-sander",topic:"Spindle sander for curves and inside corners",keywords:["spindle","sander","oscillating","drum","curve","inside","convex","concave"],answer:'An oscillating spindle sander has a drum that both rotates and moves up and down — the oscillation prevents the drum from loading with debris and burning. Use the drum diameter closest to the curve radius of the inside cut — a tight inside curve needs a smaller drum. Work the piece slowly into the rotating drum and let the sander do the work; forcing the stock removes too much and creates flat spots. Spindle sander drums come in 1/2" to 3" diameters to match various curve radii.'},{id:"me-air-compressor-shop",topic:"Air compressor selection for a woodworking shop",keywords:["air","compressor","psi","cfm","gallon","tank","nailer","spray","size"],answer:"For nailer use only: a small pancake compressor (1–2 gallon, 90 PSI) is sufficient. For a spray gun: a minimum 30-gallon tank at 6–8 CFM at 40 PSI. Larger is always better for spray finishing — small compressors cycle on and off during spraying, causing pressure fluctuation. Oil-free compressors contaminate the air with water vapor; add an inline water separator and oil-water separator for spray finishing. A quiet (under 70 dB) compressor makes the shop much more pleasant — worth the premium for extended use."},{id:"me-air-nailer-types",topic:"Air nailer types — 18 gauge, 16 gauge, 15 gauge",keywords:["air","nailer","brad","finish","framing","18","16","15","gauge","cleat"],answer:'18-gauge brad nailers shoot thin brads (1" to 2") — for light tacking while glue sets, attaching moldings, and trim work where nail holes are minimal. 16-gauge finish nailers shoot a heavier nail (1" to 3.5") — for attaching face frames, trim, and thicker stock. 15-gauge angled finish nailers shoot the heaviest finish nail (1-1/4" to 3.5") for structural trim and heavy molding. Never use a brad nailer for structural connections that will be stressed — brads pull out easily under load.'},{id:"me-outfeed-table",topic:"Table saw outfeed table — building one",keywords:["outfeed","table","table","saw","support","long","board","fold","height"],answer:'Long boards on the table saw need support as they exit the blade — without outfeed support, they tip down and bind or jerk. Build an outfeed table at exactly the same height as the saw table. A folding version (hinged and drops flat against the saw when not needed) saves shop floor space. The simplest option: a shop-built table from 3/4" plywood with adjustable legs (threaded rod and couplings). Height is critical — even 1/16" too high catches the board; 1/16" too low allows tipping.'},{id:"me-miter-saw-stand",topic:"Miter saw stand and material support",keywords:["miter","saw","stand","support","wing","long","roller","stop","repeat"],answer:"A miter saw stand needs wings that support long material on both sides of the saw at the same height as the saw table. Commercial fold-up stands have roller extensions. Shop-built stands can use benchtop wings at the correct height with a flip stop for repeat cuts. A flip stop (a hinged stop block that flips up to let the workpiece pass and then flips down to register the next cut) is the key efficiency tool — mark your stop positions in pencil on the fence for frequent cut lengths."},{id:"me-jigsaw-orbital",topic:"Jigsaw orbital action setting",keywords:["jigsaw","orbital","action","setting","wood","fast","rough","slow","clean"],answer:"Modern jigsaws have adjustable orbital action — the blade swings forward on the upstroke (cutting stroke) in addition to moving up and down. Higher orbital settings cut faster and more aggressively in thick wood but leave a rougher cut. Setting 0 (straight up-and-down only) cuts slowest but cleanest — use for laminated panels and finish cuts. Setting 3 or 4 cuts fast through thick lumber for rough cuts. For most furniture work, a middle orbital setting (1 or 2) balances speed and surface quality."},{id:"me-french-polish",topic:"French polish — shellac pad technique",keywords:["french","polish","pad","shellac","rubber","charge","oil","lubricant","figure-8"],answer:'French polishing applies shellac with a cloth pad (the "rubber") using figure-8 and circular motions. The pad has a core of wool or cotton wrapped in lint-free cloth, charged with dilute shellac (1-lb cut). A tiny drop of mineral oil on the pad face lubricates it against sticking. Work quickly in sweeping figure-8s, never stopping on the surface. Layer thin coats — the accumulated film builds slowly over hours or days of work. Finish with a spirit-off coat (pure alcohol) to remove the oil residue. It produces the most stunning, deep finish achievable by hand.'},{id:"me-bleaching-wood",topic:"Bleaching wood for lighter color",keywords:["bleach","wood","color","lighten","oxalic","two","part","A","B"],answer:"Two-part (A/B) wood bleach uses sodium hydroxide (part A) followed by hydrogen peroxide (part B) to break down the natural color compounds in wood — dramatically lightening the color. Neutralize with dilute vinegar-and-water solution after bleaching, then let dry completely before finishing. Oxalic acid removes iron stains and tannin-based discoloration without changing overall wood color. Household chlorine bleach removes some surface mold but has minimal effect on wood color. Always test bleaching on scrap first — the result varies by species."},{id:"me-ebonizing-wood",topic:"Ebonizing wood — making light wood dark",keywords:["ebonize","black","vinegar","iron","tannin","chemical","reaction","reaction","oak"],answer:"Ebonizing uses a chemical reaction between iron acetate (rusty steel wool dissolved in white vinegar) and the tannins in wood to produce a gray-to-black color. High-tannin woods (oak, walnut, cherry, mahogany) react strongly — sometimes producing deep black in one application. Low-tannin woods (maple, pine) need a tannic acid wash applied first. The color penetrates rather than sitting on the surface, producing a more natural look than black paint or stain. Experiment on scrap — results vary by species, iron concentration, and contact time."},{id:"me-shou-sugi-ban",topic:"Shou sugi ban (yakisugi) charred wood technique",keywords:["shou","sugi","ban","yakisugi","char","burn","torch","brush","seal","exterior"],answer:"Shou sugi ban (yakisugi) chars the wood surface with a torch or fire, producing a beautiful textured carbonized layer that resists rot, insects, and fire. Traditional Japanese method used cedar; any wood can be charred. After charring, brush off loose carbon with a wire brush to reveal the texture — light brushing leaves bold texture; heavy brushing smooths it. Seal with oil or leave unsealed (the carbon itself is protective). Charred wood is a striking exterior cladding option and increasingly popular in contemporary interior furniture accents."},{id:"me-wire-brushing",topic:"Wire brushing and texturing wood surface",keywords:["wire","brush","texture","grain","soften","raised","rustic","exterior","finish"],answer:"Wire brushing scrubs away the soft early wood (spring growth) from a sawn surface, leaving the harder latewood (dark rings) raised — producing a deeply textured, rustic surface. Use a wire cup brush on an angle grinder or drill, or a hand-held wire brush for smaller pieces. Work with the grain — brushing against it tears fibers and looks wrong. The result is striking on oak, ash, and Douglas fir with bold ring patterns. Apply oil or clear finish to seal the textured surface without filling the raised grain."},{id:"me-reactive-stain",topic:"Reactive stains — iron acetate, vinegar, and salt",keywords:["reactive","stain","iron","vinegar","salt","color","tannin","chemical","natural"],answer:"Reactive stains change wood color through a chemical reaction rather than depositing pigment. Iron vinegar (vinegar with steel wool dissolved in it) reacts with tannins to create grays and blacks. Salt water accelerates some aging reactions. Ammonia vapors (in a sealed container with a bowl of ammonium hydroxide) fume oak to a deep honey-brown by reacting with the tannic acid. These reactions look completely natural because the color is in the wood itself, not on it. Results are permanent and can't be sanded off."},{id:"me-finish-adhesion-prep",topic:"Preparing surfaces for finish adhesion",keywords:["prep","adhesion","oil","grease","clean","wax","naphtha","mineral","spirits"],answer:"Wax, oil, silicone, and skin oil prevent finish adhesion. Before finishing, wipe the entire surface with naphtha or mineral spirits on a clean cloth — this removes surface contamination and flashes off quickly. Don't use water (raises grain) or acetone (can affect some woods and is too aggressive for some finishes). After cleaning, avoid touching surfaces with bare hands — even clean skin oils can cause adhesion problems. Apply finish while the shop is as dust-free as possible after the final sanding."},{id:"me-spray-gun-setup",topic:"Setting up an HVLP spray gun",keywords:["hvlp","spray","gun","needle","cap","fluid","air","pressure","adjust","tip"],answer:"HVLP spray gun setup: set air pressure to the gun manufacturer's recommended inlet pressure (typically 10–25 PSI at the gun). Thin the finish to the correct viscosity using a viscosity cup (#4 Zahn cup) — target 15–20 seconds flow time for most finishes. Adjust the fluid needle to control material output (open 1.5–2 turns for most jobs). Pattern knob controls fan width (vertical ellipse to circle). Test spray on cardboard — look for even, stipple-free atomization with no heavy center or heavy edges. Adjust air or fluid until the pattern is even."},{id:"me-spray-gun-clean",topic:"Cleaning a spray gun after use",keywords:["spray","gun","clean","solvent","nozzle","needle","dry","clog","maintain"],answer:"Clean immediately after use — dried finish in the gun passages is very difficult to remove. Pour out remaining finish, fill the cup with appropriate solvent (lacquer thinner for lacquer, water for waterborne), and spray through until clean. Disassemble the fluid needle, nozzle, and air cap; soak in solvent. Use a gun cleaning brush set for small passages. Dry all parts and lightly oil the needle and packing nut. A dedicated gun-cleaning station (closed container that recycles solvent) keeps waste minimal. Never soak O-rings in harsh solvents — they swell and fail."},{id:"me-color-matching-repair",topic:"Color-matching finish for repairs",keywords:["color","match","repair","touch","up","dye","tint","blend","sample","custom"],answer:"Color-matching is the hardest finishing skill. Start by identifying the finish (shellac, lacquer, or poly) and the stain or dye color. Mix colorants (universal tints, dry dyes, Japan colors) into the finish in tiny increments — it's always easier to darken than lighten. Test on scrap or an inconspicuous area. The repair area is never perfectly invisible — feather the finish into the surrounding area with graduated coats. Lighting conditions change color appearance dramatically — always check the color match under the room's actual lighting, not shop fluorescent lights."},{id:"me-finish-over-stain",topic:"Choosing topcoat over stain — compatibility",keywords:["stain","topcoat","poly","lacquer","compatible","wait","cure","bleed","interfere"],answer:"Let oil-based stain dry thoroughly before applying topcoat — usually 24–48 hours minimum. Oil-based poly over oil stain: fine after full dry. Lacquer over oil stain: potentially problematic — the strong solvents in lacquer can dissolve and lift some stain pigments. Shellac over oil stain: fast, seals the stain. Water-based poly over oil stain: wait 3–4 days minimum for the oil to fully oxidize; otherwise the residual oils prevent adhesion. When in doubt, seal with a coat of dewaxed shellac between stain and topcoat — it's the universal compatibility bridge."},{id:"me-waterbased-dry-time",topic:"Water-based finish dry time vs cure time",keywords:["dry","cure","water","based","finish","time","hours","days","hardness","30","day"],answer:'Water-based finishes are "dry" to the touch in 1–2 hours and recoatable in 2–4 hours — much faster than oil-based. But "full cure" (maximum hardness and chemical resistance) takes 2–4 weeks. During the cure period, the finish is vulnerable to scratches, water rings, and chemical damage that it would resist when fully cured. Avoid placing objects on freshly finished surfaces for at least a week. Oil-based poly cures in 30 days — similar rules apply. The finish looks the same whether dry or fully cured; the hardness is the difference.'},{id:"me-epoxy-river-table",topic:"Epoxy river table construction",keywords:["epoxy","river","table","slab","void","fill","bubble","color","pigment","deep"],answer:'Epoxy river tables fill a natural void or gap between two live-edge slabs with colored epoxy. Use slow-cure, deep-pour epoxy rated for your pour depth — regular epoxy generates too much heat in thick pours and may crack or yellow. Pour in layers of no more than 1/2"–1" to manage heat buildup. Eliminate bubbles by warming the epoxy slightly before mixing, using a heat gun or torch briefly over the poured surface, or using a vacuum chamber for small pours. Color with alcohol inks, mica powder, or epoxy pigments — test your colors in a small cup first.'},{id:"me-finish-softwood",topic:"Finishing softwood — pine, cedar, fir special considerations",keywords:["softwood","pine","finish","blotch","seal","conditioner","resin","coat","oil"],answer:"Softwoods absorb stain very unevenly — pine is the worst offender, blotching dark in the growth rings and light between them. A pre-stain conditioner, gel stain, or very diluted wash coat of shellac before staining significantly reduces blotching. For a natural look without stain, oil finishes (danish oil, tung oil) enhance grain without the blotching risk. Cedar's natural oils can bleed through water-based finishes — seal with shellac first. Fir resins can also bleed through paint; shellac prime before topcoating."},{id:"me-resorcinol-glue",topic:"Resorcinol glue for marine and structural use",keywords:["resorcinol","marine","waterproof","dark","line","boat","structural","two","part"],answer:"Resorcinol is a two-part structural adhesive (resorcinol resin + paraformaldehyde catalyst) that produces a bond stronger than the wood and is completely waterproof — the original marine and structural glue. It produces a dark reddish-brown glue line that shows clearly on light wood. It requires precise mixing ratios, has a short pot life, and needs temperatures above 70°F during cure. For most woodworking, epoxy has replaced resorcinol except in traditional boat building where its specific properties are mandated."},{id:"me-urea-formaldehyde",topic:"Urea-formaldehyde (plastic resin) glue",keywords:["urea","formaldehyde","plastic","resin","powder","mix","water","cure","hard","yellow"],answer:"Urea-formaldehyde glue (sold as DAP Weldwood Plastic Resin) comes as a powder mixed with water. It cures rigid and hard, resists creep (doesn't compress under sustained load), and has a longer open time (15–30 min) than PVA. It's excellent for laminating cutting boards, veneered panels, and any application requiring a stiff glue line. It's water-resistant but not waterproof. Requires temperatures above 65°F during cure. The dry powder has a very long shelf life; mixed batches must be used the same day."},{id:"me-epoxy-thin-penetrating",topic:"Thinning epoxy for deep penetration",keywords:["epoxy","thin","penetrate","deep","stabilize","punky","rot","solvent","dilute"],answer:"Standard epoxy is too thick to penetrate deeply into porous or punky wood. West System's 105/205 or Smith's CPES (Clear Penetrating Epoxy Sealer) contain solvents that carry the epoxy resins deep into the fibers — the solvents evaporate and the epoxy remains. CPES is specifically designed for this application and is the best choice for consolidating punky wood, stabilizing dry rot, and sealing end grain. Do not thin regular epoxy with acetone — the result is unpredictable and usually weaker."},{id:"me-hide-glue-spring-joint",topic:"Hide glue for rubbed joints and spring joints",keywords:["hide","glue","rub","spring","joint","clamping","flat","veneer","no","clamp"],answer:`Hot hide glue has special properties that make rubbed joints possible — two flat surfaces coated and pressed together while the glue is hot will bond without clamps as the glue chills and gels. This works because hide glue has higher initial tack than PVA. Similarly, a "sprung joint" in guitar top construction uses hide glue to deliberately close a slight gap under spring tension, pre-stressing the joint. These techniques don't work with PVA or modern adhesives, which is one reason hide glue remains the standard in instrument making.`},{id:"me-ellipse-layout",topic:"Drawing an ellipse for tabletops and mirrors",keywords:["ellipse","draw","trammel","oval","table","mirror","string","pins","nail"],answer:"Two methods for large ellipses. String method: drive two nails at the focal points (calculated from the major and minor axis lengths), tie a string loop around both nails, and trace the ellipse keeping the string taut with a pencil. Trammel method: make a trammel beam with two pins set at specific distances — slide the trammel along perpendicular guide rails as the pencil scribes the ellipse. The trammel method is more accurate for furniture. Calculator: focal distance = sqrt((major_axis/2)² − (minor_axis/2)²)."},{id:"me-ogee-layout",topic:"Laying out an ogee curve",keywords:["ogee","curve","S","curve","layout","compass","tangent","foot","moulding"],answer:"An ogee is an S-curve consisting of two opposite arcs tangent to each other. Lay out an ogee with a compass: draw the baseline and the top line, divide the vertical space into equal halves. Draw the first arc (concave upward) from its centerpoint below the baseline, then the second arc (convex upward) from its centerpoint above the top line. The two arcs meet at the midpoint and must be tangent (the centerpoints and the meeting point all lie on a straight line). This geometric layout produces a perfectly smooth S-curve."},{id:"me-compound-angle-splay",topic:"Table saw compound angle settings for splayed boxes",keywords:["compound","angle","splay","box","table","saw","bevel","miter","tilt","chart"],answer:"For a 4-sided box with sides splayed at angle S from vertical: table saw miter angle = arctan(cos(45°) × tan(S)); bevel (blade tilt) = arctan(sin(45°) / cos(S)). For a common 10° splay: miter ≈ 7.1°, bevel ≈ 44.3°. For a 15° splay: miter ≈ 10.6°, bevel ≈ 43.1°. Round to the nearest 1/10° and test with scrap. Each side needs both cuts — the key is the miter tilts away from you on a standard table saw. A compound miter saw handles these cuts with a single setup if both angles can be set simultaneously."},{id:"me-pythagorean-chair-angle",topic:"Using trigonometry for chair leg angle calculations",keywords:["chair","leg","angle","trig","calculate","degree","splay","rake","math"],answer:"Chair legs that splay in two directions (splay and rake) require compound angles for the seat mortises. Net angle from vertical = arccos(cos(splay) × cos(rake)). For 5° splay and 7° rake: net angle = arccos(cos(5°) × cos(7°)) ≈ 8.6°. The twist angle for the mortise (rotation in the seat plane) = arctan(sin(rake) / sin(splay)). These calculations are usually done once for a design and then set on a jig. Many experienced chairmakers measure the angles empirically from a full-scale drawing instead of calculating."},{id:"me-sequence-wood-cuts",topic:"Cutting sequence math — largest parts first",keywords:["cut","sequence","plan","largest","first","crosscut","rip","optimize","layout"],answer:`Always cut largest parts first from a board. Rip to the widest needed width first, keeping the reference edge; then crosscut to the longest needed length. Never cut short pieces from a long board without planning what the remainder can provide — a 3" offcut may save another cut if planned. Mark all cut lines on the board before any cuts, then sequence from largest to smallest. This approach minimizes waste and avoids the situation where you've cut too short for a needed piece.`},{id:"me-trestle-table",topic:"Trestle table design and stability",keywords:["trestle","table","base","x","stretcher","leg","knock","down","long"],answer:'Trestle tables use an A-frame or X-frame base at each end connected by a central stretcher. The stretcher is the key structural element — it ties the two bases together and prevents racking. Traditional trestle tables are knock-down (the stretcher is held with a tusk tenon) for easy transport. Leg spread determines stability — a wide stance at the feet prevents tipping. The stretcher height matters too: too low catches legs; too high interferes with seating. 6"–10" from the floor is the standard range.'},{id:"me-pembroke-table",topic:"Pembroke drop-leaf table design",keywords:["pembroke","drop","leaf","table","swing","leg","gate","rule","joint"],answer:"Pembroke tables have two small drop leaves supported by swing-out legs (gate-leg or fly-leg style). When leaves are up, the swing leg pivots out on a pivot point; when down, the swing leg tucks back against the apron. The leaves connect to the fixed top with rule joints (matched cove and roundover) and the hinges are set below the pivot of the rule joint. Pembroke tables are among the most space-efficient occasional table designs — compact with leaves down, useful dining or work table with leaves up."},{id:"me-highboy-design",topic:"Highboy (tall chest) design elements",keywords:["highboy","tallboy","chest","high","cabriole","bonnet","period","upper","lower"],answer:"A highboy consists of a lower case (often with cabriole legs) topped by a taller upper case. The upper case typically has a bonnet pediment (curved top with finials), while the lower case has one or two rows of drawers above an apron. The connection between upper and lower is a precise fit with a few locating pins. Traditional highboys are Queen Anne or Chippendale period pieces in mahogany or walnut. Building one requires mastering a wide range of skills: case construction, drawer fitting, carved feet, and cornice moulding."},{id:"me-secretary-desk",topic:"Secretary desk design and fold-down writing surface",keywords:["secretary","desk","fold","down","writing","surface","lid","support","drawer","cubbies"],answer:'A secretary desk has a slant-front or vertical drop-front lid that opens to a horizontal writing surface. The lid is held at 90° by chains, lid stays, or sliding "lopers" (pull-out wooden rails). Interior cubbies and small drawers provide document organization. The lid hinges carry the full weight when open — use heavy-duty or continuous hinges rated for the load. The slant-front style reveals the cubbies at a slight angle, which some find easier to access; the drop-front style creates a flat, level writing surface.'},{id:"me-ladder-back-chair",topic:"Ladder back chair construction",keywords:["ladder","back","chair","slat","rung","post","woven","seat","shaker","weave"],answer:"Ladder back chairs have horizontal slats between the rear posts that form the ladder-like back. Slats are typically steam-bent or flat-sawn and mortised into the rear posts. All post-to-rung and post-to-slat joints are round tenon in round mortise — drilled at compound angles. Seats are traditionally woven rush, cotton tape, or splint. The Shaker variant is one of the most replicated ladder backs — simple proportions, fine turnings on the back posts, and cotton tape seating. It's an excellent first chair project for a hand-tool woodworker."},{id:"me-workbench-vises",topic:"Workbench vise placement and selection",keywords:["workbench","vise","face","tail","leg","shoulder","wagon","placement","choose"],answer:"A basic bench needs at least one face vise. The classic placement is front-left corner for right-handers. If adding a second vise, the tail vise (end vise for bench dog clamping) goes at the right end. Leg vises and shoulder vises are more specialized — the leg vise provides a huge clamping surface for long work; the shoulder vise allows work to overhang the bench end. For most hobby woodworkers, a quality quick-release face vise is the only vise needed for the first few years."}],n=[{id:"mf-electrical-safety-shop",topic:"Electrical safety in the woodworking shop",keywords:["electrical","gfci","outlet","extension","cord","grounded","short","fire","circuit"],answer:"Wood shops need dedicated circuits for major tools — a table saw and dust collector on the same circuit can trip breakers or cause voltage drops. Use GFCI-protected outlets near sinks and wet areas. Never use undersized extension cords for power tools — a 10-gauge cord is minimum for 15-amp tools; undersized cords cause voltage drop that overloads motor windings and starts fires. Keep cords off the floor where they collect sawdust (fire risk). Inspect cords regularly for cuts and frays."},{id:"mf-fire-extinguisher",topic:"Fire extinguisher types for the woodworking shop",keywords:["fire","extinguisher","ABC","CO2","class","sawdust","finishing","spray"],answer:"Every shop needs a minimum 5-lb ABC dry chemical extinguisher near the exit. For finishing rooms with flammable solvents, a CO2 or clean-agent extinguisher is preferred — CO2 leaves no residue on equipment and doesn't conduct electricity. Mount extinguishers at eye level on the wall between you and the exit (so you can grab it while moving toward the exit). Check the gauge monthly. Know how to use it before a fire — the PASS method: Pull, Aim, Squeeze, Sweep."},{id:"mf-shop-lighting",topic:"Shop lighting for safety and accuracy",keywords:["lighting","shop","lumen","raking","overhead","task","led","fluorescent"],answer:"Adequate lighting is a safety issue — poor light leads to missed layout lines and misjudged cuts. Overhead LED shop lights provide general illumination; aim for 50+ foot-candles at the bench and tool surfaces. Raking light (angled from the side) reveals surface defects, plane tracks, and glue lines that overhead light obscures. A movable task light at each major tool dramatically improves both safety and work quality. Shadow-free LED panel lights eliminate the flicker of old fluorescent tubes that causes eye fatigue."},{id:"mf-machine-layout-workflow",topic:"Machine placement for workflow and safety",keywords:["machine","placement","layout","workflow","outfeed","clearance","traffic","zone"],answer:"Place machines so their outfeed zones don't overlap — the table saw outfeed area should never face into the jointer's infeed zone, or someone using one tool creates a hazard for the other. Allow 4' of clearance behind and to the side of every major machine for the longest material you'll handle. Place the dust collector where its hose reach covers all machines without creating trip hazards. Put the bench against a wall (not in a traffic area) and orient it so natural light or overhead light falls from your left (for right-handers) onto the work."},{id:"mf-lathe-catch",topic:"Lathe catch — causes and prevention",keywords:["lathe","catch","dig","in","grab","spindle","bowl","speed","sharp","tool","rest"],answer:"A lathe catch happens when a turning tool digs into the spinning wood instead of cutting it — usually from presenting the tool at the wrong angle or with the edge below the tool rest height. The result is a violent jerk that can fling the tool or send material flying. Prevention: always have the tool rest adjusted close to the work; present tools with the bevel rubbing the wood first, then gently lift the handle to engage the edge; keep turning tools sharp; use the correct tool for the operation (bowl gouge for bowls, spindle gouge for spindles). If you feel resistance, retract immediately."},{id:"mf-router-table-start-pin",topic:"Starting pin on the router table for freehand profiling",keywords:["start","pin","router","table","freehand","pivot","curved","stock","entry"],answer:"The starting pin (a small metal pin set into the router table near the bit) provides a pivot point for starting freehand cuts on curved stock — where you can't use a fence. Hold the workpiece against the starting pin, then pivot it into the spinning bit. Without the starting pin, the bit grabs the end of the stock and kicks it backward (a potentially dangerous catch). Once the stock is fully past the bit entry, you can remove it from the pin and maintain contact with just the bit bearing. Never start a freehand cut against a spinning bit without a starting pin."},{id:"mf-circular-saw-kickback",topic:"Circular saw kickback prevention",keywords:["circular","saw","kickback","bind","pinch","anti","kickback","clutch","stance"],answer:"Circular saw kickback occurs when the blade pinches — the blade stops and the saw is thrown backward at high speed. Prevention: support the material so it doesn't sag and pinch the blade (use sawhorses with the off-cut supported); start cuts with a straight blade, no angle; never force the saw; use a riving knife behind the blade (modern saws have one); stand to the side of the blade, not directly behind it. Retract the guard manually only when absolutely necessary (starting an angled cut into a corner) and never hold it retracted during the cut."},{id:"mf-vibration-white-finger",topic:"Vibration white finger (hand-arm vibration syndrome)",keywords:["vibration","white","finger","HAVS","circulation","numb","chainsaw","grinder","time"],answer:"Hand-Arm Vibration Syndrome (HAVS) results from prolonged use of vibrating tools — grinders, chainsaws, and reciprocating saws are the worst offenders. Symptoms include numbness, tingling, loss of dexterity, and in severe cases permanent vascular damage that causes fingers to turn white in cold temperatures. Limit continuous use of high-vibration tools; take regular breaks; use anti-vibration gloves (limited effectiveness); and address vibration at the source by keeping cutting tools sharp (which reduces vibration). Report symptoms to a doctor early — the condition is progressive."},{id:"mf-back-safety",topic:"Back safety when handling heavy lumber",keywords:["back","safe","lift","heavy","sheet","lumber","technique","assist","dolly"],answer:`Full sheets of 3/4" plywood weigh 60–75 lbs and are awkward to handle alone. Lift with your legs, not your back — squat, keep the sheet close to your body, and don't twist while holding heavy material. Use a sheet good cart or panel dolly for moving plywood. For heavy lumber like 8/4 walnut, have a partner on the other end. A panel carrier hook ($15) lets one person carry a 4×8 sheet vertically. Don't try to be a hero with material over 50 lbs — back injuries are the most common woodworking-adjacent health problem.`},{id:"mf-ergonomic-injury",topic:"Repetitive strain injuries in woodworking",keywords:["repetitive","strain","RSI","carpal","tunnel","tendinitis","grip","wrist","prevent"],answer:"Repetitive motions like hand planing, sanding, and routing can cause tendinitis, carpal tunnel syndrome, and other repetitive strain injuries. Prevention: take breaks every 30–45 minutes of continuous repetitive work; use anti-vibration gloves for grinding; vary your grip frequently; keep tools sharp (more force = more strain); adjust workbench height so you're not working with arms raised or hunched over. Symptoms like tingling, numbness, or persistent aching after work should be evaluated by a doctor before they progress."},{id:"mf-splinter-treatment",topic:"Treating wood splinters in the shop",keywords:["splinter","remove","tweezers","needle","clean","infection","exotic","tropical"],answer:"Most splinters can be removed with a needle or fine-tip tweezers under magnification. Clean the area with alcohol, remove the splinter completely (no fragments left), clean again, and cover with a bandage. Wood splinters that aren't fully removed become infected more readily than most other foreign bodies. Exotic wood splinters (wenge, rosewood, cocobolo) may carry allergens or toxic compounds — remove completely and watch for allergic reactions. If a splinter is deep or you can't remove it completely, see a doctor — retained splinters cause serious infections."},{id:"mf-sanding-fire-risk",topic:"Sanding fire risk from friction heat and dust",keywords:["sanding","fire","risk","friction","heat","spontaneous","combustion","bag","filter"],answer:"Belt sander and random orbit sander bags collect fine, warm sawdust that can smolder. Empty the bag after each session — don't leave a full, warm bag overnight. Fine dust generated by sanding is also explosive in high concentrations in an enclosed space — keep shop ventilated. Black walnut dust is especially prone to slow combustion in the bag. After sanding oily woods (teak, tung-oil-finished stock), shake the bag contents into a metal can and leave outdoors to cool before disposal."},{id:"mf-parallel-jaw-clamp",topic:"Parallel jaw clamps for panel glue-ups",keywords:["parallel","jaw","clamp","even","pressure","Bessey","panel","face","racking"],answer:'Parallel jaw clamps (Bessey K-Body, Jorgensen, Jet) have a fixed and a movable jaw that remain parallel regardless of clamping pressure — unlike pipe clamps, which tend to rotate and produce a bow in the glued-up panel. For wide panel glue-ups, alternate clamps above and below the panel and place them every 6–8" to distribute pressure evenly. Wax the clamp jaws or use wax paper at joint lines to prevent the clamps from bonding to squeeze-out. Parallel jaw clamps are the most versatile clamp type for furniture production.'},{id:"mf-band-clamp-use",topic:"Band (strap) clamps for polygons and frames",keywords:["band","strap","clamp","polygon","frame","miter","corner","octagon","hexagon"],answer:"Band clamps wrap a ratcheting nylon strap around irregular shapes — polygon frames, bent laminations, and box corner miters that would be impossible to clamp with parallel jaw or bar clamps. The strap applies even pressure all the way around the perimeter simultaneously. Add corner protectors (plastic or shop-made wood corners) to prevent the strap from cutting into the corners at pressure points. For picture frames and polygon boxes, they're indispensable. Check that all corners are equally tight before the glue sets."},{id:"mf-wooden-handscrew",topic:"Wooden handscrew clamps for face work",keywords:["wooden","handscrew","parallel","jaw","adjust","angle","face","taper","clamp"],answer:`Wooden handscrew clamps (also called parallel jaw wooden clamps) have two independently adjustable wooden jaws connected by two threaded rods. The two-rod adjustment allows the jaws to clamp tapered or angled pieces that would slip out of a single-screw clamp. They're excellent for clamping work to the workbench face, clamping face frames directly to cabinet carcases, and as a third-hand holder for jigs and templates. The wooden jaws don't mark soft workpieces. Sizes range from 4" to 24" jaw opening.`},{id:"mf-cam-clamp",topic:"Cam clamps for quick light-duty work",keywords:["cam","clamp","luthier","quick","release","light","guitar","instrument","assembly"],answer:"Cam clamps use an eccentric (cam) lever to apply and release clamping pressure instantly — no screwing required. They're faster than any other clamp type for repetitive tasks. Popular in instrument making for clamping thin pieces where torque from screw clamps would crush the material. Applying pressure with a cam clamp: simply push the lever. Release: push back. They don't apply as much force as screw clamps but plenty for light wood-to-wood joints. Buy them or make them from plywood and a wooden toggle."},{id:"mf-t-track-jigs",topic:"T-track and miter track for jigs and stop blocks",keywords:["T","track","miter","stop","block","jig","router","table","fence","adjustable"],answer:'T-track (extruded aluminum channel) is embedded in jigs, fences, and router table surfaces to allow bolt-on adjustable components like stop blocks, featherboards, and hold-downs. Standard T-track accepts 5/16"-18 hex-head bolts with T-nuts. Miter track (3/4" × 3/8" typically) fits table saw and router table miter slots. Design jigs with T-track from the start rather than trying to add it later — routing an accurate T-track channel requires careful setup but pays off in every jig you build afterward.'},{id:"mf-vacuum-bag-pressing",topic:"Vacuum bag pressing for veneer and bent lamination",keywords:["vacuum","bag","press","veneer","lamination","form","even","pressure","pump"],answer:"Vacuum bags press veneered panels and bent laminations with perfectly even pressure in all directions — impossible to achieve with individual clamps. The bag is sealed and air evacuated with a vacuum pump, applying 14.7 psi uniformly across the entire surface. For flat panels, a simple bag and a flat caul work. For curved forms, the form goes inside the bag and the atmospheric pressure presses the lamination against the form perfectly. Good vacuum bags for woodworking use a 2-stage or 1-stage pump — 22–25 inHg vacuum is typical."},{id:"mf-clamping-cauls",topic:"Making and using clamping cauls",keywords:["caul","clamping","curved","even","pressure","wax","straight","bow","prevent"],answer:`Cauls are auxiliary pieces placed between clamps and the workpiece to distribute pressure over an area or protect the surface. Straight cauls on edge-glued panels prevent cupping under clamp pressure (clamp every 8–10" alternating top and bottom). Curved cauls (with a slight bow) apply extra pressure at the center of a panel. Wax your cauls so glue squeeze-out doesn't bond them to the work. Particleboard or MDF cauls stay flat and don't dent soft wood surfaces as readily as solid wood cauls.`},{id:"mf-dovetail-jig-compare",topic:"Dovetail jig comparison — Leigh, Keller, Porter Cable",keywords:["dovetail","jig","leigh","keller","porter","cable","compare","router","half","through"],answer:"The Porter Cable 4212 uses a fixed-spacing aluminum template for both half-blind and through dovetails — fast setup, good results, but limited to equal spacing. The Leigh D4R allows variable spacing and ratios, and makes half-blind, through, and box joints with one jig — more flexible but complex to set up. Keller jigs are simple, accurate, and produce through dovetails with variable spacing, though limited compared to the Leigh. Hand-cut dovetails remain faster for one-offs once you have the skill; jigs pay off in batches of four or more identical boxes."},{id:"mf-shooting-board-miter",topic:"Miter shooting board for accurate 45° cuts",keywords:["shooting","miter","board","45","accurate","frame","picture","plane","end","grain"],answer:"A miter shooting board has a 45° fence on the platform — place the mitered piece against the fence and plane the end grain to exactly 45°. A sharp, well-set No.5 or No.7 plane works well for the end grain cuts. Shoot one piece, check with a reference square, adjust, then shoot all similar pieces in sequence without re-adjusting. For picture frames, even 0.5° of error in a miter produces a visible gap at the corner — the shooting board eliminates this. Make two mirror-image shooting boards (left and right 45°) for a complete set."},{id:"mf-glue-up-assembly-table",topic:"Assembly table for flat panel glue-ups",keywords:["assembly","table","flat","reference","glue","up","caul","level","torsion"],answer:"Gluing up panels on a flat, level assembly table keeps glue-ups from setting up bowed or twisted. A torsion-box top (hollow core with a grid of internal ribs, MDF skin) produces a very flat, light surface. Level the table with adjustable feet. Keep the table surface free of clamp pressure dents by using sacrificial strips. For a simpler option, a guaranteed-flat surface reference table (cast iron or thick MDF) serves the same purpose — just cover it with wax paper to prevent glue bonding."},{id:"mf-jewelry-box",topic:"Jewelry box construction — lining and hinge",keywords:["jewelry","box","lining","felt","velvet","hinge","lid","small","lock","tray"],answer:"Jewelry boxes need a lined interior (felt, suede, or velvet), a fitted lid with a small hinge, and optional lift-out trays. Cut the lid from the assembled box with a thin blade (scroll saw or fine table saw blade) for a perfect fit. Use small knife hinges or barrel hinges for a clean hidden look. Line the interior after finishing — apply contact cement to the wood and back of the felt, let dry, and press into place. A removable tray (a shallow tray that sits inside the main compartment on ledges) adds organization."},{id:"mf-wine-rack",topic:"Wine rack construction and bottle spacing",keywords:["wine","rack","bottle","spacing","angle","diameter","wood","lattice","stacking"],answer:'Standard wine bottles are about 3"–3.5" in diameter and 12" long. A simple slot-style wine rack needs openings slightly larger than the bottle neck for easy in-and-out — about 4"×4" or a 3.5" circular hole. Bottles should rest at 5°–15° below horizontal (cork stays wet). A lattice-style rack (crossing diagonal strips) is the classic design. Use clear or lightly-finished hardwood for appearance. Space the openings on a grid and calculate the total grid size for the number of bottles — 75mm center-to-center (about 3") is the tightest practical spacing.'},{id:"mf-knife-block",topic:"Kitchen knife block construction",keywords:["knife","block","slot","width","angle","wood","bamboo","magnetic","food","safe"],answer:`Knife blocks have angled slots cut at 15°–20° from vertical so the blades hang at a slight angle and are easily gripped. Slots are typically 3/32"–1/8" wide and 5"–7" deep (matching common blade length). Stack thin strips of wood with spacers between them, clamp and glue, then drill or rout the slots from the front face. Use a dense, fine-grained hardwood (cherry, maple, walnut) that won't generate splinters at the slot edges. Finish with a food-safe oil (mineral oil, walnut oil). Alternative: a magnetic knife strip mounted on the wall is simpler to make.`},{id:"mf-cutting-board-end-grain",topic:"End grain cutting board assembly tips",keywords:["end","grain","cutting","board","assembly","strips","rotate","glue","flat","oil"],answer:"For an end grain cutting board, rip a thick board into strips, rotate them 90° (end grain up), and glue them back together. The key challenge is keeping the glue-up flat — end grain is unforgiving with clamps. Apply glue quickly (PVA has short open time when end grain is absorbent), use cauls above and below, and alternate clamp directions to avoid bowing. After curing, flatten on a drum sander or with a hand plane. Finish with multiple coats of food-grade mineral oil applied liberally — end grain is thirsty and absorbs a lot on the first several coats."},{id:"mf-serving-tray",topic:"Serving tray with handles — design and construction",keywords:["serving","tray","handle","cut","out","bottom","panel","frame","carry"],answer:"A serving tray typically has a flat bottom panel in a frame with short sides and cut-out handles at each end. The bottom can be a floating panel (solid wood) or fixed plywood. Handle cut-outs are made with a jigsaw or router after the frame is assembled. Round over all edges that hands will contact — sharp edges on handles are uncomfortable. The frame joints need to be very strong (mortise-and-tenon or well-glued finger joints) because a loaded tray puts significant stress on the handle-to-frame corners."},{id:"mf-desktop-organizer",topic:"Desk organizer and pen holder construction",keywords:["desk","organizer","pen","holder","box","divider","dado","compartment","office"],answer:'Desk organizers are great beginner projects using dado and rabbet joints. Build the main box from 1/2" hardwood with dadoed dividers creating compartments of different widths. A pencil cup (a cylinder or square tube) can be a section of turned wood or a box joint cylinder. Finish with a light oil for a natural look, or milk paint for a colored option. Proportions: keep the overall height of back compartments at 4"–5" for pens and markers; front sections at 2"–3" for paper clips and rubber bands.'},{id:"mf-picture-frame",topic:"Picture frame construction and glass sizing",keywords:["picture","frame","miter","rabbet","backing","glass","mat","art","size"],answer:'Picture frames use 45° miter joints at corners, reinforced with splines, biscuits, or nails plus glue. The rabbet (rebate) on the back inside edge holds the glass, mat board, art, and backing in place. Rabbet depth: typically 1/4"–3/8" to accommodate glass + mat + backing. Inside dimension of the rabbet = mat size. For standard size mats (8×10", 11×14", etc.), work backward from the mat size when laying out the frame. Key fit order: cut all pieces from the same stick to get identical profiles, miter, dry-fit with a band clamp, check square, then glue.'},{id:"mf-mirror-frame",topic:"Mirror frame construction and hanging",keywords:["mirror","frame","rabbet","clip","keyhole","hang","weight","backing","plate"],answer:'Mirror frames are built like picture frames with a deeper rabbet (the glass is heavier). Use mirror mounting clips or aluminum channel to secure the mirror — never glue mirrors directly into a frame with solvent-based adhesives (they attack the silvering). Mirrors are heavy: a 24×36" mirror with frame weighs 15–25 lbs. Hang using keyhole brackets or French cleat — never just a single hook. French cleats are the strongest and most adjustable option. On the wall, find studs or use toggle anchors rated well above the actual mirror weight.'},{id:"mf-plant-stand",topic:"Plant stand construction and indoor use",keywords:["plant","stand","indoor","spill","water","finish","height","pot","moisture"],answer:`Plant stands need moisture resistance because pots overflow and drip. Use a waterproof finish (oil-based poly or exterior varnish) on all surfaces. Design the top with a slight lip to contain water spills, or add a tray. Elevation height depends on the plant light requirements; taller stands push plants closer to windows. Splayed legs (angled outward) make stands more stable and look more elegant than straight vertical legs. The top opening for a pot should match the pot's outer diameter — allow 1/4" clearance all around.`},{id:"mf-step-stool",topic:"Step stool construction and safety requirements",keywords:["step","stool","safe","height","load","stability","kitchen","footrest","anti-slip"],answer:'A step stool must be extremely stable — base footprint should be wider than the top platform. Legs should splay outward in both directions (typically 7°–10° from vertical). Mortise-and-tenon or well-glued and screwed joints are mandatory for safety. Test load capacity by standing on it yourself and bouncing gently. Add non-slip rubber feet and non-slip strip on the platform surface. CPSC recommends step stools support 300 lbs minimum. Keep height proportional to stability — a 12" step needs a wide base to avoid tipover.'},{id:"mf-blanket-chest",topic:"Blanket chest construction and lid hardware",keywords:["blanket","chest","chest","cedar","lid","hinge","tray","tills","storage"],answer:"Blanket chests are traditionally lined with aromatic cedar for moth protection. The case is typically frame-and-panel or solid wood with breadboard ends on the lid. The lid is attached with heavy-duty continuous (piano) hinge or large butt hinges — it must support repeated opening and closing under full weight. A lid stay (chain or lid support hardware) is essential to prevent the lid from falling and hitting a child or slamming shut. Optional interior tills (removable partitioned trays) provide organized storage within the chest."},{id:"mf-tool-chest-construction",topic:"Hand tool chest design and organization",keywords:["tool","chest","tray","till","interior","organize","dovetail","lid","dutch"],answer:"The classic wooden tool chest (like the Dutch chest style) has a deep base with a sliding interior till, and sometimes a smaller till above. Hand tools are stored upright in the base (planes, saw, mallet) and smaller tools in the till (chisels, gauges, small planes). The lid typically has a small tray inside. Dovetailed corners are traditional and show the maker's skill. Felt or leather lining protects tools from rust and scrapes. Size the chest to the specific tools it will hold — pre-plan the interior before building."},{id:"mf-birdhouse",topic:"Birdhouse construction and hole sizing",keywords:["birdhouse","hole","size","species","bluebird","wren","drill","cedar","roof"],answer:'Birdhouse hole diameter determines which species will use it: 1.25" for wrens, 1.5" for chickadees, 1.5" for nuthatches, 1.56" for bluebirds, 2" for flickers. Interior floor size and depth also matter — bluebirds need a 5"×5" floor with 8" of depth. Avoid perches (predators use them). Make the roof removable or a side panel hinged for cleaning each fall. Use untreated cedar, redwood, or pine — no pressure-treated wood near nesting birds. Leave the wood unfinished or use exterior latex paint in earth tones only; avoid creosote or bright paints.'},{id:"mf-outdoor-bench",topic:"Outdoor garden bench construction",keywords:["outdoor","bench","garden","seat","rot","resistant","cedar","teak","mortise","span"],answer:`Garden bench seats are typically 2" thick decking boards or 2×6 lumber spanning 4' between supports. The seat spans should be no more than 18"–24" between supports to prevent deflection under load. Mortise-and-tenon or through-bolt connections at the leg-to-seat support joints. Use rot-resistant wood (cedar, teak, ipe, black locust) and stainless or hot-dip galvanized hardware. Leave small gaps (1/4") between seat boards for drainage. Angle the seat very slightly (2°–5°) toward the back so rainwater drains toward the back rather than pooling.`},{id:"mf-garden-gate",topic:"Garden gate construction and bracing",keywords:["garden","gate","brace","diagonal","sag","hinge","latch","lumber","pressure"],answer:"Wood gates sag at the latch corner over time if not properly braced. A diagonal brace must run from the bottom hinge corner up to the top latch corner (compression along the diagonal when the gate sags). Getting this wrong is a common mistake — a brace from top-hinge to bottom-latch is in tension and doesn't work as well in wood. Use rot-resistant lumber, galvanized hardware throughout, and at least three hinges on any gate taller than 4 feet. The gate frame should be rigid before adding diagonal bracing."},{id:"mf-spice-rack",topic:"Spice rack design — wall mount vs counter",keywords:["spice","rack","wall","mount","counter","depth","opening","jar","label"],answer:'Wall-mounted spice racks use a simple case (3"–4" deep) with 2"–3" lips on the front of each shelf to keep jars in place. Make shelf depth based on your specific jar diameter — most common spice jars are 2" diameter. A tiered wall rack (angled shelves) lets you see labels on all jars simultaneously. Counter racks can be pull-out drawers or tiered trays. Mount wall racks with keyhole brackets for easy removal when cleaning. Label orientation matters — design the shelf angle so labels face out.'},{id:"mf-mudroom-locker",topic:"Mudroom locker and bench with storage",keywords:["mudroom","locker","bench","storage","hooks","cubbies","seat","shoe","boot"],answer:`Mudroom lockers combine a bench (for sitting while putting on shoes), storage cubbies above, coat hooks, and sometimes enclosed cabinet sections. Typical bench height: 17"–18". Cubbies above the bench should be at a comfortable reach height — 60"–70" maximum for an adult-height installation. Make each cubby about 12"–15" wide for a person's bag and jacket space. Waterproof the floor of the bench storage area (shoes bring in moisture). PVC edge banding on plywood cubbies is more moisture-resistant than solid wood banding in this environment.`},{id:"mf-floating-nightstand",topic:"Wall-mounted (floating) nightstand construction",keywords:["floating","nightstand","wall","mount","stud","cantilever","shelf","drawer"],answer:'A floating nightstand must be mounted into studs or substantial blocking — it carries 20–40 lbs of load on a cantilever. Use a French cleat (wide for distributed load) or heavy-duty shelf brackets concealed inside the case. The cleat must catch at least two studs or be into solid blocking installed behind the drywall. Single-drawer or open-shelf designs work best for floating nightstands — drawers add weight and movement. Size: 14"–16" wide × 10"–12" deep is typical for a single bed; wider for a king.'},{id:"mf-turned-bowl",topic:"Bowl turning on the lathe — basic technique",keywords:["bowl","turn","lathe","gouge","outside","inside","scraper","wall","thickness"],answer:'Mount the blank on a faceplate or chuck (glued to a waste block). Shape the outside with a bowl gouge cutting from the rim down to the center. Reverse the blank to finish the foot, then reverse again to hollow the interior. Interior cuts go from the rim toward the center, never from center to rim (which causes dig-ins). Target wall thickness for a wooden bowl: 1/4"–3/8" for decorative pieces, thicker for utility bowls. Sand while spinning at low speed (600 RPM or less) starting at 80 grit if the tool finish is rough, ending at 220 or 320.'},{id:"mf-segmented-bowl",topic:"Segmented bowl turning basics",keywords:["segmented","bowl","turning","rings","miter","glue","layer","pattern","angle"],answer:"Segmented turning builds up rings from individual wood segments glued at mitered angles. Each ring segment is cut at the same miter angle (360° ÷ number of segments ÷ 2). Common segment counts: 12 per ring (30° miter each) or 16 (22.5° miter). Cut all segments for a ring identically, glue into a ring using a band clamp, flatten each ring, then glue rings into a stack. The turning process is the same as solid wood turning, but segments must all be well-glued — a failed glue line becomes a dangerous projectile at lathe speed."},{id:"mf-humidor-construction",topic:"Cigar humidor construction and wood selection",keywords:["humidor","cigar","spanish","cedar","humidity","seal","hygrometer","70","percent"],answer:"Cigar humidors maintain 65–70% relative humidity — ideal for cigar storage. The interior must be lined with Spanish cedar (a tropical hardwood, not true cedar) which is the traditional and proven lining material for its ability to absorb and release moisture consistently while imparting a pleasant aroma to cigars. The box must seal well — test by closing the lid and watching for immediate spring back from trapped air. Include a hygrometer and humidifier element. Never use aromatic eastern red cedar in a humidor — its strong oils are too harsh for cigars."},{id:"mf-threaded-insert",topic:"Threaded inserts for removable hardware in wood",keywords:["threaded","insert","T","nut","bolt","machine","screw","removable","wood"],answer:'Threaded inserts are brass or steel barrels installed into wood to accept machine screws repeatedly without stripping. Options: press-in, drive-in (with a hex driver), or glue-in inserts. Choose the insert diameter to match the drill bit and the screw thread (M6, M8, or 1/4"-20 are common). Apply a small drop of CA glue to the outside threads before installing to prevent back-out. Threaded inserts are essential for jigs and fixtures that need frequent disassembly, adjustable parts like router table inserts, and removable hardware that needs to be tightened reliably.'},{id:"mf-hinge-mortising",topic:"Hinge mortising by hand and with a router",keywords:["hinge","mortise","butt","chisel","router","depth","mark","knife","outline"],answer:"By hand: trace the hinge on the wood with a marking knife, chop just inside the knife lines with a bench chisel, then pare to depth. Test-fit the hinge — it should sit perfectly flush. With a router: clamp a simple L-shaped guide fence to locate the router exactly, set depth to the hinge leaf thickness, and rout in multiple passes toward the corners. Finish corners by hand with a chisel. The most common mistake: setting router depth to the full hinge leaf thickness and forgetting that two hinges stack — the combined recess equals one leaf thickness total per piece."},{id:"mf-drawer-front-adjust",topic:"Adjusting a drawer front for even reveals",keywords:["drawer","front","adjust","reveal","gap","screw","slot","up","down","left","right"],answer:"Most inset drawer fronts attach to the drawer box with two screws through the box front face into the back of the drawer front. Use screws through slotted holes (elongated vertically and horizontally) to allow adjusting the front up/down and left/right. Drill the attachment holes slightly oversize in the drawer front to allow adjustment. Set the drawer into the opening, hold the front in the correct position with the reveals you want, drive the screws while holding position (a second person helps), then check reveals and adjust. On frame-and-panel cabinets, set the gap with playing card shims while fastening."},{id:"mf-shelf-standard",topic:"Adjustable shelf standards and brackets",keywords:["shelf","standard","bracket","metal","pilaster","hole","adjustable","load","wall"],answer:`Metal shelf standards (pilasters) mount vertically in pairs, and brackets clip in at any height on the standard's slotted holes. They're the fastest adjustable shelf system for utility shelving. For a bookcase, recessed standards look much cleaner than surface-mounted. Most standards are 1" wide and require a groove routed in the cabinet side to recess them flush. Load rating per bracket varies — heavy loads need brackets every 12"–16" and robust standards. For heavy loads (reference books), double up the standards or use continuous standards the full case height.`},{id:"mf-lid-support-types",topic:"Lid support hardware types for boxes and chests",keywords:["lid","support","chain","stay","pneumatic","hold","open","angle","prevent","drop"],answer:"Lid supports prevent the lid from falling to a destructive angle or onto hands. Chain stops simply limit opening angle — very simple but allows the lid to drop to the end of the chain with a jolt. Surface-mounted lid stays (flat metal arm) hold at 90° and are common on boxes. Pneumatic (gas spring) lid supports slow the opening and hold open with silky smooth operation — the best option for larger chests and hope chests where finger pinch is a serious risk. Pneumatic springs are sized by force in Newtons — choose based on lid weight and arm leverage."},{id:"mf-pocket-hole-hardware",topic:"Pocket hole jig accessories and variations",keywords:["pocket","hole","jig","Kreg","Festool","setup","clamp","face","frame","variations"],answer:"Pocket hole jigs range from $20 single-hole units to bench-mounted production jigs with dual holes and built-in clamps. The Kreg K4 and K5 are the workhorses — clamp the board, adjust for material thickness, drill both holes in one setup. A face clamp (Kreg clamp or similar) holds joints together while driving pocket screws — without it, the screw angle pushes the boards apart. For production face frame assembly, a dedicated pocket hole clamp system is faster than repositioning a bench clamp for every joint."},{id:"mf-scary-sharp",topic:"Scary sharp system — sandpaper on glass",keywords:["scary","sharp","sandpaper","glass","psa","adhesive","progression","flat","cheap"],answer:`The "Scary Sharp" system uses PSA (pressure-sensitive adhesive) sandpaper stuck to a flat glass plate as a cheap, flat sharpening medium. Start at 220 grit to establish the bevel, work through 400, 600, 800, 1000, 2000 for polishing. The advantage: perfectly flat surface (glass doesn't dish), inexpensive to get started, and fine grits produce excellent edges. The disadvantage: sandpaper wears quickly compared to stones and must be frequently replaced. Stick the paper to a piece of float glass (from a hardware store mirror) — thicker glass is flatter.`},{id:"mf-tormek-system",topic:"Tormek wet grinder system for tool sharpening",keywords:["tormek","wet","grinder","slow","wheel","jig","angle","leather","hone"],answer:"Tormek systems use a slow-speed (90 RPM) wet grinding wheel that removes steel without overheating, followed by a leather honing wheel. The system's jigs (sold separately) hold plane irons, chisels, gouges, knives, and other tools at precise, repeatable angles. The slow wheel is nearly impossible to overheat. The main advantages: tool-specific jigs produce consistent bevel angles; the wet wheel creates no sparks or heat stress. Tormek's main limitations: slow (faster to freehand on a waterstone once skilled), and the wheel costs $30–80 to replace."},{id:"mf-plane-iron-camber",topic:"Plane iron camber — when and how to add it",keywords:["camber","plane","iron","curve","edge","jack","scrub","crown","track"],answer:`Camber (a slight curve across the iron's edge) is added to roughing planes (jack planes and scrub planes) so they take a heavy, scooping cut without leaving sharp track marks. A No.5 jack plane iron is often cambered 3/32"–1/8" across a 2" wide iron. To add camber: hone the corners of the iron back by concentrating strokes on them, checking progress with a straightedge across the edge. Smoothing plane irons should have just a whisper of camber (1/1000" crown) to prevent leaving edge tracks on finished surfaces.`},{id:"mf-lapping-film",topic:"Lapping film for high-polish sharpening",keywords:["lapping","film","mylar","micron","final","polish","razor","sharp","automotive"],answer:"Lapping film (available in micron ratings: 30, 15, 9, 5, 3, 1, 0.3 micron) provides extremely fine cutting action for final edge polishing. Stick it to a glass plate or granite surface plate. The finest lapping films (0.3–1 micron) produce mirror-polish edges beyond what most whetstones achieve. They're used by knife makers for the final polish on razors and woodworking tools. Automotive-grade (2000–5000 grit) wet/dry sandpaper provides similar performance at lower cost for most woodworking needs."},{id:"mf-drawknife-sharpen",topic:"Sharpening a drawknife",keywords:["drawknife","sharpen","file","flat","stone","bevel","outside","wire","edge"],answer:"Drawknives have a single bevel on the flat side and a flat back (like a chisel). To sharpen: hone the bevel on a flat stone (the curve of the blade makes it challenging — use a rocking motion to follow the curve). Remove the wire edge on the flat back with light strokes on the flat stone. A leather strop helps because it conforms to the blade's curve. Some drawknives have a slight hollow grind from the factory; maintain this with a bench grinder held stationary while the drawknife rolls across it — tricky but effective."},{id:"mf-saw-sharpening",topic:"Filing and setting hand saw teeth",keywords:["saw","sharpen","file","set","tooth","joint","fleam","gullet","maintain"],answer:"Sharpening a hand saw: first joint (lightly file the tips flat to equalize height), then shape (restore tooth profile with a triangular file at the correct fleam angle), then set (bend alternate teeth outward with a saw set tool). Rip saws are filed straight across (0° fleam, 0° rake). Crosscut saws use 15°–25° fleam angle and 10°–15° rake. Use a saw vise (or wooden jaws in a bench vise) to hold the saw. Full saw sharpening takes 20–45 minutes. Modern hard-point saws (gray teeth) can't be sharpened."},{id:"mf-convex-grind",topic:"Convex (Appleseed) edge grind on chisels",keywords:["convex","grind","appleseed","edge","bevel","freehand","fat","back","strength"],answer:"A convex grind (sometimes called an appleseed edge) has a slightly convex bevel rather than perfectly flat or hollow. This is the natural result of freehand sharpening on a flat stone with a rocking motion. Proponents argue it's more durable than a flat grind (more steel behind the edge) and rolls over the stone with less friction. Critics prefer hollow or flat grinds for their precise edge geometry. For heavy mortise work, a slightly convex bevel is very durable. For paring, a flat or hollow grind allows a more consistent angle presentation."},{id:"mf-lumber-defects-buying",topic:"Defects to accept and reject when buying lumber",keywords:["defect","buy","reject","accept","knot","check","warp","sticker","shadow","fungus"],answer:"Accept: tight knots in appropriate projects (rustic style), small checks that can be cut around, mild bow (can be flattened), sticker shadows (will mill out), and mineral streaks if you like the look. Reject: boards with loose knots near structural sections, severe twist that would leave too little flat thickness, boards with insect damage (active powderpost beetles especially), extensive end checks that go deep into usable sections, or boards with very irregular grain near defects that can't be predicted."},{id:"mf-sequencing-mill",topic:"When to mill lumber in relation to the project schedule",keywords:["mill","schedule","rough","dimension","allow","move","acclimate","two","stage"],answer:'Mill lumber in two stages for best results. Stage 1 (rough mill): get boards close to final thickness (1/16" to 1/8" heavy) and rough width, but leave them 2"–3" longer than final length. Stack and sticker the rough-milled stock in the shop for 1–2 weeks to allow it to move and stabilize. Stage 2 (final mill): flatten and true the now-stable boards to final dimensions and cut to final length. This two-stage approach dramatically reduces warping and twist in finished furniture parts.'},{id:"mf-online-lumber",topic:"Buying lumber online — pros and cons",keywords:["online","lumber","buy","shipping","cost","source","figured","species","risk"],answer:"Online hardwood dealers (Bell Forest Products, Woodworkers Source, Hearne Hardwoods, Cook Woods) offer excellent species variety including exotics and figured wood. The risk: you can't personally select the boards, and even photos don't capture true figure, color variation, or hidden defects. Buy from dealers who offer liberal return policies and good customer service. Shipping for heavy lumber is expensive — calculate total cost before assuming online pricing is better than a local yard. Figured veneer is excellent to buy online (lighter, easier to evaluate from detailed photos)."},{id:"mf-urban-lumber",topic:"Urban lumber — finding and using city trees",keywords:["urban","lumber","city","tree","remove","sawmill","species","free","local"],answer:"Urban trees (walnut, cherry, oak, elm from parks, streets, and backyards) are often excellent quality — wide, straight-grained trees from open-grown conditions. When a tree is removed, the logs often go to a chipper unless you arrange otherwise. Connect with local arborists, tree services, and city parks departments. Have a contact ready with a portable sawmill who can come to the site and mill the logs. The wood may need years to dry but can be spectacular — large walnut crotches and wide cherry slabs from urban trees are worth the wait."}],l=[{id:"mg-grain-filler",topic:"Grain filler for open-pore woods",keywords:["grain","filler","paste","open","pore","oak","mahogany","flat","smooth","finish"],answer:"Open-pore woods (oak, ash, mahogany, walnut) have large pores that show through film finishes as dimples unless filled first. Apply paste wood filler with a stiff brush across the grain, pressing it into the pores; wipe across the grain with burlap to remove excess. Let fully cure (24 hrs minimum), then sand lightly to level. The result is a perfectly flat base for a smooth film finish. Tinted fillers can match the wood color; contrasting fillers highlight the pore pattern. Without grain filler, five coats of varnish still won't fully level large pores like white oak."},{id:"mg-glaze-antiquing",topic:"Antiquing with glaze to fake age and depth",keywords:["antique","glaze","age","fake","depth","color","darken","recess","profile"],answer:"Glazing simulates decades of wear by adding dark color in recesses, corners, and profiles. Apply a base coat of finish, seal it, then brush a thin oil-based glaze (clear oil medium + raw umber or burnt umber pigment) over the surface. Wipe the flat areas clean, leaving color only in routed profiles, carvings, and corners. Seal with a topcoat. The result fakes age in carved furniture, period pieces, and decorative cabinets. Raw umber produces a neutral gray-brown; burnt umber is warmer. Practice on scrap to learn when to stop — too much glaze looks fake."},{id:"mg-pre-stain-conditioner",topic:"Pre-stain conditioner — when to use it",keywords:["pre","stain","conditioner","blotch","pine","birch","maple","apply","seal","even"],answer:"Pre-stain wood conditioner (Minwax, General Finishes) is a thin sealer that partially closes the grain to limit stain penetration and reduce blotching on problematic species like pine, birch, and soft maple. Apply it with a cloth or brush, let it soak for 15 minutes, then apply stain before the conditioner fully cures (usually within 2 hours — check label). The conditioner reduces blotching but also reduces the overall color intensity of the stain — you may need a darker stain to compensate. Test the combination on scrap first."},{id:"mg-finish-brush-types",topic:"Finish brush types — natural vs synthetic",keywords:["brush","natural","synthetic","bristle","china","oil","water","foam","chisel"],answer:"Natural bristle (China bristle) brushes hold more oil-based finish and lay it down smoother — use them for oil-based varnish, oil-based poly, and lacquer. Never use natural bristle with water-based finishes — the bristles absorb water and go limp. Synthetic (nylon or polyester) brushes work for both water and oil finishes. Chisel-tip brushes (angled) are better for cutting in at edges. For water-based poly on furniture, a high-quality nylon brush with fine tips lays down finish with minimal brush marks. Buy good brushes — cheap brushes shed bristles into the wet finish."},{id:"mg-finishing-softwood-paint",topic:"Paint over wood — primer and topcoat systems",keywords:["paint","primer","topcoat","wood","latex","oil","adhesion","sand","knots"],answer:"For painted furniture, proper primer is the difference between a lasting and a peeling finish. Oil-based primer (Zinsser BIN or Cover Stain) blocks tannins, knots, and resin — essential for pine, oak, and cedar under paint. Water-based primer is fine over MDF and poplar. Apply primer, sand at 150 grit to knock down grain, apply second coat of primer if needed, then topcoat with a water-based or oil-based paint. Semi-gloss or gloss topcoats are most durable for furniture. Apply two thin topcoats rather than one thick coat."},{id:"mg-melamine-paint",topic:"Painting over melamine and laminate",keywords:["paint","melamine","laminate","plastic","adhesion","bonding","primer","sand","degloss"],answer:"Melamine and laminate don't readily accept paint — they need deglossing and a bonding primer. Scuff with 220 grit or liquid deglosser, then apply a bonding primer (INSL-X Stix, Zinsser Bulls Eye 1-2-3, or spray shellac). The bonding primer chemically adheres to the slick surface; the topcoat bonds to the primer. Latex paint works but oil-based provides better hardness on melamine surfaces. Sand lightly between coats. The result will chip more than paint on wood — handle painted melamine carefully and avoid sharp impacts at edges."},{id:"mg-sanding-bare-oak",topic:"Sanding red vs white oak — blending grain fillers",keywords:["oak","sand","red","white","open","pore","grit","filler","blend","figure"],answer:"Oak's large, open pores require careful sanding — going too fine (above 180 grit) before staining closes the surface pores with sanding dust, which then pops loose under stain. For stained oak, stop at 150 grit for the final bare-wood sanding. Grain filler on oak: oil-based paste filler in a shade slightly darker than the final finished wood tone gives the pores a rich depth rather than just a flat fill. Red oak absorbs stain much more dramatically than white oak — a half-strength stain test will tell you quickly how dark the final result will be."},{id:"mg-danish-oil-vs-oil-varnish",topic:"Danish oil vs straight oil-varnish blend",keywords:["danish","oil","varnish","blend","penetrating","protection","durable","coats","compare"],answer:"Danish oil is essentially a pre-made oil-varnish blend — boiled linseed oil or tung oil plus alkyd varnish, thinned with mineral spirits. You can replicate it at any ratio by mixing your own (1/3 boiled linseed oil + 1/3 alkyd varnish + 1/3 mineral spirits). Commercial products vary by brand — some are mostly oil (thin, fast-penetrating), others more varnish (thicker, more film-building). Mixing your own lets you tune the balance for the task: more oil for deeply penetrating, more varnish for faster build of protective film."},{id:"mg-finish-inside-cabinet",topic:"Finishing cabinet interiors — why it matters",keywords:["interior","cabinet","finish","inside","moisture","stability","warp","seal"],answer:"Finishing cabinet interiors isn't just cosmetic — an unfinished interior absorbs moisture unevenly compared to the finished exterior, which can cause the case sides and shelves to cup. Apply at least a coat or two of the same finish to all sides (inside and outside) of every panel. For kitchen cabinets where moisture is a concern, interior finish is especially important. A single coat of shellac on the interior is the minimum — it seals the wood, prevents odors, and provides a cleanable surface. Full-finish interiors also look more professional and are easier to clean."},{id:"mg-tack-cloth-use",topic:"Using tack cloths between sanding and finishing",keywords:["tack","cloth","dust","wipe","residue","finishing","between","lint","clean"],answer:"Tack cloths are gauze-like cloths impregnated with sticky resin that grabs and holds sanding dust without leaving residue. Use them as the final step before finishing — after vacuuming and blowing off with compressed air, wipe lightly with the tack cloth folded into a pad. Don't scrub or press hard — the sticky resin transfers to the wood surface if overworked. Unfold and refold to expose a fresh surface regularly. Store tack cloths in a sealed bag; they dry out and stop working quickly if left open."},{id:"mg-oil-finish-buildup",topic:"Building up a genuine oil finish with multiple coats",keywords:["oil","finish","buildup","coats","cure","between","wipe","flood","mineral"],answer:"Pure oil finishes (linseed, tung) require many thin coats to build meaningful protection. First coat: flood the wood liberally and let it soak for 20–30 minutes, then wipe off excess. Cure 24–48 hours. Repeat. After 4–6 coats, the oil stops soaking in and builds a thin film on the surface. Final coats: apply very sparingly, wipe nearly dry, and buff with a soft cloth while still slightly wet. Each coat must fully cure before the next (tacky oil traps the next coat). 8–10 coats of pure oil provide moderate water resistance — not as protective as film finishes."},{id:"mg-interior-stain-order",topic:"Color workflow — stain first or dye first",keywords:["stain","dye","order","color","layer","depth","pop","first","sequence","workflow"],answer:'For maximum color depth and figure enhancement: dye first, then stain. The dye penetrates deeply and adds transparency and color. A pigment stain on top adds body color that fills the pores and surface while the dye effect shows through. The dye provides the "pop" and transparency; the pigment stain provides the rich surface color. A common sequence for cherry-look on walnut: amber dye first, then a brown pigment stain wipe coat, then clear finish. Test every combination on scrap — layered color work is highly species-specific.'},{id:"mg-pitch-pockets",topic:"Pitch pockets in pine and fir",keywords:["pitch","pocket","pine","fir","resin","bleed","finish","seal","problem","knot"],answer:"Pitch pockets are resin-filled voids in pine and Douglas fir between growth rings. Small ones can be sealed with thin CA glue (wick it in, cure, sand level). Large pitch pockets may need to be routed out and filled with colored epoxy. If pitch remains and you finish over it, the resin eventually bleeds through oil-based finishes and causes permanent tacky spots or staining. Seal pitch pockets with shellac before finishing — shellac blocks petroleum-based bleed-through. In paint-grade work, prime with shellac-based primer over any pitch areas."},{id:"mg-reaction-wood-milling",topic:"Managing reaction wood when milling",keywords:["reaction","wood","stress","release","bind","saw","kick","spring","cut","stable"],answer:`Reaction wood releases internal stress as it's cut — boards can spring open or close on the saw blade. Signs: the wood bends toward or away from the fence after passing the blade. Safety first: use a riving knife to prevent the board from closing on the blade (kickback). After milling, stack and sticker the pieces — they often move further over the next few days as internal stresses equalize. Cut parts from reaction-wood boards 1/4" oversize and let them rest for a week before final dimensioning.`},{id:"mg-wood-stain-bleaching",topic:"Removing water stains and iron stains from wood",keywords:["water","stain","iron","black","remove","oxalic","bleach","strip","neutralize"],answer:"Water stains (gray rings from wet glasses on tables) are often iron tannin reactions. Treat with oxalic acid solution (saturate and let dry), then neutralize with baking soda solution and rinse. Multiple applications may be needed. Household chlorine bleach occasionally removes some water stains but isn't as effective as oxalic acid. For finished surfaces, the stain must penetrate the finish — try the oxalic acid treatment before full stripping. If the stain is in the wood itself, sand to bare wood and apply oxalic acid, then refinish."},{id:"mg-glue-joint-show",topic:"Why glue lines show after finishing",keywords:["glue","line","show","visible","dark","light","stain","reject","cause","fix"],answer:"Glue squeeze-out that isn't removed before sanding spreads as a thin transparent film that seals the wood grain and prevents stain penetration — producing a visible lighter patch exactly along the glue line. Prevention: remove squeeze-out at the rubbery stage (15–30 min) with a sharp chisel, and check the joint area with naphtha before finishing. If you discover the problem at the finishing stage, sanding will spread it further; scraping is better. The only real fix is to scrape down to bare wood at the glue line and refinish."},{id:"mg-machined-vs-handplaned",topic:"Machine-sanded vs hand-planed surfaces under finish",keywords:["machine","sanded","hand","planed","burnish","finish","absorb","difference","depth"],answer:"Hand-planed surfaces absorb finish differently than sanded surfaces. The planed fibers are cut cleanly and swell less from finish; sanded surfaces are slightly more open from abrasion and may absorb more finish initially. Under an oil finish, a hand-planed surface often shows more figure and depth — the sharp plane cuts across fibers cleanly rather than scratching them with abrasive particles. Many woodworkers finish highly figured wood with a hand plane then light card scraping, skipping the sander entirely, for the most transparent and figure-enhancing result."},{id:"mg-wide-board-movement",topic:"Managing very wide boards in furniture",keywords:["wide","board","movement","solid","tabletop","slab","split","allowance","float"],answer:'A 24"+ wide solid wood tabletop can move 3/4" or more annually. Design every fastener location, edge treatment, and structural connection to accommodate this. Breadboard ends must slot-screw. Apron clips must float. Any cross-grain screw line or glue bond is an eventual crack point. Narrower glued-up tops from multiple narrower boards move the same total amount but distribute the movement between more glue joints — sometimes easier to manage structurally. Live-edge slabs often have irregular edges that constrain movement — account for this when positioning the slab on its base.'},{id:"mg-checking-finish-preparation",topic:"Checking wood surface quality before finishing",keywords:["check","surface","finish","light","angle","raking","sand","track","glue","flat"],answer:"Before applying any finish, check the surface with strong raking light from a low angle. Move a lamp along the surface in a dark shop — every scratch, mill mark, handplane track, and glue smear will show up clearly. This inspection takes 5 minutes and saves hours of refinishing work. Mark any problem spots with pencil and address them (scraping, targeted sanding) before finishing. If an area looks marginal under raking light now, it will be completely obvious and ugly under finish — especially under high-gloss finishes that magnify surface defects."},{id:"mg-grain-tearout-fix",topic:"Fixing tearout before finishing",keywords:["tearout","fix","repair","before","finish","filler","scrape","sand","patch"],answer:"Small tearout can be repaired before finishing. For minor torn fibers: dampen the area with water to raise the torn fibers, let dry, sand lightly in the correct grain direction. For deeper tearout: carefully shape a matching wood patch, glue with thin CA or PVA, clamp, and sand flush when cured. Large tearout patches may be slightly visible under finish but far less obvious than the original defect. Prevention is always better — sharp tools, correct grain direction, and backing boards eliminate most tearout before it happens."},{id:"mg-side-table",topic:"Side table design — proportions and construction",keywords:["side","table","nightstand","height","sofa","end","proportion","leg","top"],answer:'Sofa side tables should stand level with or slightly below sofa arm height — typically 22"–26". Nightstands are typically 24"–26" to match mattress-plus-box-spring height. The top should extend beyond the base enough to be usable — 14"×20" is a minimum useful size. A single drawer adds significant utility. Mortise-and-tenon apron-to-leg joints are preferred for durability. The leg-to-apron connection is the most stressed joint in a side table — pocket screws alone will fail from the leverage of items being placed and removed.'},{id:"mg-coffee-table",topic:"Coffee table design and ergonomics",keywords:["coffee","table","height","sofa","seat","proportion","size","storage"],answer:'Coffee table height: 16"–18" — roughly equal to sofa seat cushion height for comfortable reach. Size: at minimum 2/3 the length of the sofa; ideally matching sofa length. Width: at least 18" to hold books, remotes, and glasses. Clearance from sofa: 14"–18" to allow comfortable leg room. Lower shelf storage adds utility. Solid slab tops on simple bases are popular; frame-and-panel tops are durable. For families with small children, consider rounded edges and avoid sharp corners at eye-level when a toddler is standing.'},{id:"mg-dining-chair-height",topic:"Dining chair seat height and table clearance",keywords:["dining","chair","height","table","clearance","seat","cushion","standard"],answer:'Dining chair seat height is typically 17"–19" to work with a standard 30" dining table. The critical measurement is the clearance between the seat top (or cushion top) and the table underside — you need at least 10"–12" for thighs to fit comfortably. A thick cushion raises effective seat height by 2"–4" and must be factored in. For chair designs, measure from seat surface to table underside after adding the cushion. Armchairs must also clear the table apron — check arm height vs apron bottom with a mock-up before building.'},{id:"mg-console-table",topic:"Console (sofa back) table design",keywords:["console","sofa","back","table","narrow","wall","entry","tall","proportions"],answer:'Console tables sit behind a sofa or against an entryway wall — narrow depth (12"–16") and standard table height (28"–30"). Entry console tables often run at 30"–36" height to keep items at a convenient grab-and-go height. Their narrow depth means they need significant bracing or stretchers to resist racking — the long, narrow stance makes them inherently less stable than a square table. A lower shelf ties the two ends together and provides storage. Slender tapered legs suit the visual weight of a long, narrow top.'},{id:"mg-bookshelf-ladder",topic:"Leaning (ladder) bookshelf design",keywords:["leaning","ladder","bookshelf","wall","angle","no","anchor","balance","stability"],answer:"Leaning bookcases rest against the wall without wall anchors. The angle must be shallow enough to lean stably (typically 8°–15° from vertical) but not so shallow books slide off. The base extends forward to provide a stable footprint — the wider the base, the more stable. The top must contact the wall firmly but not be secured (allow for wall irregularity). Rubber pads on the base feet prevent sliding. Load the bottom shelves more heavily than the top for better stability. Check local building codes — in earthquake zones, bookcase restraint may be required regardless of design."},{id:"mg-murphy-desk",topic:"Murphy desk (wall desk) construction",keywords:["murphy","desk","fold","down","wall","hinge","spring","small","office","space"],answer:'A wall-mounted fold-down desk uses a leg-and-hinge mechanism — the desk folds up against the wall when not in use. The desktop surface needs a minimum 24"×36" to be functional. When closed, the desk front forms a cabinet door that stores supplies inside. Piano hinge along one long edge bears the weight when open; leg supports (fold-out metal legs or hinged wooden legs) take the load at the opposite edge. Gas-spring or torsion-spring hardware assists lifting the desk closed against gravity. Mount into studs — the desk carries 30–50 lbs plus dynamic work loads.'},{id:"mg-window-seat",topic:"Window seat with storage construction",keywords:["window","seat","storage","hinge","lid","box","height","seat","cushion"],answer:'Window seat height: 17"–19" with cushion height considered. Typical configuration: a plywood box with a hinged lid (the seat surface) that opens for storage below. The lid can be one piece (piano hinge across the back) or in sections. Cushion: custom foam cut to size, wrapped in fabric, with ties or clips to prevent sliding. Fasten the seat box to the floor (lag bolts through the back rail into the wall framing). Ensure the box is structurally sound for sitting load — the lid must be thick enough (3/4" minimum) not to sag under adult weight.'},{id:"mg-bathroom-vanity",topic:"Bathroom vanity construction for moisture resistance",keywords:["bathroom","vanity","moisture","humidity","finish","plywood","waterproof","seal"],answer:"Bathroom cabinetry lives in a consistently humid environment — standard furniture-grade construction will eventually delaminate, swell, or mold. Use marine-grade or at minimum void-free birch plywood for the case. Seal all exposed surfaces (including the interior) with a waterproof finish (catalyzed varnish, conversion varnish, or oil-based poly). Solid wood doors and drawer fronts must be finished on all six sides equally to prevent uneven moisture absorption and warping. Rubber-backed drawer slide mounting on particleboard is especially vulnerable — use plywood case sides."},{id:"mg-kitchen-drawer",topic:"Deep kitchen drawers for pots and pans",keywords:["kitchen","drawer","deep","pot","pan","heavy","slide","full","extension","load"],answer:'Deep drawers (8"–12" deep) for pots and pans carry very heavy loads — 30–50 lbs is common. Use heavy-duty full-extension undermount slides rated for 100+ lbs (soft-close optional but recommended for heavy drawers). The drawer box needs to be more robust than a typical box — 5/8"–3/4" sides rather than 1/2". The drawer front should be secured with four screws minimum. A divider system inside (vertical dividers for lids, roll-out trays for smaller items) makes deep drawers functional rather than just a big box. Level the slides carefully — heavy drawers amplify leveling errors.'},{id:"mg-pull-out-shelf",topic:"Pull-out shelves (roll-out trays) in base cabinets",keywords:["pull","out","shelf","tray","drawer","base","cabinet","slide","install","blind","corner"],answer:'Pull-out trays in base cabinets make the back of the cabinet accessible without kneeling and reaching. Build them like a shallow drawer (3"–4" high sides) on full-extension slides. The tray width must fit inside the face frame opening (typically 1/2" per side clearance for the slides). In a full-depth base cabinet, use 18"–22" long slides. Install slides level and parallel — a non-level pull-out slides sideways and binds. Blind corner pull-outs use specialty hardware to access the otherwise-wasted corner space in an L-shaped kitchen layout.'},{id:"mg-roll-top-desk",topic:"Roll-top desk tambour construction",keywords:["roll","top","desk","tambour","slat","canvas","groove","curve","track"],answer:"A tambour is the flexible panel of the roll-top desk — individual wood slats glued to a canvas backing that allows the panel to flex around a curve into a retaining groove. Individual slats are milled to identical width and thickness, then glued in order onto canvas laid flat. The tambour track is a curved groove routed in the desk side panels. Getting the tambour to move smoothly requires careful fitting of the groove to the tambour thickness (should slide with moderate hand pressure). Tambour construction is a time-consuming specialty skill best learned from a dedicated reference."},{id:"mg-inlay-work",topic:"Basic wood inlay technique",keywords:["inlay","route","depth","string","bandings","tight","flush","template","knife"],answer:'Wood inlay involves routing a cavity to receive a contrasting material (different species, metal, shell). The cavity must be exactly the depth and shape of the inlay piece. For straight-line banding (stringing), a marking gauge scribes the sides and a shoulder plane or router establishes the depth. For shaped inlays, knife or laser cut a template, rout to depth, and fit the inlay piece snug. Glue in with hide glue or CA. The inlay should be slightly proud, then hand-planed flush after curing. Tolerances are tight — a gap of 1/32" is clearly visible.'},{id:"mg-intarsia-basics",topic:"Intarsia — assembled mosaic wood art",keywords:["intarsia","mosaic","picture","scroll","saw","species","color","natural","wood","art"],answer:"Intarsia is a wood mosaic art form where individual pieces of different species are fitted together to create pictures or patterns — no staining required; the natural colors provide the palette. Each piece is cut on a scroll saw from the appropriate wood species for color. Pieces are shaped on a drum sander to create the relief effect (raised areas appear to advance). The back is a single piece of thin plywood. Unlike marquetry (which is flat veneer), intarsia has a sculptural, 3D quality from the sanding relief shaping."},{id:"mg-marquetry-basics",topic:"Marquetry — decorative veneer inlay technique",keywords:["marquetry","veneer","inlay","pattern","window","stack","knife","chevalet"],answer:"Marquetry assembles pieces of veneer to create flat decorative patterns — from simple geometric to elaborate pictorial scenes. Window method: cut a hole in one veneer sheet (the background), fit a contrasting piece, and tape to hold; repeat until the pattern is complete. Stack cutting method: stack multiple veneers and cut through all simultaneously, then interchange pieces between stacks for matching sets. Veneer saw or a chevalet (specialized marquetry saw) are traditional tools; a craft knife works for simple patterns. All pieces are glued to a substrate simultaneously under vacuum."},{id:"mg-chip-carving",topic:"Chip carving basics — tools and technique",keywords:["chip","carving","knife","knife","triangular","cut","basswood","pattern","geometric"],answer:"Chip carving removes small triangular chips from a flat surface using two or three cuts per chip — a stabbing cut (straight down) and one or two slicing cuts. The knife is a straight chip carving knife and a stab knife. Basswood or butternut is the easiest species. Draw the geometric pattern on the surface first (triangles, diamonds, rosettes) and always cut with the grain advantage when possible. Press firmly but let the sharp knife do the work — forcing a dull knife causes ragged chips. Seal with a light coat of shellac when complete to pop the crisp cut edges."},{id:"mg-carving-relief",topic:"Relief carving basics — tools and approach",keywords:["relief","carving","gouge","mallet","bench","background","detail","walnut","oak"],answer:"Relief carving creates a 3D design raised above the background of a flat panel. First, set in the outline with a V-tool or narrow veiner. Next, lower the background to the desired depth with wider gouges and a mallet. Then model the design forms with various sweep gouges. Finish with detail work and texturing. Keep all gouges extremely sharp — dull gouges crush and tear fibers rather than slicing them cleanly. Linden, butternut, and basswood are the easiest relief carving woods. Walnut and cherry are beautiful but significantly harder."},{id:"mg-guitar-basic",topic:"Acoustic guitar construction — an overview",keywords:["guitar","acoustic","top","back","side","bracing","glue","joint","soundhole","neck"],answer:"Acoustic guitar construction is a specialized discipline with many unique techniques. The soundboard (top) is typically quartersawn Sitka spruce and braced with a scalloped X-brace pattern that stiffens the top while allowing it to vibrate. Sides are bent over a heated bending iron. Back plates (rosewood, mahogany, or maple) are braced with lateral strips. The neck is attached to the body with a mortise-and-tenon or bolt-on joint. Hide glue is the traditional adhesive throughout because of its stiffness and reversibility. Building a guitar from a kit is the standard starting point."},{id:"mg-ukulele-build",topic:"Ukulele construction as a beginner instrument build",keywords:["ukulele","build","small","instrument","top","back","neck","fingerboard","glue","fret"],answer:"A ukulele is an excellent first instrument building project — smaller and simpler than a guitar. Kits are available with pre-bent sides, pre-cut tops, and pre-slotted fingerboards. The top is typically solid Sitka spruce or cedar; back and sides are mahogany or koa. Kerfed linings (bent strips with notches) attach the top and back to the sides inside the box. A transverse brace under the soundhole is the primary bracing. The neck is carved or cut to shape and attached with either a dovetail mortise or bolts. Traditional construction uses hide glue throughout."},{id:"mg-dulcimer-build",topic:"Mountain dulcimer — simplest stringed instrument build",keywords:["dulcimer","mountain","appalachian","simple","instrument","hourglass","fret","board"],answer:"The mountain dulcimer is one of the simplest stringed instruments to build from scratch. The hourglass or teardrop body is made from thin solid wood (cedar top, walnut or cherry back and sides). Sides are steam-bent or sawn into curved shapes. The fingerboard lies on top of the body (unlike guitar where it's on the neck). The unique feature is that the frets are diatonically spaced — not chromatic like a guitar. Plans and kits are widely available; a complete dulcimer can be built in a weekend with basic hand tools and a few specialty jigs."},{id:"mg-arc-length",topic:"Calculating arc length for curved rails and aprons",keywords:["arc","length","radius","angle","curve","apron","rail","chord","lumber"],answer:'Arc length = radius × angle in radians = radius × (angle in degrees × π / 180). For a curved cabinet apron with a 36" radius and 60° sweep angle: arc length = 36 × (60 × π / 180) = 36 × 1.047 = 37.7". The piece of straight lumber needed to make this arc is at least the arc length. Account for the kerf-bent or steam-bent waste factor. For a chord (straight-line distance between endpoints): chord = 2 × radius × sin(angle/2).'},{id:"mg-dovetail-math",topic:"Calculating dovetail spacing mathematically",keywords:["dovetail","spacing","math","calculate","divide","even","pins","half","formula"],answer:"For a board of width W, with half-pins at each end of width P, and N full tails of width T with gaps G: W = 2(P) + N(T) + (N+1)(G). Rearranged: T = (W − 2P − (N+1)G) / N. Choose N and G to give a pleasing tail-to-pin ratio (typically T is 2×G or 3×G). Solve for T and verify by multiplying out. In practice, most woodworkers use dividers to step off the spacing visually until the dividers divide the space evenly — the math verifies the answer."},{id:"mg-lathe-speed-calc",topic:"Lathe speed calculation formula",keywords:["lathe","speed","rpm","formula","surface","feet","per","minute","sfm","safe"],answer:'Safe surface speed for wood turning: 1000–2000 SFPM (surface feet per minute). RPM = (SFPM × 12) / (π × diameter in inches). For a 10" bowl blank at 1500 SFPM target: RPM = (1500 × 12) / (3.14 × 10) = 18000 / 31.4 ≈ 573 RPM. Use the lower end for rough unbalanced blanks; the higher end for trued-up blanks nearing final dimension. A simpler rule of thumb: 6000 / diameter in inches = approximate maximum RPM for balanced stock.'},{id:"mg-feed-rate-router",topic:"Router feed rate and chip load",keywords:["router","feed","rate","chip","load","RPM","flute","speed","cut","quality"],answer:'Feed rate (inches per minute) = RPM × number of flutes × chip load. A 1/2" 2-flute upcut spiral bit at 18,000 RPM with a 0.004" chip load: feed = 18000 × 2 × 0.004 = 144 IPM. Moving too slow burns the wood and dulls the bit faster; too fast causes rough cuts and potential bit breakage. Chip load (material removed per tooth per revolution) varies by material — harder wood requires smaller chip load. Most woodworkers adjust feed rate by sound and feel: a smooth, consistent hum with chip-like shavings (not dust) indicates correct feed rate.'},{id:"mg-golden-rectangle",topic:"Constructing a golden rectangle with compass and straightedge",keywords:["golden","rectangle","construct","compass","phi","ratio","geometric","design"],answer:"To construct a golden rectangle: draw a square (side = S). Bisect the bottom side. Draw an arc from the midpoint of the bottom side, radius = midpoint to top-far-corner. Where the arc crosses the extended bottom baseline is the golden rectangle width (S × 1.618). This gives the exact golden ratio geometrically without calculation. Use this construction to set out furniture proportions when designing from scratch at the bench — a compass and straightedge rather than a ruler and calculator."},{id:"mg-shop-layout-planning",topic:"Planning a shop layout on paper",keywords:["shop","layout","plan","machine","clearance","workflow","floor","area","grid"],answer:`Draw the shop floor on graph paper at 1/4"=1' scale. Cut scale templates for each machine (including outfeed clearance zones in a different color). Arrange templates to minimize material handling steps — the flow of lumber from rough to finished should move logically through the space without backtracking. The table saw is usually the anchor machine; other machines orbit around it. Leave at least 3' walkway between any two machines when both are in use simultaneously. Consider machine noise — noisy machines (router table, jointer) near walls reduce echo compared to the center of the shop.`},{id:"mg-lumber-grade-yield",topic:"Calculating usable yield from different lumber grades",keywords:["grade","yield","common","FAS","percent","calculate","cutting","list","buy"],answer:`FAS grade yields 83%+ clear cuttings (minimum 6"×8" or 3"×7" clear sections). #1 Common yields 66%+. #2 Common yields 50%+. In practice, FAS from a good dealer often yields 90%+ for furniture parts. #1 Common from the same dealer might yield 75% for smaller parts. Calculate: take the board foot count of your cut list, multiply by the inverse of expected yield, and that's how much to buy. For #1 Common at 75% yield with a 30 BF cut list: buy 30 / 0.75 = 40 BF minimum, then add 15% for errors.`},{id:"mg-moisture-species-correction",topic:"Moisture meter species correction factors",keywords:["moisture","meter","species","correction","calibrate","pin","reading","douglas","fir"],answer:"Most pin-type moisture meters are calibrated for Douglas fir. Other species require a correction factor. Hard maple reads about 1% high on a Douglas fir scale; walnut reads about 0.5% low; red oak about right. The meter's species correction table (or built-in species selection) accounts for the different electrical resistance of each wood species. Always set the species correctly before taking readings — an uncorrected reading on dense hardwood can be 2–3% off from the actual moisture content, which matters when deciding if lumber is ready to use."},{id:"mg-skip-planed",topic:"Skip-planed lumber — what it means",keywords:["skip","planed","rough","surfaced","partial","yard","see","color","figure"],answer:`Skip-planed (also called "skip-dressed") lumber has been run once lightly through a wide-belt sander or planer — not fully surfaced. The result shows most of the wood's color and figure (so you can see what you're buying) while leaving the board with irregular thickness that still needs final milling. Many hardwood dealers offer skip-planed stock as a premium service — you can select for color and figure without buying fully rough stock. The cost is between rough sawn and S2S.`},{id:"mg-slab-flattening-router",topic:"Flattening a slab with a router sled",keywords:["slab","flatten","router","sled","rail","bit","skim","large","surface","flat"],answer:'A router sled spans across the slab on two flat rails set level with each other. The router rides on a crossmember that moves along the rails, and the bit (usually a 1.5"+ surfacing bit) skims the slab to a consistent depth. Move the router in overlapping passes to cover the full surface. Lower the bit slightly after each pass until the entire surface has been cut. The rails must be perfectly level and rigid — flex in the rails produces a wavy surface. This technique works for slabs too wide for any jointer or planer.'},{id:"mg-reclaimed-hardwood-barn",topic:"What to expect from antique barn oak and chestnut",keywords:["reclaimed","barn","oak","chestnut","wormy","character","old","growth","nail","gray"],answer:'Antique barn wood (often white oak, American chestnut, or mixed hardwoods) is typically old-growth timber with very tight grain, extreme density, and character marks from a century of use. American chestnut is now functionally extinct in living trees — reclaimed chestnut from old buildings is the only source. "Wormy chestnut" has distinctive worm channels from chestnut blight beetle damage. Expect nail holes, surface weathering, and variable moisture content. Plane conservatively — old-growth oak can be very hard and dull tooling fast. The payoff is irreplaceable material.'},{id:"mg-router-plane-depth",topic:"Setting router plane depth precisely",keywords:["router","plane","depth","set","hinge","mortise","groove","consistent","stop"],answer:`The router plane sets depth by clamping the blade at the desired projection below the sole. To hit an exact depth: set the blade tip on a known surface (the work or a flat reference), zero your depth reference, then raise the blade the desired amount. Use the micro-adjust lever if your plane has one. For hinge mortises, set to the exact hinge leaf thickness (typically 1.5mm or 1/16") and make a test cut. The beauty of the router plane is its ability to trim down exactly to the baseline you've established — you can't overshoot the depth.`},{id:"mg-shoulder-plane-fitting",topic:"Using the shoulder plane for tenon shoulder gaps",keywords:["shoulder","plane","fit","tenon","gap","square","paring","tight","closing"],answer:"When a tenon shoulder doesn't fully close against the mortised piece, you see a small gap at the shoulder — a shoulder plane fixes this. Check which shoulder (top, bottom, or sides) has the gap by test-fitting and looking carefully. Set the shoulder plane very fine, rest the sole flat on the tenon face, and take thin shavings from the shoulder that has the gap. Check frequently. The goal is a shoulder that seats completely around the perimeter with no visible gaps. Work one shoulder at a time to avoid removing too much material and creating a sloppy joint."},{id:"mg-plane-tearout-figured",topic:"Planing highly figured wood without tearout",keywords:["figured","plane","tearout","curly","birdseye","tight","mouth","cap","iron","angle"],answer:`Highly figured wood (curly, birdseye, crotch) has grain that reverses direction frequently — there's no single grain direction to plane with. Strategies: tighten the mouth opening to its minimum; set the cap iron very close to the edge (1/32" or less); increase the cutting angle to 50°–55° (steepen the frog); take extremely thin shavings (0.001" or less). A cabinet scraper is often the better choice for final prep on highly figured wood — it cuts at nearly 90° and can't cause tearout in the same way. Accept more sanding time on these beautiful but challenging boards.`},{id:"mg-chisel-chopping-mortise",topic:"Chopping a mortise — step-by-step technique",keywords:["chop","mortise","chisel","mallet","sequence","depth","half","flip","clean"],answer:'Lay out the mortise with a mortise gauge. Working about 1/16" inside the layout line: chop straight down in 1/8" depth increments, moving along the mortise length. After reaching half the mortise depth from one side, flip the board and chop from the other side until the chips fall out in the middle. Clean the walls on the layout line on the final pass. Never lever against the mortise wall — lever against the waste between chop locations. Work from the center out toward the ends (not end to end), which gives the waste somewhere to fall.'},{id:"mg-handsaw-types",topic:"Panel saws vs backsaws — when to use each",keywords:["panel","saw","back","saw","spine","rip","crosscut","length","accuracy"],answer:"Panel saws (no stiffener spine) are for rough cutting full-length boards where the depth of cut exceeds what a back saw's spine would allow. They're less accurate than back saws. Back saws (the spine stiffens the plate) are for precise joinery cuts — dovetails, tenon shoulders, bridle joints. Use a panel saw to cut rough lumber to approximate length, then a back saw to cut joinery at exact layout lines. The distinction: panel saw for breaking down, back saw for precise cuts. A Japanese ryoba (no spine, pull-stroke, very thin plate) bridges the two uses effectively."},{id:"mg-cabinet-making-foundation",topic:"Foundation skills for cabinetmaking",keywords:["foundation","skill","cabinet","joint","square","measure","layout","plane","chop"],answer:"Before building furniture, master these five foundation skills: (1) reading and marking accurate layout lines with a marking knife and square; (2) planing wood flat and square with a bench plane; (3) cutting to a knife line with a back saw; (4) chopping a mortise and fitting a tenon; (5) sharpening your tools to a working edge. These skills are the vocabulary of furniture-making. Without them, every project becomes a frustrating battle against the material. Spend time on each skill in isolation — small practice boards — before combining them in a project."}],d=[{id:"mh-measuring-tape-accuracy",topic:"Getting accurate tape measure readings",keywords:["tape","measure","accuracy","hook","bend","end","zero","true","reliable"],answer:'Tape measure hooks are designed to shift by exactly the thickness of the hook for both inside and outside measurements — but cheap tapes have sloppy hooks that introduce error. Test your tape by measuring the same distance with the hook pulled out (outside measure) and pushed in (inside measure). Both should read the same. Mark your most-used tapes with a Sharpie to identify which are most accurate. For precise joinery, a 6" steel rule is more reliable than any tape measure.'},{id:"mh-pencil-vs-knife",topic:"When to use a pencil vs a marking knife",keywords:["pencil","marking","knife","line","accurate","when","which","thickness","reference"],answer:`Use a pencil for rough layout, dimensioning long boards, and marking waste areas. Use a marking knife at shoulder lines, dovetail baselines, and any line where the saw or chisel must hit exactly — the knife severs surface fibers cleanly and leaves a crisp reference line that's sharper than any pencil line. The knife line also creates a tiny trench that the chisel registers in automatically, giving you mechanical guidance. The general rule: if a mismatch of 1/64" matters, use a knife; if 1/32" is acceptable, use a pencil.`},{id:"mh-dry-fit-always",topic:"Why dry-fitting before gluing is mandatory",keywords:["dry","fit","assemble","test","clamp","glue","up","problem","find","practice"],answer:"Always dry-fit an entire assembly before applying glue. This reveals joints that won't fully close, clamp positions that don't reach, parts assembled in the wrong order, and square problems. Once glue is applied, you have 5–10 minutes to fix problems — not enough time to discover them. A good dry-fit with all clamps staged and checked means glue-up is simply a repeat of the dry run. Rushing to glue without a dry-fit is one of the most common and expensive beginner mistakes in furniture making."},{id:"mh-test-cut-scrap",topic:"Always make a test cut in scrap first",keywords:["test","cut","scrap","same","material","dial","in","jig","bit","blade"],answer:"Make every first cut in scrap from the same board (or at least the same species and thickness) as your project material. A setup dial-in in different material may not transfer — different species have different machine resistance, causing routing depth or blade position to shift. This applies to every new jig setup, every first rip on a new board, every router bit change, and every miter angle setup. The 2 minutes spent on a test cut prevents the most frustrating outcome in woodworking: a ruined piece of expensive lumber."},{id:"mh-sandpaper-loading",topic:"Preventing sandpaper loading — chalking and changing",keywords:["sandpaper","load","clog","resin","pine","chalk","change","fresh","clean"],answer:"Sandpaper loads (clogs) when sanding residue fills the abrasive grit, reducing cutting action and causing heat. Loaded paper produces burn marks and deposits residue into the wood rather than removing it. With resinous woods (pine, cherry), the problem is worst. Use a rubber abrasive cleaning stick (sandpaper cleaning stick) — drag it across the moving belt sander or ROS pad to clean the grit. Chalk the surface before sanding resinous wood — the chalk breaks the resin adhesion slightly. Change paper frequently; loading is cumulative."},{id:"mh-layout-reference-face",topic:"Reference face and edge — marking and maintaining",keywords:["reference","face","edge","mark","datum","square","check","consistent"],answer:"Mark your reference face (face side) with a loop and your reference edge (face edge) with a tick mark as soon as a board is flattened. All measurements and markings originate from these faces. Always place the reference face down on the jointer and against the planer infeed table. Always place the reference edge against the table saw fence. This consistency ensures parts that appear to have the same dimensions actually do have them — measuring from mixed faces introduces cumulative error. Never lose track of which face is which during a project."},{id:"mh-squaring-carcase",topic:"Squaring a cabinet carcase during glue-up",keywords:["square","carcase","cabinet","diagonal","clamp","rack","diagonal","adjust"],answer:"Check diagonal measurements immediately after clamping and before the glue stiffens. Equal diagonals mean square. If one diagonal is longer, push the longer-diagonal corners together by angling a clamp or bar diagonally across the out-of-square direction. A clamp placed diagonally on the long diagonal compresses it. Re-check diagonals. Also ensure the carcase isn't in wind (twisted) — set it on a known-flat surface or check with winding sticks across the top and bottom. A twisted carcase is harder to fix than a racked one."},{id:"mh-checking-flat-handplane",topic:"Checking a panel for flat using a winding stick and straightedge",keywords:["flat","check","winding","stick","straightedge","panel","twist","cup","hump"],answer:"Check a panel in three ways before final assembly. Winding sticks across both ends reveal twist. A straightedge along the length (both diagonals and down the middle) reveals bow. A straightedge across the width reveals cupping. All three checks are necessary — a board can pass two tests and still have a significant defect in the third direction. Hand-plane to address each condition in order: flatten twist first, then bow, then cup. After each correction, re-check all three before moving on."},{id:"mh-glue-squeeze-out-interior",topic:"Cleaning glue from cabinet interiors",keywords:["glue","squeeze","out","interior","cabinet","corner","reach","clean","finish"],answer:"Interior cabinet corners are the hardest place to remove glue squeeze-out. Use a small chisel held flat against the panel surface to pare the gel-stage squeeze-out. A glue scraper with a corner profile (or a sharpened wooden stick) reaches into the corner. Alternatively, tape the inside corner with masking tape before glue-up — pull the tape while squeeze-out is still wet for a clean corner. Interior glue residue blocks stain and is visible through finishes, so clean completely before finishing."},{id:"mh-assembly-stage-sequence",topic:"Staging complex assembly — sub-assemblies first",keywords:["assembly","stage","sub","sequence","complex","order","accessible","reach","clamp"],answer:"Large furniture assemblies (bookcases, tables with multiple stretchers) are impossible to glue in one step within the open time of the adhesive. Break the project into sub-assemblies and identify the correct order. Typically: glue the two-rail subassemblies first (like two side frames), let cure, then connect those with cross rails. Identify which joints are inaccessible after other parts are assembled — those must be glued early in the sequence. Write the assembly order on paper and rehearse it completely dry before touching any glue."},{id:"mh-masking-tape-tearout",topic:"Masking tape to prevent tearout on sensitive cuts",keywords:["masking","tape","tearout","veneer","plywood","laminate","score","cut","line"],answer:"Applying a strip of blue painter's tape along a cut line supports the surface fibers and dramatically reduces tearout on veneered plywood and crosscut ends. Apply tape, mark and score the cut line through the tape with a knife, then saw right through both tape and wood. Remove tape after cutting. The tape keeps the fibers supported right up to the saw kerf. This works for table saw crosscuts, circular saw cuts, and jigsaw cuts where tearout is otherwise unavoidable. On veneer and melamine, tape reduces splintering to near-zero on the top face."},{id:"mh-registration-marks",topic:"Registration marks for assembly orientation",keywords:["registration","mark","assembly","orient","pencil","triangle","face","edge","match"],answer:"Before disassembling any dry-fitted structure, mark all mating joints with matching marks — a triangle across the joint is the classic method (half on each piece). When the triangle points are aligned at assembly, the parts are in the correct orientation. This is essential when parts look identical but aren't (face frames, carcases with subtle asymmetry) and when multiple similar joints could be mixed up. Mark inside surfaces that won't be visible in the final piece."},{id:"mh-wax-lubricant",topic:"Wax as a lubricant in the shop",keywords:["wax","lubricant","drawer","runner","plane","sole","table","saw","resist","sticky"],answer:"Paste wax (or toilet bowl wax) lubricates drawer runners, plane soles, saw table surfaces, and router table tops. On a wooden drawer runner, wax reduces drag dramatically. On a cast iron machine table, wax prevents rust and allows workpieces to glide smoothly. On a hand plane sole, wax reduces the effort needed to push the plane. Avoid silicone spray in the shop — it contaminates wood surfaces and causes fisheye in finishes. Wax is always the safe choice: it won't hurt the wood and wipes off before finishing."},{id:"mh-wood-movement-rules",topic:"The five rules of wood movement in furniture",keywords:["movement","rule","grain","direction","allow","float","glue","seasonal","design"],answer:"Rule 1: Wood moves across the grain only (tangential and radial), negligibly along the grain. Rule 2: Never glue solid wood cross-grain — it will crack. Rule 3: Float solid panels in frames without glue. Rule 4: Attach solid tabletops with clips or figure-8s that allow movement. Rule 5: Orient all boards in a panel with grain running the same direction. Follow these rules and seasonal movement becomes a managed design element rather than a destructive force."},{id:"mh-prototype-mockup",topic:"Building a prototype or mockup before the real thing",keywords:["prototype","mockup","cardboard","cheap","pine","test","proportion","sit","chair"],answer:"For seating (chairs, benches), always build a prototype at full scale before committing to expensive material. A cardboard or cheap pine mockup reveals whether angles are comfortable and proportions look right in reality vs how they appeared in a drawing. For chairs especially, sit in the prototype extensively before building the final piece. A 2-hour mockup can save a 40-hour build from producing an uncomfortable chair. The same principle applies to cabinets — a full-scale paper template on the wall shows whether a cabinet will fit and look right in the actual space."},{id:"mh-panel-glue-up-strategy",topic:"Strategy for successful wide panel glue-ups",keywords:["panel","glue","up","wide","board","arrange","alternate","grain","direction","joint"],answer:"For glued-up solid wood panels: arrange boards in multiple combinations before committing to a grain pattern. Alternate the direction of the annual ring curves (one board ring-side up, next ring-side down) to reduce potential cupping — this is traditional advice, though its effectiveness is debated. More important: keep grain directions consistent for planing, and book-match adjacent boards from the same log for visual continuity. Mark the layout in pencil on the face side before disassembling. Glue in groups of 2–3 boards rather than all at once to manage open time."},{id:"mh-shop-math-rule-of-thumb",topic:"Rule-of-thumb measurements that every woodworker should know",keywords:["rule","thumb","measurement","standard","approximate","estimate","quick","common"],answer:`Useful shop rules of thumb: 3/4" is the most common furniture panel thickness. 1.5" square is the minimum leg size for a dining table that won't look spindly. 2" square to 2.5" feels substantial. Tenon thickness = 1/3 the stock. Shelf sag: 3/4" ply sags noticeably over 36" under book loads. A comfortable seat height is 17"–18". Desk height is 28"–30". Standard cabinet depth for kitchen uppers: 12". For base cabinets: 24". Bevel angle for a 1:6 dovetail: 9.5°. These numbers become automatic with experience.`},{id:"mh-using-offcuts",topic:"Getting value from lumber offcuts",keywords:["offcut","scrap","small","wood","use","wedge","shim","caul","test","setup"],answer:"Never throw away hardwood offcuts immediately — they're useful for wedges (align cabinet feet, shim clamping cauls), setup test pieces (confirm bit depth, blade height, finish compatibility), small parts (drawer stops, shelf pin filler pieces, hinge backing), and clamping cauls. Keep a scrap bin organized by species and thickness. The greatest value of a scrap bin: being able to make one more test cut on identical material before committing to the actual workpiece. When scrap exceeds what you can use, donate or sell it."},{id:"mh-finish-schedule",topic:"Creating a finishing schedule for a project",keywords:["finish","schedule","plan","sequence","grain","stain","seal","coat","timeline"],answer:"Write a finish schedule before opening any can. Specify: surface prep steps and grits; raise grain (Y/N); stain or dye steps; wash coat or sealer steps; topcoat product; number of coats; grit between coats; final rub-out approach. Test the complete schedule on sample boards before touching the project. A finish schedule prevents the common mistake of applying products in the wrong order (stain over sealed wood, wax over un-cured poly) and ensures you have all products on hand before starting."},{id:"mh-restoring-old-planes",topic:"Restoring old Stanley or Record hand planes",keywords:["restore","old","plane","stanley","record","rust","clean","lap","frog","adjust"],answer:"Old Stanley No.4 and No.5 planes from flea markets and estate sales are often better-quality steel than new budget planes. Restoration: soak in WD-40 and scrub with a wire brush for initial rust removal. Flatten the sole on a sheet of 120-grit sandpaper on plate glass. Flatten the back of the iron. Sharpen to a working edge. Check that the frog sits flat and the lever cap has correct tension. Adjust the chip breaker gap. The whole process takes 1–2 hours and produces a very capable plane. A rusty vintage No.5 for $15 often outperforms a new $50 import plane."},{id:"mh-oiling-cast-iron",topic:"Caring for cast iron machine surfaces",keywords:["cast","iron","rust","oil","protect","clean","machine","table","saw","jointer"],answer:"Cast iron rusts quickly in humid shops. After use: wipe the machine table clean of sawdust, then apply a thin coat of paste wax or a few drops of camellia oil (traditional Japanese tool oil) and buff lightly. This leaves a micro-thin protective film. For existing light rust: scrub with 0000 steel wool and WD-40, then apply the protective wax. For heavy rust: use a rust eraser or sandpaper (120 grit) on a flat block to remove the rust without damaging the flatness of the table. Never use coarse sandpaper on a precision machine surface."},{id:"mh-joint-wont-close",topic:"Why a joint won't fully close and how to fix it",keywords:["joint","close","gap","shoulder","tenon","mortise","fix","gap","trim"],answer:"A joint that won't close usually has a high spot somewhere. Rub chalk or pencil on the tenon faces, assemble, disassemble, and read where the chalk transferred to the mortise walls — those are the high spots. Remove material only from the high spots, working incrementally. Gaps at tenon shoulders (the flat faces around the tenon) are fixed with a shoulder plane. Gaps caused by a mortise that's not quite square are fixed by paring the mortise wall square. Never force a tight joint with a mallet — identify and fix the cause."},{id:"mh-racking-frame",topic:"Preventing and fixing a racked frame after glue-up",keywords:["racked","frame","diagonal","square","push","pull","fix","adjust","glue"],answer:"A racked frame (one that's parallelogram-shaped instead of rectangular) must be corrected before the glue cures — after that it's very difficult to fix. Prevention: check diagonals immediately after clamping, adjust by angling a clamp diagonally across the longer diagonal. If the frame has already cured racked: cut it apart at the joints (carefully with a handsaw and chisel), clean the joint surfaces, and reglue squarely. For minor racking on face frames and cabinet backs, a diagonal back panel (plywood) screwed across the back can force the carcase square as it's fastened."},{id:"mh-dovetail-gap-causes",topic:"Diagnosing gaps in hand-cut dovetails",keywords:["dovetail","gap","cause","diagnose","tail","pin","fit","open","tight","chisel"],answer:"Gaps in dovetails have specific causes. Gap at the baseline: the bottom of the tails isn't seated (chop the baseline deeper on the pin board or the baseline of the tail board). Gap in the middle of a tail: the pin is too wide in the middle; pare the mortise walls. Gap at the outside of the joint (at the face): either the tails or pins are slightly too narrow at the outside — accept it as cosmetic or re-cut the joint. Tails won't enter at all: pins too wide; pare the pin sides carefully in the direction that's tight."},{id:"mh-tenon-too-loose",topic:"Fixing a tenon that's too loose in its mortise",keywords:["tenon","loose","sloppy","wobble","fix","shim","veneer","glue","rattle"],answer:`A tenon that's too loose in its mortise produces a joint with inadequate glue contact and poor mechanical strength. Small slop (1/64"–1/32"): a bit of extra PVA thickness will bridge it — the joint will be somewhat weaker but functional. More slop: glue a thin veneer or wood shim to the tenon face, let cure, then pare to the correct thickness. The ideal is to re-cut a new tenon from a new piece of stock — patching a very sloppy tenon rarely looks or performs well. Prevention is always better: sneak up on tenon thickness in multiple passes.`},{id:"mh-miter-gap-fix",topic:"Fixing a visible gap in a miter joint",keywords:["miter","gap","fix","burnish","sawdust","glue","color","match","rub"],answer:`A small miter gap (less than 1/32") can be closed by burnishing — rub the surface of the miter with a smooth rod (burnisher or chisel back) to compress and raise the wood fibers into the gap. This works on solid wood, not veneer or plywood. For slightly larger gaps: fill with a mixture of the same wood's fine sawdust (from sanding the mating piece) and glue, let cure, sand flush. For miter gaps on frame-and-panel projects: a spline added after assembly is the structural fix; filling is only cosmetic.`},{id:"mh-desk-ergonomics",topic:"Desk ergonomics — height, monitor, and keyboard",keywords:["desk","ergonomics","height","monitor","keyboard","adjustable","standing","wrist"],answer:`Ergonomic desk height: elbows at 90° when hands rest on the keyboard — typically 25"–29" depending on person height. Monitor eye level at arm's length (18"–24") from eyes; top of screen at or slightly below eye level. A fixed-height desk optimized for typing (lower) conflicts with monitor height (ideally higher) — the traditional solution is a keyboard tray under a standard 30" desk. Adjustable-height (sit-stand) desks are increasingly preferred as the healthiest option for all-day computer work.`},{id:"mh-arm-chair-dimensions",topic:"Armchair dimensions for comfort",keywords:["armchair","dimension","seat","arm","height","depth","back","comfort","lounge"],answer:'Lounge armchair dimensions: seat height 15"–17" (lower than dining chair for relaxed posture). Seat depth 18"–22" (deeper than dining chair). Seat width 22"–26". Arm height above seat: 7"–8". Back angle from vertical: 15°–25° (more recline than dining). Overall seat back height: 30"–36" for head support. For upholstered chairs, finished dimensions after cushion must match these targets — calculate the required unupholstered frame dimensions by subtracting cushion thickness from the target seat height.'},{id:"mh-shelf-depth-standards",topic:"Shelf depth standards for different items",keywords:["shelf","depth","standard","book","dinnerware","pantry","closet","linen"],answer:'Standard shelf depths by application: paperback books 8"–9"; hardcovers and trade paperbacks 10"–12"; oversized art books 14"–16"; average dinner plate 12"–14"; standard closet shelf 12"–14"; linen closet 12"–16"; pantry items 12"–16"; garage shelving 18"–24". In custom shelving, depth affects the visual weight of the piece — deeper shelves look heavier; shallow shelves lighter. Always measure your specific items before finalizing depth — a shelf 1" too shallow for your items is worthless.'},{id:"mh-drawer-width-height",topic:"Drawer sizing by intended contents",keywords:["drawer","size","width","height","silverware","file","clothing","deep","contents"],answer:'Size drawers for their contents. Silverware drawer: 2"–3" interior height. Shallow utility drawer (office supplies): 3"–4". Clothing: 6"–8" height per drawer for folded clothes. File drawers: letter file is 8.5" wide minimum clear (12"–14" for hanging files); legal is 14"–15". Kitchen utensil drawer: 3"–4" interior height. Deep pot and pan drawer: 8"–12" interior height. Width: plan each drawer for its specific function — a kitchen knife drawer should be as long as your longest knife (usually 14"+).'},{id:"mh-closet-standard-heights",topic:"Closet rod and shelf height standards",keywords:["closet","rod","height","shelf","double","hang","long","short","standard"],answer:`Single-hang closet rod: 66"–68" from floor (for full-length dresses and coats). Double-hang top rod: 80"–82"; bottom rod: 40"–42". Short-hang (shirts, jackets) rod: 40"–42". Shelf above single rod: 82"–84". Standard closet shelf above the rod: 8"–12" of clearance above the rod to the shelf. For custom closets, measure the specific garments to be stored — a tall person's shirts hang longer; account for this in the short-hang section.`},{id:"mh-router-table-height",topic:"Router table bit height setting techniques",keywords:["router","table","bit","height","set","ruler","reference","fence","groove","depth"],answer:"Set router table bit height with a setup block (a dedicated piece of MDF or solid wood set to a known height) or a router table setup gauge. For edge profiles, the bit height relative to the fence surface determines where the profile appears on the edge. Test on scrap before cutting good material. For grooves or rabbets, use a steel rule on the table to measure from the table surface to the highest point of the bit. After dialing in, never adjust the bit height during a cut — retract the workpiece first, adjust, then run through again."},{id:"mh-bandsaw-curve-technique",topic:"Cutting curves on the bandsaw",keywords:["bandsaw","curve","technique","feed","relief","pivot","tight","exit","steer"],answer:"Cut curves on the bandsaw by feeding slowly and steering gently — never force the turn. If the curve is tighter than the blade width allows, make relief cuts (straight cuts from the outside edge to the cut line at intervals) so the waste falls away in sections as you cut the curve. For a very tight radius, switch to a narrower blade before attempting the cut. Exit the cut the same way you entered — pull the workpiece straight back out if you need to stop mid-cut. Blade drift means you may need to steer slightly to keep the cut on the line."},{id:"mh-jigsaw-circle",topic:"Cutting circles with a jigsaw and pivot guide",keywords:["jigsaw","circle","pivot","guide","radius","smooth","round","cut"],answer:'A jigsaw pivot guide clamps to the saw base and allows scribing a circle by pivoting around a fixed center nail. The nail drives into the center of the desired circle; the guide sets the radius. Feed the jigsaw slowly and steadily around the circle. The result is smoother than cutting freehand but still needs sanding. For circles under 12" diameter where a router circle jig is impractical because of bit reach limitations, the jigsaw pivot guide is the quickest approach. Finish with a drum sander or router flush-trim bit for a truly smooth edge.'},{id:"mh-drill-press-speed-chart",topic:"Drill press speed selection by bit size and material",keywords:["drill","press","speed","rpm","bit","size","material","hardwood","softwood","forstner"],answer:'General drill press speed guide (RPM): 1/4" bit in hardwood: 3000. 1/2" in hardwood: 1500. 1" Forstner in hardwood: 500–750. 1-1/2" Forstner in hardwood: 300–400. 2" Forstner: 200–300. In softwood, use speeds 25% higher. Spade bits in softwood: use higher speeds for clean cutting (2000–3000 for small sizes). Hole saws (1-1/2"+ diameter): 400–600 RPM. Twist drills in metal (if needed in the wood shop): much slower than in wood. The general rule: larger bits need lower speeds to maintain safe rim cutting velocity and prevent burning.'},{id:"mh-pocket-hole-angle",topic:"Why pocket hole joints drive at an angle",keywords:["pocket","hole","angle","15","degree","jig","clamping","counter","torque"],answer:"Pocket hole jigs drill at 15° — this angle allows the screw to pass from one workpiece and cross-grain into the mating piece without the shallow angle that would exit through a face. The 15° angle also provides mechanical advantage when tightening — the screw threads engage wood fibers across a longer length than a perpendicular screw would. A pocket hole clamp (Kreg or similar) is essential because the angled screw exerts a force that shifts the mating pieces apart as the screw drives — the clamp holds them together until the screw is fully seated."},{id:"mh-table-saw-riving-knife",topic:"Installing and setting a riving knife correctly",keywords:["riving","knife","set","height","distance","blade","anti","kickback","position"],answer:"A riving knife must be: the same thickness or very slightly thinner than the kerf of the blade (so the cut workpiece can move past it without binding); positioned behind the blade (never beside or in front); set so the top of the knife is below the top of the blade (to allow the workpiece to pass over it on the exit side). The knife follows the blade as it tilts. Never use a blade thinner than the riving knife (the knife would then be wider than the kerf, splitting the cut wood and causing binding). Replace the riving knife any time you change blade thickness."},{id:"mh-random-orbit-technique",topic:"Random orbit sander — move it slowly",keywords:["random","orbit","sander","move","slow","fast","swirl","cross","scratch","pressure"],answer:"The most common ROS mistake is moving too fast — at one inch per second, the random pattern doesn't develop, leaving quasi-directional scratches that appear as swirl marks under finish. Move the sander at half an inch per second or less. Apply only the sander's own weight — extra pressure forces the pad to spin in a fixed pattern. Sand the entire surface in overlapping passes before changing grit. Inspect under raking light after each grit change — previous grit scratches must be fully removed before moving to the next finer grit."},{id:"mh-track-saw-setup",topic:"Setting up a track saw for accurate cuts",keywords:["track","saw","setup","align","anti-splinter","offset","score","parallel","fence"],answer:"Track saw setup: place the track's anti-splinter strip exactly on the cut line (the strip marks where the blade will cut, not an offset to account for). Clamp the track at both ends. Make sure the track is long enough to support the saw for the full cut length. Score lightly first if the material chips easily. The track's factory anti-splinter strip may need trimming on first use — run the saw along the track without a workpiece to cut the strip to its exact width. After that, align the strip edge to the cut line for perfect accuracy."},{id:"mh-screw-species-hold",topic:"Screw holding power in different wood species",keywords:["screw","holding","power","species","withdrawal","load","hardwood","softwood"],answer:"Screw withdrawal resistance scales with wood density. Hard maple holds screws roughly twice as strongly as pine. Walnut, cherry, and white oak have excellent screw holding. Soft, low-density woods (balsa, basswood, western red cedar) hold screws poorly. In any species, face grain screws hold far better than end grain screws. In sheet goods (particleboard, MDF), screw holding depends on the particulate size and glue quality — generally much weaker than solid wood. Use coarser threads and larger diameters in softer materials to compensate."},{id:"mh-mortise-hinge-depth",topic:"Hinge mortise depth — avoiding common error",keywords:["hinge","mortise","depth","leaf","thick","measure","recess","plate","error"],answer:'The most common hinge mortising error: cutting the mortise to the full hinge open thickness instead of one leaf thickness. Each leaf of the hinge gets its own mortise — one in the door edge, one in the frame or carcase. Each mortise depth equals one leaf thickness (typically 1.5mm or 1/16"). Measure the leaf thickness with a dial caliper, not a ruler. Too deep a mortise makes the door bind when closing (hinges bottom out). Too shallow means the door face sits proud of the carcase face. A correctly mortised hinge sits perfectly flush on both pieces.'},{id:"mh-wood-screw-drive",topic:"Screw drive types — slotted, Phillips, square, star",keywords:["screw","drive","slotted","phillips","square","star","Torx","cam","out","strip"],answer:"Slotted screws strip easily and are no longer used in furniture. Phillips (cross) drive cams out intentionally at a design force limit — useful in production but causes strip-out when the screw is over-torqued. Square (Robertson) drive is the favorite of cabinetmakers for its positive engagement and no cam-out. Star (Torx) has even better engagement and is common in structural and stainless screws. For pocket hole and face frame work, use square drive or Torx drive screws — they strip out far less often than Phillips and don't require holding pressure on the driver."},{id:"mh-toggle-bolt-wood",topic:"When NOT to use toggle bolts in wood",keywords:["toggle","bolt","drywall","anchor","hollow","wood","wrong","alternative"],answer:"Toggle bolts are designed for hollow walls (drywall, hollow block) — in wood, they create unnecessarily large holes and provide less holding power than a properly sized wood screw or lag bolt. For hanging heavy items on wood shelves or cleats, use a through-bolt with washer and nut on the back, or lag bolts into the studs or solid blocking. If you must attach to a panel where you can't reach the back, a screw-in threaded insert for wood provides better holding power than any toggle in a wood member."},{id:"mh-glue-and-screw",topic:"Glue and screws together — redundant or synergistic",keywords:["glue","screw","together","combine","redundant","face","frame","cabinet"],answer:"Glue and screws together are synergistic for face frames and non-structural assembly — the screws clamp the joint while the glue cures and the glue makes the joint permanent. In structural joints, the screw adds little to a well-glued joint because the glue bond far exceeds the screw's holding power in face grain. Never rely on screws as the primary structural fastener in joinery under stress — the screw acts as a clamp during the glue-up, and after the glue cures, the wood fiber failure load exceeds any reasonable screw count."},{id:"mh-finishing-before-assembly",topic:"Pre-finishing — applying finish before assembly",keywords:["pre","finish","before","assembly","glue","area","inside","corner","mask"],answer:"Pre-finishing applies finish to individual parts before assembly, then assembles the finished parts. This allows you to coat inside corners and narrow recesses that would be inaccessible after assembly. Mask the glue areas with tape before finishing — glue won't bond to finished surfaces. After finishing, remove tape, apply glue to bare wood areas, and assemble. Touch up any finish damage from assembly after the glue cures. Pre-finishing is particularly useful for bookcases with fixed shelves and any case with dado-joined parts."},{id:"mh-finish-wood-species-guide",topic:"Recommended finish by wood species",keywords:["finish","species","recommend","walnut","cherry","oak","maple","pine","match"],answer:"Walnut: oil or wiping varnish to preserve the natural color; avoid heavy poly that obscures the grain. Cherry: oil or shellac; let UV develop the color naturally. Oak: oil finish or wipe-on poly; grain filler first for smooth results. Hard maple: water-based poly (no amber to yellow the white color); or Danish oil for a more natural look. Pine: gel stain to control blotching; shellac primer before paint. Mahogany: wiping varnish or oil; grain filler first. These are starting points — test on scrap from your specific board first."},{id:"mh-furniture-wax-maintain",topic:"Maintaining wax-finished furniture",keywords:["wax","maintain","furniture","reapply","buff","polish","annual","beeswax","carnauba"],answer:"Wax finishes (beeswax, carnauba, Briwax, Renaissance Wax) on furniture need periodic reapplication — typically once a year in normal use or whenever the surface looks dry. Clean the surface with a slightly damp cloth, dry thoroughly, apply thin wax coats, and buff. Never use silicone-based furniture polish on wax-finished pieces — silicone contaminates the surface and prevents future refinishing. Avoid water and heat (hot cups) on wax surfaces — wax provides minimal protection against either. Wax finishes are beautiful but require more maintenance than film finishes."},{id:"mh-aniline-dye-use",topic:"Using aniline dye for intense transparent color",keywords:["aniline","dye","intense","transparent","alcohol","water","NGR","mix","color","fade"],answer:"Aniline dyes produce the most intense, transparent color available for wood — the grain figure shows through brilliantly. Available in water-soluble, alcohol-soluble (NGR), and oil-soluble forms. Water-soluble dyes raise grain — pre-wet and sand first. Alcohol (NGR) dyes dry almost instantly — ideal for spray but tricky to brush. Oil-soluble dyes extend pot life for brushing and don't raise grain. Aniline dyes are generally not lightfast (fade with UV) — use them as a basecoat under a UV-filtering topcoat for furniture that will receive sunlight."},{id:"mh-finishing-turned-bowls",topic:"Finishing turned bowls for food use",keywords:["bowl","finish","food","safe","mineral","oil","wax","tung","water","contact"],answer:"For wood bowls used with food (salad bowls, fruit bowls, serving pieces): use finishes that are food-safe when fully cured. Pure mineral oil (pharmaceutical or food-grade) is safe, widely available, and easy to apply — flood the bowl, let soak, wipe dry. Repeat 4–6 times. Mineral oil doesn't harden, so it needs periodic renewal. Mixed mineral oil + beeswax (board butter) provides a slightly harder surface. Fully cured pure tung oil and linseed oil are also considered food-safe. Film finishes (poly, lacquer) may be food-safe when cured but opinions vary — avoid them on cutting contact surfaces."},{id:"mh-moving-fillister",topic:"Moving fillister plane for rabbets with fence",keywords:["moving","fillister","plane","rabbet","rebate","fence","depth","stop","skewed"],answer:"The moving fillister plane cuts rabbets across or with the grain using an adjustable fence (for width) and a depth stop. The nicker (a small round knife) scores the fibers ahead of the iron for clean crossgrain cuts — critical for cutting across grain without tearout. Set the nicker just fractionally wider than the iron. This plane handles the most common rabbet cuts in traditional furniture and cabinet work without the tearout risk of a router, and with more flexibility than a fixed-width rabbet plane."},{id:"mh-combination-plane",topic:"Stanley 45 and 55 combination planes",keywords:["stanley","45","55","combination","plane","groove","tongue","plough","profile"],answer:"The Stanley 45 and 55 combination planes accept interchangeable blades for cutting grooves, tongues, beads, and moulding profiles — a complete set of specialized planes in one tool. The 45 uses a simpler mechanism with a limited blade range; the 55 accommodates more profiles. Setting up a combination plane is fiddly — depth stop, fence, and nicker all need careful coordination. But once set, they produce perfect grooves and profiles repeatedly. Modern equivalents include the Veritas Combination Plane and the Lee Valley plow plane."},{id:"mh-shooting-miter-correction",topic:"Correcting a miter angle by shooting on stone",keywords:["miter","correct","shoot","stone","angle","error","cumulative","frame","accurate"],answer:"When mitered frame parts don't close perfectly, the error is often distributed across multiple cuts — even 0.1° off per miter produces a significant gap after four corners. Correction: shoot each miter on a shooting board, taking off the minimum needed to close the frame. Shoot two pieces identically (the two pieces that share each corner), maintaining the same angle. Reassemble and check — gaps should close. If a gap remains at one corner only, adjust just the pieces in that corner. Don't try to fix a miter by cutting it over; use the shooting board for fine correction."},{id:"mh-shop-heating",topic:"Heating a woodworking shop safely",keywords:["heat","shop","propane","electric","radiant","infrared","fire","safe","dust"],answer:"Never use open-flame propane heaters in a shop with solvent-based finishes or significant airborne dust. Radiant electric heaters are the safest option — they heat objects and people, not air, and have no open flame. For non-finishing shops, a propane forced-air heater is common but requires excellent ventilation. Wall-mounted infrared heaters (natural gas or propane) heat efficiently in larger shops. A separate finishing room with its own clean, spark-free ventilation is the safest approach for spray finishing. Minimum shop temperature for glue work: 55°F."},{id:"mh-ventilation-finishing",topic:"Shop ventilation for finishing",keywords:["ventilation","finish","spray","solvent","fume","exhaust","fresh","air","booth"],answer:"Solvent-based finishes require exhaust ventilation rated to remove fumes below explosive concentration (LEL — lower explosive limit). For spray finishing, build or buy a finishing booth with an explosion-proof exhaust fan (no brushed motors) vented to the outside. A DIY booth from rigid foam insulation and a window-mounted explosion-proof fan works for small-scale spraying. Always spray with cross-ventilation (air flowing from behind you, out through the booth). Turn off all pilot lights and ignition sources within 50 feet of solvent spray."},{id:"mh-air-filtration",topic:"Shop air filtration unit for fine dust",keywords:["air","filtration","ceiling","unit","ambient","fine","dust","0.3","micron","filter"],answer:"Ceiling-mounted air filtration units (Delta, Jet, WEN) capture the finest dust particles that escape the dust collector and float in the air. They use multiple filter stages, with the finest stage rated at 1 micron or better. Ambient dust (the invisible cloud present in any active shop) is the long-term health risk. Run an air filtration unit during sanding and for 15–30 minutes after work to clear the air. Position the unit to create a circular airflow pattern in the shop for maximum capture efficiency. This is separate from — and complementary to — source-capture dust collection."},{id:"mh-shop-floor",topic:"Shop floor materials — concrete, wood, rubber",keywords:["shop","floor","concrete","fatigue","rubber","mat","wood","comfort","standing"],answer:`Bare concrete is hard on knees and back for extended standing — anti-fatigue rubber mats at each primary work station dramatically reduce fatigue. Interlocking foam tiles cover the whole shop floor at low cost and provide cushioning; they're less durable than rubber but very comfortable. A wooden floor (3/4" plywood on sleepers) above concrete is the most comfortable but adds significant cost and raises machine heights. Dropped tools and chisels are less damaged on wood than concrete — an important consideration for hand tool users.`},{id:"mh-small-shop-strategies",topic:"Small shop strategies for limited space",keywords:["small","shop","space","limited","mobile","base","fold","wall","organize","maximize"],answer:"In a small shop (1-car garage or less), maximize vertical storage (wall-mounted tool racks, overhead lumber storage). Put major tools on mobile bases — even a 100-lb table saw can be repositioned when the machine isn't being used. Fold-down workbenches and outfeed tables reclaim floor space when idle. A combination machine (jointer-planer-table saw combination) reduces footprint significantly. Sequence your work to minimize machine moves — plan what machines you'll use each session and stage them before starting work. Many exceptional furniture makers work in 200 sq ft or less."},{id:"mh-lumber-storage",topic:"Lumber storage solutions in the shop",keywords:["lumber","storage","rack","sticker","cantilever","wall","vertical","horizontal"],answer:"Horizontal wall-mounted lumber racks (cantilever arms on a vertical wall post) keep lumber accessible and off the floor. Store the longest, heaviest stock on the lowest arms. Sticker (spacer) the stored stock for airflow even in a finished shop. Sheet goods store best vertically in a slot-style rack — horizontal storage of sheets causes them to sag and warp. A sheet caddy (with wheels) lets you transport and store sheets vertically without carrying them flat. Limit shop lumber storage to what you'll use in 6 months — long-term storage belongs in a better-ventilated and humidity-controlled space."}],h=[{id:"mi-stopped-dado",topic:"Stopped (blind) dado for clean front edge",keywords:["stopped","blind","dado","shelf","front","edge","visible","clean","stop"],answer:"A stopped dado ends before the front edge of the carcase side — the front edge remains solid and hides the groove from view. Mark the stop point, chisel a small square pocket at the stop, then rout from the back toward the stop. The shelf front gets a matching notch cut so it fits around the stopped end. This is the standard cabinet-grade method for fixed shelves where the dado would otherwise be visible from the front."},{id:"mi-housing-vs-dado",topic:"Housing joint (British) vs dado joint (American)",keywords:["housing","dado","British","American","terminology","shelf","groove","housed"],answer:"These are the same joint called by different names depending on geography. American woodworkers call it a dado; British woodworkers call it a housing. A through housing runs the full width of the panel; a stopped housing (stopped dado) ends before one edge. The joint captures the shelf end in a groove cut across the panel face, providing vertical support for the shelf. Both terms mean exactly the same construction."},{id:"mi-tee-bridle",topic:"T-bridle joint for rails meeting at mid-span",keywords:["T","bridle","tee","rail","mid","span","table","frame","slot"],answer:"When a rail meets another rail at its middle rather than at an end, a T-bridle joint (or T-halving) cuts a slot the full depth of the first rail and a matching fork on the crossing member. The two pieces interlock without fasteners and are glued flush on the faces. Used in table bases, stretcher systems, and grid frames where structural integrity at crossing members is required. Stronger than a simple lap at a T-intersection because the slot captures both cheeks of the fork."},{id:"mi-fox-wedge-technique",topic:"Fox wedging (blind wedged) mortise and tenon",keywords:["fox","wedge","blind","mortise","tenon","permanent","kerf","splay","lock"],answer:"Fox-wedging places small wedges in saw kerfs cut in the tenon end — as the tenon is driven home, the wedges hit the bottom of the mortise and are forced into the kerfs, splaying the tenon against the mortise walls. The joint is permanent; there's no way to disassemble without destroying it. The mortise must be slightly undercut (flared wider at the bottom) to allow the splayed tenon to seat fully. Cut the kerfs just over half the tenon length; wedge thickness should equal the clearance you want the tenon to splay."},{id:"mi-stub-tenon",topic:"Stub (stump) tenon for frame and panel doors",keywords:["stub","stump","tenon","short","door","panel","groove","haunch","frame"],answer:`A stub tenon is very short — typically just 3/8"–1/2" deep, the same depth as the panel groove. It's used in frame-and-panel door rails where the groove depth limits tenon length. Always add a haunch to fill the groove above or below the stub tenon. The haunched stub tenon is the standard joint for kitchen cabinet doors built with a router and cope-and-stick bits: the cope cut creates the stub tenon shape automatically.`},{id:"mi-cross-halving",topic:"Cross-halving (cross-lap) joint for grids",keywords:["cross","halving","lap","grid","shelf","divider","intersect","halfway"],answer:"A cross-halving joint interlocks two boards at their crossing point — each board has a slot half its depth cut from the opposite side, and they slide together. Used for shelf dividers, grid patterns, wine racks, and any structure where members cross each other at 90°. The slot width should equal the board thickness for a snug fit. For grids with many intersections, cut all horizontal slots on one setup, then all vertical slots on another — identical setup produces perfectly consistent joints."},{id:"mi-pocket-hole-face-frame",topic:"Pocket holes for face frame assembly",keywords:["pocket","hole","face","frame","stile","rail","assemble","clamp","align"],answer:"Face frames assembled with pocket holes are faster than dowels or biscuits and just as strong for non-structural face frame work. Drill the pocket holes on the rails (not the stiles) before assembly. Apply glue and use a face clamp to hold pieces flush while driving the screw — without the clamp, the angled screw force shifts the pieces out of plane. Wipe glue squeeze-out from the front face immediately. After assembly, a face frame router bit or flush-trim bit can level any slight offset between stile and rail faces."},{id:"mi-domino-frame",topic:"Using the Domino for timber frame joinery",keywords:["domino","festool","timber","frame","loose","tenon","floating","fast","strong"],answer:"The Festool Domino XL (DF 700) cuts larger mortises for bigger tenons — suitable for light timber frame connections and heavy furniture. It's significantly faster than hand-cutting mortises and more precise than most router setups for production work. For a table's apron-to-leg connection, the Domino XL cuts a matched mortise in both pieces in under a minute per joint. The XL tenons come in 8mm, 10mm, and 12mm widths and 22mm to 50mm lengths — choose length based on the available tenon depth in the leg."},{id:"mi-wedged-barefaced-tenon",topic:"Barefaced (single-shouldered) tenon",keywords:["barefaced","single","shoulder","tenon","frame","thin","rail","offset","groove"],answer:"A barefaced tenon has a shoulder on only one face — the other face is flush with the edge of the stock. Used when a thin rail connects to a groove on a stile (so the tenon thickness equals the groove width) or when the tenon must sit flush with the face of the mortised member. More complex to lay out accurately than a standard twin-shouldered tenon — the layout gauge must be set very precisely because any error isn't averaged over two shoulders."},{id:"mi-knapp-machine-joint",topic:"Knapp joint — Victorian drawer joinery",keywords:["knapp","machine","pin","drawer","nineteenth","century","Victorian","curved","fan"],answer:"The Knapp joint (patented 1867) was a machine-made dovetail substitute using curved pins and matching sockets — it looks like a fan or scallop pattern. It was used on 19th-century American furniture during the machine age as an alternative to hand-cut dovetails. It's not as strong as dovetails but was much faster to machine-produce. Knapp joints are now a useful dating indicator for antique furniture — pieces with them were likely made between 1870 and 1910. No modern equivalent machine is commercially produced."},{id:"mi-mitered-corner-biscuit",topic:"Biscuits in mitered box corners",keywords:["biscuit","miter","box","corner","reinforce","slot","align","orientation"],answer:'Biscuits in mitered corners are cut perpendicular to the miter face — the slot is at 90° to the beveled surface. Use a biscuit joiner with a fence set to 45° or use a dedicated miter clamp as a reference. Size 0 or 10 biscuits fit most 3/4"-thick mitered stock. The biscuit adds both alignment and considerable strength to what is otherwise a very weak end-grain glue joint. Splined miters are even stronger, but biscuits are faster to execute and adequate for most box and frame applications.'},{id:"mi-finger-joint-strength",topic:"Why finger joints are extremely strong in glue",keywords:["finger","joint","strength","surface","area","glue","mechanical","interlock","box"],answer:"Finger (box) joints have vastly more long-grain glue surface area than any other corner joint — the interlocking fingers multiply the glue area by 4–8 times compared to a simple butt joint. The glue area exceeds even dovetails of the same finger count. In tension tests, properly glued finger joints often fail in the wood rather than the glue line. They're weaker than dovetails in resisting direct pull-out (no mechanical lock), but in everyday furniture loads (racking, twisting, vibration) they're more than adequate."},{id:"mi-table-saw-tenon-full",topic:"Complete tenon cutting sequence on the table saw",keywords:["tenon","table","saw","complete","sequence","cheek","shoulder","dado","fence"],answer:"Full tenon on the table saw: (1) Set blade height to tenon cheek cut depth. (2) With a crosscut sled, cut all four shoulder lines on both ends of each piece. (3) Stand the workpiece vertically against a tenon jig; cut both cheek faces to the shoulder line. (4) Lay flat and make the narrow-direction shoulder cuts if the tenon is not square. (5) Test fit in the mortise. This sequence — shoulder cuts first, cheek cuts second — means any saw wander on the cheek cut is absorbed in the waste, not the tenon shoulder."},{id:"mi-joinery-glue-surfaces",topic:"Understanding long grain vs short grain vs end grain glue joints",keywords:["long","grain","short","end","glue","strength","orientation","compare"],answer:"Long-grain to long-grain is the strongest glue joint — properly done, it's stronger than the wood itself. Long-grain to face grain is slightly weaker but still very strong. Long-grain to end grain is very weak — end grain absorbs glue like a sponge but provides little mechanical bond. Size end grain with a dilute coat of glue, let dry, then apply regular glue for the joint. Short-grain joints (wood fibers at a steep angle to the surface) are intermediate in strength. Design joints so primary load paths run through long-grain connections."},{id:"mi-shellac-pound-cut-table",topic:"Shellac pound cut guide for different applications",keywords:["shellac","pound","cut","application","spray","brush","seal","french","polish"],answer:"Shellac cut (pounds per gallon of denatured alcohol) for different uses: 1/2-lb cut — French polishing, first thin seal coat. 1-lb cut — wiping on between coats, sealing over stain before topcoat. 2-lb cut — brushing on for a full film finish, sealing knots. 3-lb cut — very thick for filling wood pores, repairs. Premixed SealCoat (Zinsser) is a 2-lb cut dewaxed shellac. Spraying requires thinning to 1-lb cut or less for HVLP guns — the full 2-lb cut will clog a fine gun nozzle."},{id:"mi-waterbased-poly-bubbles",topic:"Eliminating bubbles in water-based polyurethane",keywords:["bubbles","water","based","poly","foam","brush","flow","floetrol","thin"],answer:"Water-based poly foams easily from overbrushing, a contaminated surface, or incorrect application temperature. Fix: don't shake the can (stir gently); apply thin coats with a good-quality synthetic brush using long, light strokes (no scrubbing back and forth); tip off bubbles with the brush held nearly flat immediately after application. Adding Floetrol extender (10–15%) slows dry time and lets bubbles release before the film skins over. Working in temperatures above 75°F also causes faster skinning — work in cooler conditions or thin slightly."},{id:"mi-poly-brush-marks",topic:"Eliminating brush marks in oil-based polyurethane",keywords:["brush","marks","poly","level","tip","off","mineral","spirits","thin","quality"],answer:'Oil-based poly brush marks can be minimized with: a high-quality natural-bristle brush held at a low angle; thinning the first coat 10% with mineral spirits; flowing the finish on without going back over partially dried areas; and "tipping off" (final light pass the length of the panel with barely any pressure). Work in a dust-free environment at 65–75°F. If brush marks are already in the cured coat, sand level with 400-grit paper on a flat block before the next coat. The final coat can be rubbed out with steel wool and wax for a perfectly smooth finish.'},{id:"mi-varnish-oil-stain-wait",topic:"How long to wait after oil-based stain before topcoat",keywords:["stain","wait","dry","oil","topcoat","varnish","poly","hours","days","cure"],answer:"Oil-based stain must be fully dry before topcoating or the topcoat traps wet stain beneath it — the finish stays soft and the stain bleeds. Minimum wait: 24 hours in warm (70°F), dry (below 50% RH) conditions. In cool or humid conditions, wait 48–72 hours. Check dryness: press a clean cloth firmly on the stained surface and lift — no color transfer means it's dry. Oil-based stains with Japan driers added dry faster. Gel stains need the same wait time. Water-based stains dry in 1–2 hours."},{id:"mi-finish-vertical-surfaces",topic:"Applying finish to vertical surfaces without runs",keywords:["vertical","surface","finish","run","drip","brush","apply","thin","coat"],answer:"Vertical surfaces run and drip easily — apply thin coats and keep the brush moving. On doors and cabinet sides: start with the recessed panels, then the rails, then the stiles. Apply finish in short horizontal strokes to fill the area, then tip off vertically with a nearly-dry brush. Never leave a heavy wet edge on a vertical surface. Lay the workpiece horizontal for the first coat if possible — it dries without runs. If a run does occur in wet finish, brush it out immediately; wait until fully dry and sand level if missed."},{id:"mi-lacquer-sand-between-coats",topic:"Why you don't sand between lacquer coats",keywords:["lacquer","sand","between","coats","bond","chemical","recoat","window"],answer:"Lacquer recoats bond chemically — each new coat dissolves slightly into the previous one, creating a unified film. This means sanding between coats is unnecessary and counterproductive if you recoat within the recoat window (typically 30 minutes to 2 hours for fast lacquer). If you wait too long (the lacquer has fully cured), you must sand to scuff the surface for mechanical adhesion — the chemical bonding window has closed. The final coat can be sanded and rubbed out for a glass finish after it's fully cured (24–48 hours)."},{id:"mi-oil-finish-reapply",topic:"Reapplying oil finish to worn furniture",keywords:["oil","finish","reapply","maintain","worn","dry","clean","danish","penetrating"],answer:`Oil-finished furniture can be refreshed without stripping. Clean the surface thoroughly with naphtha to remove wax, grime, and contamination. Lightly scuff with 0000 steel wool. Apply a fresh coat of the same oil (danish oil, linseed, tung) and wipe off excess. Allow to fully cure. This "feeding" of the wood restores the look and adds another layer of protection. Oil finishes are the easiest to maintain because there's no film to chip or peel — just periodic renewal of the penetrating layer.`},{id:"mi-conversion-varnish-safety",topic:"Safety when spraying conversion varnish",keywords:["conversion","varnish","catalyzed","isocyanate","acid","PPE","respirator","hazmat"],answer:"Some conversion varnishes use isocyanate (urethane) catalysts — extremely hazardous to the respiratory system even in minute concentrations. With isocyanate catalysts, a supplied-air respirator or full face-piece respirator with organic vapor + P100 cartridges is mandatory. Acid-catalyst conversion varnishes are less acutely hazardous but still require OV + P100 respirators and excellent ventilation. Never spray conversion varnish in an unventilated space. The extreme durability of the finish is proportional to its extreme hazard during application."},{id:"mi-finishing-end-grain",topic:"Finishing end grain to match face grain color",keywords:["end","grain","color","seal","stain","dark","pre","coat","even","equalize"],answer:"End grain absorbs stain several times faster than face grain, turning dramatically darker. To equalize: apply a thinned seal coat (10% oil-based poly in mineral spirits, or 1-lb shellac) to the end grain only; let dry; then apply the same stain to the whole surface. The seal coat limits end grain absorption. Another approach: apply the stain overall, then apply a lighter diluted stain to the face grain only for build-up, bringing the face grain closer to the darker end grain color — working from darker to lighter is generally easier."},{id:"mi-gel-stain-technique",topic:"Gel stain application technique",keywords:["gel","stain","apply","brush","wipe","thick","time","grain","build","coat"],answer:"Gel stain is applied with a brush, sponge, or cloth and wiped off with a clean cloth after a short dwell time (2–5 minutes typically). Work in manageable sections — gel stain on a large surface can dry unevenly if you apply it all before wiping. Apply with the grain; wipe across and then with the grain for the final wipe to remove streaks. For more color intensity: apply a second coat over the first (dried overnight) rather than a longer dwell time, which can leave a patchy result. Finish immediately over gel stain once dry."},{id:"mi-ammonia-fuming-detail",topic:"Ammonia fuming oak — setup and results",keywords:["ammonia","fume","oak","tent","plastic","container","honey","brown","tannin"],answer:"Ammonia fuming uses ammonium hydroxide vapors (26–28% concentration from industrial sources — not household ammonia) to react with tannins in oak, turning it honey-brown to deep chocolate without any stain. Set the piece in a sealed tent (plastic sheeting and tape) with a small bowl of ammonium hydroxide inside. Leave for 4–24 hours depending on depth of color desired. Wear a respirator and gloves — the fumes are extremely irritating. The color penetrates the entire board, not just the surface, and doesn't fade like surface stains."},{id:"mi-sandpaper-grit-science",topic:"How sandpaper grits and abrasive types differ",keywords:["sandpaper","grit","aluminum","oxide","silicon","carbide","ceramic","garnet","CAMI","FEPA"],answer:"Aluminum oxide (the orange or brown standard paper) is the most common woodworking abrasive — durable and cuts well on most species. Silicon carbide (wet/dry paper, darker gray) is used for sanding between finish coats and on very hard materials. Ceramic aluminum oxide (Siafast, 3M Cubitron) lasts 4–10x longer than standard paper and cuts faster — worth the premium for production work. CAMI grit numbers (US) and FEPA P-grades (European) overlap but are not identical above 220 grit — P320 is roughly 280 CAMI. Garnet paper is natural and gentle; use it for hand-sanding delicate surfaces."},{id:"mi-outdoor-finish-maintain",topic:"Exterior finish maintenance schedule",keywords:["exterior","outdoor","finish","maintain","recoat","season","schedule","oil","varnish"],answer:"Penetrating oil finishes (teak oil, linseed-based outdoor oil): reapply annually in spring after cleaning with a brush and mild detergent. Spar varnish (film finish): inspect annually for peeling, checking, or crazing — sand and recoat affected areas before failure reaches bare wood. Once varnish peels back to bare wood, full strip-and-refinish is required. The key rule for exterior finishes: maintain before failure, not after. A 20-minute annual wipe-on application is far less work than a complete strip and refinish."},{id:"mi-wipe-on-poly",topic:"Wipe-on polyurethane — make your own",keywords:["wipe","on","poly","make","thin","mineral","spirits","50","percent","easy"],answer:"Commercial wipe-on poly is simply oil-based polyurethane thinned 50% with mineral spirits. Make your own: mix one part oil-based poly with one part mineral spirits by volume. Apply with a lint-free cloth in thin, even coats. Each coat dries faster (4 hours vs 8) and levels without brush marks. Build 4–6 coats for a thin but durable film. Final sheen: add a coat of paste wax for satin; use 0000 steel wool plus wax for matte. Wipe-on poly is ideal for curved turnings, carvings, and any surface where brush application would leave drips."},{id:"mi-shaker-cabinet-design",topic:"Shaker cabinet design — exact proportions",keywords:["shaker","cabinet","proportion","door","stile","rail","size","panel","design"],answer:'Shaker cabinet door proportions: stile and rail width typically 2"–2.5"; panel setback from frame face: 1/4"–3/8". Door height to width ratio: taller-than-wide is more Shaker-authentic (2:1 to 3:2 ratio). The floating panel is typically raised (shadow line visible around panel perimeter) or flat depending on Shaker variant. Shaker pulls are simple wood knobs or small oval brass knobs — nothing decorative. The restraint of the Shaker style means proportional errors are immediately visible; study original pieces before designing.'},{id:"mi-bookcase-back",topic:"Bookcase back options — open back vs closed",keywords:["bookcase","back","open","closed","plywood","rabbet","fixed","adjustable","access"],answer:'Open-back bookcases (no back panel) are lighter and allow access from both sides but are less rigid — the back panel of a closed bookcase dramatically stiffens the case and prevents racking. For heavy book loads or freestanding bookcases, a 1/4" plywood back in a dadoed rabbet is the minimum. Attach the back with screws (not glue) so it can be removed if the bookcase ever needs to go through a doorway. For wall-mounted bookcases, the wall serves as the back — anchor cleats to the studs for load-bearing support.'},{id:"mi-bed-joinery",topic:"Bed rail-to-post connection options",keywords:["bed","rail","post","connect","bolt","hook","hanger","joint","knock","down"],answer:"Options for bed rail-to-post connections in order of strength: (1) Bed bolts (barrel nuts) — very strong, fully removable; (2) Metal bed-rail hook hangers (mortised into rail, bolt to post) — fast and strong; (3) Mortise and tenon with bed bolt reinforcement — traditional and strongest; (4) Pocket screws alone — not recommended, will loosen over time. Whatever method, the connection must resist a 200–400 lb prying force from someone rolling in bed. Test by grabbing the headboard and pushing hard — any wobble means the joint needs reinforcement."},{id:"mi-table-leg-attach",topic:"Attaching table legs — options and strength",keywords:["table","leg","attach","hanger","bolt","dowel","mortise","socket","bolt"],answer:"Common leg attachment methods: (1) Threaded leg-leveling bolt with T-nut in the apron corner — fast, adjustable, allows leg removal; (2) Mortise-and-tenon leg-to-apron — traditional and strongest; (3) Corner block with hanger bolt — fast and removable; (4) Direct screw from below — weakest, not recommended for dining tables. For a coffee table or bed frame that needs to disassemble for moving, hanger bolts and threaded inserts in the top of the leg allow easy assembly and disassembly while maintaining strong connection."},{id:"mi-wall-cabinet-hang",topic:"Hanging wall cabinets level and securely",keywords:["wall","cabinet","hang","level","cleat","stud","french","screw","secure"],answer:"Wall cabinets must anchor into studs — toggle bolts in drywall alone will eventually fail under kitchen cabinet loads. Find studs, mark their centers, and verify the cabinet can be screwed into at least two studs. French cleats (a beveled cleat on the wall, matching cleat on the back of the cabinet) allow easy leveling and adjustment and distribute the load along the full cleat length. For a run of cabinets, hang the highest first, then work down using a laser level for the reference line."},{id:"mi-garage-cabinet",topic:"Garage cabinet construction for utility",keywords:["garage","cabinet","plywood","robust","heavy","duty","simple","construction"],answer:'Garage cabinets prioritize durability and load capacity over appearance. Use 3/4" Baltic birch or sanded plywood (not particleboard — it fails in humidity). Dado-joined shelves at fixed locations are stronger than pin-supported shelves for heavy tool storage. Screw carcase joints with 2" construction screws in addition to glue. Use heavy-duty European hinges rated for heavier doors. Skip veneer and paint — a single coat of oil-based primer seals the wood. Anchor base cabinets to the wall and each other for stability under heavy loads.'},{id:"mi-laundry-room-cabinet",topic:"Laundry room cabinetry — moisture considerations",keywords:["laundry","cabinet","moisture","humidity","seal","finish","solid","melamine"],answer:"Laundry rooms have higher humidity than most rooms. Use melamine-faced particleboard (easy to clean, moisture-resistant surface) or paint-grade plywood finished with oil-based paint. Avoid MDF in laundry rooms — it swells when it gets wet. Solid wood doors and drawer fronts should be finished on all six sides equally. Keep the floor-level base cabinet off the floor on a toe kick — water on the floor wicks into unfinished particle board quickly. Opt for simple construction with no unfinished edges exposed."},{id:"mi-tv-cabinet",topic:"TV stand and media console construction",keywords:["tv","stand","media","console","component","ventilation","cable","height","screen"],answer:`TV stand height should put the center of the screen at eye level when seated — typically 42"–48" from floor. Open back or vented sides allow heat to escape from AV components. Cable management: plan conduit holes through shelves and a cable exit at the back before building. Cabinet depth: 18"–24" is standard for modern AV components; measure your deepest component. Use 3/4" plywood for a sturdy box; 1/2" for shelves with limited load. The cabinet must support the TV's weight on a wide, stable footprint.`},{id:"mi-vanity-tower",topic:"Bathroom linen tower construction",keywords:["linen","tower","bathroom","tall","narrow","shelf","door","proportion","anchor"],answer:'A linen tower is a tall, narrow cabinet (typically 16"–20" wide, 72"–84" tall) for bathroom linen and toiletry storage. Because of the tall-narrow proportions, it must be wall-anchored — a top-heavy freestanding cabinet is a tipping hazard especially with children. Anchor through the back panel into a stud or use a wall cleat. Adjustable shelves on the 32mm system allow flexible organization. Use moisture-resistant construction (plywood, melamine, or solid wood with complete finish) for the humid bathroom environment.'},{id:"mi-floating-mantel",topic:"Floating fireplace mantel construction",keywords:["mantel","fireplace","float","hang","heat","clearance","build","code","clearance"],answer:'A floating (cantilevered) mantel shelf mounts on hidden structural supports — typically 3/4" steel tubes that pass through the mantel into wall studs. Building code requires minimum clearance from combustible materials to the firebox opening — typically 12" above and 6" to the side of the opening; check local codes. Use solid wood or MDF over a structural frame. Mount the hidden tubes into studs at the correct spacing (matching pre-drilled holes in the mantel back). The mantel slips over the tubes and sits tight to the wall without visible fasteners.'},{id:"mi-reception-desk",topic:"Reception desk construction — curved and complex",keywords:["reception","desk","curved","laminate","bending","substrate","commercial","face"],answer:"Reception desks with curved fronts typically use bending plywood as the substrate, with a laminate (high-pressure laminate or wood veneer) face. Build the box frame first with the curved profile established by carefully bent MDF ribs. Attach the bending ply in thin layers, gluing and stapling each layer to the frame. Veneer or laminate the exterior. The counter surface is typically solid surface material or a thick hardwood slab. Plan the electrical (receptionist computer, lighting) and wire management through the desk structure before closing it up."},{id:"mi-sawhorse-design",topic:"Sawhorse design — foldable vs fixed",keywords:["sawhorse","design","fold","fixed","height","brace","weight","pair","support"],answer:'A good sawhorse pair supports 1000+ lbs combined — the legs must be well braced to resist lateral racking. Fixed sawhorses (non-folding) are stronger; foldable versions trade some strength for storage convenience. Standard height: 28"–32" depending on your working height preference. Use 2×4 or 2×6 construction lumber for legs and top rail. A 15°–20° leg splay on all four legs gives good stability. For sheet goods, a third sawhorse in the middle prevents heavy plywood from sagging and binding the saw.'},{id:"mi-outfeed-roller-stand",topic:"Roller stand for supporting long stock",keywords:["roller","stand","support","outfeed","long","board","planer","table","saw","infeed"],answer:'A roller stand supports long boards on the infeed and outfeed sides of stationary tools — preventing them from tipping or binding. The top roller must be exactly the same height as the machine table — even 1/8" difference causes the board to catch or tip. Adjustable-height roller stands (most commercial versions) allow dialing in the exact height. Heavy-duty stands have a single wide roller; lighter stands may use a ball roller for omnidirectional support. For work with a consistent material height (tabletop after planing), fixed-height roller stands simplify the setup.'},{id:"mi-workmate-bench",topic:"Black & Decker Workmate as a portable bench",keywords:["workmate","portable","bench","clamp","vise","folding","jobsite","lightweight"],answer:"The Workmate (Black & Decker) is a folding portable workbench with a built-in vise formed by two separate top surfaces that clamp together. It's widely used on job sites and in cramped spaces without a real workbench. The clamping capacity isn't as strong as a real vise but is adequate for most light work. It folds flat for storage. For hobbyists without a dedicated workshop, the Workmate is a legitimate starting point; it handles hand tool work, power tool support, and clamping for assembly surprisingly well."},{id:"mi-poplar-green-heart",topic:"Poplar heartwood green color explanation",keywords:["poplar","green","heart","color","paint","wood","mineral","streak"],answer:'Yellow poplar (Liriodendron tulipifera) has heartwood that can range from olive-green to dark green or purple-gray — a result of mineral deposits during growth. This green color looks unusual on unfinished stock but completely disappears under paint. The green color can bleed through water-based primers in some cases — use a shellac primer first if concerned. For natural (clear) finishes, the green heartwood can actually be attractive mixed with the cream sapwood. Most cabinet grades specify "no mineral streaks" for paint-grade work.'},{id:"mi-hickory-uses",topic:"Hickory beyond tool handles — furniture and floors",keywords:["hickory","hard","heavy","floor","furniture","char","character","rustic"],answer:"Hickory is the hardest and heaviest North American hardwood (Janka ~1820) and is extremely shock-resistant — making it the traditional material for axe handles, hammers, and sporting equipment. As a flooring material, it's exceptionally durable. As furniture material, it's challenging — very hard on tools, difficult to machine smoothly, and heavy to handle. Character hickory (with prominent color variation between cream sapwood and dark reddish-brown heartwood) has a bold, rustic look popular in farmhouse-style furniture."},{id:"mi-teak-gluing-prep",topic:"Preparing teak for gluing — degreasing required",keywords:["teak","glue","oil","prep","acetone","wipe","adhesion","failure","surface"],answer:"Teak's high natural oil content prevents most adhesives from bonding — oil-soaked fibers repel water-based glues and interfere with epoxy cross-linking. Always wipe teak surfaces with acetone immediately before gluing — this removes the surface oil layer and lets it evaporate completely (wait 5 minutes after wiping before applying glue). The degreasing must be done right before gluing; if you wait hours, the oil wicks back to the surface. The same process applies to other oily tropical hardwoods like cocobolo, rosewood, and ipe."},{id:"mi-white-oak-outdoor",topic:"White oak for outdoor use — why it works",keywords:["white","oak","outdoor","closed","pore","barrel","rot","resistant","tight"],answer:"White oak's pores are plugged with tyloses — microscopic growths that fill the vessel cells. This makes white oak naturally water-resistant and is why it's used for whiskey barrels and traditional boat planking. For outdoor furniture, white oak outperforms red oak dramatically — red oak's open pores allow water to penetrate deeply and promote rot. Quartersawn white oak is most stable outdoors. Finish with penetrating oil or exterior varnish to protect the surface while maintaining the natural look."},{id:"mi-cherry-mineral-spot",topic:"Cherry gum pockets and dark mineral spots",keywords:["cherry","gum","pocket","dark","spot","mineral","grain","select","avoid"],answer:"Cherry develops dark spots called gum pockets or mineral deposits — natural discolorations that appear as black or dark brown irregular patches in the board. Tight small spots (gum pockets) are usually surrounded by good wood; large mineral zones may signal stressed growth and can be unpredictable in how they take finish. Select around these areas for visible furniture parts, or embrace them as character marks in rustic designs. Gum pockets don't affect structural integrity — only appearance."},{id:"mi-ash-color-age",topic:"White ash color and aging characteristics",keywords:["ash","white","cream","age","darken","figure","ring","open","porous"],answer:"White ash is nearly pure white to cream color when freshly cut, with bold dark growth rings creating a strong figure. It doesn't darken dramatically with age like cherry — it stays light with slight yellowing. Ash absorbs stain readily and evenly due to its open, ring-porous structure; dark stains look dramatic on ash. It's one of the best species for fumed (ammonia-treated) finishes, which work well on tannin-rich ash. Ash is also excellent with wire brushing to reveal the dramatic ring-porous grain texture."},{id:"mi-maple-blotch-control",topic:"Controlling blotching on hard maple",keywords:["maple","blotch","stain","control","conditioner","wash","seal","coat"],answer:"Hard maple blotches badly with oil-based stains because its tight pores absorb unevenly. Strategies: use a pre-stain conditioner (reduces but doesn't eliminate blotching); use gel stain instead of liquid (sits on surface, can't penetrate unevenly); use a very dilute NGR dye instead of oil stain (penetrates more evenly); or skip staining and use a tinted oil finish. Maple's natural white-cream color often looks best with a clear finish and no stain — the wood's own figure is the appeal."},{id:"mi-router-table-startup",topic:"Router table startup sequence and checks",keywords:["router","table","startup","check","bit","collet","fence","featherboard","before"],answer:"Before starting a router table session: check that the bit is fully seated and the collet nut is tight (two-wrench tighten); set the bit height with the router OFF; set and lock the fence; position the featherboard; check the bit rotation direction and plan your feed direction (always against the rotation — right to left for a standard right-hand router); start the router with nothing near the bit; wait 5 seconds for it to come to full speed before feeding stock. This 30-second ritual prevents most router table accidents."},{id:"mi-hand-tool-workflow",topic:"Hand tool workflow for a small furniture project",keywords:["hand","tool","workflow","sequence","order","flatten","joint","mark","cut","fit"],answer:"A hand-tool furniture workflow: (1) rough-crosscut lumber to rough length (hand saw or miter saw); (2) flatten one face with a jack plane, then smoother; (3) joint one edge with a jointer plane; (4) mark and gauge all thickness lines; (5) thickness the opposite face to the line; (6) rip to width on the bench; (7) final crosscut to length; (8) layout all joinery with knife and gauge; (9) cut joinery (mortises, tenons, dovetails); (10) dry-fit and fit adjustments; (11) glue-up; (12) surface prep and finish. Each step depends on the precision of the last."},{id:"mi-saw-kerf-allowance",topic:"Allowing for saw kerf when marking cut lists",keywords:["kerf","allowance","mark","measure","cut","list","account","lost","waste"],answer:`Each cut removes about 1/8" of wood (the kerf width). When cutting multiple pieces from a single board, account for this or your last piece will be 1/8" short for each cut made before it. On a cut list with three 12" pieces from a 37" board: 3 × 12" = 36" + 2 kerfs (at 1/8" each) = 36.25" required. The 37" board provides 0.75" of waste margin. Mark each line from the last cut end using a square and ruler — don't measure from the board end after every cut (cumulative error).`},{id:"mi-thickness-check",topic:"Checking consistent thickness across a board",keywords:["thickness","check","consistent","dial","caliper","variance","flat","panel"],answer:'Use a dial caliper or marking gauge to check thickness at multiple points across a board after milling. Variance of 0.005"–0.010" (about 1/64") is acceptable for most furniture work. More than that and the board needs another pass through the planer or hand planing to level the high spots. Check both edges, both ends, and the middle — 5 measurement points are usually sufficient. Consistent thickness is especially critical in stacked glue-ups and in parts where edge-to-edge alignment is important (stile-and-rail doors, drawer sides).'},{id:"mi-twist-removal-order",topic:"Hand planing sequence to remove twist",keywords:["twist","remove","plane","diagonal","winding","stick","order","sequence","flat"],answer:"To remove twist with a hand plane: identify the high corners with winding sticks. Work diagonally from high corner to high corner first — this is the most efficient direction for removing the high corners. Traverse planing (at 90° to the grain) is also effective for removing high spots fast. After each series of diagonal strokes, check with winding sticks again. When the sticks appear parallel, switch to strokes parallel to the grain to clean up the surface. The jack plane is the right tool for twist removal — its cambered iron handles the aggressive diagonal cuts well."},{id:"mi-cabinet-square-check",topic:"Checking cabinet squareness at every stage",keywords:["cabinet","square","check","diagonal","stage","before","after","clamp","cure"],answer:'Check a cabinet carcase for square at three stages: before assembly (confirm parts are square individually); immediately after clamping while glue is wet (correct any diagonal discrepancy now); and 30 minutes after clamping (one final check — the parts may have moved as clamp pressure distributed). After the glue fully cures, installing a square back panel helps maintain squareness permanently. A 1/16" diagonal discrepancy in a 24" wide cabinet is barely visible; 1/8" will be obvious in the door reveals.'}],c=[{id:"mj-craftsman-bungalow",topic:"Craftsman bungalow built-in design elements",keywords:["craftsman","bungalow","built","in","bookcase","bench","window","seat","period"],answer:"Craftsman bungalow built-ins share visual elements: quartersawn white oak or Douglas fir with prominent grain, simple straight lines, through-tenon details with wooden pegs, and wide stiles and rails that look structurally massive. Built-in bookcases flank fireplaces; window seats with storage below line bay windows. Finish is typically a light oak stain or fumed finish with a low-sheen varnish. Exposed wood hardware (wooden knobs, wooden pulls) completes the Craftsman aesthetic."},{id:"mj-colonial-furniture",topic:"American colonial furniture characteristics",keywords:["colonial","american","pine","maple","simple","painted","early","puritan","utility"],answer:"Early American colonial furniture (1620–1780) was built from locally available materials — primarily pine, maple, and cherry — by craftsmen trained in English and Dutch traditions. Designs were functional rather than decorative, with simple proportions, minimal ornamentation, and painted finishes that hid the common-grade wood. Mortise-and-tenon joinery, peg construction, and turned elements are characteristic. Later colonial furniture (Georgian, Queen Anne period) adopted more sophisticated carving and proportions."},{id:"mj-biedermeier-style",topic:"Biedermeier furniture style characteristics",keywords:["biedermeier","german","austrian","veneer","fruit","wood","simple","bourgeois","Empire"],answer:"Biedermeier furniture (1820–1848, German-speaking Europe) was the middle-class response to Empire style — simpler, more domestic, using fruitwoods (cherry, pear, apple) and birch as primary woods with dark ebony inlay accents. Forms are clean and geometric without imperial ornament. Veneer work is prominent, often with bold matched grain patterns on flat surfaces. Comfortable chairs and settees with upholstered backs and seats are central to the style. Biedermeier is currently very popular with collectors."},{id:"mj-wabi-sabi-design",topic:"Wabi-sabi in Japanese woodworking design",keywords:["wabi","sabi","japanese","imperfect","natural","beauty","knot","live","edge","simple"],answer:"Wabi-sabi is a Japanese aesthetic philosophy that finds beauty in imperfection, impermanence, and incompleteness. In woodworking, it manifests as appreciation of live edges, natural knots, the mark of the hand tool, and asymmetrical forms. A perfectly handmade dovetail with a tiny gap tells the story of a human making it — wabi-sabi. Contemporary furniture makers like George Nakashima embraced this philosophy, using natural slab edges and butterfly keys to highlight rather than hide natural wood character."},{id:"mj-nakashima-style",topic:"George Nakashima style furniture",keywords:["nakashima","slab","live","edge","walnut","butterfly","natural","organic","japanese"],answer:"George Nakashima (1905–1990) is the most influential 20th-century American furniture artist — he combined Japanese joinery sensibility with Western craft and deep respect for the wood's natural form. His signature pieces: live-edge walnut slabs on simple Minguren bases, butterfly keys stabilizing cracks, and turned wooden pegs joining breadboard ends. His philosophy: the furniture's form should come from the specific material, not be imposed upon it. Nakashima's work established the studio furniture movement and the modern live-edge slab aesthetic."},{id:"mj-eames-plywood-influence",topic:"Charles and Ray Eames influence on bent plywood",keywords:["eames","plywood","molded","chair","leg","splint","organic","war","production"],answer:"Charles and Ray Eames developed molded plywood technology during WWII for lightweight military splints, then applied it to revolutionary furniture — the DCW (Dining Chair Wood) and LCW (Lounge Chair Wood) of 1945–46. Their innovation: bonding veneer layers in 3D molds (not just bending in one direction) created compound-curved plywood forms impossible with traditional techniques. The Eames Lounge Chair (1956) later used this technology in the iconic walnut-and-leather lounge. Their work permanently changed what furniture design considers possible."},{id:"mj-chair-seat-angle",topic:"Chair seat angle and back angle relationship",keywords:["chair","seat","angle","back","rake","comfortable","tilt","pitch","dining","lounge"],answer:"The seat-to-back angle determines chair comfort type. Dining chairs: seat at 2°–5° down toward the back, back at 5°–10° from vertical — keeps the sitter upright and alert. Lounge chairs: seat at 5°–10° down, back at 20°–30° from vertical — promotes relaxed posture. The angle between seat and back should be 95°–100° for dining (just over 90° to prevent slumping), 105°–115° for lounge. The back angle is measured from the vertical — a 90° back is perfectly upright and quickly becomes uncomfortable for sustained seating."},{id:"mj-drawer-design-proportion",topic:"Drawer face design and proportion for visual balance",keywords:["drawer","face","proportion","reveal","overhang","handle","center","align","visual"],answer:'Drawer faces should align with adjacent doors and each other in a continuous vertical reveal. In overlay construction, all faces typically overlap the carcase edge by the same amount (usually 3/8"–1/2"). Face-to-face reveals (gaps between drawer faces) should be uniform — 1/8" is a common standard for production furniture; hand-fitted inset drawers can achieve 1/16" with careful work. Pulls placed consistently (centered, or at 1/3 from the top for tall drawers) create visual rhythm that reads as intentional.'},{id:"mj-color-wood-selection",topic:"Using wood color as a design element",keywords:["color","wood","palette","contrast","warm","cool","dark","light","species","design"],answer:"Wood color selection is as important as form in furniture design. Contrast creates interest: dark walnut against light maple; black ebony accent on pale cherry. Warm and cool combinations: red-brown cherry with gray-green wenge creates a striking complementary palette. Monochromatic designs (all one species, different figure) create calm sophistication. The finish dramatically affects perceived color — oil finishes deepen and warm colors; water-based finishes maintain the cool natural tone. Consider the room's existing wood tones and adjust the furniture's species palette to complement or contrast intentionally."},{id:"mj-furniture-line-weight",topic:"Visual weight and line in furniture design",keywords:["visual","weight","line","thick","thin","heavy","light","proportion","leg","top"],answer:"Visual weight is the apparent heaviness of a piece based on proportions and details, independent of actual weight. Thick tops on thin legs create tension; thin tops on thick legs look stable. Long horizontal lines read as calm and grounded; tall vertical lines read as elegant or imposing. Curves soften; straight lines strengthen. The viewer's eye is drawn to contrast — a single curved detail in an otherwise rectilinear piece becomes a focal point. Study furniture silhouettes in black silhouette form — if the form works as a pure shape, it will work in wood."},{id:"mj-router-dado-depth",topic:"Setting router dado depth in multiple passes",keywords:["router","dado","depth","pass","multiple","sneak","burn","chip","load"],answer:'Rout dados in multiple passes rather than full depth in one cut — this reduces load on the bit, minimizes tearout, and produces cleaner walls. First pass: half depth. Second pass: full depth. For wide dados (more than 1"), make a first pass at the near edge, a second pass at the far edge, then clean the middle in a final pass. Going full depth in one pass overloads the bit, produces burning and chip-out, and can move the router away from the fence. Use an upcut spiral bit for cleanest results — it pulls chips out of the groove.'},{id:"mj-bandsaw-resaw-fence",topic:"Setting the bandsaw drift fence for resawing",keywords:["bandsaw","drift","fence","resaw","angle","compensate","straight","cut","align"],answer:"Bandsaw blade drift is the tendency of the cut to wander off a parallel line — each blade has its own drift angle. To find it: freehand cut a straight line into a piece of scrap, then stop and mark the fence angle where the cut was going straight. Clamp a point fence at this angle and test-cut. The drift angle compensates for the blade's tendency to wander right or left, so the fence guides the cut straight even though it's not parallel to the blade. A full fence parallel to the table slot will cause curved cuts if drift isn't accounted for."},{id:"mj-lathe-spindle-turning",topic:"Spindle turning between centers — tool sequence",keywords:["spindle","lathe","between","centers","rough","smooth","detail","gouge","skew"],answer:"Spindle turning sequence: mount the blank between centers, start at low speed, check balance, increase speed. (1) Roughing gouge or skew chisel to knock off corners and make a true cylinder; (2) Spindle gouge for coves, beads, and details; (3) Skew chisel for smooth cylinders and V-cuts; (4) Parting tool for tenons and width references. Calipers check diameters. Work from one end to the other; sand at low speed with the grain moving past you. The spindle roughing gouge is only for between-centers work — never on a faceplate setup."},{id:"mj-planer-board-too-thin",topic:"Thickness planer minimum board thickness",keywords:["planer","minimum","thin","board","thickness","feed","roller","support","crush"],answer:`Most thickness planers have a minimum board thickness of 1/4"–3/8" — thinner boards can be caught by the feed rollers, flexed, and shattered. Check your planer's manual for its specific minimum. For thin stock (1/8"–3/16"), run the board taped or clamped to a carrier board (a sled of known thickness) — the sled provides support. Alternatively, use a drum sander for stock thinner than 1/4". Never attempt to plane a board thinner than the manufacturer specifies — bent boards can be ejected violently.`},{id:"mj-planer-grain-direction",topic:"Feeding boards through the planer — grain direction",keywords:["planer","grain","direction","tearout","feed","reversing","downhill","uphill"],answer:'Like the jointer, the thickness planer must receive boards with the grain running "downhill" in the feed direction to avoid tearout. Look at the edge grain of the board; feed the end where fibers slope downward first. For boards with reversing grain, alternate feed ends between passes and take the lightest possible cut (1/64"). A spiral head planer reduces tearout on reversing grain dramatically — the shearing cut from the helical inserts is much less likely to lift fibers than straight knives.'},{id:"mj-jointer-face-flatten",topic:"Jointing a cupped or twisted face flat",keywords:["jointer","cup","twist","flat","face","pass","depth","high","point","flatten"],answer:"On a cupped board, the edges are higher than the center — the board rocks on the jointer table. Place the cupped face down (concave up) and the high edges contact the infeed table. Take multiple light passes; the jointer removes only the high points and gradually brings the face flat. Severely cupped boards need many passes and significant thickness sacrifice. On a twisted board, the high diagonal corners contact the infeed table and are progressively removed. Hand-plane severe twist first before attempting to joint — a rocking board is difficult to control safely."},{id:"mj-table-saw-bevel-cut",topic:"Table saw bevel (tilted blade) cuts",keywords:["bevel","tilt","blade","table","saw","angle","chamfer","splay","degree"],answer:"Set blade bevel angle with the table saw's built-in indicator, then verify with a digital angle gauge or bevel gauge on the blade flat. Rip fence position for bevel cuts: on most saws, place the fence on the left (tall) side of the tilted blade — the workpiece leans against the fence and the cut-off piece falls away from the blade. On some saws (right-tilt), the fence must be on the right. Test-cut in scrap and measure the angle before cutting good material. Common bevel cuts: 45° for box corners, 15° for angled tenon cheeks, 20°–25° for drawer blade bevels."},{id:"mj-drill-press-angled",topic:"Angled holes on the drill press",keywords:["drill","press","angle","tilt","table","wedge","splay","chair","jig"],answer:"For angled holes on the drill press, tilt the table to the desired angle — most tables tilt 0°–45°. For angles beyond the table range, use a wedge shimming the workpiece instead. The critical issue: the bit must be perpendicular to the desired hole orientation, not perpendicular to the tilted surface. Clamp the workpiece securely — tilted workpieces shift more easily than flat work. For chair leg socket angles (compound), a specialized chair drilling jig holds the seat at the correct compound angle and the drill press drills straight down to produce the angled hole."},{id:"mj-hollow-chisel-mortiser",topic:"Hollow chisel mortiser for production mortises",keywords:["hollow","chisel","mortiser","production","square","bit","auger","chip","clear"],answer:`A dedicated mortising machine (bench-top or floor-standing) combines a chisel with an internal auger — the auger drills out chips while the square hollow chisel cuts the walls. This produces a perfectly square-sided mortise rapidly. Key setup: the chisel must be slightly below the auger tip (1/16") so the chisel cuts last. Don't plunge too deep on one pass — 1/8"–3/16" per pass prevents chip jamming. Lubricate the chisel occasionally with wax. The hollow chisel mortiser is faster than either hand-mortising or router mortising for production work with identical mortise sizes.`},{id:"mj-oscillating-spindle-sander",topic:"Oscillating spindle sander technique for inside curves",keywords:["spindle","sander","oscillating","inside","curve","radius","match","smooth","concave"],answer:"Match the spindle drum to the inside radius of the workpiece for best results — a drum too large leaves flat facets; too small leaves ripple marks. Move the workpiece slowly into the drum, making continuous curved passes. The oscillation (up-and-down movement of the spindle) ensures the full height of the workpiece contact area is sanded evenly — without oscillation, a horizontal band would appear. Sand at progressively finer grits by changing the sleeve. The table is adjustable for height — set it so the work contacts the middle of the drum."},{id:"mj-router-dovetail-bit",topic:"Dovetail router bit for sliding dovetails and T-slots",keywords:["dovetail","router","bit","sliding","slot","T","undercut","bit","angle"],answer:"A dovetail router bit has an angled cutter that produces a trapezoidal groove — used for sliding dovetail joints, T-slots in jig bases, and router table T-tracks. For sliding dovetails: rout the groove in the housing piece with the dovetail bit at the final depth; then rout the mating male profile on the sliding piece using the same bit at the fence (or with a dedicated dovetail slot jig). Fit the male tenon gradually — sneak up to the final dimension in multiple passes. A too-tight sliding dovetail is very hard to loosen once glued."},{id:"mj-scroll-saw-inside-cut",topic:"Scroll saw inside cuts (pierced work)",keywords:["scroll","saw","inside","pierce","thread","blade","drill","interior","relief"],answer:"For inside cuts on the scroll saw (cutting a shape with no path to the outside edge): drill a blade entry hole inside the waste area with a drill bit slightly larger than the scroll saw blade width. Detach the blade from the top arm, thread the blade through the hole, reattach to the top arm, tension, and cut. After completing the cut, detach the blade from the top again and remove the workpiece. This technique enables fretwork, letters, and complex interior shapes that would be impossible to enter from the edge."},{id:"mj-clamp-count",topic:"How many clamps do you actually need",keywords:["clamp","count","how","many","need","minimum","buy","start"],answer:'You can never have too many clamps. A practical minimum set: 4–6 parallel jaw clamps (18"–24") for panel glue-ups; 4 bar or pipe clamps (36"–48") for larger assemblies; 4 F-clamps (6"–12") for bench clamping and small work; 2 band clamps for frames. Add as projects grow. The most common shop mistake is starting a glue-up and running out of clamps — find every clamp you have before applying any glue. Common woodworking wisdom: if you own 20 clamps, you need 40.'},{id:"mj-bench-vise-wooden-jaw",topic:"Wooden vise jaw liners for marking and delicate work",keywords:["vise","jaw","wooden","liner","mark","delicate","soft","hold","add"],answer:"The metal jaws of most shop vises will dent soft woods and leave marks on finished work. Glue hardwood jaw liners (maple, beech) to the inner vise jaws — same thickness on both. The wood-on-wood contact distributes clamping force and leaves no marks. Drill dog holes through the liners aligned with bench dog positions for bench-dog clamping. Replace the liners when they accumulate too many gouges and cuts. Quick-Grip clamp-on wooden jaw pads serve the same purpose on clamps — prevent pad marks on finished work."},{id:"mj-bench-dog-use",topic:"Bench dogs and tail vise for panel clamping",keywords:["bench","dog","tail","vise","panel","hold","planing","flat","workbench"],answer:"Bench dogs work with a tail vise to clamp flat panels for hand planing — one dog in the vise, the other in a bench dog hole at the appropriate distance, with the panel between them. The vise is tightened until the dogs bear against the panel end. For wide panels, pop-up surface dogs (Veritas Wonder Dogs, for example) grip the panel face without needing the tail vise. Properly clamped with bench dogs, a panel won't move even under aggressive hand planing — far better than trying to clamp the panel with regular clamps."},{id:"mj-toggle-clamp-jig",topic:"Toggle clamps for repetitive jig work",keywords:["toggle","clamp","jig","hold","down","quick","release","horizontal","vertical","latch"],answer:"Toggle clamps (De-Sta-Co style) apply quick, repeatable, consistent clamping force with a single lever — ideal for production jigs where the same operation repeats many times. Horizontal-handle toggle clamps apply downward force from above; vertical handles apply side force. Bar-style clamps apply force across the workpiece from one side. Size the toggle clamp by its rated holding force (stated in lbs) — oversize is fine, undersized will allow the workpiece to shift. Bolt toggle clamps to jigs through the base with bolts, not wood screws — they must hold under repeated loading cycles."},{id:"mj-router-table-hold-down",topic:"Hold-down wheels and shoes for router table work",keywords:["router","table","hold","down","wheel","shoe","featherboard","vertical","pressure"],answer:"Vertical hold-down wheels or featherboards apply downward pressure to keep the workpiece against the router table surface — preventing it from lifting when the bit's upward force acts on the workpiece. Position them just before the bit. Set them to flex slightly when the workpiece is under them. A workpiece that lifts from the table while passing over the bit can catch and be kicked back or produce a wavy profile. Horizontal featherboards at the fence plus vertical hold-downs together provide the most controlled feed for profile routing."},{id:"mj-pipe-clamp-technique",topic:"Pipe clamp technique for wide glue-ups",keywords:["pipe","clamp","wide","panel","alternate","above","below","bow","caul"],answer:"Pipe clamps on wide panels must alternate above and below the panel — one clamp on top, the next below, the next on top. This alternating pattern counteracts the tendency for pipe clamps to bow the panel (the ends rise as the middle is pressed down from one side only). Add clamping cauls (straight sticks with slight camber) across the panel perpendicular to the clamps to distribute pressure evenly across the joints. A straight caul distributes force; a slightly crowned caul puts extra pressure at the center where it's needed most."},{id:"mj-clamp-alignment",topic:"Aligning parts while clamping glue-ups",keywords:["align","clamp","slip","register","pin","stop","nail","drift","prevent"],answer:"Glued surfaces are slippery — parts shift as clamping pressure is applied. Prevention strategies: tap small finishing nails into one surface and cut off the heads to leave registration pins (pull out after cure); use biscuits or Dominoes for alignment; add a registration strip (a clamped-on batten that keeps the edge flush) at the joint. Start with light clamping pressure to check alignment, adjust if needed, then tighten fully. For long panel glue-ups, a flat reference surface (assembly table with waxed top) prevents parts from shifting planes."},{id:"mj-guard-maintenance",topic:"Maintaining and using machine guards",keywords:["guard","maintain","use","blade","router","table","attach","dust","port"],answer:"Machine guards are safety features, not obstacles. Most modern guards integrate dust collection — a connected guard works better than an unguarded machine with no dust control. Keep guards clean and functional; replace cracked plastic guards immediately. For operations that require removing the blade guard (dado cuts, bevel cuts with old-style splitters), use alternative safety measures: anti-kickback pawls, correct stance, reduced feed speed. Never operate a table saw or jointer without some form of guard or riving knife unless the specific operation makes it impossible and you've minimized risk in other ways."},{id:"mj-sharp-tool-safer",topic:"Why sharp tools are actually safer",keywords:["sharp","tool","safe","force","control","dull","slip","pressure","cut","accident"],answer:"Dull tools require more force — the extra force causes slipping, loss of control, and fatigue that leads to accidents. A sharp chisel pares cleanly with hand pressure only; a dull one requires a mallet and levers unpredictably. A sharp hand saw tracks straight in the kerf; a dull one wanders. Sharp plane irons cut with a quiet hiss; dull ones drag and chatter. The most common shop injuries come from forcing dull tools. Time spent sharpening is time invested in both quality and safety — the shop is significantly safer when all tools are maintained sharp."},{id:"mj-clutter-safety",topic:"Shop organization and floor safety",keywords:["clutter","trip","floor","safety","offcut","extension","cord","clear","organize"],answer:"Shop floor clutter is a direct safety hazard — a trip over an offcut near a spinning saw is catastrophic. Sweep the floor frequently during work sessions; have an offcut bin within arm's reach of the table saw. Route extension cords overhead or along the wall, never across the floor. Keep areas around machine exits clear — don't lean boards against machines in the outfeed zone. After each machine use, clear the area before moving to the next machine. Five minutes of cleaning at session end makes the next session start safely."},{id:"mj-chemical-storage",topic:"Storing finishing chemicals safely",keywords:["chemical","storage","finish","solvent","flammable","cabinet","cool","ventilate","code"],answer:"Flammable finishing chemicals (lacquer, mineral spirits, paint thinner, acetone) must be stored in a flammable materials storage cabinet or a well-ventilated outbuilding — not in the living space or in an unventilated closet. Keep quantities small; don't stockpile more than you'll use in a few months. Store containers tightly sealed and upright. Check local fire codes — many jurisdictions limit the quantity of flammable liquids in residential attached garages. Dispose of partly-used and old solvents at a hazardous waste facility, not in the trash or drain."},{id:"mj-tool-inspection",topic:"Pre-use tool inspection routine",keywords:["inspect","tool","before","use","blade","sharp","guard","cord","check","routine"],answer:"Before using any power tool: check the cord for damage (cuts, frays, exposed wires), verify the blade or bit is sharp and properly installed, confirm all guards are in place and functional, check that adjustments (depth, angle, fence) are locked and set correctly, and remove the setup key (if a drill press) before turning on power. This 30-second inspection catches problems that could cause injury — a blade installed backwards, a loose collet nut, or a frayed power cord are all findable before they become accidents."},{id:"mj-dust-collection-filtration",topic:"Dust collector filter ratings explained",keywords:["filter","micron","dust","collector","1","5","30","MERV","efficiency","fine"],answer:"Dust collector filters are rated by the smallest particle size they capture. A 30-micron felt bag captures most large chips and shavings — visible dust — but allows fine particles (the dangerous ones) to pass through. A 5-micron cartridge filter catches most of the fine dust that reaches the lungs. A 1-micron or HEPA (0.3 micron at 99.97% efficiency) filter is needed to capture the finest particles. For serious health protection, use a 1-micron cartridge filter in your collector AND a ceiling-mounted air filtration unit to catch what escapes."},{id:"mj-first-aid-shop",topic:"Shop first aid essentials",keywords:["first","aid","kit","emergency","bleed","bandage","eye","wash","cut","shop"],answer:`Shop first aid kit essentials: sterile gauze pads (2"×2" and 4"×4"), medical tape, elastic bandage, butterfly closures for deeper cuts, antiseptic wipes, eye wash station (at least a portable bottle), nitrile gloves, tweezers for splinter removal. Mount the kit visibly near the shop exit. Know the emergency contact numbers. For serious bleeding (arterial), apply firm direct pressure and call emergency services — don't attempt to remove embedded objects. For eye injuries from chemical exposure, flush with water for 15–20 minutes continuously and seek medical attention.`},{id:"mj-green-wood-turning",topic:"Turning green (wet) wood on the lathe",keywords:["green","wet","wood","turn","crack","rough","thin","dry","twice","turn"],answer:`Green wood turns much easier than dry — it's softer, cooler on the tools, and the shavings are beautiful long ribbons. The challenge: it will crack as it dries unless the wall is thin enough to move with the drying stress. Rough turn green bowls to 10% of the diameter in wall thickness (a 10" bowl gets 1" walls), let dry for weeks or months in a bag or with end seal, then finish-turn when dry. Alternatively, rough turn, boil for an hour (stabilizes), dry, and finish-turn. "Once-turned" green bowls can dry successfully at 1/8" thickness.`},{id:"mj-rough-lumber-yield",topic:"Expected yield from rough sawn lumber",keywords:["rough","sawn","yield","milling","loss","flatten","twist","width","length"],answer:'Expect to lose 15–25% of rough sawn lumber to milling operations. A 5/4 (1.25" nominal) rough board yields about 0.9"–1" after surfacing. Boards with significant bow, cup, or twist lose more — a heavily bowed board might yield only 60% of its nominal thickness. Rough width is also oversize by 1/2"–1" per side. When planning a cut list, measure your rough boards in their rough state and calculate available milled dimensions before planning parts. Thin rough boards (4/4 with significant warp) may not be usable without gluing up for required thickness.'},{id:"mj-sticker-spacing",topic:"Sticker spacing for air drying and shop storage",keywords:["sticker","spacing","dry","stack","support","sag","airflow","even"],answer:'Sticker (spacer strip) spacing for air drying: every 16"–24" along the length for boards up to 8/4 thickness; every 12"–16" for thicker stock that tends to sag between supports. Use dry, consistent-thickness stickers (3/4"×1" is standard) to ensure the stack is level and even pressure is applied. Position end stickers within 12" of board ends to reduce end checking. Align all stickers vertically (one directly above another in all layers) so the weight is transferred straight down without horizontal bending stress on the wet boards.'},{id:"mj-board-selection-straight",topic:"Selecting boards for straight grain — furniture strength",keywords:["straight","grain","select","wood","run","out","strength","bend","furniture"],answer:"Straight grain (no run-out) is critical for stressed furniture parts like legs, stretchers, and chair spindles. Run-out means the grain lines angle across the surface rather than running parallel to the length. Even 5° of run-out dramatically reduces bending strength — the fibers break across the grain rather than along it. To check: look at the edge of the board; grain lines should run parallel to the edge. For bent laminations, quartersawn stock with perfectly straight edge grain is strongest. Reject boards with significant run-out for structural applications."},{id:"mj-freshly-sawn-smell",topic:"Identifying wood species by smell when freshly cut",keywords:["smell","identify","species","scent","fresh","cut","cedar","cherry","walnut","pine"],answer:"Many wood species have distinctive smells that are diagnostic when freshly cut. Cedar: strong aromatic camphorous smell. Cherry: sweet, almost fruity. Pine: resinous, sharp turpentine. Black walnut: a rich, slightly astringent smell. Sassafras: unmistakable root beer or tea smell. Camphor: intense medicinal camphor. Rosewood/cocobolo: a distinctive sweet-spicy resinous smell. These scents fade within days of cutting or drying. An experienced woodworker can identify 20+ species by smell — it's a useful field identification skill at the lumber yard."},{id:"mj-sequential-boards",topic:"Buying sequential boards for panel continuity",keywords:["sequential","board","match","color","figure","continuous","panel","adjacent","same","log"],answer:"Boards cut sequentially from the same log are similar in color, figure, and grain character. Ask the dealer to pull sequential boards from the same pack. They'll have nearly identical grain direction, similar mineral content, and compatible wood movement. When glued into panels, the grain appears to flow continuously across the joint — the most natural-looking result. Buy all boards for a single project from the same pack or log if possible; mixing boards from different trees produces panels with jarring color or figure discontinuities across joints."},{id:"mj-wavy-planer",topic:"Fixing wavy planer output",keywords:["wavy","planer","washboard","snipe","knives","slow","feed","chatter"],answer:"Wavy or washboard output from a planer (parallel ripples across the surface) is caused by knife marks repeating at a frequency set by the knife count, spindle RPM, and feed rate. Fix: slow the feed rate (more overlapping knife strikes per inch); sharpen or replace the knives (dull knives cause chatter); check that all knives are set to identical height (a high knife cuts more and marks more deeply). On a helical head planer, wavy output usually means a carbide insert is chipped — rotate or replace the offending insert."},{id:"mj-bandsaw-cut-drift",topic:"Bandsaw cut drifts during use — mid-session",keywords:["bandsaw","drift","wander","change","session","blade","tension","heat","guide"],answer:"If the bandsaw cut starts drifting during a session but was fine at the start, the blade is heating and changing tension. Blade heat from extended use can alter the drift angle. Another cause: the blade guides are worn or set incorrectly, allowing lateral blade movement under load. Check: let the blade cool, re-check drift angle with a test piece. If drift angle changed, readjust the fence. If it persists, check guide wear. Carbide guide blocks and ceramic cool blocks maintain their positioning better than old steel guides under heat."},{id:"mj-table-saw-burning",topic:"Table saw burning on the cut — causes and fix",keywords:["table","saw","burn","scorch","mark","blade","speed","feed","dull","resin"],answer:"Burning on table saw cuts has three main causes: (1) Dull blade — replace or sharpen; (2) Feed rate too slow — move the board faster through the cut; (3) Fence is pinching the wood against the blade (fence is toe-in at the back) — adjust fence to be parallel or very slightly toe-out. Resinous woods (pine) burn more easily than hardwoods — speed up the feed rate. Never stop mid-cut or the blade will burn a visible mark at that point. Cleaning blade pitch with oven cleaner or blade cleaning spray also helps; pitch buildup makes burning worse."},{id:"mj-glue-creep",topic:"Glue creep — why joints slip over time",keywords:["creep","glue","slip","PVA","sustained","load","stress","relax","hard"],answer:"Creep is the slow deformation of a glue joint under sustained load — the joint doesn't fail suddenly but gradually slips over months or years. PVA wood glue has measurable creep under sustained stress, especially at elevated temperatures. For joints under sustained tension or shear (stacked shelf joints carrying book load, chair stretchers), use a harder-curing adhesive: urea-formaldehyde (plastic resin), epoxy, or hide glue. Hot hide glue is harder when cured than most PVAs and resists creep better. PVA's creep is usually not a problem in furniture joints, but it matters in woodworking jigs and instrument-making."},{id:"mj-finish-peeling",topic:"Why finish peels and how to prevent it",keywords:["peel","finish","adhesion","prep","contamination","oil","seal","over","coat"],answer:"Finish peels when adhesion between the finish and the substrate (or between finish coats) fails. Common causes: oil, wax, or silicone contamination on the wood surface; applying incompatible topcoat over the wrong sealer; applying a film finish over uncured penetrating oil; not sanding between coats; applying finish in too-cold conditions. Prevention: clean with naphtha before finishing; seal with shellac as a universal bonding agent; sand between coats of varnish/poly; work in temperatures above 55°F. Once finish is peeling, strip completely and start over — partial repairs over peeling finish never hold."},{id:"mj-checking-flatness-long",topic:"Checking flatness on long narrow pieces",keywords:["flat","long","narrow","check","board","winding","sight","line","straight"],answer:"Long, narrow pieces (rails, stiles, drawer sides) can have bow, twist, or spring that's hard to see visually. Use a long straightedge or a known-flat reference board held alongside the piece — any gap at the center or ends reveals bow. Sight down the edge (eye at one end, looking along the length) to see wind (twist) easily. For high-precision work, mark the high points with chalk and plane or sand to the reference. A bowed drawer side won't slide smoothly in its case; straighten it before final fitting."}],p=[{id:"mk-measuring-inside",topic:"Measuring inside dimensions accurately",keywords:["inside","measure","dimension","cabinet","opening","story","stick","tape","accurate"],answer:"Inside dimensions (cabinet openings, drawer box width) are difficult to measure accurately with a tape — the hook slides and the tape flexes. Better methods: a folding rule with an extension reads inside width precisely. A story stick (mark both sides, then measure the stick length) eliminates reading errors. A digital caliper measures inside widths up to its reach. For openings wider than a caliper's reach, use two straightedges touching the inside faces, mark where they overlap, and measure the combined length."},{id:"mk-repeat-cuts-stop",topic:"Stop blocks for identical repeat cuts",keywords:["stop","block","repeat","cut","identical","miter","saw","table","saw","fence"],answer:"A stop block positions the workpiece identically for every cut — all pieces come out exactly the same length. On a miter saw: clamp a block to the fence at the desired distance from the blade. On a table saw crosscut sled: clamp a block to the sled fence. Critical: always push the workpiece firmly against both the stop block AND the fence before cutting. A gap at either contact point means the cut piece will be the wrong size. For production runs, a flip-down stop block (tuck away, flip up to position) saves repositioning after each cut."},{id:"mk-template-routing-basics",topic:"Template routing for identical parts",keywords:["template","route","pattern","flush","trim","bit","bearing","identical","repeat"],answer:`Template routing produces identical parts by guiding a flush-trim or pattern bit's bearing along a master template. Make the template from 1/2" MDF or plywood, sanded smooth. Attach the template to the workpiece with double-sided tape. Rough-cut the workpiece to within 1/8" of the template edge first (reducing router bit load). Run the bearing against the template and the bit trims the workpiece flush. Perfect for curved parts (chair legs, corbels, bracket feet) made in quantities of two or more.`},{id:"mk-wood-filler-types",topic:"Wood filler types — when each is appropriate",keywords:["filler","wood","putty","epoxy","stainable","latex","oil","finishing","nail","hole"],answer:"Nail hole filler (Timbermate, Famowood) fills small holes that receive paint — not stain. These latex-based fillers don't accept stain well. Stainable wood filler (Minwax stainable) accepts oil stain moderately — never perfectly matches the wood. Epoxy filler (two-part, hard when cured) fills larger voids, gap fills around hardware, and resists impact — best for structural or high-wear repairs. Wax stick fillers (Mohawk products) fill small holes in finished work for touch-up. Color-match any filler to the finished surface, not the raw wood."},{id:"mk-drying-boards-kiln",topic:"Building a solar kiln for air drying lumber faster",keywords:["solar","kiln","build","faster","dry","lumber","plastic","greenhouse","fan","months"],answer:"A simple solar kiln (a greenhouse-like structure) accelerates air drying by capturing solar heat and circulating warm, dry air over stickered lumber. A basic version: a south-facing frame covered with black plastic on the back (absorber) and clear plastic on the front (collector), with a fan circulating air through the stacked lumber. Solar kilns dry lumber 4–6 times faster than open air drying with acceptable checking rates. Hardwoods that take 2 years to air dry often kiln-dry in 3–4 months in a well-designed solar kiln."},{id:"mk-wood-species-hardness-compare",topic:"Comparing common wood hardnesses for furniture selection",keywords:["hardness","compare","janka","furniture","use","dent","soft","maple","oak","pine"],answer:"Quick hardness reference by Janka rating: Balsa 100, Western white pine 420, Butternut 490, Douglas fir 660, Black cherry 950, Hard maple 1450, Red oak 1290, White oak 1360, American walnut 1010, Black locust 1700, Hickory 1820. For tabletops and desk surfaces: 1000+ is recommended to resist everyday denting. For cutting boards: 1400+ for durability. For flooring: 1200+ minimum. Softer woods work for painted pieces and secondary members where denting is less visible."},{id:"mk-hand-tool-maintenance",topic:"Regular maintenance schedule for hand tools",keywords:["maintenance","hand","tool","oil","protect","rust","edge","handle","schedule"],answer:"Regular hand tool maintenance: after each use, wipe metal surfaces with an oily rag (camellia oil or 3-in-1) to prevent rust; hang or rack tools rather than piling them in a drawer where edges contact each other; check and touch up edges before each session (a few strokes on a strop or fine stone keeps edges working longer between full sharpenings); occasionally apply raw linseed oil to dry wooden handles; inspect handles for cracks and replace before they fail. A well-maintained set of hand tools lasts generations."},{id:"mk-sandpaper-backing",topic:"Sandpaper backing materials — paper vs cloth vs film",keywords:["sandpaper","backing","paper","cloth","film","wet","dry","flexible","stearate"],answer:"Paper-backed sandpaper is the most common and economical — A (lightest) through E (heaviest) weight for different rigidity. C and D weights for hand sanding; E weight for machine belts. Cloth-backed is more durable and flexible for belt sanders and curved sanding. Film-backed (Mylar) is dimensionally stable, tears cleanly, and is used in very fine grits (400–2000) for finish sanding. Stearated (soap-coated) sandpaper resists loading on finish coats — the soap prevents resin from clogging the abrasive. Always use stearated paper for between-coat finish sanding."},{id:"mk-clamp-bar-pipe",topic:"Bar clamps vs pipe clamps — which to buy first",keywords:["bar","clamp","pipe","buy","first","compare","extension","parallel","which"],answer:`Pipe clamps (heads that thread onto standard 3/4" black iron pipe) are the most economical for getting many long clamps — buy extra heads and cut your own pipes to various lengths. They're heavy and can rack panels (alternate above/below to compensate). Bar clamps have fixed lengths but less weight. For a first purchase: 4 Bessey parallel jaw clamps (they don't rack) for small to medium glue-ups, plus 4 pipe clamp heads with 36" and 48" pipes for larger work. This combination handles most hobby woodworking.`},{id:"mk-hand-plane-choice",topic:"Which hand plane should I buy first",keywords:["first","plane","buy","number","4","5","cheap","stanley","lie","nielsen"],answer:"A No.5 jack plane is the single most versatile hand plane — use it for roughing, flattening, and surface prep. A refurbished vintage Stanley No.5 ($15–40 from flea markets) performs as well as a premium plane once properly tuned. If budget allows new: the Veritas or Lie-Nielsen No.4 is the quality workhorse smoother. Don't buy cheap imported planes — they warp, have soft irons, and are frustrating to use. Start with one quality plane and master it before buying more. The quality of the iron's steel is the most important variable."},{id:"mk-wood-screw-gauge",topic:"Wood screw gauge (number) system explained",keywords:["screw","gauge","number","#6","#8","#10","diameter","size","chart"],answer:'Screw gauge numbers are the most confusing part of fastener selection. The gauge (#) corresponds to the shank diameter: #6 = 0.138", #8 = 0.164", #10 = 0.190". Higher gauge = thicker screw. Most furniture assembly uses #6 and #8 screws. #10 is for heavy structural work and metal hardware. Lengths are straightforward (1-1/4", 1-1/2", 2", 2-1/2", 3"). The most common pocket hole screw is a #8 × 1-1/4" for 3/4" material. For face screws through hardwood, a #8 × 1-1/2" or 2" is standard.'},{id:"mk-glue-pot-setup",topic:"Setting up a hide glue pot for regular use",keywords:["glue","pot","hide","temperature","double","boiler","thermostat","brush","pearl"],answer:"Hide glue pots maintain 140–145°F precisely — too hot degrades the glue; too cool and it gels before the joint is made. A purpose-built electric glue pot (Lee Valley, Lie-Nielsen) maintains temperature automatically. DIY option: a small slow cooker on the lowest setting, checked with a thermometer. Mix granules with cold water (approximately 1 part glue to 2 parts water by weight for a standard working consistency) and let soak for 30 minutes before heating. Use a natural bristle brush; rinse immediately after use with hot water."},{id:"mk-cutting-plywood",topic:"Cutting large plywood sheets accurately",keywords:["plywood","cut","large","sheet","accurate","track","saw","circular","straight","edge"],answer:"Large plywood sheets are unwieldy on a table saw — safer and easier to break them down on the floor or a work table with a circular saw and straight edge guide. Clamp the guide, set depth just past the plywood thickness (reduces kickback risk and leaves a clean exit), and run the saw along the guide. A track saw system gives the most accurate results with a zero-tearout anti-splinter strip. After breaking down to manageable pieces, finish cut to final dimensions on the table saw for precision."},{id:"mk-bookend-joinery",topic:"Bookend and book display construction",keywords:["bookend","display","book","weight","base","steel","heavy","stable","pair"],answer:'Functional bookends need weight or a mechanism to prevent books from pushing them over. Options: embed lead shot or steel weight in a hollow base; use a steel plate base with wood face; attach an L-bracket that slides under the books and uses their weight to anchor the bookend; or simply make them from dense hardwood (walnut, oak) thick enough to have inherent mass. A pair of 4"×5"×2" solid walnut bookends weighs about 3–4 lbs each — enough to hold most book collections. Felt feet on the base protect shelves.'},{id:"mk-turned-legs",topic:"Turning table and chair legs on the lathe",keywords:["turn","leg","lathe","between","centers","taper","cove","bead","repetition","duplicate"],answer:"Table legs turned between centers start with a square blank, roughed to a cylinder, then detailed. Taper from the full diameter at the top to a smaller diameter at the foot — use calipers to check diameter at reference points. Mark reference diameter positions with a parting tool before turning the shape. For matched sets: make a story stick with all diameters marked; use calipers to match each diameter to the story stick. Or duplicate-turn using a simple jig that holds a template and a pointer showing the required diameter at each position."},{id:"mk-raising-figure-finish",topic:"Oil finishes to raise figure in wood",keywords:["oil","raise","figure","chatoyance","depth","pop","walnut","maple","curly"],answer:`Oil finishes — danish oil, penetrating oil, pure tung oil — dramatically "pop" the figure in wood by filling the surface with a medium that has a different refractive index than air. Curly maple transforms from flat-looking to a deeply shimmering 3D chatoyance with even one coat of oil. Walnut deepens from a pale gray-brown to rich chocolate. Always apply a light coat of danish oil or mineral oil to bare wood before committing to a finish — the "wet look" test shows what the finished board will look like. It's the fastest way to evaluate a board's figure potential.`},{id:"mk-lacquer-retarder",topic:"When to use lacquer retarder",keywords:["retarder","lacquer","slow","dry","blush","hot","humid","summer","extend"],answer:"Lacquer retarder (slow thinner or retarder additive) extends the lacquer's open time and prevents blush in hot, humid conditions. Add 5–15% by volume to the lacquer. In summer conditions (above 80°F, above 60% RH), standard lacquer thinner dries so fast the lacquer can't level properly. Retarder slows the evaporation rate, allowing the solvents to escape slowly and the lacquer to flow smoothly. Use sparingly in cool, dry conditions — too much retarder leaves the finish tacky for hours."},{id:"mk-dewaxed-shellac-universal",topic:"Dewaxed shellac as the universal finish compatibilizer",keywords:["dewaxed","shellac","universal","compatibilizer","between","coats","anything","bond"],answer:"Dewaxed shellac (Zinsser SealCoat or flake-mixed) bonds to everything and allows everything to bond to it — making it the universal compatibilizer between incompatible finishes. Stain won't bond to wax? Apply dewaxed shellac first. Not sure if old finish is compatible with new? Apply dewaxed shellac between them. Want to apply water-based poly over oil stain that might bleed? Dewaxed shellac sealer first. Want to spray lacquer over suspicious substrate? Dewaxed shellac sealer first. This single product solves most finish compatibility questions."},{id:"mk-applying-wax-buffing",topic:"Applying and buffing paste wax correctly",keywords:["paste","wax","apply","buff","thin","coat","hazing","cloth","rotary","manual"],answer:"Apply paste wax very thin — a common mistake is applying too thick a coat, which hazes badly and is hard to buff. Use a soft cloth or fine steel wool (0000) to apply a thin coat; the wax should barely color the applicator cloth. Let the wax haze (set up) for 5–15 minutes at room temperature. Buff vigorously with a clean cloth or buffer — the friction and compression produce the shine. A second thin coat after 24 hours builds more depth. Too thick a coat simply peels off during buffing and wastes wax."},{id:"mk-natural-finishes",topic:"Natural and zero-VOC finishes for health-conscious woodworkers",keywords:["natural","finish","low","VOC","zero","health","safe","oil","wax","beeswax"],answer:"For the most health-conscious finishing: pure mineral oil (food-safe, non-drying, zero VOC — for cutting boards); beeswax and carnauba wax blends (natural, minimal hazard); hardwax oil (Osmo, Rubio — plant-based oils with low VOC, very low hazard); pure linseed oil (drying oil, low VOC but fire hazard in rags); milk paint (casein-based, minimal toxicity). Avoid: solvent lacquers, oil-based poly, and solvent-based stains in enclosed spaces. Water-based finishes are lower VOC than oil-based equivalents but not zero."},{id:"mk-finish-over-glue",topic:"Why finish won't penetrate over glue spots",keywords:["glue","spot","finish","block","stain","light","seal","residue","sand","scrape"],answer:"Dried wood glue is essentially a plastic resin — water-based stains and finishes can't penetrate it, causing lighter spots exactly at the glue line or squeeze-out location. Prevention is the only cure at the finishing stage — if the glue is already under the finish, you must strip back to bare wood. Check for glue contamination before staining by wiping naphtha over the surface — glue spots are slick and don't absorb naphtha while bare wood does. A card scraper (not sandpaper) removes the glue film without spreading it into surrounding grain."},{id:"mk-bedroom-layout",topic:"Bedroom furniture proportions and layout",keywords:["bedroom","furniture","proportion","clearance","dresser","nightstand","bed","layout"],answer:'Bedroom layout guidelines: 24"–36" clearance around the bed for comfortable movement; 18"–24" clearance at the foot of the bed. Dresser height: 32"–36" for standard dressers; 48"–56" for tall chests. Nightstand height within 2"–4" of mattress top (accounting for box spring and mattress thickness). Mirror height: center at approximately eye level for the person using it (typically 60"–65" from floor). If the room is small, a bed with integrated storage drawers below maximizes space without adding furniture footprint.'},{id:"mk-dining-table-extend",topic:"Extending dining table mechanisms",keywords:["extending","table","leaf","mechanism","butterfly","slide","rule","joint","fold","store"],answer:"Extending table mechanisms: butterfly leaf (leaf folds and stores under the top, unfolds to extend); slide mechanism (top halves separate on metal slides, leaf drops in between); drop-in leaf (top splits, separate leaf added to fill gap); accordion mechanism (multiple fold-up leaves stored inside the table). The butterfly leaf is the most space-efficient (no separate leaf to store). The drop-in leaf is the most traditional and allows larger extension. All mechanisms require precise alignment hardware — the leaf surface must be level with and flush to the fixed top sections."},{id:"mk-murphy-table",topic:"Wall-mounted folding table for small spaces",keywords:["wall","fold","table","murphy","bracket","hinge","support","leg","dining","small"],answer:'Wall-mounted folding tables use a fold-down mechanism with a hinged leg or bracket system. The table surface is attached to the wall with a full-width piano hinge along one long edge and folds to vertical when not in use. The support can be a fold-out leg, a retractable bracket, or a cable. Size for function: a 12"×24" coffee table; 24"×36" for desk work; 30"×48" minimum for dining. In very small apartments, a single wall-mounted folding table that serves as dining, desk, and hobby surface is a legitimate design solution.'},{id:"mk-room-divider",topic:"Room divider and bookshelf as architectural element",keywords:["room","divider","bookcase","double","sided","freestanding","anchor","partition","open"],answer:"Double-sided bookcases or room dividers function as furniture and architectural elements simultaneously. They must be wall-anchored at the top (anti-tip) even if the design is freestanding — a full bookcase can weigh 400+ lbs when loaded. Open-back designs allow light to pass through; closed-back designs provide privacy and acoustical separation. Height: full ceiling height feels like a wall; half-height allows visual connection between spaces. The structural challenge: a double-sided unit has no back panel for racking resistance — add internal diagonal bracing or design a grid structure."},{id:"mk-hand-cut-vs-router-dovetail",topic:"Hand-cut vs router-cut dovetails — honest comparison",keywords:["hand","cut","router","dovetail","compare","quality","speed","strength","appearance"],answer:"Both produce strong, functional joints. Router jig dovetails (evenly spaced, identical angle and size) are fast for production work and consistent across a batch. Hand-cut dovetails can have varied pin and tail spacing, angles adjusted to look their best, and a slightly organic quality that signals hand work. Structurally they're equivalent when both fit well. Aesthetically: evenly-spaced router dovetails read as machine-made; hand-cut with subtle spacing variation reads as handmade. Neither is inherently superior — they serve different goals."},{id:"mk-half-lap-strength",topic:"Half-lap joint strength and appropriate applications",keywords:["half","lap","joint","strength","table","face","frame","apron","rail"],answer:"A well-glued half-lap joint has significant long-grain glue area and is adequate for most frame construction applications. Its weakness is resistance to racking (the frame racking out of square) — in an unbraced frame, racking forces eventually work the joint loose. Resist racking by: adding a back panel, adding diagonal bracing, or using a stronger joint (mortise-and-tenon with haunched tenon). Half-laps are commonly used in face frames, ladder-back chair frames, and window sash — applications where the surrounding structure provides racking resistance."},{id:"mk-miter-spline-router",topic:"Routing spline slots in mitered frames",keywords:["spline","router","miter","slot","frame","reinforce","bit","angle","corner"],answer:"Slot the spline groove across the mitered corner after assembly — or before assembly with each piece registered at 45° to the fence. Before assembly: set the router table with the fence at 45° from the blade (or use a dedicated miter spline jig) to cut the slot centered in the miter face. After assembly: rest the assembled corner on a V-block jig and run across a router bit or table saw blade. The spline goes in perpendicular to the miter face; use cross-grain plywood for the spline to resist splitting. Glue and let dry; trim flush."},{id:"mk-pocket-hole-exterior",topic:"Pocket holes on exterior projects — special considerations",keywords:["pocket","hole","exterior","outdoor","screw","stainless","seal","moisture","rot"],answer:"Outdoor pocket hole joinery needs stainless steel pocket screws (regular steel screws rust and stain the wood black). Use type 316 stainless for truly marine-grade outdoor work. The pocket hole itself is an open void that traps water — seal pocket holes in outdoor work with silicone caulk or fill with a wooden plug and exterior grade adhesive. PVA glue in outdoor pocket hole joints will eventually fail from moisture exposure — use polyurethane or epoxy adhesive for outdoor applications."},{id:"mk-spline-kerf-thickness",topic:"Matching spline thickness to the kerf",keywords:["spline","kerf","thickness","match","snug","plywood","solid","fit","groove"],answer:`A spline must fit the groove snugly — not too loose (rattles, weak joint), not too tight (splits the groove when driven home). Plywood splines are the safest choice: 1/4" plywood fits a standard dado blade's 1/4" groove closely; cut a test strip and check the fit before cutting all splines. Solid wood splines must have the grain running perpendicular to the joint line (short grain) to resist splitting the groove. For decorative keyed miters, use the same thickness as the table saw blade's kerf — a thin kerf blade leaves a very tight fit.`},{id:"mk-router-table-rabbet",topic:"Routing a rabbet on the router table",keywords:["router","table","rabbet","fence","bit","straight","bearing","depth","width"],answer:"Two methods for router table rabbets: (1) A straight bit set at the fence — fence position determines rabbet width; bit height determines rabbet depth. Most versatile. (2) A rabbeting bit with a bearing — the bearing rides the workpiece edge, its diameter determines the rabbet width, and bit height determines depth. The bearing method needs no fence but can follow the edge irregularities. For production work with consistent widths, the fence method is faster; for shaped pieces (curved backs, irregular edges), the bearing method follows the shape automatically."},{id:"mk-soft-maple-varieties",topic:"Soft maple species — silver, red, bigleaf",keywords:["soft","maple","silver","red","bigleaf","species","compare","cabinet","coast"],answer:'Soft maple includes several species: silver maple (Acer saccharinum) — very soft, common in the East; red maple (Acer rubrum) — intermediate hardness, common painted cabinet wood; bigleaf maple (Acer macrophyllum) — West Coast species often sold as Pacific maple, frequently figured. All are significantly softer than sugar (hard) maple. Red maple is the most common in commercial lumberyards as "soft maple." Bigleaf maple produces spectacular quilted and curly figures rivaling hard maple curly for beauty.'},{id:"mk-white-vs-yellow-pine",topic:"Eastern white pine vs southern yellow pine for woodworking",keywords:["white","pine","yellow","pine","soft","hard","east","south","compare","knot"],answer:"Eastern white pine is very soft (Janka 380) with tight grain, few knots in upper grades, and minimal resin — perfect for carving, painted furniture, and trim work where a soft, workable wood is needed. Southern yellow pine (longleaf, loblolly, shortleaf) is significantly harder (Janka 870–1225) and resinous — more durable for structural use and painted cabinetry where hardness matters. SYP is the standard structural lumber in the South; EWP is the standard for fine furniture and architectural millwork in New England."},{id:"mk-madrone",topic:"Pacific madrone — a rare and beautiful West Coast wood",keywords:["madrone","pacific","arbutus","west","coast","red","bark","turning","difficult"],answer:"Pacific madrone (Arbutus menziesii) has smooth cinnamon-red bark and produces wood with a warm, orange-red tone and fine grain. It's considered one of the most beautiful native West Coast hardwoods but is notoriously difficult to season — it checks severely during drying and requires very slow, carefully controlled drying. Most madrone is used for turning and small decorative pieces rather than furniture lumber because of the drying challenges. Find it from Pacific Northwest urban lumber sources when trees are removed."},{id:"mk-catalpa-outdoor",topic:"Catalpa as an underappreciated outdoor furniture wood",keywords:["catalpa","outdoor","rot","light","soft","paint","natural","decay","resistant"],answer:"Catalpa is one of the few genuinely rot-resistant softwoods in North America — its natural oils protect it in outdoor use similar to cedar. It's very light (comparable to western white pine) and easy to work with hand tools. It takes paint beautifully and holds up well outdoors without finish. The coarse, open grain gives a rustic character. It's widely available in the Southeast and Midwest but rarely stocked at lumber yards — source from local tree services. An excellent choice for painted outdoor furniture where weight and workability matter."},{id:"mk-osage-orange-tools",topic:"Osage orange for tool handles and mallet heads",keywords:["osage","orange","tool","handle","mallet","head","dense","yellow","shrink"],answer:"Osage orange (hedge apple) is ideal for mallet heads and striking tool handles because of its shock resistance and density. The bright yellow wood darkens to golden brown within days of cutting. It's nearly impervious to rot, weather, and insects, making it traditionally used for fence posts and wagon parts in the Midwest. For tool handles, the straight-grained splits have exceptional strength-to-weight ratio. It's incredibly hard on cutting tools — sharpen often and use carbide when machining. Available from Midwestern urban lumber sources and specialty dealers."},{id:"mk-willow-basket",topic:"Willow — basket weaving and cricket bats",keywords:["willow","basket","cricket","bat","weave","flexible","rods","osier","light"],answer:"Weeping willow and basket willows (Salix species) produce flexible rods used in basket weaving when harvested young. Cricket bats (a specialty application) are made exclusively from White Willow (Salix alba) — it absorbs impact shock without splitting or splintering. Willow wood is very soft and light, unsuitable for most furniture. In woodworking, willow occasionally appears as carving material (very easy to carve) and as basket bases for chair seats. The ornamental weeping willows are not the same species used for basket weaving."},{id:"mk-lumber-moisture-season",topic:"Best time of year to buy lumber",keywords:["buy","lumber","season","time","year","winter","summer","humidity","dry","best"],answer:"The best time to buy lumber for interior furniture is late winter or early spring — heating season has dried interior spaces, lumber yard stock has been in relatively dry conditions, and the wood will be at or near its lowest moisture content. Lumber bought in summer (high humidity) or from an outdoor yard in the rain will have elevated moisture and must be thoroughly acclimated before use. Ask the dealer when their next kiln-dried shipment arrives — fresh KD stock from the kiln is the most consistently dry lumber available."},{id:"mk-board-feet-mental",topic:"Quick board feet mental math for the lumber yard",keywords:["board","feet","mental","math","quick","estimate","yard","calculate","rough"],answer:`Mental board feet calculation for common situations: a 1"×6"×8' board = 4 BF (easy: 6"×8' ÷ 12). A 1"×8"×8' = 5.3 BF. A 1"×4"×12' = 4 BF. Rule of thumb for common sizes: multiply width in feet times length in feet (for 4/4 stock). A 6" board = 0.5' wide; × 8' = 4 BF. For 5/4 stock, multiply by 1.25. For 8/4, multiply by 2. These mental math shortcuts work because the width denominator of 12 cancels with the factor of 12 in the width/12 calculation.`},{id:"mk-plywood-waste-factor",topic:"Plywood waste factor for nesting parts",keywords:["plywood","waste","nesting","factor","lay","out","calculate","sheet","count"],answer:"When calculating plywood sheet count, a good rule is to add 15% waste to the optimized layout. This accounts for: kerf waste between parts; off-square ends that must be ripped clean; one bad section per sheet (bubble, void, damaged corner); and the off-cut triangles at the end of angled cuts. For a project requiring 15 sq ft of parts, that's about half a 4×8 sheet (32 sq ft), but with 15% waste you need about 18 sq ft of usable area — still one sheet but planned more conservatively."},{id:"mk-color-change-light",topic:"Displaying wood color change (patina) intentionally",keywords:["color","change","cherry","walnut","patina","light","uv","darken","expose"],answer:"Many premium furniture woods darken or change color significantly with light and age — cherry turns from pale pink to rich red-brown; walnut lightens from chocolate to warm tan; white oak develops golden undertones. To develop patina intentionally: place the finished piece where it receives regular light exposure. Protect newly finished pieces from object placement that leaves light marks (a book left on cherry for a month leaves a pale rectangle). After several months, the patina evens out across the surface regardless of early uneven exposure."},{id:"mk-French-cleat-system",topic:"French cleat wall organization system",keywords:["french","cleat","wall","organize","storage","tool","cabinet","shop","hook"],answer:'A French cleat system is the most flexible shop wall organization: horizontal strips of plywood (or solid wood) with 45° beveled edges mounted in rows across the wall. Any accessory (tool holder, hook, small shelf, bin) with a matching 45° slot hangs anywhere on the wall and is instantly repositionable. Cover an entire shop wall with cleat strips (spaced 2"–4" vertically) and you can reconfigure the entire storage layout in minutes. Use 3/4" plywood cut on the table saw at 45° for the strongest cleats; mount into studs for a full wall of heavy tool storage.'},{id:"mk-wall-mounted-tool-storage",topic:"Wall-mounted tool storage for hand tools",keywords:["wall","mount","storage","chisel","plane","saw","rack","holder","hook","shadow"],answer:"Hanging tools on the wall above the bench puts them within arm's reach and keeps the bench clear. Shadow board approach: trace each tool's outline on painted plywood, then add hooks and clips in the matching positions. This shows immediately when a tool is missing. Chisel racks: a strip of wood with routed or drilled openings for the handles keeps edges protected and chisels accessible. Plane storage: shelf with lip (keep irons retracted); or hang planes on their sides on wide hooks. The goal: every tool has a designated place and goes back there after every use."},{id:"mk-finishing-room-setup",topic:"Setting up a dedicated finishing area",keywords:["finishing","room","area","ventilate","light","dust","clean","filter","spray"],answer:"The ideal finishing area is a separate room or section of the shop: explosion-proof fan venting outdoors, dedicated overhead LED lighting (bright enough to see runs immediately), filtered air intake (keep fresh clean air flowing in while solvent vapors go out), and a sealed floor that can be cleaned. Minimize dust by finishing early before any machining for the day, wiping down all surfaces with a damp mop, and letting the air filtration run for 30 minutes before starting. Even a curtained-off corner with a portable exhaust fan significantly improves finish quality."},{id:"mk-mobile-machine-bases",topic:"Mobile machine bases for small shop flexibility",keywords:["mobile","base","machine","wheel","lock","small","shop","move","floor","castors"],answer:'Mobile machine bases (HTC, Jet, Rockler versions) let heavy machines roll out of position for use and lock in place during operation. They lift the machine on casters and have locking mechanisms to prevent movement during use. Critical: the locking mechanism must be positive — a table saw on unlocked casters is extremely dangerous. For very heavy machines (over 400 lbs), use bases rated appropriately and check that all four locks engage firmly before use. Mobile bases add 2"–3" to machine height — adjust outfeed tables accordingly.'},{id:"mk-dust-collection-pipe",topic:"Dust collection pipe sizing and layout",keywords:["dust","collection","pipe","size","diameter","4","6","main","trunk","branch"],answer:`Dust collection system sizing: the main trunk line should be at least 6" diameter for a 1.5+ HP collector. Branch lines to individual machines: 4" is standard. Avoid reducing the trunk line below 4" at any branch connection. Long runs reduce suction — every 10' of pipe equals about 1" of pressure drop. Minimize elbows (each 90° elbow equals 7' of straight pipe pressure drop) and use sweep bends (gentle curves) rather than sharp elbows. Smooth-bore PVC pipe produces less friction loss than corrugated flex hose — use flex only for short final connections to the machine.`},{id:"mk-wood-identification-key",topic:"Simple wood identification key for the shop",keywords:["identify","wood","key","species","pore","smell","color","weight","grain"],answer:"Quick identification key: (1) Is it heavy for its size? Yes → likely oak, maple, hickory, walnut, or exotic. No → pine, poplar, cedar, basswood, or other soft species. (2) Open pores (clearly visible with a loupe)? Yes → ring-porous: oak, ash, elm, hickory. No → diffuse-porous or softwood. (3) Color: dark brown → walnut or mahogany; red-orange → cherry or cedar; white to cream → maple, ash, pine, or poplar. (4) Smell the fresh sawdust — cedar, cherry, walnut, and pine all have distinctive scents. Most species can be narrowed to 2–3 candidates with these four steps."}],u=[{id:"ml-coping-rail-door",topic:"Cope-and-stick router door construction",keywords:["cope","stick","router","door","frame","panel","cabinet","bit","set","quickly"],answer:"Cope-and-stick bits produce cabinet doors quickly: the stick profile runs the full length of stiles and rails, cutting a groove and decorative edge in one pass. The cope profile cuts the rail ends to match — the coped shoulder mates with the stile stick profile. Always run the stick profile first, then the cope. The joint provides alignment but minimal racking resistance — many woodworkers add a Domino or pocket hole for strength. Use matched sets from the same manufacturer; mixing cope and stick bits from different makers produces mismatched profiles."},{id:"ml-krenov-furniture",topic:"James Krenov influenced cabinet making",keywords:["krenov","cabinet","maker","shop","handcraft","hand","plane","joinery","aesthetic"],answer:`James Krenov's aesthetic emphasizes quiet elegance, careful wood selection, hand tool work, and joinery that reveals the material's beauty. His cabinets use hand-fitted sliding dovetails, through-tenons with visible wedges, and surfaces prepared with a hand plane rather than sanders. The Krenov-style cabinet on stand is the signature piece — a case mounted on a separate base with exposed joinery connecting the two. His book "The Fine Art of Cabinetmaking" is essential reading for woodworkers interested in this thoughtful approach.`},{id:"ml-chair-back-curve",topic:"Shaping chair back slats with curves",keywords:["chair","back","slat","curve","steam","bend","bandsaw","spokeshave","flat","sawn"],answer:"Chair back slats can be curved in three ways: steam-bent after rough cutting (produces a true bend through the wood's fibers), bandsaw-cut from a curved grain layout (strongest when grain follows the curve), or sawn flat and given a thickness taper that creates visual curve without structural bend. Steam-bent slats are strongest and most comfortable. Flat-sawn curves from straight stock have cross-grain weak points but are far easier to produce. The grain must follow the slat curve for structural integrity in any slat that will be loaded in bending."},{id:"ml-coopered-panel",topic:"Coopered cabinet door panels",keywords:["coopered","door","panel","curve","stave","drum","cabinet","convex","concave"],answer:'A coopered panel uses beveled stave joints to create a curved surface — each stave edge is cut at the same angle so the glued-up panel curves across its width. This creates convex or concave curved door panels without bending or steam. The curve radius depends on the number of staves and the bevel angle: for a gentle curve on an 18" wide panel, eight staves at 11° per edge gives a shallow but elegant arc. After glue-up, the face is hand-planed smooth. Coopered panels are seen on high-end custom cabinetry and contemporary furniture.'},{id:"ml-rule-joint-setting",topic:"Setting the rule joint hinge position precisely",keywords:["rule","joint","hinge","position","pivot","center","radius","drop","leaf","bind"],answer:`The rule joint hinge's knuckle center must align exactly with the center of the roundover radius — if it's off even 1/32", the joint will bind or gap when the leaf drops. To set: rout the roundover and cove profiles, find the center of the roundover radius (the center of the bit's cutting circle), and mortise the hinge so its knuckle aligns with that center. The hinge is mounted below the joint, and its knuckle sits recessed from the joint line. This is one of the most precisely-located hinge installations in all of woodworking.`},{id:"ml-biscuit-alignment-trick",topic:"Using biscuits for alignment without clamping them",keywords:["biscuit","align","dry","assemble","orient","trick","no","clamp","swell"],answer:"Biscuits can be used as dry alignment aids without glue — they swell slightly when they contact water-based glue but can be inserted dry for positioning. When edge-gluing boards, dry-fit biscuits to align the boards perfectly, then replace with glued biscuits for final assembly. For cases where you want to glue up without the biscuit swelling and causing a hydraulic fit problem, use a very small amount of glue (half a bead), or use biscuits only as positioning aids while primary glue is on the long-grain faces."},{id:"ml-drawbore-sizing",topic:"Drawbore hole offset calculation",keywords:["drawbore","offset","hole","1/16","pin","pull","tight","calculate"],answer:`The standard drawbore offset is 1/16" — the hole through the tenon is drilled 1/16" closer to the tenon shoulder than the holes through the mortise walls. When the tapered peg is driven, this offset forces the tenon to draw tight against the mortised piece. Too much offset (1/8" or more) can split the mortise walls or the tenon. Too little (1/32") doesn't pull tight reliably. Drill the mortise holes first, dry-assemble, mark through the mortise holes onto the tenon, and redrill the tenon hole 1/16" toward the shoulder from this marked center.`},{id:"ml-green-wood-joinery",topic:"Green woodworking joinery principles",keywords:["green","wood","joinery","dry","wet","shrink","lock","rung","post","joint"],answer:"Green (unseasoned) woodworking exploits wood movement for joinery. The classic technique: turn a rung or spindle slightly oversize from green wood, dry it, and insert it into a hole drilled in a dry post. The dry rung, at lower moisture content than the air, absorbs moisture from the surrounding wood and swells into the mortise — creating a locked joint without any glue. This technique is used in Windsor chair construction and produces joints that tighten over time rather than loosening."},{id:"ml-butt-joint-reinforced",topic:"Reinforcing butt joints for adequate strength",keywords:["butt","joint","reinforce","screw","pocket","dowel","corner","bracket","metal"],answer:"Plain butt joints (end grain meeting face grain) rely entirely on adhesive to end grain — which provides very little glue strength. Reinforce them: pocket screws through the face grain into the end grain add mechanical strength; dowels or biscuits provide alignment and some additional glue area; metal corner brackets add rigid mechanical reinforcement. For boxes and carcases under stress, always reinforce butt joints or switch to a better joint. Butt joints are acceptable for non-structural applications like back panels screwed in place, but not for structural corners."},{id:"ml-ebony-inlay-stringing",topic:"Ebony and boxwood stringing inlay",keywords:["ebony","boxwood","stringing","inlay","line","band","furniture","edge","router","chisel"],answer:'Stringing (thin decorative lines of contrasting wood inlaid into a groove) is a classic 18th and 19th century furniture technique. Ebony and boxwood are the traditional combination — ebony for dark lines, boxwood for light. Cut grooves with a router, scratch stock, or side rabbet plane to exactly the stringing thickness. Stringing strips are typically 1/32"–1/16" thick and 1/16"–1/8" wide. Glue with hide glue for reversibility. Trim flush with a sharp chisel when cured. The visual precision required is very high — the groove must exactly match the stringing width for a gap-free result.'},{id:"ml-japanese-joinery-variation",topic:"Kanawa tsugi — Japanese splice joint",keywords:["kanawa","tsugi","japanese","splice","scarf","join","complex","beam","lock"],answer:"The kanawa tsugi is one of the most complex traditional Japanese splice joints — it joins two beams end-to-end with an interlocking stepped profile that locks without any fasteners or glue. The joint is self-locking under load and can be disassembled by sliding perpendicular to the beam axis. Traditional Japanese temple builders used it where accessibility for future repair or disassembly was required. Modern woodworkers build it as an exercise in precision and geometry — cutting one takes days even for experienced craftspeople. CNC makes it more accessible, but the hand-cut version is a benchmark of skill."},{id:"ml-cabinetry-assembly-order",topic:"Assembly order for a four-door base cabinet",keywords:["assembly","order","cabinet","base","four","door","sequence","glue","back","shelf"],answer:"Standard assembly sequence for a face-frame base cabinet: (1) dado the shelf and back grooves in sides; (2) attach the bottom to the sides with dado joints and pocket screws; (3) attach the top rail and nailer strip; (4) square and install the back panel; (5) attach the face frame with glue and pocket screws; (6) mount door hinges in the doors; (7) hang doors and adjust reveals. Install the cabinet in its final location before attaching the countertop. Install hardware last. Working through this order prevents installing parts that will block access to the next step."},{id:"ml-finish-over-wax",topic:"Why you cannot apply finish over wax",keywords:["wax","finish","over","adhesion","fail","peel","strip","contaminate","shellac"],answer:"Wax creates a non-porous, slick surface that new finish cannot bond to — the fresh finish beads up and peels off in sheets as it dries. If you want to refinish a waxed piece, you must strip the wax completely first. Strip with naphtha (mineral spirits or VM&P naphtha) scrubbed in with fine steel wool, then rinse with clean naphtha and let the surface completely dry before applying any new finish. Shellac can sometimes be applied over light wax residue, but it's best to strip wax first regardless."},{id:"ml-teak-oil-products",topic:"Teak oil products vs real teak treatment",keywords:["teak","oil","product","commercial","linseed","mineral","marketing","outdoor","real"],answer:`"Teak oil" is a marketing term for various penetrating oil finishes — most contain linseed oil, mineral spirits, and driers. They are not pressed from teak trees. For actual teak wood, penetrating oil does maintain the golden color, but teak's own oils provide more inherent protection than the applied oil. On non-teak species, "teak oil" products perform similarly to danish oil. The main advantage for outdoor work: they penetrate rather than film, so they don't peel. Reapply annually after cleaning with a teak cleaner (oxalic acid based) for best results.`},{id:"ml-lacquer-types-compare",topic:"Nitrocellulose vs CAB-acrylic vs catalyzed lacquer",keywords:["lacquer","nitrocellulose","CAB","acrylic","catalyzed","compare","clear","yellow","durable"],answer:"Nitrocellulose lacquer yellows amber with age — it's traditional for furniture and guitars but reads warm rather than clear. CAB-acrylic lacquer (cellulose acetate butyrate) is clearer and less ambering — better for maple and light-colored woods where you want the clearest possible finish. Both are spray-only and not particularly durable. Catalyzed lacquer (pre-cat and post-cat) is much more durable than either — adds a crosslinker that creates a harder film — but is more expensive and has limited pot life. For the clearest, most durable result on furniture, pre-catalyzed lacquer is the best choice in a spray environment."},{id:"ml-penetrating-vs-film",topic:"Penetrating finish vs film finish trade-offs",keywords:["penetrating","film","finish","trade","off","maintain","repair","water","protect"],answer:"Penetrating finishes (oil, hardwax oil, danish oil) soak into the wood fibers and harden there — they don't form a film on the surface. They're easy to apply, easy to repair locally, show no peeling or cracking, and maintain a natural look. Trade-off: less water and abrasion resistance than film finishes. Film finishes (poly, varnish, lacquer) form a hard plastic-like layer above the wood — more durable against water, chemicals, and scratches, but peel and chip when they fail, require full sanding for repair. Choose penetrating for natural-look and easy maintenance; film for maximum protection in demanding environments."},{id:"ml-shellac-sealer-advantages",topic:"Advantages of shellac as a wood sealer",keywords:["shellac","sealer","seal","bond","adhesion","knot","bleed","speed","dry","universal"],answer:"Shellac is the best universal sealer for four reasons: (1) It bonds to everything including oily woods, and everything bonds to it; (2) It dries in 30–45 minutes — stack coats in hours not days; (3) It seals knots, resin pockets, and tannin bleed that would cause problems under water-based topcoats; (4) It's fully reversible with alcohol — useful for recoating without stripping. Zinsser Bullseye Shellac (dewaxed) is the standard product. The limitation: shellac itself isn't very durable or water-resistant, so always topcoat with a more durable finish for surfaces in use."},{id:"ml-finish-temperature",topic:"Temperature effects on finish application",keywords:["temperature","cold","hot","finish","apply","cure","harden","minimum","slow"],answer:"Oil-based finishes require above 55°F for application and curing — below this, they may never cure properly (remain sticky). Water-based finishes are more sensitive: below 60°F they can coalesce improperly, leaving a milky, weak film. Above 85°F, water-based finishes dry too fast to level. Ideal temperature for most finishing: 65–75°F. Cold shop in winter: bring the workpiece and finish materials inside (room temperature) before applying; don't finish cold work with warm finish. Lacquer is most tolerant of temperature variation but still shouldn't be applied below 55°F."},{id:"ml-finish-humidity",topic:"Humidity effects on finish application",keywords:["humidity","finish","blush","water","based","oil","50","percent","RH","dry"],answer:"High humidity (above 70% RH) causes problems with most finishes. Lacquer blushes (turns milky) as moisture gets trapped in the quickly-drying film. Oil-based finishes dry much more slowly in high humidity. Water-based finishes can have adhesion issues and slower curing. Ideal finishing humidity: 40–55% RH. In very high humidity, add lacquer retarder, heat the shop slightly (reduces RH), or wait for drier conditions. Dehumidifiers in the finishing area are a worthwhile investment in humid climates. Low humidity (below 30%) can cause water-based finishes to dry too fast to level."},{id:"ml-danish-oil-open-time",topic:"Working time with danish oil",keywords:["danish","oil","open","time","wipe","off","excess","tacky","30","minutes"],answer:"Danish oil has a specific working window: apply, allow 5–30 minutes of penetration time (species-dependent — softer or more porous woods absorb faster), then wipe off all excess before it becomes tacky. If you wait too long, the excess gels on the surface and produces a sticky, uneven film. Wipe off excess while the surface is still wet to the touch. In a cool shop (below 65°F), you have more time; in a warm shop, the oil skins faster. Always err toward wiping off too early rather than too late — additional coats build depth."},{id:"ml-spray-pad-application",topic:"Pad (cloth) application vs spray for finishes",keywords:["pad","cloth","wipe","spray","compare","apply","control","thin","coat","quality"],answer:"Pad application (wiping on with a lint-free cloth or Scotch-Brite pad) works well for penetrating finishes, wiping varnishes, diluted shellac, and oil-based poly thinned 50%. Advantages: no spray equipment, no overspray, thin coats naturally, and good control on complex shapes. Disadvantages: limited to thin coats per application — film builds slowly, taking 6–8 coats for protective film thickness. Spray provides faster film build and better leveling on flat surfaces but requires setup, cleanup, and ventilation. For furniture refinishing in a home workshop, pad application is often the most practical choice."},{id:"ml-natural-oil-drying",topic:"Why linseed and tung oil need many coats",keywords:["linseed","tung","oil","coats","many","thin","build","protect","cure","layers"],answer:"Natural drying oils (linseed, tung) cure by absorbing oxygen — each thin coat needs to cure completely before the next can absorb and cure. A thick coat skins over on the surface while the interior remains uncured and sticky indefinitely. Very thin coats (applied and wiped off immediately) cure in 24–48 hours; thicker coats may take a week. After 6–10 thin coats, the pores are filled and the wood is protected. The cumulative film is thin but hard. This is why natural oil finishing is a multi-session project spanning weeks, not a single afternoon task."},{id:"ml-acacia-wood",topic:"Acacia for furniture and cutting boards",keywords:["acacia","koa","hard","dense","warm","color","cutting","board","table","top"],answer:`Acacia is a diverse genus with several commercially important species. Hawaiian koa (Acacia koa) is a premium guitar and luxury furniture wood with stunning golden-brown color and wavy figure. Australian blackwood (Acacia melanoxylon) resembles koa and is used similarly. Other acacia species are sold as wood for cutting boards (commonly sold at big box stores as "acacia cutting boards"). The wood is hard and dense, finishes well, and is moderately rot-resistant. It's sustainable due to fast growth rates in its native range.`},{id:"ml-myrtle-wood",topic:"Oregon myrtle (California bay laurel)",keywords:["myrtle","oregon","bay","laurel","figure","color","turning","bowl","premium"],answer:"Oregon myrtle (Umbellularia californica) produces a spectacularly figured wood with olive-green to golden-brown color, often with curly or wavy figure and pronounced luster. It's highly prized by turners and carvers on the West Coast. The strong aromatic smell when fresh-cut (bay laurel) is pleasant but can be irritating to some. It's available primarily in the Pacific Coast states; very limited commercial production elsewhere. Myrtle figures exceptionally well when quartersawn and produces beautiful bowls and small furniture pieces."},{id:"ml-camphor-wood",topic:"Camphor wood characteristics and traditional uses",keywords:["camphor","aromatic","chest","box","storage","natural","repel","insect","asian"],answer:"Camphor (Cinnamomum camphora) has very strong camphor aromatic oils that repel insects — historically used throughout Asia for treasure chests, clothing storage, and medicine chests for exactly this reason. The heartwood is reddish-brown with dark streaks and fine figure. It's moderately hard and works well with hand tools. The aroma is stronger and more medicinal than cedar. Antique camphor wood chests from China and Japan are highly collectible. Newly worked camphor releases intense aromatic oils — ventilate well and be aware of sensitivity reactions."},{id:"ml-pine-wormy-character",topic:"Wormy wood — character or defect",keywords:["wormy","character","wood","beetle","track","hole","pin","chestnut","southern"],answer:'Wormy wood has channels, holes, and tracks left by wood-boring beetles or insects. American chestnut killed by the blight often has wormy character from the chestnut bark beetle; southern yellow pine has "mineral staining" and tracks from pine beetles. "Character wormy" grades embrace these marks as design elements rather than defects. The wood itself is structurally sound if the infestation is historical (not active). Active powder post beetle infestations require heat treatment or fumigation — the wood is not safe to bring into a shop or home until treated.'},{id:"ml-ironwood-species",topic:"Different woods called ironwood",keywords:["ironwood","dense","heavy","hardest","Osage","hornbeam","desert","various"],answer:`"Ironwood" is used for dozens of species across the world — any wood that's extremely dense and hard gets this nickname. Desert ironwood (Olneya tesota) from the American Southwest is extremely dense, dark brown, and used for small turned pieces and knife handles. Eastern hornbeam (Carpinus caroliniana) is sometimes called ironwood. Australian ironwood species are similarly dense. Black locust and Osage orange are sometimes informally called ironwood in the Midwest. When buying, ask for the botanical name — the common name "ironwood" is nearly meaningless without it.`},{id:"ml-rift-sawn-floor",topic:"Rift and quartersawn flooring vs plain sawn",keywords:["rift","quartersawn","floor","stable","wear","even","grade","cost","premium"],answer:"Rift and quartersawn flooring wears more evenly (the end grain pattern presents harder latewood across the surface), is dimensionally more stable (resists cupping and gapping), and shows less grain pattern variation from board to board. Plain sawn (flat sawn) flooring is much less expensive because it produces more footage from a log. The premium for rift/quartersawn flooring is 30–100% over flat sawn. For kitchens and high-traffic areas, the extra cost of quartersawn is worthwhile; for bedrooms and lower-traffic spaces, flat sawn is perfectly appropriate."},{id:"ml-reading-veneer-grain",topic:"Reading veneer grain direction before applying",keywords:["veneer","grain","direction","before","apply","book","match","sequential","lay"],answer:'Veneer sheets must be applied with consistent grain direction — lay them face-up on a well-lit surface and sight across them at a low angle to see the grain direction. The "cathedral" arch of flat-cut veneer must run consistently (all peaks pointing up, or down, but not randomly). Bookmatched sheets must be oriented with the mirror-image grain meeting at the center joint. Mark the face side and top of each sheet before unstacking — veneer leaves look identical on both sides but grain direction matters for how the finish will appear.'},{id:"ml-track-saw-kickback",topic:"Track saw kickback prevention",keywords:["track","saw","kickback","bind","rail","cut","splinter","prevent","secure"],answer:"Track saws rarely kick back compared to circular saws because the track constrains the saw's movement, but kickback is still possible if the kerf closes on the blade (workpiece bending) or the track shifts. Prevention: support the workpiece fully so it can't sag and pinch the blade; clamp the track securely at both ends; let the saw come to full speed before beginning the cut; use a sharp blade appropriate for the material. A track saw should always be used with the splitter/riving knife in place."},{id:"ml-biscuit-joiner-fence",topic:"Biscuit joiner fence adjustment for face frames",keywords:["biscuit","joiner","fence","face","frame","90","align","flush","register"],answer:"For face frame assembly, set the biscuit joiner fence to 90° so slots are cut perpendicular to the face. Register the fence against the face surface of the rails, not the edge. This ensures the biscuit aligns the joint flat (faces flush). For mitered corners and angled cuts, adjust the fence to the miter angle. Always clamp the workpiece before cutting — biscuit joiner vibration will shift an unclamped piece and misalign the slot. Mark the joint location on both pieces before slotting so the slots align."},{id:"ml-router-spiral-bits",topic:"Upcut vs downcut spiral router bits",keywords:["upcut","downcut","spiral","bit","router","chips","tearout","direction","application"],answer:"Upcut spiral bits pull chips up and out of the cut — excellent chip evacuation for deep cuts, mortises, and plunge cuts, but can lift the workpiece or cause tearout on the top face of veneered stock. Downcut spiral bits push chips downward into the cut — better for veneered surfaces (no top face tearout), but chips pack in the cut and cause heat on deep cuts. Compression spiral bits have an upcut bottom section and downcut top section — produce clean cuts on both faces of a veneered panel, ideal for CNC through-cuts."},{id:"ml-router-mortise-depth",topic:"Routing mortises accurately — depth stops and passes",keywords:["router","mortise","depth","stop","plunge","pass","multiple","accurate","clean"],answer:'Plunge routers have a depth stop rod with a turret stop — set the turret steps to incremental depths (1/4" steps are common) so you can plunge to three progressively deeper positions without resetting. This allows multiple shallow passes to final depth without jamming the bit. For a 1" deep mortise with an upcut spiral bit: first pass at 1/4", second at 1/2", third at 3/4", final pass at full depth with a slow feed to clean the walls. The final cleaning pass uses the same depth setting but a very slow feed rate for flat, clean mortise walls.'},{id:"ml-bandsaw-radius-capability",topic:"Bandsaw blade width vs minimum radius table",keywords:["bandsaw","blade","width","minimum","radius","curve","tight","turn","1/4","1/2"],answer:'Minimum cutting radius by blade width: 1/8" blade → 1/4" radius. 1/4" blade → 3/4" radius. 3/8" blade → 1.5" radius. 1/2" blade → 2.5" radius. 3/4" blade → 5" radius. 1" blade → 10" radius. Choose your blade width based on the tightest curve in your design, then use the same blade for all ripping and straight cuts in that session. Switching from a wide ripping blade to a narrow curve blade mid-project is time-consuming — design your cuts to allow one blade for the session if possible.'},{id:"ml-jointer-width-limit",topic:"Jointer capacity limits and alternatives",keywords:["jointer","width","limit","wide","board","8","6","hand","plane","alternative"],answer:`Most hobby jointers are 6"–8" wide — boards wider than the table can't be edge-jointed on one side and must be handled with a hand plane. For tabletop glue-up edge jointing on boards up to 10"–12" wide, a well-tuned No.7 jointer plane produces equal quality to a power jointer. Boards wider than the jointer's capacity for face flattening require a router sled, wide drum sander, or hand planing. The alternative to a wider jointer is building up wide panels from narrower boards — each strip is within the jointer's capacity.`},{id:"ml-table-saw-micro-adjust",topic:"Micro-adjusting the table saw fence",keywords:["table","saw","fence","micro","adjust","fine","tune","repeatable","lock","accurate"],answer:`For precise rip cuts (to 1/64" or better), you need reliable fence micro-adjustment. On premium fences (Biesemeyer, T-Square style), the fence locks rock-solid and a graduated scale reads the width. On budget saws, loosen the fence, tap it with a rubber mallet for small adjustments, and test-cut in scrap before committing. Keep a digital caliper at the saw to measure actual cut width rather than reading the fence scale — the scale may be off by 1/16" or more. Any fence you can't trust to hold position reliably makes precise ripping impossible.`},{id:"ml-drill-press-depth-stop",topic:"Drill press depth stop for consistent hole depth",keywords:["depth","stop","drill","press","consistent","hole","shelf","pin","dowel","limit"],answer:'The drill press depth stop (a threaded rod that limits how far the quill travels down) ensures all holes are exactly the same depth — essential for shelf pin holes, dowel holes, and any repeat drilling task. Set by lowering the bit to the desired depth with the stop unlocked, then tighten the stop nut against the quill stop. Test in scrap to confirm the depth. For shelf pin holes (typically 3/8" deep for 5mm pins), wrap tape around the bit at the correct depth as a visual reference in addition to the depth stop.'},{id:"ml-sander-grit-sequence",topic:"Never skip sandpaper grits — the science",keywords:["grit","skip","sequence","scratch","remove","next","impossible","sanding","rule"],answer:"Each grit leaves scratches a specific depth. The next grit must fully remove those scratches and replace them with its own shallower ones — which takes significant time at each step. Skipping a grit means the next grit must remove the previous grit's much-deeper scratches, which takes far longer than the skipped step would have. Example: going from 80 to 220 skipping 120 and 150 means the 220 grit paper must remove 80-grit scratches — work that would have taken minutes at 120 takes half an hour at 220, and the 220 paper dulls quickly working against deep scratches."},{id:"ml-pocket-hole-alignment-clamp",topic:"Pocket hole alignment clamp technique",keywords:["pocket","hole","align","clamp","flush","face","force","apart","Kreg"],answer:"The pocket screw angle pushes the top board away from the bottom board as the screw drives — without a clamp, the face offset is significant and ugly. The Kreg face clamp (or any right-angle clamp) holds both pieces in the exact position you want before driving screws. Position the clamp while the joint is dry and correct, tighten, apply glue, then drive the screws while the clamp holds. The clamp should be removed only after the screw is fully seated. For face frame assembly on the bench, a shop-made clamping station with stops and hold-downs speeds up this process for production."},{id:"ml-nail-gun-selection",topic:"Nail gun selection for trim and cabinet work",keywords:["nail","gun","15","16","18","gauge","brad","finish","coil","pneumatic","cordless"],answer:"For cabinet face frames and trim carpentry: 15 or 16-gauge angled finish nailers drive heavier nails that hold trim reliably. For attaching thin moldings, tacking while glue dries, and detail work: 18-gauge brad nails cause smaller holes and less splitting risk. 23-gauge pin nailers drive almost-invisible headless pins — they hold nothing structurally, but are excellent for holding small parts while glue cures. Cordless nailers (lithium battery) have eliminated the need for compressors in many situations — the performance is now nearly equal to pneumatic for most furniture applications."},{id:"ml-bathroom-mirror-frame",topic:"Framing an existing bathroom mirror",keywords:["bathroom","mirror","frame","existing","clip","adhesive","add","border"],answer:`Adding a wood frame to an existing frameless bathroom mirror: either mount the frame directly to the wall overlapping the mirror edges, or adhere the frame to the mirror surface with a mirror adhesive (not solvent-based — it damages the silvering). For wall-mounting: build a frame, rabbet the inside edges so the frame lip covers 1/2" of the mirror edge, and secure the frame to studs or with construction adhesive plus toggle anchors. The frame hides the mirror's cut edges and dramatically upgrades the look without removing or replacing the mirror.`},{id:"ml-shoe-bench",topic:"Entryway shoe bench with seat",keywords:["shoe","bench","entryway","seat","storage","rack","below","cubby","shoe"],answer:'An entryway shoe bench combines a seat (17"–18" height, 15"–16" depth) with shoe storage below. Storage options: open cubby shelf (most accessible, shows the shoes), slatted rack at 45° angle (space-efficient, keeps pairs together), or basket/bin inserts in cubbies. Seat surface should be sturdy enough for a sitting adult — 3/4" plywood minimum, or solid wood. Add a lid and inside storage for off-season shoes. Consider a hook rail or hook bar above the bench for coats and bags to complete the entryway function.'},{id:"ml-art-easel",topic:"Artist easel construction",keywords:["easel","art","studio","adjustable","tripod","canvas","angle","wood","tilt"],answer:"A simple studio easel uses three legs in a tripod arrangement with the rear leg adjustable for angle. The canvas ledge (a strip of wood with a lip) slides up and down on the two front legs on a friction-pinch or bolt-through-slotted-channel mechanism. The top retaining ledge (or strap) holds the canvas from the front. The key is a stable front-leg-to-rear-leg connection that can be adjusted without wobbling. Hardwood (maple or birch) for the structural members; the rear leg often has a threaded rod for fine angle adjustment."},{id:"ml-litter-box-cabinet",topic:"Pet litter box cabinet furniture",keywords:["litter","box","cabinet","pet","hidden","vent","door","furniture","access"],answer:'A litter box cabinet hides the box while providing cat access through a hole in the side or door. Key design considerations: adequate ventilation (grille inserts or gaps at the back), easy access for cleaning (hinged front door or lift-off top), tall enough for the litter box plus 4"–6" clearance for the cat, and durable, easy-to-clean finish. A simple box on legs with a cat door cut into one side serves the function. Ventilation is the most commonly overlooked element — without it, odor concentration inside is extreme.'},{id:"ml-router-table-build",topic:"Building a shop-made router table",keywords:["router","table","build","shop","made","insert","plate","fence","cabinet","base"],answer:'A simple shop router table: a router (base removed) mounted upside-down in a plate that drops into a table-saw extension wing or a dedicated table. The table surface must be flat and stiff — 3/4" MDF with a plastic laminate top is common. The insert plate (router mounts to this) must be flush with or very slightly below the table surface for consistent results. A T-slot fence with featherboard channels, a starting pin, and a bit guard completes the setup. Plans for router table bases are widely available online — any stable, flat surface at a comfortable standing height works.'},{id:"ml-drill-press-table-build",topic:"Auxiliary drill press table with fence and stop",keywords:["drill","press","table","auxiliary","build","fence","stop","mdf","t-track"],answer:'An auxiliary drill press table significantly improves usability. Build from 3/4" MDF: a platform that bolts or clamps to the existing cast iron table, with a sacrificial MDF insert in the center. Mill a T-slot into the front edge for a sliding fence. Add a stop block to the fence for consistent hole positioning. A small clamp built into the fence holds workpieces for single-handed operation. The table should extend to cover the full drill press footprint. The fence must be perpendicular to the table center — check with a square before first use.'},{id:"ml-chess-board",topic:"Chess/checkerboard construction technique",keywords:["chess","checker","board","squares","contrast","glue","strip","alternating","cut"],answer:"Classic chess board construction: (1) Edge-glue alternating strips of contrasting woods (maple and walnut is classic) into a panel, trimming strips to identical width. (2) Cut the panel into strips perpendicular to the glue lines, same width as the strips. (3) Alternate and flip every other strip end-for-end to create the checker pattern. (4) Edge-glue the repositioned strips into the finished board. Add a solid wood border to frame the playing surface. The key: all strip widths must be identical (a thin rip jig helps) or the squares won't be consistent."},{id:"ml-key-cabinet",topic:"Key cabinet with hooks",keywords:["key","cabinet","hook","small","door","wall","hide","mount","organize"],answer:'A key cabinet is a small hinged-door box that mounts on the wall. Inside: a series of small hooks for keys. The door hides the keys and the box contents. Typical size: 8"×10"×3" deep. Construction: simple box with butt or miter corners, piano hinge along one side, small magnetic catch to hold closed. Hooks can be small cup hooks, bent wire, or specialty key hooks. A mirror inside the door is a useful addition. Finish to match the surrounding decor.'},{id:"ml-spice-drawer",topic:"Spice drawer — tiered for label visibility",keywords:["spice","drawer","tiered","insert","step","organize","label","see","pull","out"],answer:`Tiered spice drawer inserts raise spice jars at the back so labels on all jars are visible when the drawer is open. Build from 1/4"–3/8" plywood: a low front step and higher back steps, with divider strips between jars. The step height equals the jar height divided by the number of tiers — for 3" jars in a two-tier insert: front tier 0", back tier 1.5". Size the drawer insert to the drawer's inner dimensions, or build it as a removable tray insert. This simple shop project dramatically improves kitchen organization.`},{id:"ml-polygon-side-length",topic:"Calculating side lengths for regular polygons",keywords:["polygon","side","length","hexagon","octagon","regular","formula","radius"],answer:"For a regular n-sided polygon inscribed in a circle of radius R: side length = 2R × sin(π/n). Examples: equilateral triangle (n=3): side = R × 1.732. Square (n=4): side = R × 1.414. Hexagon (n=6): side = R (a regular hexagon has sides equal to the circumradius). Octagon (n=8): side = R × 0.765. Use this to determine how long to cut each stave for a coopered cylinder, how to size table legs for a round table, or how to cut a polygon frame from a circle template."},{id:"ml-drawer-slide-calc",topic:"Calculating drawer box dimensions for specific slides",keywords:["drawer","slide","calculate","width","height","clearance","full","extension","spec"],answer:`Drawer box sizing for common slide types: Side-mount slides (e.g., Grass, Hettich): drawer box width = cabinet opening width minus 2× slide thickness (typically 1/2" per side = 1" total). Undermount slides (e.g., Blum Tandem): drawer box width = opening width minus 1/2" (slides are inset). Bottom-mount center slides: drawer box width = opening width minus 1/4". Height clearance: typically 1/2"–5/8" below the cabinet top or bottom of adjacent drawer. Always check the specific slide manufacturer's installation sheet — specs vary by slide series and thickness.`},{id:"ml-stock-planning",topic:"Planning stock dimensions for a furniture project",keywords:["stock","planning","cut","list","thick","width","length","rough","buy","organize"],answer:'Efficient stock planning steps: (1) Write a complete cut list with all parts and final dimensions. (2) Group parts by thickness (all 3/4" parts together, etc.). (3) For each thickness group, organize by width. (4) Calculate board feet needed per group plus 20% waste. (5) Plan which parts can be cut from the same board (matching grain, same length). (6) Write a "shopping list" by thickness and total board feet. This prevents the common situation of buying wood and running out of one thickness while having excess of another.'},{id:"ml-protective-eyewear",topic:"Eye protection — safety glasses vs goggles vs face shield",keywords:["eye","protection","safety","glasses","goggles","face","shield","ansi","Z87"],answer:"Safety glasses provide front and side impact protection — adequate for most woodworking. Goggles seal around the eyes for protection against fine dust and chemical splash — better for turning, routing, and finishing spray. Face shields protect the entire face but must be worn over safety glasses (they don't seal around the eyes). All eye protection for the shop should be rated ANSI Z87.1 for impact resistance. Regular prescription glasses are not safety rated — add safety glass clip-ons or over-glasses if you wear prescription lenses."},{id:"ml-shop-apron",topic:"Shop apron function and selection",keywords:["apron","shop","protect","leather","canvas","pocket","safety","clothing"],answer:"A leather or heavy canvas shop apron protects against flying chips, minor burns, and abrasions. It provides tool pockets for frequently-used chisels, marking tools, and pencils — keeping them accessible and off the bench. Avoid loose apron strings near spinning tools — tie them short or use a roll-up design. A leather apron resists sparks from grinding and is more durable than canvas. Keep the apron clean of accumulated oily residue (spontaneous combustion risk). The apron should be snug enough not to flap near tool blades or bits."},{id:"ml-shop-safety-children",topic:"Workshop safety when children are present",keywords:["child","children","safety","supervise","tool","lock","switch","danger","zone"],answer:"When children are present in the shop: lock all power tools with a lockout key or padlock on the power switch. Store chisels, saws, and other sharp hand tools locked away. Never allow children near machines that are running — the distraction alone is a safety hazard. For supervised child participation: start with hand tool projects (simple cutting and assembly) away from power tools. Never leave a child alone in the shop even for a minute. A child-sized work apron, eye protection, and ear protection (child-sized versions are available) should be standard if any tool use is planned."},{id:"ml-router-bit-failure",topic:"Router bit failure — causes and prevention",keywords:["router","bit","failure","break","chip","carbide","speed","overload","cheap"],answer:"Router bit failure (a carbide tip fracturing or the bit shearing at the shank) can cause a catastrophic safety incident — carbide fragments at high speed are extremely dangerous. Causes: running bits too fast for their diameter; taking too heavy a cut; using cheap bits with inferior brazing; a collet that doesn't grip the full shank length; a bent or unbalanced bit. Prevention: use quality bits (Freud, CMT, Whiteside); inspect bits before use for chips, cracks, or buildup; use the correct speed for the bit diameter; keep bits properly tensioned in the collet. Discard any bit with a visible chip in the carbide."},{id:"ml-saw-blade-storage",topic:"Storing saw blades safely between uses",keywords:["saw","blade","store","protect","hang","rust","tooth","plastic","sleeve"],answer:"Store saw blades in their original plastic sleeves or in fabric blade wallets — bare blades stacked in a drawer chip each other's teeth and are dangerous to retrieve by hand. Hang blades on wall hooks between uses. Wipe blades with a light oil before storage to prevent rust — rust in the plate causes expansion that can warp the blade. Remove pitch buildup with blade cleaner after every 10–15 hours of use — pitch buildup causes burning and puts extra stress on the motor. Never reach into a cabinet or drawer for a bare blade by feel."}],g=[{id:"mm-bench-vise-quick-release",topic:"Quick release vise mechanism — how it works",keywords:["quick","release","vise","mechanism","disengage","fast","adjust","width"],answer:"Quick-release vises have a half-nut mechanism that disengages the main screw from the nut — allowing the jaw to slide freely to the approximate width, then re-engage and tighten with just a fraction of a turn. A quarter-turn back on the screw disengages the half-nut; turning forward re-engages it. This allows instant repositioning without spinning the handle through the full range. Older Record and Stanley vises use this mechanism; modern Bessey, Lie-Nielsen, and Benchcrafted vises have similar mechanisms but with different geometry. Always re-engage fully before tightening or the half-nut can be damaged."},{id:"mm-pipe-clamp-alignment",topic:"Pipe clamp parallel bar for non-racking glue-ups",keywords:["pipe","clamp","parallel","bar","attachment","non-rack","panel","add","accessory"],answer:"Pipe clamps rack panels out of flat because the upper and lower jaw don't stay in the same vertical plane — the jaw rotates as you tighten. Add pipe clamp parallel bar accessories (extenders that clip to both jaws to make them stay parallel) or simply alternate clamps above and below. Another approach: use parallel jaw clamps (Bessey K-Body) which are inherently non-racking. For long panel glue-ups where you must use pipe clamps, place a flat caul bar across the clamps perpendicular to them — the caul resists the jaw rotation and keeps the panel in plane."},{id:"mm-clamp-rack",topic:"Clamp storage rack designs",keywords:["clamp","storage","rack","wall","pipe","bar","parallel","organize","hang"],answer:'Clamp storage must be accessible and organized by type. Wall-mounted horizontal rails (pairs of horizontal dowels or pipe flanges spaced 16" apart) hold bar and pipe clamps by their bars. Pipe clamps hang vertically on hooks through the pipe. F-clamps hang on a horizontal rail by their sliding bars. Spring clamps live in a bin. Parallel jaw clamps are bulky — a dedicated shelf or vertical slot rack works. Group clamps by type so you can grab the right one quickly. Store clamps with the screw mechanism closed to maintain the thread over time.'},{id:"mm-crosscut-sled-stop-blocks",topic:"Crosscut sled stop block system for multiple lengths",keywords:["crosscut","sled","stop","block","multiple","flip","length","production","setting"],answer:"A flip-down stop block system on a crosscut sled allows production cutting of multiple lengths without re-clamping. Multiple stop blocks at different lengths are mounted to a common rail — flip down the one you want, cut, flip it up, and the next cut is at a different length. Commercial T-track stop blocks allow infinite adjustment along the fence. For a run of identical pieces, glue a stop block to a strip of MDF clamped to the sled fence — mark its position in pencil so it can be repositioned accurately next session. Consistent stop block contact is essential — always push the stock firmly against the stop before cutting."},{id:"mm-corner-clamp",topic:"Corner clamps for picture frames and boxes",keywords:["corner","clamp","picture","frame","box","right","angle","hold","glue"],answer:"Corner clamps hold two pieces at an exact 90° angle while glue cures — indispensable for picture frames, drawer corners, and box glue-ups. Models range from simple plastic spring-loaded versions (Bessey) to heavy cast versions with screw-adjustable jaws (Woodpeckers). The critical alignment: the inside corner must be exactly 90°, not just the clamp's rated angle. Check with a square after clamping. For picture frames, use a band clamp plus corner protectors to pull all four corners tight simultaneously rather than clamping one corner at a time."},{id:"mm-glue-joint-jigging",topic:"Jigging edge glue-ups for consistent alignment",keywords:["jig","edge","glue","up","align","straight","biscuit","fence","reference"],answer:"For edge glue-ups that must be dead flat, work on a known-flat reference surface (a torsion-box assembly table or a reliable flat bench). Clamp a straight fence along one edge to keep all boards aligned. Alternate clamps above and below. Use biscuits only for alignment (not strength) — they prevent the boards from slipping sideways as clamps are tightened. The real key to flat panels: joint the edges perfectly (the No.7 plane or jointer) so there are no gaps before clamping. Clamp pressure can't close a gap; it only pulls boards laterally, not vertically into alignment."},{id:"mm-garden-bench",topic:"Garden bench construction with dowel back slats",keywords:["garden","bench","seat","back","slat","dowel","round","tenon","outdoor","cedar"],answer:'A simple garden bench has: a seat of two or three 2×4 planks; two legs and back posts (2×4 or 2×6) at each end; a cross stretcher; and optional back slats. Back slats can be through-bolted to the back posts, dadoed into them, or mortised with round tenons on a lathe. Cedar, teak, or pressure-treated lumber for all structural members. Stainless or galvanized fasteners throughout. The seat slats should have 1/4"–3/8" gaps between them for drainage and airflow. Round all exposed edges with a roundover router bit — sharp edges on outdoor furniture splinter over time.'},{id:"mm-floating-shelf-cleats",topic:"Floating shelf with concealed wooden cleats",keywords:["floating","shelf","cleat","wooden","concealed","French","dovetail","route","slot"],answer:`Concealed wooden cleats mount to the wall; the shelf has a matching routed slot that slides over the cleat from the front. The dovetail-style cleat (tapered or angled) locks as the shelf slides in and can't be pulled forward without sliding it off sideways. Cut the cleat and matching slot with a router and a straightedge guide. The cleat must be level, and the slot in the shelf must match the cleat width exactly — even 1/16" too tight will prevent the shelf from seating. This approach hides all mounting hardware without any visible screws or brackets.`},{id:"mm-bar-cabinet",topic:"Bar cabinet (liquor cabinet) design",keywords:["bar","cabinet","liquor","wine","glass","bottle","rack","overhead","storage"],answer:'A bar cabinet typically has: bottle storage in the base (adjustable dividers or bottle wine rack), glass storage overhead (inverted glass hangers or shelves), and a pullout counter surface or drop-leaf shelf for mixing. Interior lighting (LED strip) dramatically improves the look and functionality. Overhead glass storage: route channels or dados for an inverted T-bar that glasses hang from. Bottle dividers should accommodate standard wine bottles (3.5" diameter) plus standard liquor bottles (3" diameter). A small sink (plumbed or dry bar) can be incorporated in more elaborate builds.'},{id:"mm-kids-furniture",topic:"Child-sized furniture dimensions",keywords:["children","kid","furniture","dimension","height","desk","table","chair","age"],answer:'Child furniture dimensions vary by age. Table height: age 2–4 → 18"–20"; age 5–8 → 20"–22"; age 9–12 → 24"–26". Chair seat height: 2 inches below the table height. Desk height: same as table for young children; adults: 28"–30". Toy box: 18"–24" height (accessible without tipping). Bookshelves for children: eye-level top shelf at their standing eye height. All child furniture should use rounded edges, non-toxic finishes, and no small-part hardware that could be swallowed. ASTM and CPSC standards apply to commercially sold pieces but are good guides for shop-made items.'},{id:"mm-wine-glass-rack",topic:"Overhead wine glass rack construction",keywords:["wine","glass","rack","overhead","inverted","hang","stem","cabinet","slot"],answer:'An overhead wine glass rack hangs glasses upside-down by the stem in slots or channels routed in the underside of a shelf or cabinet bottom. The slot width should match the stem diameter plus a small clearance (typically 3/8"–1/2" wide, 3/4" deep). Route parallel channels with spacing matching the glass bowl diameter plus 1/2" clearance. Glasses hang by the rim resting on the wood on either side of the slot while the stem passes through. For larger glasses, use a grid of routed channels in both directions for a more secure hold. Mount it in a bar cabinet, under an upper cabinet, or as a standalone ceiling-mount piece.'},{id:"mm-platform-bed",topic:"Platform bed with slat base construction",keywords:["platform","bed","slat","base","low","profile","modern","storage","mattress"],answer:'Platform beds sit lower to the ground (typically 8"–12" total height) and support a mattress directly on a slat or solid base. Slat construction: 2.5"–4" wide hardwood slats (poplar, pine) spaced 3" maximum to fully support the mattress. Slats should flex slightly but not sag. For a king bed, a center support rail running lengthwise from headboard to foot, with a center leg to the floor, prevents slat deflection. Platform beds with storage drawers below use a taller case (18"–22") with full-extension drawer slides in the base structure.'},{id:"mm-headboard",topic:"Headboard construction and wall mounting",keywords:["headboard","mount","wall","upholster","panel","attach","height","above","mattress"],answer:'A simple wood-panel headboard mounts directly to the wall or to a floor-standing frame attached to the bed frame. Wall-mount headboards should be anchored into studs — a headboard catches pillows and occasional leaning, applying side-to-side forces. Top of headboard: 20"–30" above the finished mattress height is typical for a standard headboard. Upholstered headboards: build a plywood panel, glue on 2"–3" foam, wrap in batting, and staple fabric to the back. For tall statement headboards (72"+), anchor at top and bottom into studs.'},{id:"mm-breakfast-bar",topic:"Kitchen breakfast bar overhang dimensions",keywords:["breakfast","bar","overhang","counter","knee","clearance","stool","height","dimension"],answer:`Kitchen breakfast bar dimensions depend on stool height. Counter height (36"): standard bar stools, 12"–15" overhang for knee room. Bar height (42"): tall bar stools, 12" overhang minimum. For seated knee clearance: the overhang must extend at least 12" from the supporting cabinet face. Counter top thickness: 1.5"–4" depending on material (laminate: 1.5"; butcher block: 2"–3"; concrete or stone: 2"–4"). Support the overhang with corbels or knee braces for overhangs beyond 12" that will carry sitting load — the substrate alone can't canteliver a heavy stone top more than a few inches.`},{id:"mm-dollhouse",topic:"Dollhouse construction — scale and materials",keywords:["dollhouse","scale","1:12","miniature","plywood","thin","construction","paint"],answer:'Standard dollhouse scale is 1:12 (one inch = one foot). For 1:12 scale, 1/8"–1/4" plywood simulates full walls and floors realistically. Construction uses the same joints as full-size cabinetry but at miniature scale: dados, rabbets, and small nails or wood glue. Windows and doors can be purchased as pre-made laser-cut sets. Lightweight materials (balsa for trim, thin plywood for structure) make the house manageable. Paint interiors before assembly — access becomes impossible in corners once assembled. A classic 12-room dollhouse is a multi-year project; start with a simple 4-room version.'},{id:"mm-workshop-cabinet",topic:"Shop storage cabinet — maximizing efficiency",keywords:["shop","storage","cabinet","drawer","bin","shallow","hardware","organize","workshop"],answer:`A shop storage cabinet for hardware and supplies should have many shallow drawers (2"–3" high) rather than a few deep ones — small items in deep drawers are impossible to find. Plan: 8–12 shallow drawers for hardware (screws, nails, bolts sorted by size); 4–6 medium drawers (4"–6") for larger hardware, tape, measuring tools; 2–3 deep drawers or doors for bulk supplies. Label every drawer on the front. Drawer boxes in shop cabinets don't need the finishing quality of furniture drawers — simple dado-joined plywood boxes that glide smoothly serve perfectly well.`},{id:"mm-crib-safety",topic:"Baby crib and toddler bed safety requirements",keywords:["crib","baby","toddler","safety","rail","space","standard","entrapment","finish"],answer:'CPSC crib standards are strict and non-negotiable for baby safety. Key requirements: slat spacing maximum 2-3/8" to prevent entrapment of head; no lead paint or toxic finishes; no drop-side rails (banned in US since 2011); mattress height adjustable; corner posts no higher than 1/16" above the end panels (loose clothing catch risk). For a shop-made crib, purchase and conform to CPSC standards meticulously — a non-compliant crib is a serious safety risk. Many woodworkers choose to build a toddler bed instead (for children over 15 months) where standards are less strict.'},{id:"mm-log-bench",topic:"Simple log bench from a halved tree trunk",keywords:["log","bench","half","trunk","chainsaw","slab","leg","rustic","simple"],answer:"The simplest bench is a log halved lengthwise with a chainsaw or portable band mill — flat face up, bark face down (or bark retained as a design element). Legs can be round branches with angled socket holes drilled into the underside (staked bench), or the log can be supported by two solid end pieces set in deep mortises. A staked log bench: drill four angled holes into the flat face at each corner, shape round tenons on straight branches, and drive them home. Green log benches shrink as they dry, tightening the leg joints. An enduring rustic garden piece."},{id:"mm-saw-blade-selection",topic:"Choosing the correct saw blade for the material",keywords:["saw","blade","material","aluminum","non","ferrous","wood","laminate","correct"],answer:"Using the wrong blade for the material causes binding, burning, and dangerous kickback. Wood ripping: 24–40 ATB or FTG teeth. Plywood and crosscuts: 60–80 ATB teeth. Aluminum and non-ferrous metals: specific aluminum-cutting blade with negative hook angle and no-climb feed. MDF and composite: triple-chip grind (TCG) blades reduce edge chipping. Laminate (HPL) and melamine: 80+ tooth TCG blade. Never use a wood blade on metal — the teeth shatter; never use a metal blade on dry wood — it burns and binds. Always check that the blade's rated RPM exceeds your saw's no-load RPM."},{id:"mm-extension-cord-safety",topic:"Extension cord selection for power tools",keywords:["extension","cord","gauge","AWG","length","amps","power","tool","undersized"],answer:"Undersized extension cords cause voltage drop that overloads motor windings, creating heat and premature motor failure. Minimum cord gauge by tool amperage and length: up to 15 amps, up to 25 feet: 14 AWG. Up to 15 amps, 25–50 feet: 12 AWG. Up to 15 amps, 50–100 feet: 10 AWG. Table saws and planers draw 12–15 amps at full load — always use 12 AWG or thicker, and keep cords as short as practical. Never use a cord with a damaged jacket — replace it before use. Three-prong (grounded) cords are mandatory for all power tools."},{id:"mm-kickback-stance",topic:"Correct stance at the table saw to avoid kickback injury",keywords:["kickback","stance","position","body","table","saw","side","injury","zone"],answer:"The kickback danger zone at a table saw is directly behind the blade in a narrow arc extending rearward. Stand to the left of the blade line for right-handed rip cuts — your body is out of the danger zone. For crosscuts (using a miter gauge or sled), stand to either side of the blade, not directly behind it. Never lean over the top of the blade to reach for an offcut. Keep your left arm behind your body rather than extended toward the blade when feeding narrow stock. After any cut where a piece becomes small enough to possibly bounce back, step to the side before reaching for it."},{id:"mm-carbon-monoxide",topic:"Carbon monoxide hazard from combustion heaters",keywords:["carbon","monoxide","CO","detector","heater","propane","combustion","shop","detector"],answer:"Combustion heaters (propane forced-air, natural gas radiant) in enclosed shops produce carbon monoxide — an odorless, colorless, potentially fatal gas. CO accumulates in unventilated spaces faster than is detectable by smell. Install a CO detector in any shop with a combustion heater — mounted at breathing height (CO is slightly lighter than air). Ensure fresh air ventilation is adequate for the heater's BTU rating; most heaters require specific CFM of outside air. Battery-powered CO detectors are recommended over plug-in models in shops where power may be unreliable."},{id:"mm-spokeshave-concave",topic:"Round-soled spokeshave for concave curves",keywords:["spokeshave","round","sole","concave","hollow","chair","seat","back"],answer:"The round-soled spokeshave has a convex sole that works inside concave curves — the curve of the sole follows the hollow rather than bridging it the way a flat-soled spokeshave would. Use it on the inside of chair back curves, the inside of bent forms, and any concave surface too curved for a flat tool to reach without the corners catching. The round-soled type takes some practice to set — adjust the iron for very light cuts and test on scrap until you understand how the curved sole affects the cutting action."},{id:"mm-marking-gauge-set",topic:"Setting a marking gauge accurately",keywords:["marking","gauge","set","accurate","ruler","measurement","repeat","lock"],answer:"Setting a marking gauge from a ruler: hold the ruler vertically with the end on a flat surface; set the marking pin to the desired measurement against the ruler face; tighten the fence lock. A better method: set from a reference piece — hold the fence against the reference, adjust the pin to touch the opposite face, and lock. This takes the dimension directly from the work rather than from a ruler, eliminating any ruler-reading error. Always verify by scribing a test line on scrap and checking it with a caliper before scribing the actual workpiece."},{id:"mm-chamfer-handplane",topic:"Cutting chamfers and bevels by hand",keywords:["chamfer","bevel","hand","plane","block","angle","45","consistent","guide"],answer:"A block plane creates chamfers on edges easily and quickly. For consistent 45° chamfers, sight by eye (the reflection in the blade should show equal amounts of the top and side face) or use a simple guide — a piece of wood with a 45° surface that rides on both faces simultaneously. Start the chamfer with a light pass to establish the angle; check it; adjust if needed; then take progressive passes to the desired width. A scratch gauge (mortise gauge) set to the chamfer width scribes both faces to give a target width line to work to."},{id:"mm-hand-plane-lateral",topic:"Lateral adjustment of a bench plane iron",keywords:["lateral","adjust","plane","iron","skew","straight","shaving","width","even"],answer:"The lateral adjustment lever on a bench plane moves the iron sideways — correcting skew so the cutting edge is parallel to the sole and produces even-width shavings across the full width. Look down the sole from the toe with the plane bottom-up: adjust until the iron shows as a thin, perfectly even sliver across the full mouth opening. An iron skewed too far one way produces shavings only on one side of the cut, leaving ridges. Test on scrap and check that shavings come from both sides of the blade simultaneously before starting on good material."},{id:"mm-chisel-paring-direction",topic:"Paring chisel direction for clean cuts",keywords:["paring","direction","grain","chisel","with","against","clean","slice","control"],answer:"Pare with the grain whenever possible — the chisel slices cleanly along fiber direction. When paring across the grain (as at a dovetail baseline), the knife wall severs the fibers first; the chisel then clears the waste. Paring end grain requires very sharp chisels and steady hand pressure — the fibers run directly into the blade. For dovetail corners: pare from both sides toward the center of the corner to prevent the chisel from splintering the far corner. Never extend the cutting hand past the chisel edge in any direction the chisel could plunge if it slips."},{id:"mm-gouge-carving-technique",topic:"Carving gouge technique — push and mallet",keywords:["gouge","carve","push","mallet","cut","relief","depth","direction","grain"],answer:"Carving gouges are driven either by hand push (for fine detail and finishing cuts) or a mallet (for roughing and setting-in). For mallet work: hold the gouge at a steeper angle (more perpendicular to the surface) and drive with short controlled strokes. For hand-push paring: hold at a lower angle (more parallel to the surface) and use your shoulder and body weight for control rather than just wrist pressure. Always cut down-grain (the wood fibers slope away from the cut direction). Avoid cutting up-grain — it lifts fibers and tears the surface rather than slicing clean."},{id:"mm-handsaw-track",topic:"Keeping a handsaw tracking straight",keywords:["handsaw","track","straight","drift","guide","accurate","control","tilt"],answer:"A handsaw that drifts sideways is usually dull or has uneven set (teeth bent more one side than the other). On a fresh saw: start with the blade perfectly vertical using the reflection in the side of the blade as a guide; small corrections early are much easier than correcting a deep drifted cut. A bench hook provides a right-angle edge to register the saw against. For a perfectly straight cut in thick material, a saw guide (a clamped hardwood block with a kerf) keeps the saw vertical and on line for the full depth of the cut."},{id:"mm-design-sketch",topic:"Sketching furniture designs before building",keywords:["sketch","design","drawing","perspective","plan","elevation","orthographic","idea"],answer:`Sketch furniture designs in orthographic views (front, side, and top) at a consistent scale — 1"=1' or 1/2"=1'. Orthographic drawings reveal proportional errors that perspective sketches hide. Add key dimensions (overall height, width, depth; leg size; shelf spacing; door size) to each view. A plan view (top down) helps with leg placement and apron clearances. After the orthographic layout, do a perspective sketch for the client presentation or your own visualization. SketchUp (free version) works well for 3D furniture design without architectural CAD background. DoveDesign handles this natively in 3D.`},{id:"mm-pull-placement",topic:"Door and drawer pull placement for visual consistency",keywords:["pull","placement","door","drawer","consistent","visual","center","offset","line"],answer:'On cabinet doors: pulls on face-frame overlay doors are typically centered on the stile at a height of 1/3 from the top or bottom. On inset doors: centered in the stile at the same height. Drawer pulls: always centered left-to-right; on narrow drawers, centered top-to-bottom; on tall drawers, placed at the top 1/3 for easy one-finger-pull open. All pulls in a run of cabinets should be at the same height from the same datum (cabinet top or floor) for visual consistency. A drill jig made from 1/4" hardboard ensures all pull holes land in exactly the same position on every door and drawer.'},{id:"mm-shadow-lines",topic:"Creating shadow lines in furniture for visual depth",keywords:["shadow","line","reveal","setback","depth","detail","visual","interest","inset"],answer:'Shadow lines are small recesses or setbacks that create dark lines of shadow on a surface — adding visual depth and interest without physical decoration. A drawer face set 1/8" back from surrounding face frame creates a subtle shadow line all around. A panel set 3/16" back from a surrounding frame creates a line that reads as defined and crisp from across a room. A back-beveled edge (a very slight chamfer on the back of an edge that sets it back from the adjacent surface) creates a thin shadow line that looks much more finished than a simple square edge. These details are "the difference" in high-quality furniture design.'},{id:"mm-furniture-hardware-finish",topic:"Matching hardware finish to wood species",keywords:["hardware","finish","brass","oil","bronze","nickel","chrome","oil","rub","match"],answer:"Hardware finish should complement the wood's warmth and color. Warm woods (walnut, cherry): oil-rubbed bronze, antique brass, unlacquered brass (will patina). Cool or light woods (maple, ash, white oak): brushed nickel, satin stainless, matte black. Dark woods (ebony, wenge): polished chrome, satin nickel, or contrast with brass. Mid-century modern: brushed gold, matte brass. Shaker and Arts & Crafts: hand-forged iron, rubbed bronze, simple wood knobs. Mixed metal rules: it's fine to mix warm and cool metals if they're different finishes (e.g., brass pulls + nickel hinges) — never mix two of the same metal in different finishes."},{id:"mm-cut-list-marking",topic:"Efficient cut list marking and stock layout",keywords:["cut","list","mark","layout","stock","triangle","waste","side","pencil","knife"],answer:"Efficient cut list layout: (1) Mark the reference face (face side) and reference edge on each rough board before milling. (2) After milling, lay out all parts from the cut list on the surfaced board before cutting anything. (3) Mark the saw line on the waste side. (4) Mark each part with its label (rail, leg, stile) before cutting — parts look identical before cut and can be confused. (5) Cut longest parts first. (6) Mark the waste area with an X to prevent accidentally cutting on the wrong side of the line. A well-marked board takes 5 minutes at the bench and prevents expensive cutting errors."},{id:"mm-fitting-drawer-by-hand",topic:"Fitting a drawer to its opening by hand",keywords:["drawer","fit","hand","plane","shave","snug","slide","smooth","open","close"],answer:"Fitting a hand-fit drawer: the box should enter the opening with slight resistance and no racking. Check all four corners of the face for the same small gap. A drawer that binds on one side: lightly plane that side; check fit again. A drawer that's too high: plane the top edge. Too much side-to-side slop: add a thin wood shim to the inside of the drawer side. The final fit should slide in smoothly with light hand pressure and stop flush. Wax the drawer bottom edges and runners for easy sliding. Over-fitting (planing too much) results in a sloppy drawer that's difficult to put back."},{id:"mm-troubleshoot-no4-plane",topic:"Troubleshooting a No.4 plane that won't cut well",keywords:["no4","plane","troubleshoot","dull","chatter","tearout","set","fix","adjust"],answer:'Checklist for a No.4 plane that cuts poorly: (1) Is the iron sharp? Dull irons produce dust, not shavings. (2) Is the cap iron/chip breaker set too far back from the edge? Bring it to 1/16"–1/32" for smooth work. (3) Is the mouth too open? Close the frog. (4) Is the sole flat? Check with a reliable straightedge. (5) Is the chip breaker seating fully against the iron (no gap that chips can lift into)? (6) Are you planing against the grain? Reverse direction. (7) Is the iron centered laterally? Adjust with the lateral lever. Address these in order — #1 (sharpness) is responsible for 80% of all plane problems.'},{id:"mm-chiseling-hinge",topic:"Chiseling a perfect hinge mortise by hand",keywords:["hinge","mortise","chisel","hand","precise","knife","wall","clean","corner"],answer:"Perfect hand-chiseled hinge mortise technique: (1) Scribe the outline with a marking knife using the hinge as a template. (2) Chop just inside the knife line with a bench chisel to sever fibers. (3) Pare the waste away in thin layers starting from the center; work toward the knife line. (4) Use a wide chisel to pare the bottom flat — ride the chisel bevel-up for a flat bottom. (5) Test-fit the hinge; it should sit perfectly flush. Common mistakes: setting the chisel on the knife line and widening the mortise; removing too much at once; not checking flatness of the bottom."},{id:"mm-wood-carving-tools",topic:"Essential carving tool starter set",keywords:["carving","tool","set","starter","essential","gouge","v-tool","chip","sweep"],answer:"A practical starter carving set: a #2 sweep straight gouge (flat, wide — for background removal and flattening); a #5 or #6 sweep medium gouge (the workhorse for most carving tasks); a #9 deep sweep bent gouge (for deep hollows and relief backgrounds); a #11 or #12 veiner (narrow deep U-gouge for outlining and veins); and a V-parting tool (#12 60° for straight lines and outlining). This set handles 80% of chip carving, relief carving, and letter carving. Add specialized tools (long-bent, fishtail, spoon gouge) only when a specific project demands them."},{id:"mm-tool-buying-strategy",topic:"Tool buying strategy — buy once buy good",keywords:["tool","buy","quality","once","cheap","good","invest","starter","priority"],answer:'The "buy once, buy good" rule: cheap tools are often false economy — they rust quickly, hold edges poorly, break at critical moments, and are often less safe due to poor construction. Priority for investment: sharpening equipment (a good stone set lasts decades); at least one quality bench plane; one quality chisel set. Everything else: buy mid-tier (Stanley, Lee Valley, Narex), not the cheapest and not the premium. Power tools: mid-tier is usually excellent (DeWalt, Bosch, Makita). Buy used quality tools rather than cheap new tools — a vintage Stanley No.5 that needs cleaning beats a new $30 import every time.'},{id:"mm-starting-wood-selection",topic:"Wood selection advice for beginning woodworkers",keywords:["beginner","wood","select","start","species","easy","forgiving","poplar","pine"],answer:"For beginners: poplar is the best all-around starter hardwood — inexpensive, machines cleanly, takes paint, holds screws well, and is available everywhere. Pine is good for learning hand tools (soft, easy to work) but tears out easily under machines. Soft maple is a good alternative to poplar with a nicer natural color. Avoid starting with figured hardwoods (curly maple, walnut with wild grain) — they're expensive when mistakes happen and challenging to surface without tearout. Save the expensive, beautiful species for projects after you've built confidence with more forgiving woods."}],w=[{id:"mn-steam-bending-setup",topic:"Steam bending setup and technique",keywords:["steam","bend","setup","steam","box","form","time","moisture","species","radius"],answer:"Steam bending requires: a steam box (sealed wooden chamber with a steam source), bending forms (the shape to bend around), and bending straps (metal strap to support the outer fibers in compression during bending). Steam time: typically 1 hour per inch of thickness. Bend quickly — the wood is pliable for only a few minutes after leaving the box. Clamp firmly to the form and leave until fully dry (24–72 hours). Best species for steam bending: white ash, hickory, white oak, cherry, elm. Poor benders: maple, pine, walnut, plywood."},{id:"mn-finishing-walnut-dark",topic:"How to keep walnut looking dark after finishing",keywords:["walnut","dark","finish","lighten","gray","bleach","oil","preserve","color"],answer:"Freshly sanded walnut is darker than it will look after a few weeks with light exposure — it lightens to gray-brown. To maximize dark color: apply an oil finish (danish oil or tung oil) which deepens the brown tones. Avoid water-based poly which can make walnut look grayish or greenish. Avoid heavy sanding past 150 grit which burnishes the surface and alters color absorption. Oil or wiping varnish deepens and enriches walnut color better than any water-based product. The color will stabilize after a few weeks of exposure regardless of finish."},{id:"mn-breadboard-slot-peg",topic:"Breadboard end slot and peg construction details",keywords:["breadboard","slot","peg","elongate","center","glue","only","middle","one","peg"],answer:"A breadboard end (a cross-grain cap on a tabletop end) requires careful construction to allow movement. Attach the breadboard with a tongue-and-groove or series of mortise-and-tenon joints. Glue only the center joint — all other connections must allow movement. Elongate the outer tenon mortises or peg holes parallel to the tabletop grain direction, allowing the top to move while keeping the breadboard aligned. Pegs (wooden pins through the joint) pass through elongated holes in the top; only the center peg hole is round and tight. A common error: gluing all pegs, which cracks the top at the breadboard joint within a season."},{id:"mn-wainscoting-install",topic:"Installing wood wainscoting panels",keywords:["wainscoting","install","wall","panel","chair","rail","base","cap","level"],answer:'Wainscoting installation steps: (1) Find level reference lines for the chair rail height (typically 32"–36") and mark around the room with a level. (2) Install the base (bottom) rail using the existing baseboard or a new base rail. (3) Install vertical stiles (every 16"–24") plumbed and fastened to studs. (4) Float the panels in place (not glued). (5) Install the chair rail cap on top. Pre-finish the wainscoting before installation for easier painting of edges. Acclimate the wood panels in the room for at least a week before installation to reduce movement after installation.'},{id:"mn-cove-cut-table-saw",topic:"Cove cuts on the table saw",keywords:["cove","cut","table","saw","auxiliary","fence","angle","slow","feed","radius"],answer:"A table saw cove cut produces a concave rounded profile by running the workpiece diagonally across the blade. An auxiliary angled fence (a board clamped to the table at the desired angle) guides the workpiece at an angle to the blade, and each slow pass removes a small amount until the cove depth is reached. The profile width and depth depend on the angle and depth of cut. This is a dangerous operation requiring slow feed rates and light passes — never force a cove cut. Clean saw marks with a curved scraper or sandpaper wrapped around a matching radius dowel."},{id:"mn-template-half",topic:"Making half-templates for symmetrical parts",keywords:["half","template","symmetrical","trace","flip","accurate","consistent","leg","bracket"],answer:'For symmetrical parts (chair legs, bracket feet, apron profiles), make only a half-template — trace it on the stock, flip it over the centerline, and trace again to get the perfectly symmetrical full profile. This guarantees the two halves are identical and eliminates asymmetry introduced by freehand drawing. Make the template from 1/4" MDF or hardboard; cut accurately with a scroll saw or jigsaw and sand smooth. One half-template also takes up less storage space than a full template and works for both the left and right mirror-image halves of an asymmetric piece.'},{id:"mn-raised-panel",topic:"Raised panel router bit operation",keywords:["raised","panel","router","bit","solid","large","slow","speed","profile","door"],answer:'Panel-raising bits (cope-and-stick panel raisers) are large-diameter bits (2.5"–3") that produce the raised field on a door panel. They require slower router speeds (10,000–12,000 RPM maximum) because the large diameter produces very high rim speed at normal RPM. Feed direction: always against the bit rotation (conventional). Make multiple passes: first a climb cut (light) to prevent tearout on cross-grain areas at panel ends; then one or two conventional passes to full profile depth. Solid-wood panel must float in the door frame — never glue it into the groove.'},{id:"mn-half-blind-dovetail-layout",topic:"Laying out half-blind dovetails precisely",keywords:["half","blind","dovetail","layout","depth","front","wall","mark","gauge","sequence"],answer:'Half-blind dovetail layout sequence: (1) Mark the drawer front thickness on the tail board — this is the baseline for the tails. (2) Set a marking gauge to the front wall thickness (typically 3/16"–1/4") and mark the depth line on the tail board end grain and pin board front face. (3) Lay out tails on the tail board end, angle and space as desired. (4) Saw the tails; chop the baseline. (5) Transfer the tail positions to the pin board by setting the tail board on the pin board end and scribing. (6) Saw the pins; chop the waste carefully without breaking through the front face. The front wall makes this joint significantly more difficult than a through dovetail.'},{id:"mn-hand-cut-tenon",topic:"Hand-cut tenon — saw sequence and fitting",keywords:["tenon","hand","cut","saw","sequence","shoulder","cheek","fit","mortise","trim"],answer:"Hand-cut tenon sequence: (1) Mark all four shoulder lines with a marking knife. (2) Scribe the cheek lines with a mortise gauge set to the mortise width. (3) Saw the shoulder cuts just to the knife line (cross-grain cuts, with a bench hook). (4) Saw the cheek cuts from the end with a rip saw or wide backsaw, staying on the waste side of the line. (5) Check fit in the mortise — if tight, pare the cheeks with a shoulder plane or router plane until the fit is snug. (6) Saw the haunch if required. Work to fit the mortise you actually cut, not a theoretical dimension."},{id:"mn-frame-panel-door-sequence",topic:"Frame-and-panel door assembly sequence",keywords:["frame","panel","door","assembly","sequence","float","glue","dry","clamp","stile"],answer:'Frame-and-panel door assembly sequence: (1) Cut all rails and stiles to final length. (2) Rout the groove in all frame members. (3) Cut the haunched tenons on the rails and fit to the stile mortises (dry). (4) Cut the panel to size — allow movement (1/8" per foot of panel width, both directions). (5) Dry-fit the entire door with the panel to check squareness and fit. (6) Apply glue only to the mortise-and-tenon joints — never to the panel or the groove. (7) Clamp, check square, and set flat. A well-built frame-and-panel door stays flat indefinitely because the panel floats freely.'},{id:"mn-router-table-edge-profile",topic:"Edge profiling sequence on the router table",keywords:["edge","profile","router","table","sequence","order","face","edge","full","partial"],answer:"Sequence for routing edge profiles on all four sides of a panel: (1) Route the two end-grain edges first (cross-grain, higher tearout risk). (2) Route the two long-grain edges. This order means any tearout at the end of the end-grain cuts is cleaned up by the subsequent long-grain cuts. If you route long-grain first, tearout at the corners on the end-grain pass is still visible. Keep the bit below final height and take two passes: a light first pass at 2/3 depth, then a final pass at full depth. This reduces tearout and load on the bit."},{id:"mn-turning-hollow-form",topic:"Hollow form turning on the lathe",keywords:["hollow","form","turning","vase","inside","tool","hollowing","light","thin","wall"],answer:`Hollow form turning (closed-top vessels) uses long curved hollowing tools that can reach inside through a small opening. The challenge: you can't see the interior, so you feel the cuts and use a wall-thickness gauge to check thickness. Work in concentric circles from the inside out, taking light cuts. The opening must be just large enough for the tool clearance — typically 1"–2". Use a catch box or rest at the opening to control the tool. A digital wall thickness caliper reads the thickness through the wood wall using magnets. Remove the tailstock support once the outside is shaped and the wall is thin enough for completion.`},{id:"mn-pen-turning",topic:"Pen turning on the lathe — basics",keywords:["pen","turning","lathe","blank","tube","bushings","kit","mandrel","assemble"],answer:"Pen turning requires a lathe, pen turning mandrel, pen blanks (wood or acrylic), and a pen kit (hardware). Process: drill the blank to tube diameter, press in brass tubes with CA glue, mount on mandrel with matching bushings, turn to match bushing diameter, sand through fine grits, apply finish (CA glue polish is the fastest), and assemble the click mechanism. Pens are an excellent project for using exotic wood offcuts too small for furniture. A pen turning kit costs $5–15; the lathe setup time once familiar is under 30 minutes per pen."},{id:"mn-router-bit-burning",topic:"Why router bits burn wood and how to prevent it",keywords:["router","bit","burn","scorch","dull","slow","feed","speed","resin","pitch"],answer:"Router bit burning happens when the bit generates too much heat. Causes: feed rate too slow (bit stays in one place too long); bit is dull or has resin buildup; RPM too high for bit diameter; too deep a cut in one pass. Fix: increase feed rate (move the router faster); clean the bit with pitch remover; reduce RPM for large bits; take multiple lighter passes. A sharp bit fed at the right rate should produce chips, not dust. Burning in pine and resinous woods happens more easily — increase feed rate and reduce depth per pass for these species."},{id:"mn-white-oak-staining",topic:"White oak staining tips and challenges",keywords:["white","oak","stain","even","open","grain","pore","absorb","conditioner"],answer:"White oak is ring-porous with large open pores in the early wood — stain absorbs heavily in the ring pores and lightly between, creating a dramatic but sometimes uneven result. For even staining, either embrace the ring-porous pattern (it looks intentional) or use gel stain which sits on the surface. The large pores can be grain-filled before staining for a uniform, closed-pore appearance. Fumed white oak (ammonia vapors) produces the most natural, even color change — the tannins react uniformly throughout the wood. Test any stain or treatment on a scrap from the same board."},{id:"mn-maple-species-selection",topic:"Selecting maple boards for consistent color in a project",keywords:["maple","select","consistent","color","creamy","white","yellow","tone","project"],answer:"Hard maple varies widely in color — from pure creamy white to yellowish to light tan. For a project that will be painted, any variation is acceptable. For natural or stained pieces, inconsistent color between boards looks jarring. Buy all maple for a project from the same tree or kiln lot at once; color consistency within a single lot is much better than between different orders. Steamed maple is more consistent in color than unsteamed. Avoid mixing western and eastern maple — the two regions produce notably different color tones that don't blend well in adjacent panels."},{id:"mn-cherry-matching",topic:"Matching cherry panels — color and grain consistency",keywords:["cherry","match","color","grain","same","lot","sequential","panel","consistency"],answer:"Cherry's color varies between boards from the same tree and varies dramatically between trees and growing regions. For a multi-panel project (kitchen doors, large tabletop), buy all the cherry from the same lot — preferably sequential boards from the same log. The color will still vary but will develop together as the patina darkens. Mismatched cherry (from different lots or different boards of wildly different initial color) produces panels that look dramatically different after patination, even if they appeared similar when purchased. Fuming cherry with ammonia can somewhat equalize initial color variation."},{id:"mn-spalt-turning",topic:"Turning spalted wood on the lathe",keywords:["spalted","turn","lathe","safe","respirator","P100","soft","stabilize","zone"],answer:"Spalted wood turning requires specific precautions. Mildly spalted wood (firm to the touch, clean zone lines) is safe to turn with a P100 respirator — the spalt fungi may still be viable in the wood. Heavily punky spalted wood is dangerous: it's structurally weak and can fly apart at lathe speed. Stabilize punky areas with penetrating epoxy before mounting. Test the blank by tapping — it should ring, not thud. Start at very low speed and increase gradually while listening and feeling for vibration. Wear full face shield plus safety glasses for spalted wood turning as an extra precaution against fragmentation."},{id:"mn-burl-turning",topic:"Turning wood burls — mounting and challenges",keywords:["burl","turn","lathe","faceplate","balance","mount","crazy","grain","void"],answer:"Burls have chaotic grain in all directions, making them spectacular for turning but challenging to work. Mount on a faceplate (not a drive spur) using lag screws into solid wood. Expect severe imbalance — start at the lowest speed setting and increase very slowly. Voids and bark inclusions are common in burls; decide whether to fill them (tinted epoxy) or leave them as natural features. The wildly interlocked grain means the tool will catch in every direction — take very light cuts and keep tools sharp and properly supported on the rest. Wear a full face shield at all times when turning burls."},{id:"mn-sap-heartwood-ratio",topic:"Sapwood vs heartwood in furniture decisions",keywords:["sapwood","heartwood","ratio","use","include","exclude","contrast","stability"],answer:"Most furniture woodworkers exclude sapwood because it often contracts differently from heartwood, is less rot-resistant in outdoor applications, and (in stained or natural-finish work) produces jarring color contrasts. However, cherry sapwood next to heartwood produces beautiful warm contrast that many designers intentionally use. Black walnut with its cream sapwood is another case where the contrast is a deliberate design element. For painted work, sapwood vs heartwood doesn't matter. For exterior use, exclude sapwood from rot-resistant species (cedar, teak) — the sapwood doesn't have the same natural preservative oils."},{id:"mn-pine-pitch-sealing",topic:"Sealing pine pitch pockets before painting",keywords:["pine","pitch","sealing","paint","shellac","primer","bleed","stain","knot"],answer:"Pine contains pitch (resin) in knots and pitch pockets that bleeds through almost any topcoat or paint if not sealed. The pitch oozes through water-based primers and paints over time, leaving yellow or brown greasy spots. Solution: seal all knots and pitch pockets with shellac primer (Zinsser BIN) before any other finish. Two coats of shellac blocks pitch and tannin reliably. Oil-based primer also blocks pitch effectively. Water-based primers do not stop pitch bleed regardless of how many coats are applied."},{id:"mn-veneered-panel-vs-solid",topic:"Veneered panel vs solid wood — when to choose each",keywords:["veneer","panel","solid","wood","choose","stable","wide","book","match","cost"],answer:"Choose veneered panels when: extreme dimensional stability is needed (computer desks, large flat doors); wide matching patterns are required (bookmatched figure impossible in solid wood at that scale); weight reduction matters; or cost of solid wood is prohibitive. Choose solid wood when: the edges will be shaped, carved, or detailed (veneer has no material to remove); repair and refinishing over decades is expected (veneer has limited sanding life); raw edges will be exposed (solid wood edges look better); or the piece will be subjected to heavy localized stress. The best furniture often combines both: solid for structure and edges, veneered panels for wide flat surfaces."},{id:"mn-stain-test-protocol",topic:"Proper stain test protocol before committing",keywords:["stain","test","protocol","scrap","same","board","dry","light","observe"],answer:"A reliable stain test: cut scrap from the same board as the project (not different scrap — species vary significantly in stain uptake). Sand to the same grit you'll use on the project. Apply the stain exactly as you will on the project (same brush or rag, same dwell time). Apply a topcoat sample over the dried stain — the topcoat changes the perceived color. Let dry completely and view under the room's actual lighting (not shop fluorescent lights). Compare to the target color. Adjust if needed — you can mix stains, add more coats, or apply a toner. Never skip this step for expensive or irreplaceable material."},{id:"mn-buying-used-tools",topic:"Buying used woodworking tools — what to check",keywords:["used","tool","buy","check","inspect","estate","flea","market","online","condition"],answer:"At estate sales and flea markets, check hand tools for: cracks in handles (deal-breaker for struck tools); severe pitting on cutting surfaces (affects sharpening time, not always a deal-breaker); completeness (missing adjusting screws or nuts may be unfindable replacements); and flatness of soles on planes (rock on a flat surface to check). For power tools: check power cord condition, run it briefly if possible and listen for bearing noise, verify the fence or guides aren't bent. Online (eBay, Craigslist): research model numbers first to avoid buying a tool that had design flaws or missing parts that are unavailable."},{id:"mn-shellac-compatibility",topic:"Shellac compatibility with all other finishes",keywords:["shellac","compatible","over","under","any","finish","universal","prime","seal"],answer:"Dewaxed shellac is the only finish that bonds reliably to everything and has everything bond to it. Apply dewaxed shellac over: wax (with some prep), unknown existing finishes, oil-soaked wood, resinous wood, tannin-rich wood. Apply dewaxed shellac under: any lacquer, any varnish, any poly (water or oil based), any paint. The one exception: waxed shellac (not dewaxed) may not accept oil-based varnishes over it reliably. Always use dewaxed shellac (Zinsser SealCoat, or flake-mixed without natural wax) when using shellac as a compatibility bridge."},{id:"mn-oily-wood-gluing",topic:"Gluing oily tropical hardwoods reliably",keywords:["oily","wood","glue","teak","cocobolo","rosewood","acetone","wipe","reliability"],answer:'Oily tropical hardwoods (teak, cocobolo, rosewood, ipe) require surface degreasing before gluing or the bond will be weak or fail entirely. Wipe both glue surfaces with acetone immediately before applying glue — "immediately" means within 2–5 minutes; oils wick back to the surface quickly. Let acetone evaporate fully (30–60 seconds) before applying adhesive. Slow-cure epoxy provides the best gap-filling and oil-penetrating bond. Two-part structural adhesives (epoxy, Weldwood plastic resin) outperform PVA on oily species. Test the bond on scrap before gluing a large assembly — a simple shear test reveals adhesion quality.'},{id:"mn-shop-built-tools",topic:"Essential shop-made tools and jigs worth building early",keywords:["shop","made","tools","jig","bench","hook","shooting","board","winding","stick"],answer:"Build these shop tools early in your woodworking journey: (1) Bench hook — holds work for crosscutting. (2) Shooting board — guides a hand plane for accurate end-grain trimming. (3) Winding sticks — reveals twist in boards. (4) Story stick for current project — eliminates repeated measuring. (5) Crosscut sled for table saw — safer and more accurate than a miter gauge. (6) Box joint jig — for clean finger joints in boxes. (7) Marking gauge (if you don't have one) — easier to make than buy in some cases. Each of these takes 1–4 hours to build and pays back that investment on the first project that uses it."},{id:"mn-moisture-content-furniture",topic:"Target moisture content for indoor furniture by climate",keywords:["moisture","content","target","indoor","furniture","climate","humid","dry","percent"],answer:"Target moisture content (MC) for interior furniture varies by climate. Dry climates (American Southwest, heated interiors): 5–7% MC. Moderate climates (most of continental US): 7–9% MC. Humid climates (Gulf Coast, Pacific Northwest): 8–11% MC. The rule: build furniture at the MC it will live at. A piece built in a humid shop (12–14% MC) that moves into a dry heated home (6% MC) will shrink 6–8% across the grain — enough to crack panels and open mortise joints. A moisture meter is a $30–150 investment that prevents much more expensive mistakes."},{id:"mn-wood-selection-grain",topic:"Grain selection for strength in specific parts",keywords:["grain","selection","strength","run","out","leg","rung","bend","resist"],answer:"For parts under bending stress (chair legs, table stretchers, tool handles), grain must run parallel to the length of the part with minimal runout. Even 5°–10° runout reduces bending strength dramatically — the fibers break across the grain rather than along it. For table legs: select straight-grained wood; reject boards where grain lines angle across the face on the edge view. For chair spindles: rift-sawn or riven (split) stock with absolutely straight grain. For tool handles (hammers, axes): use riven hickory or ash where the grain follows the handle shape without any runout."},{id:"mn-design-iteration",topic:"Iterating on furniture design through prototypes",keywords:["iterate","design","prototype","mockup","refine","try","adjust","cheap","repeat"],answer:"The best furniture comes from iterating — build a rough prototype, live with it for a few days (or seat test a chair for an hour), then refine the design before committing to quality wood. Cardboard, MDF, and cheap pine are prototype materials. Change proportions by adding or subtracting material. Testing a chair prototype ergonomically reveals comfort issues that no amount of drawing or calculation predicts. A day spent prototyping saves days of finishing and refinishing an uncomfortable or ugly piece. Professional furniture designers prototype consistently; hobbyists who skip it often have regrets."},{id:"mn-wood-selection-aesthetic",topic:"Wood selection for a complete piece — aesthetic strategy",keywords:["wood","select","aesthetic","strategy","piece","primary","secondary","contrast","grain"],answer:"Effective wood selection strategy for a complete piece: choose the primary wood first (usually the most visible, highest-grade material for tops, doors, drawer fronts). Choose a secondary wood that complements the primary in both color and grain character — poplar or soft maple for painted secondary members; maple or birch for natural secondary members in a walnut piece. Use contrasting accent species sparingly for emphasis: a single ebony edge pull on a maple box; walnut stringing on a cherry tabletop. The accent works only because it's rare — overusing contrast diminishes impact."},{id:"mn-furniture-scale-room",topic:"Furniture scale relative to the room",keywords:["scale","room","furniture","proportion","large","small","visual","ceiling","size"],answer:"Furniture should be proportioned to the room's scale. A massive dining table in a small dining room makes the room feel claustrophobic. A delicate side table in a large, high-ceilinged room disappears. The relationship between furniture height and ceiling height matters: in an 8' ceiling room, a 7' armoire feels appropriate; in a 10' ceiling room, the same armoire looks squat. The visual mass of furniture (not just physical size) determines whether it fills or overwhelms a space. Place paper or cardboard cutouts at scale in the room before building to check visual fit."},{id:"mn-bookmatching-asymmetric",topic:"Creating asymmetric bookmatching for dynamism",keywords:["bookmatching","asymmetric","dynamic","offset","half","book","match","design"],answer:"Standard bookmatching produces perfect bilateral symmetry — which can look static and formal. For a more dynamic composition: slip-match (position sequential veneer sheets at the same orientation, creating a flowing pattern that repeats but doesn't mirror); or book-match with an offset (center the book-match to one side of the panel intentionally, shifting the visual focal point). For a tabletop, an off-center book-match focal point creates visual movement where a centered match might look overly formal."},{id:"mn-cabinet-shimming",topic:"Shimming and scribing cabinets at installation",keywords:["shim","scribe","cabinet","installation","wall","floor","level","plumb","gap"],answer:'Walls and floors are rarely perfectly plumb, level, or flat. During cabinet installation, shim under and behind cabinets until level and plumb, then scribe the exposed sides to the wall. A scriber (compass) traces the wall contour onto the cabinet side; cut along the scribed line to create a tight fit against the irregular wall. Fill large gaps (over 3/16") with a scribe molding (a strip of solid wood applied over the gap after scribing). Cabinet leveling legs (adjustable feet inside the toe kick) simplify leveling considerably compared to loose shims.'},{id:"mn-painted-cabinet-prep",topic:"Preparing cabinet frames for a painted finish",keywords:["paint","cabinet","prep","fill","sand","primer","nail","hole","edge","MDF"],answer:"Painted cabinets require more prep work than stained — paint magnifies surface defects while stain somewhat hides them. Fill all nail holes with non-shrinking wood filler; sand flat when dry. Sand all surfaces to 120 grit to remove planer marks. MDF edges: seal with a penetrating primer or drywall compound before painting (MDF edges are very absorbent). Apply one coat of oil-based primer (blocks tannins and knots); sand at 150 grit; apply second primer coat; sand at 180–220 grit; topcoat with alkyd or high-quality latex enamel. More prep steps mean a more professional result."},{id:"mn-base-cabinet-corner",topic:"Corner base cabinet construction and access",keywords:["corner","cabinet","base","lazy","susan","blind","rotating","tray","access"],answer:"Corner base cabinets are the most awkward storage in a kitchen — the deep recessed corner is hard to access. Options: lazy susan (rotating turntable), blind corner pull-out (hardware that pulls the contents into accessible position), or simply a large open shelf with a door (most accessible, least organized). Lazy susans require accurate corner-to-corner inside dimensions for the turntable diameter. Pull-out blind corner units mount to a specific cabinet width and depth — measure carefully and order the unit before building the cabinet. The corner cabinet door must swing clear of adjacent cabinet doors."},{id:"mn-outdoor-table-drain",topic:"Outdoor table drainage design",keywords:["outdoor","table","drain","water","gap","angle","channel","stainless","seal"],answer:'Outdoor table tops should have design features that allow water to drain quickly rather than pooling. Gaps between slats (1/4"–3/8") allow rain to pass through the top entirely. Alternatively, a solid top can be angled very slightly (1°–2°) so water runs to one end. Avoid inside corners that collect water — design with outward drainage geometry. Solid outdoor tops should never have sealed perimeter edges with no drainage path — water infiltrates through the end grain and causes rot from inside. Leave end-grain faces unsealed or protected with a water-repellent penetrating end-grain sealer specifically.'},{id:"mn-laminate-countertop",topic:"High-pressure laminate countertop construction",keywords:["laminate","countertop","HPL","contact","cement","substrate","flush","trim","bit"],answer:'HPL (high-pressure laminate) countertops: build the substrate from 3/4" plywood with a second 3/4" layer laminated on top (1.5" total) for flatness and rigidity. Apply contact cement to both the substrate and the HPL sheet; let dry; align carefully (the bond is instant — use dowel rods as spacers until aligned, then remove rods one at a time and press down firmly). Trim the edges with a flush-trim bit in a router. Edge the exposed front with HPL edge banding or a wood edge strip. Sand the transition joint carefully and apply the same laminate to any exposed substrate edges.'},{id:"mn-garden-planter",topic:"Wood garden planter box construction",keywords:["planter","garden","wood","box","liner","drain","rot","cedar","redwood","waterproof"],answer:'Wooden planter boxes need: rot-resistant wood (cedar, redwood, teak, black locust — never pressure-treated wood with arsenic for food gardens); drainage holes in the bottom (minimum 1" holes every 6"–8"); and a protective liner (hardware cloth on the bottom to prevent soil spillage while allowing drainage; plastic liner on the sides to protect the wood from constant soil contact). Leave joints slightly open (1/8" gaps) rather than gluing tightly — glued joints will push apart as the saturated wood swells seasonally. Annual oil treatment on the exterior extends life considerably.'},{id:"mn-workbench-top-glue",topic:"Laminating a workbench top from dimensional lumber",keywords:["workbench","top","laminate","glue","construction","lumber","flatten","dense","mass"],answer:'A laminated workbench top from 2×4 or 2×6 construction lumber: alternate heart side (growth rings oriented different directions) to reduce seasonal cupping. Apply glue to every mating surface; use many clamps (every 6"–8"); work in manageable glue-up sections (4–6 boards at a time). After curing, joint the top flat with a hand plane (the No.5 or No.7) — a belt sander works but leaves a rippled surface from uneven pressure. The mass of a thick solid top (4"–5") is the most important feature — it resists movement during planing. Flatten every year or when high spots develop from use.'}],m=[{id:"left-tool-panel",topic:"Left tool panel tabs",keywords:["left","panel","tool","tab","model","modify","joinery","shapes","ribbon","dock","sidebar","collapse","expand"],answer:"The left tool panel has four tabs: Model (Select, Draw, Add), Modify (Cross Cut, Rip Cut, Miter, Trim, Join), Joinery (Mate, Edge Treatment, Attach Point), and Shapes (Cylinder, Sphere, Cone, Triangle, Hexagon, Custom Polygon). Click the « / » button at the top to collapse the panel to a narrow strip with abbreviated tab labels, or expand it for full tool names. Pepe the frog sits at the bottom of this panel."},{id:"draw-board",topic:"How to draw or place a board",keywords:["draw","place","board","footprint","extrude","grid","sketch","rectangle"],answer:"Open the Model tab on the left panel and click Draw. Click and drag on the grid to sketch a rectangle footprint — that becomes your board length and width. Release to create the board. Keep Draw active to chain the next board edge-to-edge (see Continuous Drawing). You can also click Add to place a board and type exact dimensions in the Inspector tab on the right."},{id:"select-move",topic:"Select, move, rotate, and scale",keywords:["select","move","rotate","scale","gizmo","transform","click","pick"],answer:"Choose Select from the Model tab. Left-click any board to select it and open the radial wheel. Use the Move, Rotate, or Scale buttons in the Inspector to change the gizmo mode. Drag the colored arrows or rings to transform. Angle snap gives you 15°, 45°, or 90° rotation steps. Click empty space to deselect, or press Escape after closing the radial wheel."},{id:"quick-dimensions",topic:"Quick Dimensions floating panel",keywords:["quick","dimensions","floating","length","width","height","size","dims","edit","panel","what is"],answer:"The Quick Dimensions panel is a floating editor that shows L (length), W (width), and H (thickness) in actual inches. Select a board, then click the Dims segment on the radial wheel to open it. Type new values and they apply live in the viewport. Nominal size (like 2×4) shows when your board matches a standard size. Undo history records when you tab out of a field or deselect. Press Escape to close the panel."},{id:"mate-tool",topic:"Using the Mate tool",keywords:["mate","face","flush","align","snap","join","connect","how","pick","board","two"],answer:'Open the Joinery tab and click Mate, or click Mate on the radial wheel. Step 1: click a face on the first board — it highlights. Step 2: optionally click a point on the ¼" face grid to set the joint origin. Step 3: click a face on a different board — the second board snaps flush and a mate record is created. After mating, the join method sub-wheel opens so you can pick screws, glue, pocket holes, and more.'},{id:"face-grid",topic:"Face grid overlay and quarter-inch snap",keywords:["grid","snap","quarter","face","overlay","attach","inch","yellow","marker","origin","offset","what is"],answer:'The face grid is a yellow ¼" snap overlay that appears when you hover a board face with the Mate tool active. Click any grid intersection to set where the joint origin sits on that face — an amber sphere marks your choice. This lets you offset a joint from the face center, which is handy for aligning screw lines or shelf pin rows.'},{id:"attachment-points",topic:"Placing and naming attachment points",keywords:["attachment","point","name","connect","cyan","double click","double-click","place","what is"],answer:"Attachment points are named connection markers on board faces. With the Mate tool active, double-click a face to drop a point — it appears as a labeled cyan marker. Double-click a second point on another board to connect them; the second board moves so the two points meet. You can also use Attach Point from the Joinery tab. Points are useful for precise point-to-point alignment beyond simple face mating."},{id:"attachment-drag",topic:"Dragging attachment points on a face",keywords:["drag","move","reposition","attachment","point","slide","dashed","line","connected","handle"],answer:'Click and drag any attachment point to slide it along its face. The point stays on the face plane and snaps to the ¼" grid. When two points are connected, a dashed line shows the link between them. Dragging updates the connection live so you can fine-tune alignment without re-mating the boards.'},{id:"radial-wheel",topic:"Radial orbital selector wheel",keywords:["radial","wheel","orbital","selector","menu","open","click","right click","right-click","segments","how","what is"],answer:"The radial wheel is a circular action menu with five segments: Dims, Mate, Edge, Flip, and Delete. With the Select tool active, left-click any board to open it — every time, reliably. Right-click any board with any tool active to open it too. The wheel positions itself offset from your click, away from the screen center, so it does not cover the board under your cursor. Clicking the same board again keeps the wheel open. Close it with Escape, by clicking empty space, or by choosing a segment action."},{id:"radial-flip",topic:"Flip board on the radial wheel",keywords:["flip","rotate","180","longest","axis","mirror","turn","over"],answer:"Click the Flip segment on the radial wheel to rotate the selected board 180° around its longest axis. This is a quick way to turn a board over or reverse its orientation without using the rotation gizmo. The wheel stays open after flipping so you can take another action."},{id:"radial-delete",topic:"Deleting a board from the radial wheel",keywords:["delete","remove","board","radial","wheel","confirm","trash"],answer:'Click the Delete segment on the radial wheel once to arm deletion — the segment turns red and shows "Confirm?". Click Delete again within a few seconds to permanently remove the board. If you wait too long, the confirmation resets and you must click Delete twice again. You can also delete from the right-click context menu.'},{id:"join-subwheel",topic:"Join method sub-wheel",keywords:["join","method","screws","nails","glue","dowel","biscuit","pocket","bracket","hardware","mortise","tenon","sub","wheel","what is","how"],answer:'After you mate two boards, the join method sub-wheel opens automatically. You can also right-click an existing mate marker in the viewport to reopen it. Choose from Screws, Nails, Glue, Pocket Holes, Biscuit, Dowel, Bracket / Hardware, or Mortise & Tenon. Glue and Mortise & Tenon skip fastener placement. All other methods enter placement mode so you can click joint faces on the ¼" grid to place 3D fastener meshes.'},{id:"fasteners",topic:"Placing physical fasteners",keywords:["fastener","screw","nail","place","joint","hardware","3d","mesh","placement","done","grid","how","what is"],answer:'After choosing a join method that needs fasteners (Screws, Nails, Pocket Holes, Biscuit, Dowel, or Bracket), you enter Fastener Placement Mode. The joint face shows a ¼" snap grid. Click intersections to place 3D fastener meshes. Click Done Placing in the viewport bar or press Escape when finished. Click an existing fastener to inspect or remove it. Fastener counts appear in the Cut List tab.'},{id:"continuous-draw",topic:"Chaining boards while drawing",keywords:["chain","continuous","draw","edge","snap","connect","amber","dot","escape","end","how"],answer:"Keep the Draw tool active after placing a board. The next stroke snaps its start to the nearest corner or edge of the last board — look for the amber dot. Dashed amber lines show join candidates between chained boards. Press Escape or switch to another tool to end the chain. This is great for sketching frames and runouts quickly without placing each board separately."},{id:"box-select",topic:"Multi-select with drag box",keywords:["select","multiple","rubber","band","box","shift","drag","rectangle","dashed","how","what is"],answer:"With the Select tool active, click and drag on empty viewport space to draw a dashed amber selection rectangle. Release to select every board whose outline intersects the box. Hold Shift while dragging to add to the current selection instead of replacing it. When two or more boards are selected, the Multi-Member Quick Join toolbar appears above the selection."},{id:"quick-join",topic:"Multi-member quick join toolbar",keywords:["join","auto","detect","miter","butt","lap","multi","toolbar","several","multiple","how","what is"],answer:'Select two or more boards using drag box or Shift+click. A toolbar appears above the selection with: Auto-Detect Joints (finds flush faces within 0.1" and creates mates), Miter (adds 45° cuts), Butt Joint (face-to-face mate), Lap Joint (overlapping preset), and Open Radial Wheel (assign join methods on the primary selection). Use Auto-Detect first, then pick join methods from the sub-wheel.'},{id:"pepe-assistant",topic:"Pepe the frog design assistant",keywords:["pepe","assistant","help","frog","suggestions","ask","workshop","offline","what is","where","how"],answer:"Pepe is your offline design assistant — a friendly frog at the bottom of the left tool panel. Click him to open Pepe's Workshop. Two tabs: Suggestions runs live rule-based analysis on your project (span warnings, missing prices, overlaps, unset join methods) — click a suggestion to highlight boards. Ask Pepe lets you type any woodworking or app question; fuzzy search matches your words to Pepe's built-in knowledge. No internet required."},{id:"pepe-location",topic:"Where to find Pepe",keywords:["pepe","assistant","help","sidebar","frog","left","panel","bottom","where"],answer:"Pepe lives at the bottom of the left tool panel, below the tool buttons. Click the green frog mascot to open his panel. Use the Suggestions tab for live project tips or Ask Pepe to search woodworking and app help. He works fully offline."},{id:"edge-treatments",topic:"Edge treatments — chamfer, fillet, and more",keywords:["edge","chamfer","fillet","round","rabbet","ogee","cove","beading","roundover","treatment","how","what is"],answer:'Select a board and click Edge on the radial wheel, or choose Edge Treatment from the Joinery tab. Hover board edges — they highlight amber. Click an edge, then pick a treatment type in the Inspector: chamfer, fillet (round-over), cove, ogee, rabbet, or beading. Set depth or radius and click Apply. Use "Apply to all parallel edges" for uniform profiles. Edge treatments appear in the Cut List tab.'},{id:"complex-shapes",topic:"Complex shapes and primitives",keywords:["shape","cylinder","sphere","cone","hexagon","polygon","primitive","triangle","prism","custom","vertex","how","what is"],answer:'Open the Shapes tab in the left panel. Click Cylinder, Sphere, Cone, Triangle Prism, or Hexagon Prism to add a primitive board. For Custom Polygon, activate the tool and click vertices on the ¼" grid to outline a footprint, close by clicking near the first point, then set extrusion height. Drag vertex handles to adjust the outline. Rectangle boards still use the Draw tool in the Model tab.'},{id:"assembly-mode",topic:"Assembly mode",keywords:["assembly","explode","build","sequence","guide","mode","reset","export","flat","how","what is"],answer:"Click Mode in the top ribbon and choose Assembly. Boards explode and spread flat on the grid with spacing. Drag them together and mate joints one at a time in build order — each mate records a step in the Assembly Guide panel. Reset Assembly re-spreads the flat layout. Export Assembly Guide downloads a plain-text build checklist you can print for the shop floor."},{id:"display-modes",topic:"Display modes — wireframe, x-ray, edges",keywords:["display","wireframe","xray","x-ray","shaded","edges","transparent","view","mode","how","what is"],answer:"Use the Display dropdown in the top ribbon. Shaded is the default with wood grain texture. Wireframe shows structure outlines only. Shaded + Edges adds orange edge lines on solid boards. X-Ray makes boards semi-transparent so internal joinery, fasteners, and hardware inside stay visible — handy for checking pocket holes and dowels."},{id:"hardware-library",topic:"Hardware library",keywords:["hardware","hinge","slide","pull","bracket","shelf pin","cam lock","barrel bolt","drawer","library","place","how","what is"],answer:"Open the Hardware tab in the right sidebar. Browse drawer slides, hinges, pulls, shelf pins, cam locks, brackets, and barrel bolts — each item has a labeled preview. Click an item to arm placement mode, then click a board face in the viewport to place it. Placed hardware appears in the Hardware list and counts toward estimating."},{id:"context-menu",topic:"Right-click context menu",keywords:["right click","right-click","context","menu","duplicate","copy","mirror","solo","isolate","undo","camera","clear","selection"],answer:"Right-click any board to open the context menu and the radial wheel together. On a board: Delete Member, Duplicate, Copy, Mirror, Open Joinery Menu, and Solo (hide all other boards). Right-click empty space for Reset Camera, Clear Selection, and Undo Last Action. Choose Show All Boards to exit Solo mode."},{id:"escape-priority",topic:"Escape key priority",keywords:["escape","esc","cancel","close","priority","order","dismiss","keyboard","shortcut"],answer:"Press Escape repeatedly to step through open UI in order: close the context menu, exit fastener placement mode, cancel the Draw tool / end a draw chain, close Quick Dimensions, close the radial wheel, then deselect all boards. Ctrl+Z undoes and Ctrl+Y redoes."},{id:"top-ribbon",topic:"Top ribbon menus",keywords:["ribbon","file","view","help","mode","design","display","menu","save","open","undo","redo","camera","grid"],answer:"The top ribbon has File (save, open, new project), View (grid toggle, camera reset, orthographic), Help, Mode (Design or Assembly), Display dropdown (Shaded, Wireframe, Shaded + Edges, X-Ray), and Undo / Redo buttons. Use Mode to switch between free design and assembly build sequencing."},{id:"right-sidebar",topic:"Right sidebar tabs",keywords:["sidebar","right","inspector","estimating","cut list","engineering","hardware","tutorial","tab","panel"],answer:"The right sidebar has six tabs: Inspector (selected board properties, cuts, joinery, and transforms), Estimating (cost ledger with tax and waste buffer), Cut List (lumber nesting, sheet layouts, and fastener counts), Engineering (beam deflection analysis), Hardware (library and placed items), and Tutorial (the full in-app guide)."},{id:"cut-list",topic:"Reading and exporting the cut list",keywords:["cut","list","nesting","lumber","sheet","export","how","what is"],answer:'Open the Cut List tab in the right sidebar. Dimensional lumber is nested onto 8, 10, and 12-foot sticks with ⅛" kerf accounted for. Sheet goods show a 48×96 layout diagram. Fastener counts and edge treatment summaries appear at the bottom. Save your project as a .wcad file from File → Save Project to keep everything together.'},{id:"estimating",topic:"Using the estimating panel",keywords:["estimating","cost","price","tax","waste","ledger","how","what is"],answer:"The Estimating tab groups boards by species and size. Set price per LF, BF, or SF for each group. Enable waste buffer and tax rate as needed. Hardware and finishes add to the total. Boards without prices trigger a Pepe suggestion so you do not forget to price a part."},{id:"save-load",topic:"Saving and loading a wcad file",keywords:["save","load","wcad","file","project","backup","how"],answer:"Use File → Save Project in the top ribbon to download a .wcad file to your computer. File → Open Project loads one back. Autosave keeps your last session in the browser, but save a .wcad file for backups you control and can share."},{id:"undo-redo",topic:"Undo and redo",keywords:["undo","redo","history","mistake","ctrl","how"],answer:"Click Undo or Redo in the top ribbon, or press Ctrl+Z and Ctrl+Y. Dimension edits in the Quick Dimensions panel commit to history when you blur a field or deselect the board. Right-click empty space and choose Undo Last Action as another shortcut."},{id:"nominal-actual",topic:"Nominal vs actual dimensions",keywords:["nominal","actual","2x4","surfaced","dimension","what is"],answer:'Lumber is sold by nominal size (like 2×4) but planed to actual inches — a 2×4 is really about 1½" × 3½". DoveDesign stores actual inches everywhere. The Quick Dimensions panel shows nominal equivalents when your board matches a standard size.'},{id:"pocket-holes",topic:"Pocket holes in DoveDesign",keywords:["pocket","hole","kreg","angled","screw","how","what is"],answer:"Mate two boards, then choose Pocket Holes from the join method sub-wheel. CSG cuts angled pilot holes on both mating faces. You can also apply pocket holes from the Join tool in the Inspector. Great for face frames and cabinet boxes — keep them on the hidden side of show faces."},{id:"engineering",topic:"Engineering and beam deflection",keywords:["engineering","deflection","beam","span","load","structural","what is"],answer:"The Engineering tab runs a simple beam deflection check. Set each member's orientation (flat or on-edge), span, species, and uniform load in lbs. Results show deflection vs recommended limits. It is a guide — not a substitute for an engineer on critical loads."},{id:"nesting",topic:"Sheet and lumber nesting",keywords:["nesting","sheet","lumber","optimize","kerf","waste","what is"],answer:'The Cut List tab automatically bins dimensional parts onto standard stick lengths and packs sheet parts on 48×96 panels. Kerf is ⅛" between cuts. Review waste bars and sheet diagrams before you head to the saw.'},{id:"screws-vs-nails",topic:"When to use screws vs nails vs glue",keywords:["screw","nail","glue","when","choose","which"],answer:"Screws give strong, removable joints — great for cabinets and furniture that may need service. Nails are fast for framing and backs where shear strength matters and disassembly is not needed. Glue adds surface-area strength on long grain-to-grain joints; combine glue with screws or clamps for best results. Pick your method from the join sub-wheel after mating."},{id:"pocket-hole-limits",topic:"Pocket hole limitations",keywords:["pocket","hole","limit","weak","end grain"],answer:"Pocket holes excel on face frames and box joints but are weak into end grain alone. Keep screw length about two-thirds into the receiving board. Not ideal for fine hardwood show faces without plugs."},{id:"dowels",topic:"Dowels and alignment",keywords:["dowel","align","drill","jig","how"],answer:'Dowels align parts and add shear strength. Use a dowel jig or center marks for hole alignment. Typical diameters are ⅜" or ½" depending on stock thickness. In DoveDesign, choose Dowel as the join method after mating, then click the ¼" snap grid on the joint face to place dowel geometry.'},{id:"biscuits",topic:"Biscuits and biscuit joiners",keywords:["biscuit","plate","joiner","alignment","how"],answer:"Compressed wood biscuits swell in glue slots to align panel glue-ups like tabletops. A biscuit joiner cuts the slots. Good for alignment more than heavy structure — pair with glue across long grain. Choose Biscuit from the join sub-wheel and place on the joint face grid."},{id:"mortise-tenon",topic:"Mortise and tenon joinery",keywords:["mortise","tenon","strong","chair","table","how","what is"],answer:"A tenon on one part fits a mortise pocket in another — among the strongest traditional joints for chairs, tables, and doors. Choose Mortise & Tenon from the join sub-wheel after mating. This method skips fastener placement because the joint geometry itself represents the connection."},{id:"dovetails",topic:"Dovetail joints",keywords:["dovetail","drawer","box","hand cut","what is"],answer:"Dovetails interlock wedge-shaped pins and tails — excellent for drawers and boxes that resist pulling apart. Use the Join tool in the Inspector for decorative CSG previews. Hand-cut dovetails take practice; routers and jigs speed production work."},{id:"finger-box",topic:"Finger and box joints",keywords:["finger","box","joint","router","jig","what is"],answer:"Finger (box) joints use square interlocking fingers on corners — strong in glue and great for boxes and drawers. Dovetails taper for pull-out resistance; fingers are simpler to machine with a table saw jig or router. Apply from the Join tool in the Inspector."},{id:"cross-rip-cut",topic:"Cross cuts and rip cuts",keywords:["cross","cut","rip","chop","saw","width","how"],answer:"Select a board, open the Modify tab, and choose Cross Cut or Rip Cut. Set the cut position or target width in the Inspector. Cross Cut is a vertical chop across the board width (like a chop saw). Rip Cut removes a waste strip to reach a target width. Both appear immediately as CSG subtractions in the 3D view."},{id:"grain-direction",topic:"Wood grain direction",keywords:["grain","direction","tearout","strength","what is"],answer:"Grain runs along the length of a board. Long-grain glue joints are strongest. Cross-grain joints need allowance for wood movement. Route and plane with the grain when possible to reduce tear-out."},{id:"board-feet",topic:"Board feet calculation",keywords:["board","feet","bf","calculate","lumber","what is"],answer:"Board feet = (thickness in inches × width in inches × length in feet) ÷ 12. A 2×4×8' nominal stick is roughly 5.33 BF in actual dimensions. DoveDesign calculates BF per member for estimating."},{id:"nominal-lumber",topic:"Why a 2x4 is not 2 by 4",keywords:["2x4","nominal","surfaced","planed","lumber","what is"],answer:'Rough lumber is named by green rough size. After drying and planing to surfaced four sides (S4S), it shrinks — a 2×4 becomes about 1½" × 3½". Always build from actual dimensions on your cut list.'},{id:"cut-list-marking",topic:"Reading a cut list efficiently",keywords:["mark","cut","list","efficient","shop","how"],answer:"Group same-length parts on one stick. Mark waste side away from your best face. Cut longest parts first so mistakes leave usable shorts. Note kerf between every cut."},{id:"kerf",topic:"Kerf and saw blade width",keywords:["kerf","blade","saw","waste","account","what is"],answer:'Kerf is the slot removed by the blade — typically ⅛" on table saws. DoveDesign adds kerf in nesting on the Cut List tab. When cutting manually, measure to the waste side of your line.'},{id:"sheet-goods",topic:"Sheet goods vs solid wood",keywords:["plywood","sheet","mdf","hdf","veneer","what is"],answer:"Plywood and MDF come in 4×8 sheets — stable for backs, tops, and carcases. Solid wood suits visible edges and parts that need thickness or repair. Match grade to use: Baltic birch for drawers, CDX for shop projects."},{id:"wood-movement",topic:"Wood movement across seasons",keywords:["movement","expand","contract","humidity","seasonal","what is"],answer:"Wood swells across grain with humidity. Allow gaps on panel inserts, orient grain consistently on tabletops, and avoid trapping wide solid panels in rigid frames without a floating panel groove."},{id:"finishing",topic:"Finishing basics and sanding grits",keywords:["finish","sand","grit","stain","poly"],answer:"Sand progressively — 120 to 150 for prep, 180 to 220 before stain, 320 between poly coats. Stop at 220 on bare wood before oil unless you want a closed pore look. Always test finish on scrap from the same board."},{id:"structural-span",topic:"Shelf span and supports",keywords:["span","shelf","sag","support","structural"],answer:'Shelves over 36" in common ¾" plywood often sag under books. Add a center divider, thicker stock, or edge banding for stiffness. Check the Engineering tab for deflection estimates on loaded members.'},{id:"assembly-order",topic:"Designing for assembly order",keywords:["assembly","order","sequence","build","how"],answer:"Plan which joints are reachable last. Face frames often go on after carcase glue-up. Pocket holes on interiors before backs are installed. Dry-fit sub-assemblies before final glue. Assembly Mode in the top ribbon helps you practice the build sequence step by step."},{id:"beginner-mistakes",topic:"Common beginner mistakes",keywords:["beginner","mistake","tip","learn"],answer:"Measure twice, cut once. Account for actual not nominal sizes. Do not skip square checks on carcases. Pre-drill hardwood screws. Let finish cure before hardware install. Save often and use undo liberally."},{id:"shop-safety",topic:"Shop safety basics",keywords:["safety","guard","eye","ear","push stick"],answer:"Wear eye and ear protection. Keep guards on tools. Use push sticks past the blade. Unplug tools when changing bits or blades. Keep floors clear of offcuts and extension cords. Never reach over a spinning blade."}],f=[...m,...e,...t,...a,...o,...i,...r,...s,...n,...l,...d,...h,...c,...p,...u,...g,...w];export{f as PEPE_KNOWLEDGE};
